<HEADLINE>
RED STORM LOSES LATE: TAR HEELS TAKE TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., N.Y.)  
 (EDS.: Subs throughout to recast piece and add analysis and
comments from players.)  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They noticed their layups rolling around the rim and
out, their execution becoming forced and shoddy, their defense
making little difference. Deep down, the St. John's players knew
what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   They did not want to know, but they did. It was obvious. They
had lost the momentum, and the game clock was now the enemy. The
less time left, the better, for they would not be able to hold off
hard-charging Purdue for long.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, 1.7 seconds less time would have been enough
because that was how much time was left when Purdue's Jaraan
Cornell pulled up from 19 feet and shot a high-arcing jumper that
bounced off the backboard and through the net. It gave the
14th-ranked Boilermakers a 70-69 come-from-behind victory Friday
night over No. 23 St. John's in the consolation game of the Chase
Preseason National Invitation Tournament at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In the tournament's championship game, No. 9 North Carolina,
starting two freshmen and an inexperienced sophomore, held off No.
3 Stanford, 57-49. The Cardinal has five returning starters from
last season's Final Four team. Point guard Ed Cota, a junior,
scored a game-high 17 points to lead the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   For the Red Storm, which led the consolation game by 16 points
with 13 minutes left, the heartbreaking loss came just two nights
after it blew a 10-point second-half lead in losing, 55-53, to
Stanford in Wednesday's semifinal round. The similarities in the
games seemed eerie, not just after Friday night's game but during
it.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the Red Storm had felt the game slipping through
its fingers, the shooting guard Bootsy Thornton replied: ``In a
sense, yeah. I didn't want it to happen, but we kept telling
ourselves, `The game's not over.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who scored 18 points, was tough on himself afterward
because he missed the first shot in a one-and-one free-throw
situation with 10.6 seconds left and the Red Storm ahead by 69-68.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about going through my routine, bending my
knees and making the free throws,'' Thornton said. ``If I'm put in
that situation again, I'm pretty sure it won't happen again. But
right now, it's an indescribable feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thornton should not bare the brunt of this loss, for the
game should have never been that close. St. John's (3-2), looking
far superior to the Boilermakers (5-1), dominated the first half,
forcing 15 turnovers with its aggressive full-court press and
building a 41-25 lead at the break.
</P>
<P>
   But even though it led by 56-40 with 13 minutes 1 second left,
something was different. Purdue had adjusted to the Red Storm's
trapping defense and was beginning to play with more confidence.
The Boilermakers' defense was starting to cause St. John's trouble,
and Purdue's shots were beginning to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue kept closing, and when Cornell made the Boilermakers'
fourth 3-pointer of the second half, it cut St. John's lead to
56-52 with 8:17 left. St. John's built the lead back to 67-61, on a
layup by Ron Artest, who led all scorers with 20 points, but Purdue
scored the next 4 points and pulled to within 2 on a layup by Greg
McQuay (19 points).
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a perfect example of the lack of execution that cost it
the game, the Red Storm committed a shot-clock violation. Still, it
looked as if St. John's would survive when Lavor Postell scored a
driving layup to make it 69-65 with 16 seconds left. But Alan
Eldridge sank a contested 3-pointer, his second in the final four
minutes, to pull the Boilermakers to within a point. That's when
Purdue sent Thornton to the line.
</P>
<P>
   When he missed, Cornell sprinted toward the left wing, received
the pass and put up the game-winner with guard Erick Barkley (9
points, 6 assists) in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I released it and saw how high the arc was, I called
bank,'' Cornell said, joking.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had one final chance, but Artest's 3-point attempt at
the buzzer was short.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
