<HEADLINE>
EARLY BIRDS UP AT CRACK OF DAWN TO GRAB HOLIDAY BARGAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Arriving at the suburban Glendale Galleria at
5:30 a.m., Gloria Mungaray gave herself a pat on the back for
beating the crowds on the first day of the holiday shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   Well, she thought she beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching K-B Toys with a few family members Friday, the Los
Angeles resident saw to her horror that her group had been outrun
by hundreds of other people who were already lined up for the
store's 6 a.m. ``door buster'' sale.
</P>
<P>
   And this crack-of-dawn arrival wasn't even her idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``My niece is the one who coerced us into doing this,'' Mungaray
said about two hours later, as she dragged a big plastic bag so
stuffed with toys that it was starting to rip.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the day after Thanksgiving, the day that
traditionally marks the first day of the holiday shopping season.
And after several years of singing the holiday blues, merchants
could well be whistling a cheerier tune this year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the crowds and cash registers at the Glendale Galleria
on Friday, Southern California's shopping season has gotten off to
a good start, said Richard Giss, a partner in the trade retail
services group at the accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP.
</P>
<P>
   The Glendale Galleria is a good mall from which to gauge general
shopping trends across the area in part because it is a regional
mall, drawing shoppers from a wide area, Giss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic right now is much heavier than last year at this
time,'' he said, scanning the bag-laden crowds surging through the
aisles at 9:45 a.m. While some stores opened as early as 6, most of
the mall opened at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden resurgence on Wall Street and a pickup in consumer
confidence were ``the last pieces that needed to fall into place''
to make this what promises to be an exceptional season, Giss said.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of Friday's bag carriers appeared to have taken
advantage of the early-bird specials offered by K-B Toys and the
J.C. Penney and Mervyn's department stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this time of the day you've got quite a few bags, and you
expect it early on,'' Giss said.
</P>
<P>
   Galleria spokeswoman Annette Bethers said about 250 people lined
up in front of K-B Toys before its 6 a.m. opening, about 300 were
at Mervyn's for the store's 7 a.m. door-buster, and 200 people
arrived at the mall's Disney Store before its 8 a.m. opening to
snap up the limited-edition mini-beanbag plush toys available
Friday only.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the number of cars in the parking lot, plus some
``eyeballing'' of the crowds, mall management estimated a 10
percent to 15 percent increase in morning shopping traffic compared
with the same time last year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, by about 10 a.m. some 75 percent of the mall's
6,300 parking spaces were filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems it's starting out stronger than it did last year,''
Bethers said.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney manager David Small said the store had ``the biggest
(opening crowd) in the last three years'' when it opened at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first two hours, in dollars, I'm 67 percent ahead of
where we were the last two straight years,'' Small said.
</P>
<P>
   The line didn't appear to have diminished outside K-B Toys as
the clock ticked toward 11 a.m., forming what looked from above
like a huge question mark curving from the door and then down the
mall's center aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Another, longer line inside started directly in front of the
checkout stand and snaked through several aisles before veering
back toward the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other shoppers jostled through the crowds, hauling
their toy-filled bags and generally trying to stay off each other's
toes.
</P>
<P>
   K-B store manager George Temourian managed the traffic like,
well, a traffic cop.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that thousands of people had gone through the store
in the morning. ``I couldn't even guess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The store's 250 Furbies, those mechanical gremlins with saucer
eyes, went fast. ``They were spoken for before 6 o'clock; we gave
out numbers,'' Temourian said.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the year's hottest items? Besides Furbies and the
ubiquitous Barbie, consumer electronics like Palm Pilots and family
band radios will be big, Giss said.
</P>
<P>
   And this could be the year of the DVD player as well. ``It's
been around, but it finally has some software you can use with it,
and the prices have come down,'' Giss said.
</P>
<P>
   Big-ticket items like jewelry and furniture could also prove
more popular with shoppers this year. ``That's because people have
money to spend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One Furby buyer was Mary Fowler of Hollywood, who had four of
the critters in her bags -- two of them hers, two her sister's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to see them -- I had a backup at another store
in case I didn't get them,'' she said as she took a breather from
shopping. ``I was going to get them one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Within her first hour or so of shopping she had spent about
$300, about half the $600 or so she expects to spend this season --
which is less than she spent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to cut back on the impulse buying,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Susie Valle was quite pleased at having successfully
dragged aunt Gloria Mungaray and the others to the mall so early.
After all, they caught all the best deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found everything I came for at this store, according to the
ad. I went through the ad and made a list,'' said the suburban
Eagle Rock resident, who dragged several bags loaded with $183
worth of toys around the mall.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same story elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's early door busters gave Kathy Suyemoto of suburban
Newhall time to hit Toys `R' Us and Wal-Mart before landing at the
Valencia Town Center a few miles away. She declared victory at
11:15 a.m., leaving that mall's K-B with five huge sacks of toys
for the 14 kids on her Christmas list. Her receipt read $189 and
some change.
</P>
<P>
   Her best find was three California Roller Girls dolls, regularly
$40, for $7.99 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up at a quarter to 6, threw on some sweats and here I
am,'' Suyemoto said. ``There were people in line waiting to get
into the store. Then there was a huge line at the cash register.
People kept saying, I'm not going to wait, I'm not going to wait --
but then you kept getting a little bit closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Others didn't want to get up so early. Mark Davis, 32, of
suburban Lancaster, arrived at the Antelope Valley Mall at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get a jump on Christmas. I also have to do some
birthday shopping,'' Davis said. ``I was away on business. Now I'm
trying to do a lot of catch-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some came just to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to watch people fight over clothes and
toys,'' said R.J. Gangloff of Malibu as he people-watched at The
Oaks mall in suburban Thousand Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   But most people were shopping, not watching.
</P>
<P>
   With a cellular phone to one ear, Tamberley Much of suburban
Brentwood paced impatiently on a sidewalk at the Camarillo Premium
Outlets shopping center in Camarillo, in neighboring Ventura
County. Already dressed for the holidays in a candy-cane sweater,
she was eager to embark on a cherished family activity: going
shopping the day after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tradition,'' said Much, whose mother showed up at her
doorstep at 8 a.m. to go shopping. ``Every day after Thanksgiving
we get up early to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   She will spend more money this year because there are more
family members. Her mother, Belinda Earl of Glendale, also expects
to shell out more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy's better,'' she said. ``It's easier to spend
more.''
</P>
<P>
   At midmorning, throngs of shoppers packed the sidewalks and
stores of the outlet center. The most popular retailers were
housewares such as Mikasa and Le Gourmet Chef. Also drawing big
crowds were stores with the deepest sales: Cole Haan was mobbed
because of discounts up to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do think we'll have a good year, better than last year,''
said Terri Cameron, general manager of Camarillo Premium Outlets.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., the main checkout lines at Wal-Mart in the Panorama
Mall in suburban Panorama City snaked past the candy-bar and
chewing-gum displays, through women's wear and next to kitchen
goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't thinking,'' said Eleanor Snyder, a San Diego
resident who returned to her hometown of North Hollywood for
Thanksgiving, and now stood with easily a dozen people before and
behind her. ``I was a retail manager for 15 years, and I told
myself I'd never do this. But I saw a good sale, and my kid needed
jeans.''
</P>
<P>
   With waits at the cash registers of the nation's only two-story
Wal-Mart running 15 minutes or more, post-holiday tempers wore
thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you spell a scream? Aahhh!'' said Armando Rodriguez, after
what he said was 10 minutes spent simply wading from one side of
the store to the other before getting in line. ``No way I'm doing
this again.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
