<HEADLINE>
BARGAIN STALLION PROVES GOLDEN AT CUTTING HORSE OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A stallion once rejected by a well-known
trainer and then purchased for a bargain price turned in the
highest opening-day score at the 1998 NCHA World Championship
Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   Chula Dual, ridden by Jon Burgess, a low-profile trainer from
Stephenville, turned in a first go-round tally of 222 as the
National Cutting Horse Association's premier show began its 17-day
run yesterday at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   That's an unusually high marking for a debuting 3-year-old
horse, especially when the Chula Dual only cost its owners, Harry
and Kathy Brinkerhoff of Stephenville, about $7,500 at a sale last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess said the colt was auctioned after Joe Heim, a former
Futurity champion who was training Chula Dual at the time, declared
that the horse did not have potential. That caused then owner Billy
Emerson of Dallas to sell the horse at a Fort Worth sale last July,
Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Brinkerhoffs purchased Chula Dual and turned the
stallion over to Burgess, Chula Dual began to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the horse for only two weeks and he was doing some very
awesome things,'' Burgess said. ``I kept asking Harry, `Why did
\REmerson\S sell this horse?''
</P>
<P>
   Though the horse appears to be a blue-chipper, Harry Brinkerhoff
said it was a gamble when he purchased Chula Dual in July of 1997.
Brinkerhoff said Emerson watched Chula Dual in a practice session
two months ago, and Emerson said he regretted that he let the
stallion slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a roll of the dice,'' Brinkerhoff said. ``He could have
gone the other direction. In fact, I have another horse that I
bought at the same sale that is standing right here \Rat
Brinkerhoff's ranch\S because he did not make the Futurity.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chula Dual, sired by the prominent stallion Dual Pep, lived
up to his billing and was entered in the Futurity, the show that
features the sport's most promising 3-year-old horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just like his daddy,'' Burgess said. ``He's a smart
sucker. He's got all of the pieces. He's smart, quick and has a lot
of cow sense and ability. He's got all of the elements to compete
with the big boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgess, 30, who has been a pro trainer for the past five years
and began riding cutters 21 years ago, said Chula Dual could be his
big break.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best horse that I've ever ridden, bar none,''
Burgess said. ``Even his bad days are good.''
NCHA Futurity Today through Dec. 13: National Cutting Horse
Association World Championship Futurity, Will Rogers Memorial
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Purse: $2.3 million, including an estimated $200,000 to the open
division winner.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Call (817) 244-6188 during business hours Monday
through Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
