u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUS-CRASH-SPI &LR;      11-28 1461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-CRASH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUS PLUNGES OFF BRIDGE AFTER ATTACKER SHOOTS DRIVER, SELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVEN GOLDSMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Metro bus plunged off the Aurora Bridge Friday after one of
its passengers shot the driver and killed himself, police sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacular mid-afternoon crash injured 33 riders, filling
seven hospital emergency rooms. Amid the wreckage the driver and
his assailant lay dead, both with gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was like an action movie come horrifyingly to life, as
the downtown-bound Route 359 Express swerved through oncoming
traffic, crashed through a guardrail and struck the roof of an
apartment building before landing in the crowded Fremont
neighborhood more than 40 feet below.
</P>
<P>
   The fall split the 40,000-pound, articulated bus into a V,
sending its front half onto the steps of the two-story apartment
building and its rear half into the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the worst tragedy in Metro Transit's nearly three
decades, dozens of paramedics and firefighters pulled bleeding
riders from the shattered bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a training exercise,'' paramedic Chris Cornett
said, ``with all the dirt on the injured faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old driver, Mark McLaughlin, died at the scene, the
victim of an apparent murder-suicide. Authorities said his body was
found on the roof of the apartment where he'd been ejected before
his bus slid off onto the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The man believed to be his attacker also was found near the bus
with a gunshot wound in his head and a fired gun nearby,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   He was pronounced dead at Harborview Medical Center, where
police reportedly recovered a second firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Transit officials said the incident happened so quickly
that McLaughlin, the driver, didn't even have time to push his
emergency alarm button.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon bus run had started routinely enough. On one of
the year's busiest shopping days, McLaughlin pulled his bus out of
the Aurora Village mall about 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some 13 minutes later, he reached the girdered Aurora Bridge two
miles north of downtown, driving in the middle of its three
southbound lanes.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, according to Rick Walsh, director of King County's
Metro Transit division, came without warning from ``someone sitting
across the aisle from the driver in the first seat behind the
(front) door.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no previous conversation,'' Walsh said. ``No tension
was apparent and ..(he) pulled out a gun and shot the driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lee, 16, of Seattle, had caught the bus at North 85th
Street and Aurora Avenue North. She was sitting in the middle, near
the flexible joint, when ``I heard two gunshots and the bus
swerved.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus continued southbound about 100 feet, authorities said,
then swerved toward oncoming traffic where it clipped a northbound
Ford Econoline van driven by Tom Foti for Seattle Tile Co.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she didn't realize the bus had run off of the bridge
until after it had hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing I know there were people falling over each
other and there were people screaming and seats were breaking,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know we were in the air. I thought it was a big
accident and we had hit a semi (truck) or something.''
</P>
<P>
   She lost one of her shoes as she was tossed around inside the
bus. When the wreckage stopped moving, she was clinging to a metal
bar.
</P>
<P>
   Lacy Olsen, 13, was on her way downtown to get her eyebrow
pierced. She was sitting in the middle of the bus when ``I saw two
flashes and heard a loud pop-pop. I saw the bus driver and his
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus then went out of control. ``It like happened in 30
seconds. Everybody was screaming and crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen said she didn't see anything before the shooting to
indicate there was a problem between the driver and assailant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear them exchange any words.''
</P>
<P>
   When the bus hit the ground ``the floorboard flew up. I got
kinda jammed up underneath,'' she said, as she was about to be
treated at Ballard Swedish Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Jurgi, 52, was standing on the porch of her house on North
36th Street, about 100 feet away, when she saw the bus go off the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in such of swirl of metal and glass,'' she said. ``I
have never seen anything go over the bridge. I couldn't believe it.
It was like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   When it crashed to the ground, ``I heard a couple of voices
saying `Help me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, more than 20 rescue units were at the scene,
some rescuers trying to lift the bus to look beneath it for
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Chris and Auli Brown heard the bus crash through the rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of crying and moaning,'' said Chris Brown.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 injured people were strewn around the bus, mostly
within 10 feet of the wreckage. Many of them were bleeding from
head injuries. Some were conscious, others were not.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he saw only a few people still inside the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy was trapped under the front of the bus,'' he said, and
about five bystanders were trying to comfort him.
</P>
<P>
   One woman was half-in and half-out of the bus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Her torso lay on the floor, and her legs were hanging out of the
bus' ripped-open side.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of guys pulled her out and put her on the ground.''
She was crying hysterically, and tried to get up. But one of the
men held her until medical help arrived. ``I think she was OK,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   He gave his jacket to a man named Henry, who had a broken leg.
He helped the man to the ground from his perch leaning against one
of the bridge supports. He watched as a doctor slit open the man's
pant leg to show the bone sticking out of his leg. When a medical
team put it in a splint, the man yelled in pain.
</P>
<P>
   The bus' fall sheared off part of the roof of the apartment
building at 905 N. 36th St., just west of Winslow Place North.
</P>
<P>
   There, post-Thanksgiving socializing turned to horror as Paul
Lauren, a 35-year-old crabboat fisherman, tried to help victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard moans and screaming,'' Lauren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never ever seen anything like this in my life. It was
like the wreckage of an airplane crash. People were twisted like
dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident scene was littered with shredded medal, concrete,
blood, and shattered glass. The area also smelled of diesel fuel,
one witness said.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren just got back from fishing in the Aleutians two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was dangerous up there. We always were worried
about getting killed. Now we're standing in the front of the house
and a bus falls on us. It's a real question of what's more
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they will not move the 72-passenger bus until
Saturday. They need heavier equipment and need to do it in the
daylight. Meanwhile, the site was being treated as a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Birt, assistant chief of northern fire operations, called
the accident ``a once in a lifetime incident. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a disaster drill, but it was for real,'' he
said. ``Everyone did everything by the book. Just right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I drive across this bridge all the time,'' Birt added,
pointing to the bridge above him, ``and often wonder how strong
those railings really are. Now we know they're not strong enough to
stop a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   An off-duty Metro driver, Ron Dunn, showed up at the scene. He
was in tears, shaken. He complained that Metro had not been
enforcing rules when it comes to unruly passengers, not cracking
down on passengers who were drinking or not paying fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metro has gone overly liberal,'' he said. ``Drivers are going
to be very outraged by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said Metro officials will talk to drivers about their
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``From everything I have heard. ... it would have made no
difference even if a police officer was sitting next to the driver.
No words were exchanged before he shot the driver,'' Walsh said.
``This is one of those unpredictable things.''
</P>
<P>
   King County Executive Ron Sims said the county emergency
response system, including Medic One, was a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest test we've had. It worked really well,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``we're worried about the bus drivers. They
realize how vulnerable they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims said there would have been no way to prevent the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have metal detectors on every single bus,'' Sims told
reporters outside the emergency room at Harborview. ``It's
virtually impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sims said this incident must be put in perspective given
that buses transport 84 million passengers annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean our buses aren't safe,'' Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last one (fatal shooting on bus) happened 25 years ago.
This was just very, very unfortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
