<HEADER>
A2722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TAR-HEELS-570&AMP;ADD     11-28 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TAR-HEELS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL NORTH CAROLINA OUTPLAYS NO. 3 STANFORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The young North Carolina Tar Heels are maturing quickly. Six
victims in six games, most notably the highly regarded Stanford
Cardinal, will attest to that.
</P>
<P>
   With two freshmen and an inexperienced sophomore in its starting
lineup, North Carolina defeated Stanford, 57-49, Friday night to
win its first Chase Preseason National Invitation Tournament
championship before 13,471 fans at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels' victory will shake up the national rankings, as
North Carolina entered the game rated ninth in the Associated Press
poll. Stanford, which has five returning starters and is viewed by
many as the country's top team, was ranked third.
</P>
<P>
   The teams were supposed to be at different stages _ Stanford
loading up for a run at the national title, while North Carolina is
trying to find an identity _ but those roles may be reversed after
this tournament. Although they stumbled at times, the Tar Heels
played with poise in defeating No. 14 Purdue in the semifinals and
Stanford (4-1) Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal, on the other hand, struggled just to get to the
championship, edging St. John's by 55-53 on Wednesday. Their lack
of quickness in the frontcourt and absence of an explosive scorer
proved to be problems in both games.
</P>
<P>
   While North Carolina's youngsters played well, it was Coach Bill
Guthridge's leaders, the junior point guard Ed Cota and the senior
forward Ademola Okulaja, who led them to victory. Cota, who grew up
in Brooklyn, recorded game highs of 17 points and 11 rebounds and
made four free throws in the final 1 minute 22 seconds to seal the
victory after Stanford had pulled to within 46-43. Cota was named
the tournament's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Okulaja followed with 14 points. Brendan Haywood, North
Carolina's sophomore center, blocked 6 shots.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this tournament, Stanford found itself
trailing at the half. A victim of North Carolina's torrid
first-half shooting (13 for 18), the Cardinal, which trailed St.
John's by 25-22 in Wednesday's semifinal, began the second half
Friday trailing by 32-23.
</P>
<P>
   But in a performance similar to the one against St. John's,
Stanford was stronger after intermission. Outplaying the Tar Heels
early in the second half, the Cardinal pulled to within 34-29, but
watched North Carolina score 4 straight points to push the lead
back to 9.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford had led early in the game _ very early. The Cardinal
scored the game's first basket, but then the Tar Heels, getting
3-pointers from Okulaja and Cota, ran off 10 straight points to
take command. The big and physical Cardinal battled back by
pounding the offensive boards. Stanford's rebounding _ the Cardinal
players grabbed nine of their missed shots for second opportunities
_ enabled them to overcome 27 percent shooting overall, including 3
of 11 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the half, Stanford picked up its defensive
intensity, making four steals, to turn a 14-7 deficit into a 19-17
lead when the reserve Ryan Mendez hit a 3-pointer. North Carolina,
behind 4 points from Cota and a 3-pointer by the freshman Jason
Capel, ended the half with a 15-4 run to take a 9-point lead into
the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   In the consolation game, Purdue beat St. John's, 70-69, on a
basket by Jaraan Cornell with 1.7 seconds left, a high-arcing
jumper from 19 feet that bounced off the backboard and through the
net.
</P>
<P>
   For the Red Storm, which led by 16 points with 13 minutes
remaining, the heartbreaking loss came just two nights after it
blew a 10-point second-half lead in losing by 2 points to Stanford
in Wednesday's semifinals. For something so similar to happen in
the consolation game seemed eerie, not just after the game but
during it.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the Red Storm had felt the game slipping through
its fingers, the shooting guard Bootsy Thornton replied: ``In a
sense, yeah. I didn't want it to happen, but we kept telling
ourselves, `The game's not over.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who played a strong game in scoring 18 points, was
tough on himself afterward because he missed the first shot in a
one-and-one free-throw situation with 10.6 seconds left and the Red
Storm ahead by 69-68.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about going through my routine, bending my
knees and making the free throws,'' Thornton said. ``If I'm put in
that situation again, I'm pretty sure it won't happen again. But
right now, it's an indescribable feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thornton should not bare the brunt of this loss, for the
game should have never been that close. St. John's (3-2), looking
far superior to the Boilermakers (5-1), dominated the first half,
forcing 15 turnovers with its aggressive full-court press and
building a 41-25 lead at the break. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
