u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUS-CRASH-WITNESSES-S     11-28 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-CRASH-WITNESSES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUS PASSENGER SHOOTS DRIVER, BUS CRASHES THROUGH BRIDGE RAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Bus 359 rolled onto the Aurora Bridge Friday, bound
for the Christmas lights and the holiday bustle of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Behind driver Mark McLaughlin sat a big man in his 40s. He sat
on the right. He carried a bag.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger said nothing. He just started firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just sitting there on the bus,'' one dazed passenger
said later as he waited for an ambulance to take him to a hospital.
He was identified only by the number paramedics had pinned to his
shirt: No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I heard this, `Pow! Pow! Pow!'''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lee, who had caught the bus at North 85th Street and
Aurora Avenue North, thought she had heard two gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus swerved,'' the 16-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-foot bus veered into the northbound lanes of the bridge
and right at Tom Foti, 50 who was driving a van in the middle lane.
``He hit me in the side and spinned me around,'' Foti said. ``I was
trying not to hit other cars.''
</P>
<P>
   On the bus, Passenger 17 felt the 40,000-pound bus lurch off the
bridge. ``I just covered my head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 feet below was the Fremont neighborhood. Abrahim
Faraj was working on his truck. P.J. Mercouriadis was in the
library of her house, in the neighborhood where she has lived most
of her life. Clare Mercy was about to go outside to join some
friends in the rare November sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Then there came the sound of metal grinding against metal and
concrete, as Bus 359 slammed into the bridge's guardrail. The bus
ripped through a 25-foot section of the rail and barreled into a
light standard, bending it at a right angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing I know there were people falling over each
other, and there were people screaming, and seats were breaking,''
Lee, the passenger, said. ``I didn't know we were in the air. I
thought it was a big accident, and we had hit a semi or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Concrete showered down. The articulated bus ricocheted off an
apartment building, then landed in a V-formation in the building's
garden, wrapped around a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like an explosion _ a first one, then a second
one,'' said Faraj, 57, who was three blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a weird crunching sound. It was metal,'' said
Mercouriadis, 62, who lives at North 38th Street and Linden Avenue
North.
</P>
<P>
   From her first-floor apartment under the bridge, Mercy, 29,
watched the bus tumble practically into her front yard and almost
on top of four friends waiting outside for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the bus fall. I heard the first noise. It was a huge
noise. It was a huge bang. It must have been the bus going through
the guardrail.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Krause, 20, watched as the concrete fell down. One chunk
grazed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked up,'' she said, ``and this bus was, like, flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the street, the truck repairs and the rest of the idle
work of a four-day weekend ended. The work of saving lives started.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Kerr ran from his house near the famed Fremont troll when
he heard what sounded like ``four or five garbage trucks hitting
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr and others running to the scene soon beheld something
ghastly _ a bad dream, maybe, or the special effects of an action
movie.
</P>
<P>
   `It would be like, take a Tonka truck and drop it off into a
little, makeshift yard with a lot of force,'' Kerr said. ``It
knocked out the tree. There's this bus in my neighbor's yard. It
was like a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin was thrown out of the bus and landed atop the
apartment building. Paramedics tried in vain to revive him. Across
the Northwest, television viewers watched as he was given CPR.
</P>
<P>
   Below the bridge, glass and metal mixed with blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a swirl of metal and glass,'' said Judy Jurgi, who
watched the accident unfold from her front porch. ``I couldn't
believe it. It was like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Sirens blared. Police, firefighters and paramedics thronged into
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fire Department was all over the place. Within two
minutes, you could hear sirens coming from all directions,'' said
David Hardesty. ``It looks just like it does on television:
Everyone doing their job and not talking much.''
</P>
<P>
   From inside the bus, voices pleaded for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a couple of voices say, `Help me!''' Jurgi, 52, said.
Some people heard worried cries about spilled diesel fuel.
Passengers struggled to get out of the bus. The injured helped one
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard hollering and moaning and saw people trying to get
out,'' Mercy said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee lost one of her shoes as she was tossed around inside the
bus. And when the wreckage stopped moving, she was holding onto a
metal bar. ``I just didn't know what to do. I was in shock. I
realized people were leaving the bus. A man helped me out of the
emergency window.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee was taken to Swedish Medical Center, where she was in stable
condition last night.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics put numbers on victims as a triage was set up. Kerr
saw one man wearing No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew then the body count was up there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One developmentally disabled passenger simply wandered away. A
neighborhood couple spotted him and kept him in safety.
</P>
<P>
   They flagged down a deputy fire chief who put the man into his
car and took him to a waiting ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Mercouriadis looked around her old neighborhood and didn't
recognize it. A man lay dying on the roof. Paramedics carried away
bloody passengers. Others waited in stunned silence for their turn
to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just crossed myself and said, `God help them,''' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
