<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS PUT ON `GREEN STAR' JERSEY AND WEAR OUT CAPITALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Maybe the Stars can petition the NHL to wear their
``green star'' jersey every game.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off one of their worst performances of the season, the
Stars last night relied on the magic of the alternate sweater,
hammering the Washington Capitals, 4-0, and remaining unbeaten
(11-0-3) in the special-events jersey since unveiling it last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, does the league dictate when we can and can't wear
those?'' defenseman Darryl Sydor asked after the game, a cartoon
light bulb virtually appearing over his head. ``I mean we want to
wear them every game.''
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. The Stars have been approved for 15 dates by the
NHL and have used up six of those so far. The next appearance of
the ``green star'' isn't until Dec. 21 against the Montreal
Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   Tough luck.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Stars are hoping they won't need luck after putting
out a total team effort against the Capitals and seemingly
restructuring their game in just one night.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defensemen Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk were
monsters, playing 24 minutes apiece, controlling the defensive zone
and chipping in two points apiece. Mike Modano had two goals and an
assist and left the Capitals' heads spinning with a series of
dazzling moves. Goalie Ed Belfour notched his first shutout of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hatcher was excellent. Modano was excellent. \RSergei\S Zubov
was excellent. Belfour was excellent,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said of the win that pushed the Stars' record to 12-4-3. ``Our
leaders led.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in direct contrast to a 5-2 loss to the New Jersey
Devils on Wednesday when Hatcher and Matvichuk struggled, Modano
was a nonfactor and Belfour was pulled after yielding three goals
in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Stars jumped ahead as Modano and Hatcher scored
even-strength goals in the first 3 minutes, 57 seconds. Modano took
a breakout pass from linemate Mike Keane, barreled in on Capitals
goalie Olaf Kolzig and, at the last instant, put on the brakes and
flicked a wrist shot past the befuddled Kolzig just 1:10 into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher then scored off a nice cross-ice pass from Jamie
Langenbrunner and, for the first time in the past three games, the
Stars weren't the team staring at a two-goal deficit in the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two goals were important, but what was just as important
was that we were playing well defensively,'' Stars center Guy
Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars continued that strong defensive play throughout the
game and never really gave the injured Capitals the chance to get
off the ice. Modano added his second goal on a second-period power
play and Hatcher then pushed it to 4-0 when he took a slick pass
from Dave Reid on an odd-man rush and shot through a Modano screen
at the 16:37 mark of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, Hatcher and Matvichuk were on the ice for all four
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The third period degenerated into a brawl as four Stars players
were in fights _ including Carbonneau, who engaged in fisticuffs
for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was good,'' Hitchcock said. ``We stood up for
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just that kind of night. Belfour, who appeared to have
his first shutout since March 22 ruined on a Steve Konowalchuk goal
with 57.8 seconds remaining, earned a reprieve when video-replay
judges declared Konowalchuk in the crease and waived off the goal.
</P>
<P>
   It had to be the magic green star, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're as superstitious as anyone,'' Sydor said. ``We want
to wear them every night.'' \Ntagtop: Mike Heika, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
