<HEADER>
A2735 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     11-28 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS FAVORED THIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The quarterback controversy has been a
distraction. So has the losing streak to a bitter archrival. Even
the quality of the bowl game is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   There always seems to be so many dilemmas swirling around USC.
But this isn't a mini-dissection of the Trojans. Instead, all of
these traumas belong to Notre Dame. Yes, Notre Dame, the
ninth-ranked team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   How a top 10 team could enter tonight's game at the Coliseum
with more problems than the Trojans seems implausible, but then
again, somebody's listening because USC has been established as an
8{-point favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a single injury, the Irish (9-1) arrive with more
doubts than the Trojans. A pretty heady accomplishment considering
USC (7-4) is coming off a seven-turnover performance against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   But when Irish quarterback Jarious Jackson partially tore the
medial collateral ligament in his right knee while intentionally
taking a safety against Louisiana State, the Irish lost a lot of
what the oddsmakers liked about the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame coach Bob Davie has not named a starter, but freshman
Arnaz Battle is expected to get the call. Battle, who has thrown
just one pass this season, played in three games before spraining
his shoulder last month against Baylor. He has fully recovered from
the injury. Junior Eric Chappell has also thrown just one pass and
played in parts of two games.
</P>
<P>
   Both quarterbacks are in the Jackson mold, meaning the Irish
will be primarily running the ball and use a little option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know much about them. We can guess,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said. ``The reality is that until the game starts and until
the game begins to unfold, we're just not going to know exactly
what we're up against. You just go in and play against what you
think they can do. That can be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time a Notre Dame quarterback has made his
initial college start against the Trojans. In 1966, Coley O'Brien
replaced the injured Terry Hanratty and led the Irish to a 51-0
victory over the Trojans, Notre Dame's most lopsided victory of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a history of teams making this change and performing
brilliantly,'' Hackett said. ``I'm hoping this is not one of those
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie has tried to remain non-committal about the quarterback
situation, offering only this tidbit about who will play the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put one criteria on it. If he leads us to a touchdown on the
first five possessions of the game, I am not going to take him out.
You can write that,'' Davie joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're approaching this like both are going to play.
You know, it's not that big of an issue. It's going to come down to
how the game goes. Both of those quarterbacks will play though. But
right now, we'll play it by ear a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, USC quarterback Carson Palmer has his first
edge in experience, about to make his fourth college start. Palmer
is debuting in this rivalry and couldn't be giddier about facing
the Irish. He has relished talking about how Notre Dame asked him
to retake his Scholastic Assessment Test, and still had problems
admitting him into school after he complied with the request. That
has only added to his motivation for playing well today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for this game for a long time,'' Palmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish are also out to break their two-game losing streak to
USC, something the Trojans can relate to after being winless the
previous 13 contests.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a lot of bowl uncertainty for both teams. USC is
pitching for a bid to the Holiday Bowl and a probable meeting with
Nebraska with a victory. If the Trojans lose, it's probably on to
El Paso, where possible opponents include Virginia Tech, Syracuse
and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an outside chance the Trojans could go to the Aloha
Bowl to play either Air Force or Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go to Hawaii,'' Palmer said, unaware that it
carries the least prestige of the three options. ``Not a lot of
people (on the team) have gone to Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame (9-1) has loftier aspirations, but a victory is a
must today. The Irish are trying to land a spot in the Rose Bowl _
if UCLA makes the Fiesta Bowl _ which sends shudders throughout the
Pacific-10 Conference. Today might be the first time every other
school actually roots for the Trojans to eliminate the chance that
Arizona will be overlooked in favor of the Irish. With a loss,
Notre Dame is expected to slide down to the Gator Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, when USC and Notre Dame play, there's always a bit
of a bowl atmosphere. The game will be televised nationally by ABC
and a crowd of about 90,000 is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people will watch this game than the UCLA game,'' Hackett
said. ``We've got to meet the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: USC legends Marv Goux and Lynn Swann spoke to the Trojans
on Friday. Goux, a former player and coach, is famous for his fiery
speeches regarding the Notre Dame game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
