 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
cut short a trip abroad Friday to reconsider the Israeli army's
long occupation of southern Lebanon after the deaths of several
Israeli soldiers there in the last week and a half. By Deborah
Sontag. (With photos and map.)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-INDULGENCE (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II announced Friday that
throughout the millennium celebration, penitents who do a
charitable deed or give up cigarettes or alcohol for a day can earn
an indulgence that will eliminate time in purgatory. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-OUTLOOK (Brussels) _ A U.S.-led attempt to set down what
NATO has become since the Cold War ended and to define its goals
for the next century is encountering European opposition on a
number of issues, threatening to undermine a 50th-anniversary NATO
summit meeting in Washington next year. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-AFRICA (Paris) _ As 34 African chiefs of state began a
French-African summit meeting here on Friday, prosecutors turned
down requests by two French human rights groups to begin criminal
proceedings against President Laurent Kabila of Congo on torture
charges. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Sticking to Britain's official hands-off
policy in the Augusto Pinochet case, Prime Minister Tony Blair said
Friday that he did not even expect to be consulted about it, and
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook assured his Chilean counterpart that
any decisions would be made free of political considerations. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MIDEAST (Washington) _ President Clinton will travel to
Gaza next month to address Palestinian leaders, the White House
said Friday. He is to speak at what the Palestinians are describing
as a historic meeting to formally revoke anti-Israel clauses in the
1964 Palestinian charter. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-OIL (Istanbul) _ An Azerbaijani group decided to delay
the development of an offshore oil field in the Caspian Sea and to
possibly delay a decision on a pipeline for the field. By Stephen
Kinzer. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-REPORTER-SLAIN (Dublin) _ A man was convicted and
sentenced to life in prison in the killing of Veronica Guerin, the
top Irish crime reporter. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YULE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ Not long ago, the day after
Thanksgiving was a time when American shoppers raced to the stores
to beat each other out of a few key items, paying full price and
never expecting a bargain. But in this decade holiday shopping has
been transformed into a giant national hunt for deals, with
retailers forced to play along. By Jennifer Steinhauer. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ESCAPE (Houston) _ For the first time since the Dust Bowl
days, when fedora-topped G-men battled backroads bandits like
Bonnie &AMP; Clyde, an inmate has succeeded in escaping from Texas'
Death Row using a daring, low-tech scheme involving dummies and a
desperate sprint through a hail of bullets. By Rick Lyman. (With
map.)
</P>
<P>
   NGO-POLICY (Undated) _ Once history's stage was peopled with
kings and princes. Now it seems that almost anyone with letterhead
stationary and a tax identification number can crowd on as well.
Nongovernmental organizations are increasingly playing roles once
considered the preserve of governments, from drafting peace
treaties to waging war. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-4-PRESIDENT (Montclair, N.J.) _ Although Bill Bradley
has said that he will decide in December whether to run for
president, several of his former longtime aides and close advisers
said they believe that he has already made up his mind to seek the
Democratic nomination. By Jennifer Preston.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-LAWSUIT _ As many as half the handguns used in crimes had
been purchased from federally licensed dealers within the previous
three years, passing far more quickly from manufacturer to dealer
to criminal than previously believed, according to new federal
law-enforcement data that are expected to play a major role in
lawsuits against the handgun industry. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) Last Sunday, ``60 Minutes'' broadcast
a step-by-step, close-up videotape of a killing and gave the
killer, Dr. Jack Kevorkian, a national platform to explain his act
as a humane deed rather than a crime. That broadcast ignited a new
round of debate about the ethics of euthanasia, the ethics of the
news media and the intersection of the two. By Peter Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ President Clinton insisted once
again Friday that he had not lied under oath about his affair with
Monica Lewinsky, in terse, formal responses to 81 questions
submitted by the House Judiciary Committee. But he reiterated that
he had misled his family, his aides and the nation about the
relationship. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-DRUGS (Washington) _ The Food and Drug Administration
on Friday issued final rules that require drug companies to conduct
much wider testing of drugs in children, so the companies can write
labels that provide more detailed information to doctors and
parents about the proper use of medications by children. The rules
were a priority for the Clinton administration but met strenuous
objections from drug companies. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-DIRECTOR (Washington) _ Kenneth Prewitt, the new director
of the Census Bureau, certainly talks like an intellectual. He has
the lifestyle of an intellectual, living in New York's SoHo section
with his wife, Susan Vogel, a collector of African art. But
Prewitt, who was confirmed last month on the day the Senate broke
for recess, has sought to put the partisan denizens of Washington's
political world on notice that he is not some pointy-headed
milquetoast from academia that they can push around. By Steven A.
Holmes. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Exxon and Mobil, the nation's two
largest oil companies, confirmed Friday that they were discussing a
possible merger, and antitrust lawyers, industry analysts and
government officials predicted that any deal would require the sale
of important large pieces of such a new corporate behemoth. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-MOBIL (Undated) _ The boards of Exxon Corp. and Mobil
Corp. are expected to meet Tuesday to consider a possible merger
agreement that would form the world's largest oil company, a source
close to the negotiations said Friday. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong's economy shrank at a 7
percent annual rate in the third quarter, its biggest contraction
ever, because of plunging consumer spending and exports and capital
flight triggered by the Asian currency crisis. Still, some
economists think the Hong Kong economy has finally bottomed out. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   VIAG-ALGROUP (Rome) _ Viag, the German utility, bought Algroup
of Switzerland in a stock swap valued at $8.7 billion, creating a
company with interests in energy, aluminum, chemicals, packaging
and telecommunications. It is the biggest foreign takeover of a
Swiss company, but whether the creation of the conglomerate makes
sense is being questioned by some.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ I confess to having a problem with
holidays. The problem began early, when The Saturday Evening Post
was still around and favored Norman Rockwell paintings of smiling,
freshly scrubbed families sitting around the table. These pictures
were so alien to my childhood experience that I at first mistook
them for satirical cartoons. By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-MOVIES (New York) _ The holiday bonanza of kiddie movies
_ which this year includes Babe, The Rugrats Movie and A Bug's Life
_ has become an annual post-Thanksgiving ritual and has parents
scheduling a hectic weekend of moviegoing. Talking to parents who
are sprinting from one movie to the next. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   MILLER-OPERA (New York) _ Profile of Jonathan Miller, director,
writer, actor, filmmaker, photographer, professor, doctor. He is
currently directing the Metropolitan Opera's production of Mozart's
``Le Nozze di Figaro.'' By Sarah Boxer. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   MOORE-BOOKS (Madison, Wis.) _ Profile of the writer Lorrie
Moore, whose most recent work is ``Birds of America.'' By Bruce
Weber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBC-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Miami college football team, which is starting to revive some of
its ornery and cocky style of play. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-HARTFORD (Hartford, Conn.) _ Connecticut
legislators look at the fine print on the stadium deal for the New
England Patriots. There are some vocal critics, but leaders still
think the benefits outweigh the giveaways. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-AGGIES-LONGHORNS (Austin, Texas) _ The best of the
post-Thanksgiving Day games will be played just behind Texas' state
capitol in Austin. Texas A&AMP;M (10-1), ranked sixth by the Associated
Press and fifth by the Times computer will face Texas (7-3). The
traditional rivalry takes on greater implications with the Big 12
conference standings and the Bowl Championship Series rankings at
stake. By Timothy Smith.
</P>
