<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2745 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-KITNA-SP     11-28 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-KITNA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITNA GOES FROM PARTIER TO STARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Promising quarterback. Devoted husband. Loving
father of two. Family man. Devout Christian.
</P>
<P>
   To the labels that Jon Kitna wears so well and with such pride,
add a new one. Not starting quarterback, although Kitna will be in
the Seahawks' game against the Tennessee Oilers Sunday at the
Kingdome, replacing the benched Warren Moon.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is a story about the side of Jon Kitna most people
don't know _ the person he no longer is, but is stronger for having
been.
</P>
<P>
   Drunken lout.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Kitna now, at 26 and seemingly in such control of his
life and destiny, it is hard to imagine he behaved that way. But
that was Kitna during his early years at Central Washington
University.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of college students drink, but Kitna was out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drinking a lot _ to the point of blackout,'' he said
this week while standing in front of his cubicle in the Seahawks'
locker room. ``There were times when I would drink and drive and
not know or remember how I got home.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna also went through the embarrassing ordeal of being
arrested for petty theft on campus.
</P>
<P>
   But his life spiraled to its lowest point one night in October
1993, when his girlfriend, and now wife, Jennifer, caught him with
another woman.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the pain he caused Jennifer was the event needed to make
Kitna step back and take a serious look at where he wanted to go,
as opposed to where he was headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the outside everything looked good,'' he said. ``I was the
starting quarterback. I had a good girlfriend. But on the inside
there was something missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that night, when Jennifer caught me with another girl,
that all this stuff came to a head,'' he said. ``It was like, `Man,
I need to make a decision. Either I'm going to continue to go down
this road, which is going nowhere, or I need to change my life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna's first call was not to his parents, Fay and Martin. Or
even Jennifer. He called former CWU wide receiver Eric Boles, who
was then with the New York Jets but had been what Kitna calls ``my
mentor'' during his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   Why Boles? ``Eric had made the same change about a year
earlier,'' Kitna said. ``So I called him and said, `How do I make
that change?'''
</P>
<P>
   Boles had dedicated himself to Christ, and told Kitna he would
have to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took me through the sinners' prayer, and immediately I felt
the guilt lift off of me,'' Kitna said. ``I wasn't changed right
away. But from that point forward, it's when everything started
changing. I stopped cussing overnight and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was raised in a church-going family and went to a private
Lutheran school in Tacoma until he was in the fourth grade. He had
tried to alter the course of his life on his own, but it didn't
work until he got serious and Boles got involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things started changing and it's been one blessing after
another,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he and Jennifer were married. They had their first
child, Jordan, last year and a second, Jada, last week. On the
field, Kitna led the Wildcats to a share of the NAIA national
championship in 1995; signed with the Seahawks as a free agent in
1996 after no other team even gave him a sniff; quarterbacked
Barcelona to a World League championship in 1997; and now, he is
not just the starting quarterback, but one of the most popular and
likable players on the team.
</P>
<P>
   With the center stage comes a platform. And Kitna plans to use
it. That's why he didn't mind opening his personal closet this week
and dragging out a few skeletons from his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If talking about what I've been through can help another kid
who's going through the same thing, that's why God put me in this
position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna also realizes talking about God and being saved is a quick
way to turn people off. That's why he doesn't bludgeon them with
his beliefs, choosing instead to select his spots and help those
who ask for it. Much like Boles did with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't want to know, they're not going to listen,''
Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   And Kitna has a message worth listening to. During his
wild-and-crazy days, he wasn't just hurting himself, but also those
he loved. And not just Jennifer. There where his parents and his
younger brother, Matt.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of college kids do the kinds of things I was doing,''
Kitna said. ``But I just took it too far. The stealing. The
drinking. When you don't know how you get home at night, that's
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   With his parents in Tacoma and Kitna raising hell in Ellensburg,
it took a while for his father and mother to realize just how far
their son had veered off the path.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was his age, I did basically some of the same things he
did,'' Martin Kitna said. ``So I didn't think it was that
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Fay Kitna did, especially when her son would come home for the
weekend only to stay out all night partying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when my mom told me, `If you're going to come
home and not stay at the house, then don't come home at all,'''
Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the breaking point, Fay Kitna said. ``It just wasn't
productive. A lot of kids that age do those things. But Jon wasn't
getting anywhere doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the entire family has survived Kitna's self-destructive
binge, his father says, ``He's a helluva lot stronger than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   And his life is in order. He considers himself a man of God
first, then a husband, a father, a family man and a preacher of the
word of God. After that comes football player.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna has a passion for the game, and loves playing it. But, he
offers, ``My life isn't good because I'm a football player. I'm a
football player because my life is good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
