<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-REIGN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REIGN BEATS SAN JOSE IN DOUBLE OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Pro basketball returned to KeyArena Friday night. Even
though Frank Brickowski showed up, the Sonics weren't in the house.
</P>
<P>
   But the Seattle Reign was, along with 7,358 spectators, who
formed the largest crowd to ever watch an American Basketball
League game here.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately capping the festive evening, the Reign remained
unbeaten in six games with a 103-97 victory over San Jose in double
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Shalonda Enis scored seven of her 37 points in the second
overtime, and Val Whiting also figured prominently with six points
in the final three minutes, relentlessly hitting the boards and the
baskets. Whiting ended up with 24 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   After playing 49 of the game's 50 minutes, Enis was exhausted
but smiling afterward. Though the Reign has been winning, last
season's ABL rookie of the year did not feel like she was
contributing, entering the game with a 10.6 scoring average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling her it's the system,'' Reign point guard Niesa
Johnson said. ``If we're still winning, that means you are doing
your job.''
</P>
<P>
   But Enis was used to being a go-to player who scores 18 points a
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been kind of struggling emotionally,'' said Enis, who was
two points away from her career high. ``I really truly needed this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle did too. This was a perfect showcase for women's pro
basketball, two gifted teams battling for 2{ hours, the lead
changing hands all night long.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wanted it to end,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reign appeared ready to walk away with a 75-72 victory until
Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil zipped around a screen and hit a 3-pointer
to tie the game as the horn sounded, ending the fourth quarter
</P>
<P>
   The first overtime ended with another surprise. Trailing 88-87,
the Reign seemed to be finished when Davis-Wrightsil rebounded a
driving miss by Niesa Johnson. But Davis-Wrightsil called a timeout
and San Jose did not have any left.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in two free throws for Seattle's Kate Starbird,
who missed the first but made the second, forcing double overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The game had a lot to do with it, but there was an energized
atmosphere that Mercer Arena can't duplicate. The KeyArena sound
system is state-of-the-art. The lights are brighter. There is a
scoreboard with replay screens. It just seemed like a bigger deal
at a better venue.
</P>
<P>
   All of the fans watched from seats in the lower bowl, which
wasn't completely packed, just sufficiently jammed. No seats in the
upper concourse were sold.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of having everyone close to the court gave the feel
of a full arena and certainly sounded like one.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have 7,000 people in your ears, my head feels like it's
going to explode,'' Enis said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Center officials asked the Reign to play this game at
KeyArena, needing dates to help satisfy conditions for suite
holders. The NBA lockout has wiped out two months of Sonics' games,
including Friday night's that was scheduled here against the
Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle fans got Kate Paye instead of Gary Payton. The referees
called Angela Aycock for a carry on her dribble, which never would
have happened in an NBA game.
</P>
<P>
   But there were similarities to the men's game. San Jose's Kedra
Holland-Corn looked like Jason Kidd on one drive, softly dropping
in a bank shot while falling to the floor. Aycock and
Davis-Wrightsil exchanged a pair of 3-pointers from the corner, a
la Dale Ellis and Rex Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the same whining and stomping coach on the
visitors' bench. Friday night Angela Beck got a technical foul, not
Danny Ainge.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Reign fans enjoyed the evening at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a bigger arena, you have more presence in the media,'' said
season ticket holder Matria Ohora of Seattle. ``It's real important
for the women's professional game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why worry about the Sonics? Go to one ABL game and you will
see an incredibly good, fast-paced game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohora, though, was unhappy with her fourth-row seat. She
normally sits directly behind the visitor's bench.
</P>
<P>
   Vernell Pratt of Seattle prefers the intimacy of Mercer Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels more like my team, my basketball game,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But KeyArena was acceptable. ``We might as well use it for good
basketball since it's being wasted,'' Pratt said, referring to the
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday night's game you could sit 10 rows from the floor at
midcourt for $20. That's where Russ Nieboer and Julie Pickett were,
watching their first Reign game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to see one,'' Nieboer said, adding that he plans
to return.
</P>
<P>
   He was part of the seventh-largest turnout for women's
basketball in the city's history, topped by the 8,170 who attended
the University of Washington's game against DePaul in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be at KeyArena with so many people here was a great
experience,'' Reign coach Tammy Holder said. ``I hope they all come
back to see what heart and soul and desire this team has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
