<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2805 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     11-28 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kervokian Makes a Legal Point of Assisted Suicide  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man known as Dr. Death got what he wanted: a murder charge,
a legal showdown and perhaps another national debate on assisted
suicide and euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Kevorkian was accused in Pontiac, Mich., of several
charges _ murder, criminal assistance to a suicide and delivery of
a controlled substance _ after he gave a lethal injection to Thomas
Youk, 52, who had a fatal neurological condition. The videotaped
death was broadcast last Sunday on CBS' ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Michigan juries have refused to convict Kevorkian. With no
state laws setting out the hows and whys of assisted suicide, a
fifth jury will decide if killing a person who wants to die is
murder.
</P>
<P>
   If he is convicted, Kevorkian says he will die a martyr's death
by going on a hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Dedman
</P>
<P>
   Urge to Merge
</P>
<P>
   Side by side they seem to be the corporate odd couple of
cyberspace: America Online, a middle-brow service catering to
online newcomers, and Netscape Communications, the Internet
software pioneer founded by whiz-kid programmers. But America
Online purchased Netscape for roughly $4.2 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The worlds of media and technology, industry analysts say, will
meld together more and more in the future, so merging these two
companies may well make sense. In a side deal, America Online
announced a joint marketing and software development alliance with
Sun Microsystems to reassure Netscape's programmers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Lohr
</P>
<P>
   Low Point in Crime
</P>
<P>
   Prison building is hot. Politicians battle over who's toughest
on crime. Parole is a four-letter word. A response to some
horrifying crime wave? Not by a long shot. New FBI figures show
that serious crimes fell in 1997 for the sixth straight year,
including a 5 percent drop in the Northeast; the murder rate
reached a 30-year low.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hubert B. Herring
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous Play
</P>
<P>
   The government announced that nearly 10 million playpens had a
deadly hazard: protruding rivets that could snag the clothing of
young children.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 15 years, eight toddlers have strangled in their
playpens when their garments _ or pacifier strings _ were caught on
such rivets, the Consumer Product Safety Commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Six manufacturers have offered to provide consumers with repair
kits or with refunds, as an incentive for parents to destroy these
products, sold over the last four decades.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Pear
</P>
<P>
   Dropout U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   The United States no longer leads the world in the percentage of
students graduating from high school.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the 29-nation Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development shows that most industrialized nations have leapt
ahead of this country and many will probably soon overtake it in
college entry rates as well.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher pay as a percentage of national income is also lower and
teacher workload higher than in many other comparable countries,
the study found.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ethan Bronner
</P>
<P>
   Sex and the Admiral
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon continues to be dogged by sex-related scandals. In
the latest case, a one-star admiral at the Navy's headquarters in
the Pentagon faces charges of, among other things, steering
$150,000 worth of military contracts to a woman with whom he was
having an adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials, fearing another media furor over illicit sex,
emphasized that the accusations of adultery were not nearly as
important as those involving the abuse of taxpayer dollars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Lee Myers
</P>
<P>
   Managing Managed Care
</P>
<P>
   After failing to slow several years of rising medical costs,
health maintenance groups are pushing the costs on to the consumer.
Americans can expect to pay 8 percent to 20 percent more for
insurance premiums next year. The rise is the sharpest since the
early 1990s and reflects big increases in the prices of
prescription drugs, surgical devices and techniques and services to
patients outside hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Aquitted of Embezzlement
</P>
<P>
   After an 11-week trial and voluminous testimony about lives of
the rich and famous, a jury in Santa Monica, Calif., acquitted
Susan McDougal of all charges of embezzling $50,000 from the
conductor Zubin Mehta and his wife, Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors said prosecutors failed to make a credible case against
Ms. McDougal, the Mehtas' former bookkeeper and President Clinton's
onetime partner in the Whitewater deal. She still faces federal
criminal contempt of court charges in Arkansas for her refusal to
answer questions from the independent prosecutor Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   _ Todd S. Purdum
</P>
<P>
   A British First
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair became the first British prime minister to address
the Parliament of the Irish Republic, declaring an end to centuries
of hostilities between Ireland and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said the two countries must now work together to rescue
the stalled Northern Ireland peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much shared history,'' he said, ``so much shared pain. And
now the shared hope of a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the IRA's refusal to disarm, Blair said it was
``time for the gun and the threat of the gun to be taken out of
politics once and for all; for decommissioning to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon Weighing Cuts In Nuclear Arsenal
</P>
<P>
   With proposed reductions in nuclear warheads bogged down in
Russia's parliament, some Pentagon officials believe the time has
come for the United States to consider unilateral cuts in its
strategic arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: the Navy and the Air Force face the prospect of
paying billions of dollars to rebuild nuclear weapons that the
United States has already agreed to scrap as part of the second
strategic arms reduction treaty, or Start II, which Russia signed
in 1993 but has yet to ratify.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Lee Myers &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Europe Lifts Ban On British Beef  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The crisis that alerted the world to the dangers of ``mad cow
disease'' came to an end when the European Union declared British
beef safe and lifted its 32-month worldwide ban on its export.
</P>
<P>
   The ban had been imposed in March 1996 after evidence emerged of
a possible link between the disease, known formally as bovine
spongiform encephalopathy, and the fatal degenerative
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that affects humans.
</P>
<P>
   Exports are expected to resume in March.
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren Hoge &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Call in the Mall: Anybody Work Here?
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers this holiday season might find the going rough, not
because of a lack of merchandise but one of help
</P>
<P>
   Retail stores, especially those in suburbia, are struggling to
hire enough employees to operate the cash registers, stock the
shelves and stave off the hysteria of consumers looking for this
year's version of Elmo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The malls need valets, and they need sales assistants,'' said
Bruce Van Kleeck, the vice president of the National Retail
Federation, an industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staff is a major issue nationwide,'' he added. ``The suburban
areas don't have the labor pools.''
</P>
<P>
   Attack of the 2000 Bug
</P>
<P>
   Americans have already been warned about that little millennial
computer problem. Now, say federal and state officials, let the
real bad news begin. Benefit payments will most likely be delayed,
or services interrupted, for some people who receive welfare,
Medicaid, food stamps or other types of assistance; most states are
lagging in upgrading their computer programs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 1203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
