<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: computer programs.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many Lords A-Weeping
</P>
<P>
   The hereditary peers of the House of Lords got their eviction
notice from the queen herself while seated in their ermine-trimmed
scarlet robes.
</P>
<P>
   The setting was the pageant-filled State Opening of Parliament
in the ornate upper body during which the monarch reads a state of
the union speech written by the government outlining its
legislative program for the year. The most noted proposal this year
fulfills the pledge by Prime Minister Tony Blair to remove the
hereditary peers' right to sit and vote in the Lords.
</P>
<P>
   They are the dukes, earls, marquesses, viscounts and barons
whose titles, some dating from the Norman Conquest, are passed down
from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
   Once they are gone, the House will be made up of 512 life peers
and 26 Lords Spiritual from the church, also unelected but named to
the body by prime ministers for accomplishments seen as more
meritorious than just being born.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony itself, the grandest occasion in the British
ceremonial calendar short of a coronation or royal funeral, was
slimmed down this year by Buckingham Palace in the name of
modernizing the monarchy. The number of attendants to the queen was
reduced from 51 to 37, eliminating some of the most gorgeously
preposterous names in the realm. Gone were people like Portcullis
Pursuivant, Maltravers Herald Extraordinary and Silver Stick in
Waiting.
</P>
<P>
   For onlookers in the hall and on television, the reduction in
panoply was barely noticeable as gilded carriages rattled up to the
front gates of Parliament, and lavishly dressed courtiers carried
golden maces, silk purses and miniver-trimmed ceremonial caps in
the procession behind the queen and her 18-foot train.
</P>
<P>
   True, Silver Stick in Waiting was no longer there. But Gold
Stick in Waiting still was.
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren Hoge &QR;
</P>
<P>
   The French, Now Sniffing At Themselves
</P>
<P>
   This is a delicate topic. It should probably not even be
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, if the French want to talk about it, why not?
</P>
<P>
   The daily Le Figaro, you see, just published a survey about
French sanitary habits _ what amounts, basically, to an entire
nation counting its dirty linen in public.
</P>
<P>
   Not washing, mind you _ counting. The French have the
unfortunate reputation of not being the cleanest people in the
world. And now, for some reason that would no doubt be clear only
if explained in French, they have given chapter and verse for what,
in fact, seem to be less than meticulous habits.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling (if you really want to know): Only 47 percent bathe
daily, just 60 percent of Frenchmen change their underwear daily
(women, no doubt, indignantly refused to answer), and just 60
percent wash their hands after using the bathroom (Germans, by the
way, buy more than twice as much hand soap as the French).
</P>
<P>
   That last point prompted one television personality to suggest
that if you run into the boss outside the office restroom, it would
be best to head off any chance of a handshake by grabbing a sizable
file folder.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, one more thing: only half the French say they use deodorant.
But after all, France is the center of the perfume universe. Has
been for centuries. In the Middle Ages, crusaders returned bearing
the secrets of perfume, and France soon dominated the industry.
Shalimar, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   _ Hubert B. Herring
</P>
</TEXT>
