<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT PATHS FOR BRONCOS AND VIKINGS  
 DEAL REACHED OVER WOODSON'S REFUSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Different Paths for Broncos and Vikings
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos and Minnesota Vikings are dominating their
respective conferences to the point that few think they will not
play each other in the Super Bowl. If they do meet, the teams will
have taken drastically different mental approaches to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos coach Mike Shanahan does not shy from talk of an
undefeated season or winning another championship. In fact, he
embraces both.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are taking the opposite approach. ``We can't think
like the Broncos,'' said the Minnesota fullback Leroy Hoard,
``because they've been there. We haven't. They can take that
approach if they want, but we want to take it one team at a time.
That's not a sexy approach like the Broncos, but it has worked for
us so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Deal Reached Over Woodson's Refusal
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Baltimore Ravens defensive back Rod
Woodson, a future Hall of Famer, refused to take a random drug test
because he had been tested several days earlier and felt he was
being unfairly targeted. Under the league's policy, a refusal
counts as a positive test, and Woodson was placed in Stage 1 of the
league's program, which calls for evaluation, counseling and
increased testing.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson had planned to appeal that decision to commissioner Paul
Tagliabue, but one team executive said a compromise was reached by
Woodson, the league and the players association late this month.
Woodson would remain in Stage 1 for an unknown period, and since no
one believes Woodson has ever used drugs, the league assumes
Woodson would pass the assessment period and then be released from
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, in his 12th season and a member of the 75th anniversary
team, has never failed a drug test, team executives said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
