<SLUG> BC-TRASH-TRUCK-TROUBLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARBAGE TRUCK DRIVERS RACKING UP OVERTIME BUT PAYING THE PRICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The city's garbage truck drivers are really
cleaning up -- on overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond costing Los Angeles more than expected, city and union
officials warn that long hours behind the wheel of 12-ton trucks
are dangerous for the drivers and public alike.
</P>
<P>
   And some drivers agree -- even though 26 of them took home more
than $20,000 apiece in overtime last year and 508 of the city's 849
trash truck drivers earned more than $5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Jose Gallegos took home $20,000 in overtime last year, on
top of his $39,000 salary. But Gallegos said overwork led him to
pull a muscle in his back while maneuvering his heavy truck into
the hills of the suburban West Valley on narrow streets and dirt
roads.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old said he feels mentally and physically exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely hard,'' said Gallegos, who worked 14 hours of
overtime each week. ``Most of the guys love their work, but they're
clamoring for more help. They want some relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start the day at 5 in the morning and you don't go home
until after it's dark again, that's a lot of work,'' said Julie
Butcher, who heads the union representing drivers. ``It's
stressful. The longer they are out there each day, the more
potential there is for problems.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Rita Walters said more must be done, including
the hiring of more drivers, to reduce their overtime hours and head
off the potential of equipment mishaps or serious crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real problem for them to be driving those hours,''
Walters said. ``The concern is about people, their physical
well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   The long hours are caused by rubble from the Northridge
Earthquake and El Nino, a 25 percent cut in the work force over the
past four years, an aging fleet of trucks that break down too much,
and a volume of refuse that has increased apace with the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Accident rates rose during the early stages of the staff cuts,
from 525 in 1994 to 666 in 1995 and 591 in 1996. However, there
were only 457 accidents last year.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Sones, a deputy director for the bureau, said the drop last
year and so far this year is largely due to the higher experience
level of the remaining drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, new safety inspection rules were adopted in 1996
after a broken hydraulic mechanism from a trash truck slammed into
a school bus, killing two 8-year-old boys.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime claims began to rise dramatically four years ago when
the Sanitation Bureau reduced its refuse collection staff by 172
drivers. The city provides pickup for about 25 percent of the trash
in Los Angeles, including all single-family homes and many
apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, the annual cost of overtime increased from
$5.5 million in 1994-95, at a staffing level of 1,026 drivers, to
$7 million in 1997-98, at a staffing level of 849 drivers.
</P>
<P>
   While savings from staff cuts have outweighed additional
overtime expenses, council members directed Sanitation Bureau
Director Judith Wilson to take steps to reduce the hours racked up
by drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Sanitation officials said they expected staff cuts to save more
money than they have so far.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the bureau has already taken measures that have cut
overtime costs from last year to the first quarter of this year,
including separating each of the six sanitation yards as cost
centers that must justify expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bureau is strongly committed to minimizing the use of
overtime in its collection operations and has initiated many
actions to focus on improving and stabilizing operations with the
intent of lowering our overtime costs and staying within budgeted
funds for the current fiscal year,'' Wilson said in the report.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is also buying 57 new trucks this year to replace
some of the older vehicles that spend a lot of time in the shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equipment breakdown is a growing problem as the fleet of
automated trucks grow,'' the report said. ``Currently (there) is an
excess of 1,000 hours of equipment failure monthly, creating a need
for overtime use which will be significantly reduced with the
replacement of the 1990-to-1992 trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sones said he plans to hire 25 new drivers this year to fill
vacancies in the work force.
</P>
<P>
   Those measures have already produced results, with overtime
payments down in the first quarter of this year compared with last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many drivers are still working long hours, making $15,000
or more so far this year in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers union is pushing for some relief, including more
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point it's cheaper for the city to have drivers work
overtime than to hire new drivers, but there's got to be a
balance,'' Butcher said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
