NYT-11-28-98 1256EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2841 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-AFFIRM-ACTION-2N     11-28 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-AFFIRM-ACTION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: desegregation plan. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lowell's admissions policy has been changed to create one cutoff
for all applicants, but for 20 percent of the class it takes into
account other factors like socioeconomic status and personal
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of affirmative action say that recent court rulings
point inescapably to the conclusion that school systems that are
not under court order to desegregate may not use any racial
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am all for diversity, but when a school says, `You're white
so you can't come; you're African-American so you can,' that's
illegal discrimination and it's wrong,'' said Steven Levine, the
lawyer-father challenging the Arlington policy.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights advocates, however, say the legal lines are nowhere
nearly so settled, and argue that because integration remains an
important and unfilled goal of public policy, schools should have
some discretion about how to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the law is clear yet,'' said Gary Orfield, who
heads the Harvard Project on School Desegregation, which compiles
statistics on the proportion of American students in segregated
schools. ``The courts have not said that race cannot be considered
at all. And there is no question that schools still need to pay
attention to race. Our last report found that we are resegregating
at the fastest rate since the Brown decision, and I think that
trend is continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   At Boston Latin, there is mixed feeling about racial preferences
among students and teachers alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be able to get in based on how smart they are,
not the color of their skin,'' said David Sullivan, a white
sophomore. He said he could tell the difference between students
admitted purely on their scores and those helped by their race.
``The kids from the quotas are kind of not as smart, some of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That perception, says John Regan, an English teacher, is a
strong argument against racial preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the kids should be admitted on the basis of their
testing scores and their GPAs,'' Regan said. ``I think that's
what's fair. The kids know that that's what's fair. Some of the
kids who are most strong in the fact that it should be just from
the exam and from the GPAs are the black kids who are tired of
being pointed at and hearing, `Oh, yeah, you just got in on special
admissions,' and stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But most said they saw both sides of the argument.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Rodrigues, a black Boston Latin sophomore who came to the
United States from Cape Verde when she was 7, said she thought the
preferences were necessary. ``I would like it to be fair and
strictly on the test scores, but in the world that we live in not
everything is fair, and it's really a dream, I think, to expect
everybody to have the same opportunities to do as well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, the litigation has heightened student awareness
of racial preferences, in a negative way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any students even knew about the quota, so they
never judged each other,'' she said. ``Now they are aware of it,
and in some ways it brought down some people's sense of value of
how well they do. I don't believe that they gave me some slack on
the test. I'd rather not think about that because it would really
bring down my self-esteem and how I rate myself as a student.''
</P>
<P>
   At Boston Latin and other schools, there was also a widespread
feeling that the best way to encourage diversity would be by
improving the public schools, so that minority students from poor
neighborhoods would be as well prepared as more affluent whites.
</P>
<P>
   At Stuyvesant High School in Manhattan, Wesley Mathewson, a
white 15-year-old sophomore, attributed the minimal representation
of black and Hispanic students at his school to the inadequacy of
so many public elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not getting a good education in minority
neighborhoods, so the odds of passing the test are stacked against
them,'' he said. ``They have a disadvantage.'' Although he wishes
his school were more diverse, he said, racial preferences would not
be a good answer. ``You can't randomly admit blacks and Hispanics
without taking away from what the school prides itself on, a
tradition of excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Arlington Traditional School, where press clippings about
the court fight are posted near the front door next to photos of
the science fair, several parents said the real issue was finding
enough places in academically sound schools. They said the
litigation had been a hot issue at the school but not particularly
divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame the people for suing,'' said Elena Manville, a
white parent of a kindergarten student at the school. ``Everyone is
hoping to get their kid in here.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers challenging racial preferences say that is a
separate issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the schools stink, people should confront that problem,
rather than engage in racial bean-counting,'' said Daniel Girard,
the lawyer handling the challenge to the San Francisco
desegregation order, adding that schools will become more diverse
as the nation generally moves in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, say that schools should be able to take action
to increase diversity in their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is even more important than busing, which was always seen
as a remedy, based entirely on the legal issue that separate but
equal had to be changed,'' said August Steinhilber, a Maryland
lawyer who represents school boards. ``This goes to the next stage,
the educational issue _ that it's critical for youngsters to
understand that they live in a society that's racially and
ethnically mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But because of the court decisions, everyone's getting very
shy. School people say they feel like their hands are tied. We're
down to the last straw. If you can't do anything about student
assignment unless you're under court order, there's nothing left of
affirmative action at the elementary and secondary level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
