<SLUG> BC-CANADA-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ACTIONS AT PROTEST PLAGUE CANADA'S GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It started out as little more than a brief spot on the
nightly news, but the treatment of protesters at an international
conference in Vancouver last year has turned into a recurring
political nightmare for Prime Minister Jean Chretien and his
government.
</P>
<P>
   The latest casualty was Solicitor General Andy Scott, Canada's
top law enforcement official, who resigned last week after he was
overheard talking about an investigation into the protest with the
person sitting next to him on an Air Canada flight.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the opposition in the House of Commons contend that
Chretien and his closest aides had directed the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police to be aggressive in keeping protesters away from
former President Suharto of Indonesia during last year's
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When protesters refused to leave a roadway where Suharto was
expected to pass, the Mounties forced them out, dousing them with
irritating pepper spray. The episode was recorded by a news
cameraman, and was replayed on the nightly news, but not
prominently.
</P>
<P>
   Little happened until this fall, when reports appeared
suggesting that Chretien had tried to keep Suharto from being
embarrassed during the meeting and had ordered the Mounties to
control protesters aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   In the daily question periods in the House of Commons, Chretien
was repeatedly criticized. He tried to deflect some of the
criticism by joking that being hit with pepper spray was better
than being hit with a baseball bat. Few people laughed.
</P>
<P>
   A special panel was established to look into the actions of the
prime minister and police. The inquiry panel revealed electronic
messages between the protesters and Terry Milewski, one of the
reporters who covered the story for the CBC _ which receives most
of its funding from the federal government. In the exchanges,
Milewski tries to gain the protesters' confidence by appearing to
be sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien's office accused Milewski of bias and filed a complaint
with a news media ombudsman. The reporter was taken off the story,
and when he wrote about the incident for a local newspaper he was
temporarily suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry itself came to a halt when the government refused to
pay lawyers fees for the protesters. It was supposed to resume last
week, but a judge put it off indefinitely while charges of bias
against one of the three panel members are investigated.
</P>
<P>
   While the inquiry was running into trouble in Vancouver, an
opposition member of Parliament told reporters in Ottawa that he
was seated near the solicitor general on a flight when he overheard
him tell another passenger that police would probably have to take
the blame for what happened in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation suggested that Scott had prejudged it. The
solicitor general's casual handling of sensitive matters also
raised doubts about his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted by reporters, Scott denied everything. He said
he could not even remember the name of the person sitting next to
him.
</P>
<P>
   But the other passenger was identified as Frederick Toole, a
lawyer from Scott's home province of New Brunswick. Toole filed an
affidavit corroborating what the opposition member had said about
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Scott resigned a few days later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      11-28 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO: A WINNING CANDIDATE ASPIRES TO A NEW JOB  
 NORTH CAROLINA: LEAVING WASHINGTON, WEIGHING COMEBACK?  
 UTAH: MORE TURBULENCE FOR STORMY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.C., Utah)  (bl) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO: A WINNING CANDIDATE ASPIRES TO A NEW JOB
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Rush has been on the national stage, off and on, for the
better part of 30 years. And now he has his eye on a bigger role.
</P>
<P>
   He started out as a member of the Student Non-Violent
Coordinating Committee, a leading civil rights group in the 1960s,
then helped lead the radical Black Panther Party.
</P>
<P>
   From there _ after serving six months in prison for illegal
possession of firearms _ he gravitated to electoral politics,
becoming a Democratic alderman in Chicago in the early 1980s. A
decade later, his radical in-your-face days behind him, he won a
seat in Congress, representing the 1st District on Chicago's
heavily black South Side.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 3 he was re-elected to a fourth term in the House with
86.4 percent of the vote. But it turns out that despite such
applause, he aspires to a different stage and role.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 23 he served notice that the job he really covets, and
intends to go after, is held by Mayor Richard M. Daley, a fellow
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   He has his work cut out.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, son of Richard J. Daley, one of the city's storied mayors
and political bosses, has twice won the job in a breeze, and
political pros say that with his father's natural political knack
and his voter-approval rating now hanging around 80 percent, he is
very likely to win a third term in next spring's election if, as is
expected, he runs again.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, 52, also faces another high political hurdle. Chicago is
only 40 percent black. So his best hope is that like the city's
first and only black mayor, Harold Washington, he can hammer
together a winning coalition of dissident black and white voters _
if the pieces still exist and if he can match Washington's delicate
consensus-building skills.
</P>
<P>
   He contends he can, saying Daley has pandered to the city's
wealthy and neglected its poor, has allowed its transportation and
school systems to deteriorate and has turned a blind eye to police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soul of Chicago,'' he said in his announcement, ``is the
hundreds of thousands of African-Americans, Latinos, Greeks, Poles,
Italians, Irish, Asians and other Chicagoans who live, work and pay
taxes in the city _ yet they are ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who already has a campaign war chest of almost $2
million, countered through an aide that if he ran, he would run on
a record that ``is one of accomplishment that reaches into all
corners of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressman also has a record that will be on display,''
the aide noted pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA: LEAVING WASHINGTON, WEIGHING COMEBACK?
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., ran for re-election this
year, he sometimes seemed to be running more against President
Clinton, labor unions and the Rev. Jesse Jackson than against his
Democratic opponent, John Edwards. He lost in one of the most
galling defeats of all for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he prepares to leave Washington, Faircloth is focusing
on clearing up some $250,000 in unpaid campaign bills. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, his campaign manager, Chuck Fuller, sent out a
fund-raising letter in which he resumed the attack on Clinton,
unions and Jackson and said the senator ``desperately needs your
help to pay these bills as quickly as possible.'' Urging the
faithful to ``send a gift of $100, $250 or $500, or whatever you
can spare,'' Fuller said the senator had been done in by a
``left-wing establishment'' assault that was ``the most
comprehensive smear campaign that North Carolina has ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot give up on our senator's conservative message of
bringing common sense to Washington,'' he said. ``We've come too
far together to turn back now. Another statewide race is just
around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   Is that a fund-raising gimmick? Or is the senator, who is 70 and
wealthy enough to retire his $250,000 campaign debt on his own,
thinking about running for governor in 2000, when that job will be
open? Or how about another try for the Senate in 2002, when a
fellow Republican, Jesse Helms, will be up for re-election?
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth offers no elaboration. And Fuller will say only that
``the senator's giving a lot of consideration to it.''
</P>
<P>
   To what?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as far as I can take it for now,'' Fuller replied.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH: MORE TURBULENCE FOR STORMY CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Election Day, when Rep. Merrill Cook, R-Utah,
figured he was right on the edge of losing his bid for a second
term, his party began a get-out-the-vote campaign that made no
mention of him but instead promoted the re-election of Sen. Robert
Bennett, who was in no political danger.
</P>
<P>
   Cook took offense and, as party officials tell it, stormed into
party headquarters, twice, shouting obscenities about the party in
general and Bennett in particular. The officials sent word that he
was no longer welcome at headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Cook went on to win re-election by more than 10 points, and
three days later, party officials say, apologized for his outburst.
His exile was lifted, tension subsided and the party basked in the
glow of an Election Day that saw a huge Republican sweep in Utah,
not the least of the victories being the surprisingly strong one by
Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Cook was tired and stressed,'' his spokeswoman,
Marianne Funk, later explained when asked about the shouting
incidents. ``Those few moments were an exception. He and party
leaders have mended fences and moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tension is back and the fences are in need of repair
again.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Cook's aides, including his chief of staff, Janet
Jenson, and his district director in Salt Lake, Robert Jeppsen,
have left his staff since Election Day, and it is not entirely
clear why.
</P>
<P>
   Jeppsen says he was let go after Cook angrily confronted him
with an article from The Salt Lake Tribune that the congressman
thought gave too much credit to his staff for his re-election
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials say Ms. Jenson was also dismissed, but she has
said very little about her departure. But, according to The
Tribune, she sent the Cook staff an e-mail message that said:
``Merrill has taken up permanent residence in wackoland and we are
all in serious jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook says that Jeppsen was ousted for poor performance in the
campaign and that Ms. Jenson resigned to seek a better job.
</P>
<P>
   Jeppsen's response to that, in an interview with The Tribune:
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has a grenade in his mouth and he's going to pull the
pin.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook then had some words to say about The Tribune and John
Heilprin, a reporter who interviewed him. He said on a radio talk
show that Heilprin screamed at him in the phone interview and that
Heilprin ``was a little bit high on something, maybe beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Heilprin calls those accusations ``irresponsible'' and
``unfounded.'' The newspaper's editor, James Shelledy, defends
Heilprin's conduct as ``professional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These sort of wild accusations give credence to the most
recent indicators that Cook is having trouble grasping that he
won,'' Shelledy said in an article the paper published about the
talk show appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Funk, the congressman's spokeswoman, said of the appearance,
``He was not at his best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
