<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENT     11-28 1434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENTS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta taking lesson in noneducator-led school systems
 &HT;    By Rochelle Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jean Dodd says hiring a superintendent who is not an
educator is like going to a nurse instead of a specialist for
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt seriously if Wachovia were looking for a president
they would come looking for an educator,'' the Atlanta school board
member says.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Atlanta school board is open to the
possibility of hiring a noneducator to lead the school system,
someone who did not come through the traditional ranks of
administration in K-12 public schools.
</P>
<P>
   That evolution in thinking, while in its infancy in Georgia,
mirrors a national trend.
</P>
<P>
   Several large urban school districts have turned to military
people, college presidents, attorneys, and government officials as
they look for leaders to fix their ills. Among them are Chicago,
Seattle, Washington D.C., San Diego, Milwaukee and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more open to it it now than they ever have been,''
said Michael Casserly, executive director of the Washington
D.C-based Council of the Great City Schools.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly says that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Going outside education circles ``stretches you to thinking
about what it is you want in a leader,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nontraditional superintendents have had mixed success.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago school superintendent Paul Vallas, who is the city's
former budget director, has been embraced by the city, including
the powerful Chicago Teacher's Union.
</P>
<P>
   But Julius Becton, a war veteran and retired Army lieutenant
general, quit the Washington D.C. school system in April after 17
months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Both men say their lack of a traditional superintendent's
experience track record has not contributed to their successes or
failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a K-12 background to run something,'' said
Becton, who headed the Federal Emergency Management Agency and
Prairie View A&AMP;M University before leading the D.C. schools. Becton
said he quit because the system's financial control board insulted
him by questioning his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need is a proven manager, which is why you are seeing
more and more cities doing what Atlanta is doing,'' Becton said.
``I had a requested budget of $525 million. Not many high school
principals have that kind of budget or experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallas was appointed CEO of Chicago schools 3 1/2 years ago when
Mayor Richard Daley Jr. took over control of the school system.
</P>
<P>
   Before that he was the city's budget director; served as revenue
analyst for the Illinois Senate President's office; was a
university public finance instructor; and taught elementary school.
He also was a captain and senior instructor in the Illinois Army
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   That varied background, plus support from Daley, he said, have
contributed to his success. In his first seven months, he and his
leadership team secured $800 million in loans to build 13 new
schools and 40 annexes, and balanced the $3 billion budget. Also,
test scores have risen during his tenure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they'll just bring in a CEO to solve their
problems. That's not necessarily going to solve your problems,''
Vallas said.
</P>
<P>
   What has worked for him, he said, is these ingredients: ``You
understand the educational issues. You know the political terrain.
You know what constitutes a good policy and can figure out how to
pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Gallagher, spokeswoman for the Chicago Teacher's
Union, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me ... you don't need someone with three doctorate
degrees who is going to come in and be profoundly educational,''
Gallagher said. ``The superintendent needs to be someone who can
run the show. That's what Vallas has.''
</P>
<P>
   But Becton got off to a rough start. He angered many parents
when he closed 13 schools, five fewer than he wanted to close. He
replaced dozens of leaky roofs, but the repairs resulted in schools
opening three weeks behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   When he quit, he was replaced by his deputy superintendent, an
educator.
</P>
<P>
   Delabian Rice-Thurston, executive director of Parents United for
the D.C. Public Schools, said Becton's problem wasn't his lack of
experience in public school systems.
</P>
<P>
   Becton's downfall resulted from several issues, Rice-Thurston
said, ranging from his refusal to listen to parents to having no
support from Congress, which appointed Becton to run D.C. schools
after taking control of it from Mayor Marion Berry and the elected
school board. ``If you have a person who can ask the right
questions and get counsel when he needs it on matters of education,
you are all right,'' Rice-Thurston said. ``The person you put in
charge has got to be willing to find high quality people who know
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Fulton County Manager John Stanford left Atlanta to run
the 47,000-student Seattle school system in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of his first year, test scores were up across all
grade levels. Stanford required principals to undergo a yearlong
training program. He led local school districts in a bid to receive
more funding from the state legislature, and he was largely
responsible for securing the $2.2 million raised by a private
foundation that supports the school system.
</P>
<P>
   Some teachers felt Stanford placed too much emphasis on test
scores, which left many of them feeling they needed to ``teach to
the test'' to raise scores, according to an article in the Seattle
Times.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Schaad-Lamphere, president of the Seattle Board of
Education, is a huge fan of Stanford's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This job and John Stanford is a match made in heaven,'' she
said recently. ``We needed a guy to really spark us into new
thinking, new believing, a new level of performance. Actually, what
we got was more like a blowtorch. It's been an unbelievable
privilege to work with him.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of private individuals offered Stanford a $500,000
performance bonus to stay in Seattle through 2001-2002. He
declined.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's turnaround of the schools has turned into a fight for
his life. In March, he was diagnosed with leukemia and an acting
superintendent _ who also has a nontraditional background _ has
taken his place. Stanford is on medical leave from the system.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Georgia's only example of a nontraditional
superintendent is David Crews, who served for a few months in
Gwinnett County, acccording to Bill Barr, head of the Georgia
School Superintendents Association. Crews was Gwinnett's associate
superintendent overseeing school finance when he was appointed
interim superintendent in late 1994 after Superintendent George
Thompson resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's superintendent search committee and school board
members agree they want an innovative leader like Vallas or
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am willing to consider any individual that I think can help
Atlanta Public Schools meet the challenges that we face,'' Atlanta
school board member Mike Holiman said. ``I guess that means I'm
open to a noneducator.''
</P>
<P>
   But board member Dodd isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Educators ``are getting so much negative press from people,''
said Dodd, a retired Atlanta school teacher and member of the
superintendent search committee. ``If we as educators can't do it,
then how can (noneducators) do it?'' The search committee, which
includes some of the city's heavy-hitters in the business
community, meets Dec. 3. to consider the top candidates drawn up by
executive search firm LAI Ward Howell. The new superintendent will
replace Benjamin O. Canada, who left Atlanta in July to become
superintendent of the Portland, Ore., school district. The search
firm's Charles Taylor has looked for people who work with large
budgets, have overseen large organizations, and have a demonstrated
compassion for children.
</P>
<P>
   Finding someone outside of the education field with the skills
to make a good superintendent has not been easy, said Taylor, who
would not name the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things it takes to do this job you are more likely to find
in people who have done this (education) business,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, ``The candidate pool is not what people think it
is,'' Casserly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were in the private sector and you were good ... you
are going to have to take a pay cut, you are going to have to work
longer hours, you are going to get no thanks for this and you are
going to have to do it all in the public,'' he said. ``It's not a
leap that most in the private sector are eager to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
