<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USA-FINANCIAL-NETWORK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge orders USA Financial Network to stop selling securities
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A federal judge has ordered Dayton-based USA
Financial Network Inc. and affiliated companies to stop selling
securities and insurance while an independent consultant reviews
the companies' operations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter H. Rice of Dayton issued the
preliminary injunction recently at the request of the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Rice also approved the motion to appoint a mutually agreed upon
consultant, who will report on the ``continued viability'' of USA
Financial and associated companies within 30 days of appointment.
The report will likely be filed with the court sometime in January,
according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the SEC filed a lawsuit against USA Financial and
its operators, Craig A. Herl and Mark May, alleging the firm sold
$3.6 million in unsecured notes to unsophisticated investors in a
``typical Ponzi scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Also named as defendants were five other companies: S-Corp.,
Financial Inc., Bancorp Mortgage Inc., Biltmore Development Corp.
and Network Financial Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit followed a one-year SEC investigation. Herl said
last month the lawsuit is ``totally without merit and ridiculous.''
Herl said the companies operate legitimate construction businesses
building homes in the Eaton area and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The civil action alleges that over the past four years, 33
investors _ mostly middle-income families in the Dayton area _ were
fraudulently sold promissory notes through companies with little or
no net worth. The alleged scheme involved using funds from new
investors to make payments to past investors.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the court froze the assets of May, 38, a Xenia
resident, and Herl, 37, of West Milton. Also frozen were the assets
of their companies plus those of May's wife, Cynthia, and USA
Trust. The lawsuit claims that from 1996 to 1998, about $292,500
was paid to Cynthia May as profit distributions although the
corporations never earned a profit.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling, the court prohibited the companies from
transferring any funds or assets to the Mays or Herl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
