<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILD-PIGS29-COX     11-28 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-PIGS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wild hogs the state's new scourge
 &HT;    By Willie Howard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Wild hogs are rooting up Florida,
scarring the land, spreading nuisance plants, carrying disease and
creating headaches for managers of parks and preserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at a wild hog the same way we look at melaleuca
trees,'' said Robert Dye, manager of Myakka River State Park, where
a trapper removes 800 pigs annually just to control the population.
``One pig is too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Although pigs are pests to land managers such as Dye, hunters
love them. Some hunters want to extend the season for hunting pigs
on public land. At the same time, animal rights advocates want the
state to crack down on what they say is inhumane treatment of pigs
removed by trappers from state parks and preserves, where hunting
is not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe hog populations are on the increase,'' said Nick
Wiley, chief of wildlife management for the Florida Game and Fresh
Water Fish Commission. ``Hunting with liberal seasons and bag
limits is effective at holding them at manageable levels. But
eradication takes trapping.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigs are not native to Florida. They were introduced by Hernando
DeSoto when he landed near Tampa Bay in 1539. And they have few
remaining natural enemies, such as the panther, to control their
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Wild pigs are the same animal, Sus scrofa, as domesticated pigs.
They're typically black, dark brown or dark red and weigh 100 to
400 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The state's feral pig population has been estimated at 400,000,
though some wildlife experts believe the state harbors as many as 1
million free-roaming swine. Sows reproduce twice a year and deliver
an average of six piglets each time. The piglets, in turn, reach
sexual maturity in six months.
</P>
<P>
   Pigs eat roots, acorns, palmetto berries, worms and snakes,
gobbling up food eaten by native animals such as white-tailed deer
and wild turkeys. They also eat the eggs of native animals,
including those of snakes, ground-nesting birds, alligators and sea
turtles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pig is a pig is a pig, and you'd better believe they eat a
lot of anything,'' said Kim Delozier, a wildlife biologist at Great
Smokey Mountains National Park in Tennessee, where 300 pigs are
removed from the land annually to minimize their effect on plants
and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   At Cape Canaveral and the nearby Merritt Island National
Wildlife Refuge, trappers remove more than 2,000 wild pigs
annually. Using dogs and traps, they took 3,384 pigs from the
refuge last year. The Space Coast pigs have eaten sea turtle eggs;
NASA employees have hit them with their cars on the way to work.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling the pig population is considered especially
important near the Kennedy Space Center because pigs can dig under
the fence that protects the space shuttle runway, though pigs have
never interfered with a shuttle landing.
</P>
<P>
   Wild pigs also contribute to the spread of noxious plants such
as the tropical soda apple. They eat the soda apple's acrid fruit,
then plant the seeds when they defecate in areas they've rooted.
</P>
<P>
   Because wild pigs can carry brucellosis, a blood-borne disease
that causes a recurrent fever, sweating and joint pain, hunters
must wear plastic gloves when cleaning them. Trapped wild pigs must
be separated from domestic pigs to prevent the spread of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Feral pigs can be hard to spot in palmetto thickets, especially
in hot months when they stay in low-lying swamps and thick
underbrush. But their calling cards are unmistakable: deep furrows
created by rooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want them rooting up native vegetation,'' said Bert
Trammel, manager of the Dupuis Reserve in northern Palm Beach and
southern Martin counties, where hog-tilled turf looks like the work
of a tractor.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters killed 199 wild pigs last year at Dupuis Reserve. But
hunting is not allowed at state parks, where trappers capture the
pigs in cages baited with rotting corn or nab them with
pig-tracking dogs that grab them by the ears.
</P>
<P>
   Dog hunting and trapping have drawn fire from animal rights
groups. The Animal Rights Foundation of Florida wrote a letter to
Gov. Lawton Chiles, urging him to ensure that hogs do not suffer
when trapped in pens or captured by tracking dogs. The foundation
asked the game commission to develop guidelines to ensure that
hunters and trappers cause feral pigs no needless suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``These animals are not here of their own volition,'' ARFF
director Joe Taksel wrote in a June 29 letter to Chiles. ``The
state has no right to cause them needless suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiles has asked state land managers to review their
hog-trapping policies to ensure the pigs are captured and
transported in a humane manner. But he noted that hog trapping must
continue as a management tool on public land.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Bryan, park management specialist with the state Department
of Environmental Protection, said pigs must be removed to keep them
in check at state parks. ``If we did nothing, the places would be
overrun,'' Bryan said. ``Every one you take off, there's going to
be less damage to the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Palm Beach County's natural areas, purchased with money
from a $100 million, voter-approved bond issue, harbor wild pigs.
``We do realize they're a problem we're going to have to deal
with,'' said Frank Griffiths, who manages the natural areas for the
county.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffiths does not consider the pigs a physical threat to
visitors unless they're cornered or harassed. ``Their natural
instinct is to run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although park managers loathe Florida's wild pigs, hunters love
them. They're plentiful, cagey and tasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to see them in the woods,'' said Robert Stossel Jr., a
West Palm Beach hunter and director of the Florida Wildlife
Federation. ``They've been here 500 years. I think they've got a
right to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter Keith Jones of Lake Worth wants the game commission to
consider expanding the season for hog hunting to include some
summer hunts on wildlife management areas and reserves.
</P>
<P>
   On private land, pigs can be removed at any time of year
regardless of their size and are considered the livestock of the
landowner.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Fulford, owner of a 6,500-acre ranch in western Okeechobee
County, takes about 100 pigs a year from his land. Hunting pigs
provides food and allows Fulford to manage the pig population on
his ranch.
</P>
<P>
   When pigs root up his cattle-grazing pastures, Fulford said, the
damage can last 10 years. ``They can literally root up the world,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent dog hunt for pigs near Fulford's ranch with hunting
guide Ernie Goolsby and fellow dog hunter David Bruner, the hunters
let their dogs roam the land and followed them in four-wheel-drive
pickups.
</P>
<P>
   As they worked the dogs downwind of the oak hammocks where they
expected to find pigs feeding on fallen acorns, the dogs paused
from time to time to sniff the wind for the scent of swine.
</P>
<P>
   As they neared a small drainage canal, the dogs took off running
and started barking. Bruner and fellow hunter David Godfrey
followed the dogs across the canal, where they had cornered a small
pig. They rolled the pig on its back and killed it with a pocket
knife.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, a multicolored pig came running across the
canal and Goolsby turned loose his catch dog, Blue, which ran out
of sight chasing the pig. Goolsby followed them in his bucking
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   When he caught up with Blue, the dog had lost the multicolored
pig and captured a young black boar by the ear. Goolsby, a veteran
rancher and cowboy, held the small boar down with his foot and
neutered it. The neutered boar will grow fatter than a nonneutered
one, Goolsby said, and it won't continue to sire piglets.
</P>
<P>
   Pig hunting with dogs has been a tradition on Florida ranches
for decades. Goolsby, 35, learned to capture hogs with dogs at age
15. Friends and relatives often gather on the Fulford ranch for
weekend hunts, which sometimes last late into the night and include
the children.
</P>
<P>
   Cur hounds used to track and hold wild pigs are often working
ranch dogs used to herd cattle. Pig hunting imposes risks on the
dogs because big boars have tusks that can wound or kill a dog. But
cur dogs aren't the least bit intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bred into them to be aggressive for that kind of
hunting,'' said Claude Thomas of the National Cur and Feist
Breeders Association. ``They're extremely strong dogs that could go
all night for a month in a row if they needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunters, too, can be gouged by a tusky boar that has been
captured by dogs. Goolsby has a few scars on his hands. Bruner said
he has never been cut after 25 years of hog hunting, but he has
friends who have gotten stitches.
</P>
<P>
   As with the dogs, the risk of going mano a mano with a wild boar
doesn't deter those who love dog hunts for pigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real adrenaline rush,'' Bruner said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
