A2884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTISMOKING-POSTER29-     11-28 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTISMOKING-POSTER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poster captures son's, health council's anti-smoking plea
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Twelve-year-old Kevin Hickman has been after his
mom for months to quit smoking, ever since he learned in his
classes at Allen Classical Academy in Dayton about the dangers of
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Karen Hall, has promised she'll try to kick her
25-year-old habit. But if she doesn't, she'll soon have looming
reminders of her son's wish: 10-foot-high billboards of a poster
Kevin designed for a local anti-smoking campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The poster shows a teen-age girl visiting the grave site of her
mother and crying, ``Mom, I miss you.'' Behind the girl, a talking
cigarette sneers, ``Do you want to die, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin submitted the winning poster among 114 entries from
second- through sixth-graders at Allen, where teachers were
approached by the Miami Valley Health Improvement Council for a
child's drawing to be featured in a monthlong billboard campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about quitting for a long time, but now I
should at least try,'' said Hall, a 40-year-old Dayton resident and
mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   The billboards will go up in late December at six locations in
Montgomery, Clark and Miami counties, including a site near the
Nutter Center. The advertising tab will be picked up by a $25,000
grant from the Physicians Charitable Foundation of the Miami
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the health improvement council thought a child's
poster would be more effective than one more slick message from an
advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin's art teacher at Allen, Martha Stegeman, agreed. ``There
is something about the innocence and honesty of a child that is so
poignant,'' she said. ``You don't walk away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Freeman, an education consultant for the health improvement
council, said she was surprised at how many of the student entries
were personal pleas for parents and grandparents to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this will help,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin said he decided to make a teen-ager the focus of his
poster after reading an article about the growing number of
American teens who are taking up the smoking habit.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley is no exception. Nearly one-fourth (23 percent)
of Dayton-area 12th-graders smoke cigarettes on a daily basis, and
nearly 15 percent smoke a half pack or more per day, according to
the latest Dayton Area Drug Survey, a collaborative effort among
Wright State University, United Health Services and Dayton-area
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kevin, he's already decided tobacco is not for him. ``I
want to run track and stuff when I'm older, but I can't do that if
I smoke,'' he said. ``I'd be all out of breath.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 1407EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
