<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-FILMWORKS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin FilmWorks students learn by doing a full-length feature
film, `In Flagrante'
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jeanne Claire van Ryzin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Lights, camera, action.'' Not exactly three
inexpensive words for a beginning filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   When ``In Flagrante,'' a black-and-white comedy, premiered at
the Dobie Theatre on Thursday, its credits listed 14 producers. A
little outside the film industry norm to be sure, but that's
because ``In Flagrante'' was the first feature film to be made by a
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any place else that offers students an
opportunity to make a full-length feature film,'' said Stephen
Mims, filmmaker and founder of Austin FilmWorks, which offers
college-level filmmaking courses to the general public. Since
starting Austin FilmWorks in 1993, Mims has offered two
semester-long courses that emphasize a hands-on approach to the
basics of film and video production.
</P>
<P>
   But after students completed the two classes, Mims said, they
were still looking for more learning opportunities. ``People would
ask us what they're supposed to do next,'' he said. That prompted
the creation of a third production course, a 12-month class during
which the students would produce their own feature film.
</P>
<P>
   The class began in January. David Layton, 32, a local filmmaker
and former student of Mims', co-taught the course. Students paid
$1,050 for the class and shared the responsibility of either
raising or contributing an equal share of the film's total budget.
Class members estimate that the ``In Flagrante'' budget was between
$9,000 and $10,000, a budget that could easily have been two to
three times more had not Austin FilmWorks provided the equipment
and editing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of first feature films are very, very expensive learning
experiences,'' said Mims, 39, who received his master's degree in
film at the University of Texas and later taught film production
there for four years. ``This is a way to do it for a fraction of
the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, Mims and Layton set some hard and fast
criteria for the project and demanded that students be committed to
it. At the first class, Mims showed students a clip from ``Red
River'' in which John Wayne's character tells his cowboys that if
they want out of the cattle drive, that's fine, but if they leave
they'll be shot. The scare tactic worked. Of the 15 students who
registered for the class (all of whom had taken previous Austin
FilmWorks classes), only one left, and he did so to attend New York
University's prestigious screenwriting program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically presented them with a structure that could not be
surrendered,'' Layton said. At the same time, Mims and Layton left
the class on its own to solve problems. ``We really let the class
sort themselves out,'' Mims said.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not a school, and therefore doesn't offer any
academic credit, Austin FilmWorks nevertheless seems to have found
its niche among degree-seeking film students, many of whom find the
few spaces in university production courses out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process to get into production classes at UT is
ridiculous,'' said Robert Robinson, 26, a part-time film major at
UT. ``This is a great alternative. It's a novel way to make an
independent film.'' Robinson worked as ``In Flagrante's'' co-editor
and boom operator. Part of the project's appeal, he said, was its
demands. ``At least I knew that this film would be finished.''
</P>
<P>
   When designing the course, Mims and Layton decided that the
script had to be generated, and voted on, by the students. Thomas
R. Chamberlain authored the winning script. ``In Flagrante'' tells
the story of new homeowners, Mia and Colin, who quickly learn they
live next door to the neighborhood eccentrics, three adult
siblings, the Dalrymples, whose inheritance and quirky behavior has
the neighborhood buzzing with rumors of their murderous family
history.
</P>
<P>
   The movie features a cast of local actors. Filming took place
during six weeks of stifling heat in July and August in an empty
fraternity house without air conditioning. ``It really went
remarkably well considering how miserable (the weather) was,''
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the eclectic group of students (among others, a lawyer,
an Apple Computer employee and a single mother of three) had to fit
the busy production schedule around full-time careers and full-time
lives. Kathy Farry, 26, who works at Motorola, said her employer
was very supportive of her while she took on the role as the film's
second assistant camera operator. ``I took vacation time and
changed my shifts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its success, Mims plans to offer the course again in
January. And what will this new crop of potential Robert
Rodriguezes (who, by the way, was Mim-- ' student at UT) and
Richard Linklaters do? Robinson said he'll continue working on his
degree and hopes to find paying work in filmmaking. Farry plans to
head to Los Angeles in a year or so to try her luck in the film
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their next step, ```In Flagrante,' a feature film'' is
bound to headline their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
