<HEADER>
A2886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-ISO29-COX     11-28 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-ISO29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Iso' is oh so nice for Longhorns
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky Brown is a sensitive sort, a soft-spoken
soul who writes love poems and takes pride in his recent Sports
Illustrated cover. (That's him in the lower left, or at least his
back, anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   Mention, though, how the Longhorns gashed Baylor with what has
become the Horns' bread-and-butter play _ the ``iso,'' in which
Brown leads halfback Ricky Williams up the middle _ and his eyes
light up at the mere mention of the associated carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Never was it more effective than on their last two touchdown
drives against the Bears, when the Horns ran it on six of their
last seven plays. It gained 47 yards and resulted in two touchdowns
to give Texas a 30-20 come-from-behind win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hypes me up when the coaches say, `We're coming at you,
right side, every time,''' Brown said. ``It's physical domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go right at them, you look at (the linebacker) from
your stance and he looks at you. He knows you're coming, and
there's nothing he can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Davis loves the play, too. It's a staple in most offensive
play books, and its macho challenge makes it a favorite of the old
school. ``First and foremost, it's an old-timey football play,''
the Longhorns' offensive coordinator said. ``I think the old-timers
would call it solid.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be called more than that _ like the play Davis calls
Friday for the carry that took Williams to the NCAA Division I-A
career rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every football team has the play, some just run it more than
others,'' Davis said. ``It depends on the fullback and the
offensive line, if they're those kind of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas has ``those kind of guys.'' In Brown, a compactly built
6-foot, 222-pounder, they have the perfect lead blocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many times you see Ricky (Williams) running, but you don't
see the other Ricky in front, putting his head in somebody's
chest,'' quarterback Major Applewhite said. ``It's easy to cut off
a linebacker when a 230-pound fullback's in his chest.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line, with an average weight of 310 pounds, can
manhandle defensive fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier for the line, easier to block,'' Williams said.
``They're so big and physical, it's to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The play is fairly simple, with the key elements being Brown's
lead block against the strongside or weakside linebacker and the
double-team with the center and guard.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he reads the blocks just like he imagines Williams
would. ``If it's cluttered inside, I'll try to take my man
outside,'' Brown said. ``I think, `Would Ricky want to go inside?
Would he want to go outside? Where would Ricky want to go?'''
</P>
<P>
   Williams can either follow behind Brown and cut off of his block
or, if he sees that hole being clogged, cut back behind the
double-team block of the guard and center.
</P>
<P>
   Said Williams: ``There are two ways I can go, so it's hard for
the defense to be right. I see a crease, and I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The iso can be run from a variety of formations, including a
split-back, but Texas runs it from the I and offset-I formations.
It can be run four ways _ right or left, strong side or weakside.
</P>
<P>
   It has its complements, too. A play-action pass version relies
on Williams' running threat to open a short middle route for
flanker Kwame Cavil or a deeper pass for split end Wane McGarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You fake to Ricky and throw the ball downfield,'' Davis said.
``Many of Wane's big catches come off the fake, when you get the
linebackers to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas self-scouts to determine its own tendencies, and in doing
that it records, among other things, the number of times it runs a
play, the average gain and the consistency of the play. Consistency
is measured in the number of times the play gains 4 or more yards
and/or results in a first down or touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shoot for about 60 percent consistency on our plays,''
Davis said. ``The iso is about 65 percent and probably averages
close to 6 yards a carry.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the value of the iso, it's not the most productive play
in the book. That distinction goes to the lead draw, the iso's slow
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing is that the draw is blocked similar to
the iso, but with a different tempo,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   In the draw, Brown and Williams first stand up as if setting
into pass protection before heading to the hole. The linemen don't
fire out but use a pass-blocking set to convince the defensive line
it's a pass play.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has run it 35 times this year _ mostly earlier in the year
before opponents caught on _ and it averaged 10.1 yards a play and
67 percent consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get my guy down, I know I'll look up and see Ricky
running down the field for a score,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas doesn't run the draw much any more after great
early-season success, because defenses are looking for it. They're
looking for the iso now, too, but that doesn't always seem to
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can average 6 yards a carry it's a good play,''
Applewhite said. ``Actually, any time it's in Ricky's hands, it's a
good play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
