<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-LIGHTUP29-COX     11-28 2505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-LIGHTUP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family's high-wattage tradition started with a single strand
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's Thanksgiving night, and they wait in the
front yard of a modest South Austin home. Hollow plastic figures
cast in the likeness of Santa, baby Jesus and snowmen. Endless
strands of multicolored lights covering every bit of greenery, wood
and plaster. A ``chandelier'' made of cocktail cups and an angel
with its eyes pointed toward heaven. Wooden cut-outs of wreaths,
reindeer and glittering, holiday-attired Mickey and Minnie Mouse,
Donald Duck and Goofy holding a sign wishing a ``Merry Christmas
from the Boortz family.''
</P>
<P>
   They all wait to be brought to life.
</P>
<P>
   In the increasingly darkening yard, Dean Boortz, the creator, is
wedged in the bushes, affixing bows to his aluminum-covered
shudders to make them look like presents. He has left his turkey
dinner and missed his wife's famous peach pie for this. At 5:30
p.m., the timer that lights the entire display directs power to the
scene and ``O Little Town of Bethlehem'' starts playing on a loop.
The wise men are illuminated as are Snoopy and the carolers. Dean
keeps working on the details, knowing he will be the only one to
notice. He half-believes the Christmas season can't start without
his yard being perfect. And it won't be perfect without his bows.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, Dean Boortz lighted his front yard on
Village Way Drive for the first time. There were no timers, just
him plugging an extension cord into an outlet for a single string
of lights in a tree. Upon seeing the lights, Dean's stepdaughter,
Shari, named it the ``lollipop tree.'' She was 4.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed. Shari is 29, married and has a 3-year-old
(Cole) and an 11-month-old (Brad). Dean, now 57, has also changed.
When he first strung up those lights, he was a hair stylist; now he
owns a driving range. His glasses are thicker now, as is his girth.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, his yard has changed. The lollipop tree has grown
into a yuletide carnival: a somewhat frightening, happily lighted
place surrealistically complete with a glowing Winnie the Pooh,
ropes of lights that spell out ``Noel'' and Mormon Tabernacle Choir
tunes piped in.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaping to judge, know there's more here than just an
eye-popping display of how cacophonous Christmas has become, more
than a statement on how one of the most sacred of Christian
holidays has bent to commercialism, kitsch and polyurethane
messiahs. Because, when it comes down to it, we're all like Dean.
All semi-obsessed with the season as we figuratively put up our own
displays _ watching Christmas specials at Thanksgiving, walking
past the bell-ringing Salvation Army volunteer with an armful of
gifts and buying soda from Coca-Cola-inspired Santas.
</P>
<P>
   This display defines Dean's holiday season, and much of the rest
of the year as well. It's his great obsession, and it elates and
worries him. The endless strands of tiny, twinkling lights are like
a love that holds him too tightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year I say, `This is going to be my last year,' but then
I get a couple weeks into it and I start to get into the spirit,''
he says. ``And then you see the faces of the kids _ their faces all
smooshed up against the car windows _ and that's when it's all
worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch Santa shake his hips
</P>
<P>
   It is Nov. 8 _ one day before Dean and his son, Jeff, 34, will
begin their 17-day task of piecing together their ode to the
holiday season; the attic is still packed with thousands upon
thousands of dollars' worth of Christmas lights and holiday icons.
At the back of the attic, some of the figures are standing in what
looks like a line for unemployed Christmas figurines. A snowman
models behind a somber-faced Joseph deep in prayer. At the front of
the line is a group of singing carolers, looking confident they
will make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, Dean, with his shoes off and feet propped up on his
couch, and his wife, Taryien, sip Burgundy wine (``It has almost no
carbohydrates,'' he says), while trying to describe what their yard
will look like. By the kitchen, a mechanized Santa gyrates his hips
to ``Jingle Bell Rock'' and the couple's two Chihuahuas, Ginger and
Tootsie, yip at their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, one side of the yard is the Christian side, and the
other is the fantasy side,'' Dean says. His cadence is slow and
drenched in a drawl. ``You see, on the fantasy side we have a
snowman village. We have 15 snowmen we set up there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure there are that many?'' Taryien cuts in. She is
blond and looks like a younger, healthier Mrs. Claus. A Mrs. Claus
who enjoys a carbohydrate-less Burgundy now and then.
</P>
<P>
   Dean thinks for a second, then nods slowly. ``Then we have a
30-foot roll of red lights that we spell out the word `Joy,'
J-O-Y.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Joy' is red?'' she asks. ``I thought it was white.''
</P>
<P>
   After this cycle is repeated a few more times, the two finally
agree. They say they do it for the neighborhood and for Austin.
It's a Christmas gift from the Boortz-- s to their city. Especially
the kids, Dean says. He loves doing it for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   But it's always been that way. It has always been a gift. When
Dean first strung up his lights in 1973, it was during the energy
crisis. President Jimmy Carter had begged us to turn down our
thermostats and conserve energy. Dean says his block was dark, no
lights anywhere. His tree in his front yard was a lone beacon, a
blue, red, green and white sign of the season. A defiant,
heart-warming message to everyone: ``Merry Christmas, there's no
energy crisis here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lighting the lollipop
</P>
<P>
   One week into the decoration process, Dean, his son, Jeff, and
Larry, a day laborer who has helped Dean for the past five years,
work into the night. Gordian knots of lights and piles of figures
lie on the backyard patio. A space has been cleared where baby
Jesus sleeps restfully.
</P>
<P>
   Years of putting up Christmas lights have spawned innovations.
In fact, Dean claims, he has shown Austin a number of lighting
techniques now widely used by others, including: 1) running a
string of lights through plastic Solo cups and framing his yard in
them (``I nail them to the ground and they look like beams going
all around the yard.''), and 2) wrapping his tree trunks in foil
before running lights around them, therefore giving the
``shimmering appearance of ice.'' (``I remember a fire marshal
sitting outside my house one night, just looking at them. Not sure
what to do. He'd never seen that before.'')
</P>
<P>
   The three finish wrapping the trees in foil and, at the last
second, decide to wrap the mailbox for continuity. Another first.
Next, they take on the task of stringing the lollipop tree.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff, a more rotund version of his father, but with less hair,
is easygoing and as talkative and knowledgeable about the Boortz
display and its history as his father. He is eloquent and precise
in his storytelling and doublechecks statistics with his father.
Years, dates, voltages, watts and lengths of strings of lights are
verified for authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jeff grew up with his mom in Midland, he kept up with his
father and Dean's second wife. Of great interest was his father's
annual yuletide obsession. Over the years, Dean has collected other
illuminating Christmas knickknacks to put in his yard. He is a
monthly fixture at Canton's famous flea market in East Texas and
Hobby Lobby's after-Christmas lights sale. The display grew. The
yard became a trade show for the newest plastic Christmas figures
and flashing lights. More important, it became a point of pride,
Dean says, a focal point for the whole neighborhood. It was,
everyone told him, where the holiday season officially started.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Jeff explains, the ``competition'' got under way and
the modern, amorphous tangle of lights and wooden Santas began to
take shape.
</P>
<P>
   Dean cuts in and explains how he and a friend named Ronny Smith
were having a conversation one day, the conversation that led to
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Ronny, and he said, `I'm going to have the
best lights in South Austin.''' Dean laughs to himself at the
memory, shaking his head. ``And I said, `No, you're going to have
the second best lights in South Austin.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two stop talking to concentrate on getting an errant strand
of lights into the top of the tree. Dean swings the string like a
lasso and loops the lights on a tall branch. The lollipop tree is
complete, and the yard is bathed in multicolored light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty, always pretty,'' says Larry, staring up at the lights.
``It looks very nice, very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   A dark Christmas
</P>
<P>
   Ronny Smith's red-brick house sits on a corner down the street.
It is dark except for a few lights in the window. A few years ago,
Ronny was diagnosed with cancer and stopped putting up his lights.
He's been sick, he says, with a disease of the legs and can't stay
on them too long. His back is killing him, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to get some help and put a few lights up, but not like
he used to. Back then, he says, he had a 10-foot, fully lit,
Styrofoam Santa and his sleigh and eight six-foot reindeer. When he
couldn't put them up anymore, he gave all his lights and the
Styrofoam Santa to his son-in-law. He hated having to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty close there between me and Dean,'' Ronny says.
``But he always had me beat. Best lights in the city if you ask
me.'' Ronny stops. His clear blue eyes look empty. ``Man, I wish I
could be doing it again. Doing it like Dean does it.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a snowman village
</P>
<P>
   In the 12 years since Jeff moved to Austin, his creative input
has been essential to the Boortz-- s' frontyard extravaganza. Jeff
walks around the yard and points to the displays that were his
ideas. He stops in front of a plastic snowman. This was his stroke
of genius. One day in 1989, he noticed that Dean had 15 snowmen,
which were placed all around the yard at random. Then came the
idea: Why not put them together, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were together,'' he says as he straightens a line of
lights strung vertically on the side of the house, ``then they
could be a village. It would be a snowman village.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff then had the idea to nail a sheet to the ground and cover
the wires trailing out of the back of the plastic snowmen with
garland. Voila, a snowman village.
</P>
<P>
   ``At night, the sheet looks like they're on snow,'' he says.
``It really does.''
</P>
<P>
   As their holiday monument takes shape, Dean and Jeff work their
regular jobs during the day and work nights under the Christmas
lights, sometimes until after midnight. First, the windows are
covered with mylar and plastic ribbon, then wooden candy cane
cut-outs are hung. A plastic church scene, complete with a singing
mother, father and child, is placed near the front of the yard. An
outline of Santa and his reindeer goes on the roof, then is covered
with lights. On a creative whim, Jeff glues glitter-covered fake
snowflakes to tree branches above his snowman village.
</P>
<P>
   That weekend Shari comes in from Schertz. Andy, her husband, is
away at National Guard training. She stands in front of the house
while Cole, in a Spiderman shirt (complete with webbing under the
arms), plays in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been doing this as long as I can remember,'' she says.
``But it hasn't been like this,'' she says waving her hand around,
``since I was in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean stops and watches Cole run around. While he insists he does
it for Austin, this display is mostly for Shari's kids. After all,
Dean needs the inspiration. In the past 10 years, he and Taryien
have lost their fathers. His mother, who loved the lights, passed
away last year, and the days of his competitions with Ronny are
over. Besides, he says, it's hard and takes a lot of time and
money. He can't go on winter vacations in case a circuit blows, and
he's afraid to sell his house for fear the next resident wouldn't
put up lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, those people call and ask me if I want siding put on
the house,'' he says placing a seven-foot angel, draped in a
gauze-like material, in the center of his lawn. ``I want the
siding. I need siding. But I got all these hooks and outlets for
the lights that would have to be moved. It's a burden.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfectionist's inch
</P>
<P>
   With Thanksgiving five days away, Jeff leaves with friends to
spend the holiday in Atlanta. Now working alone, Dean is on the
ground with a tape measure, driving plastic stakes in the ground
exactly 24 inches apart. He will run a string from stake to stake.
The string, he explains, serves two purposes. First, it keeps
people off the lawn (he has set the string two feet back after
measuring how far a car door could swing out without hitting the
barrier). Second, the string stretches all the way around his yard,
with running lights attached. The lights will circle his yard
giving it a sort of holiday-meets-runway-meets-''X Files'' effect.
It's real neat, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Patiently inspecting his work to make sure everything is in a
straight line, Dean occasionally uses a pipe cleaner to realign a
single light. If a wooden wreath isn't centered, down it comes. If
the row of plastic cups, which have been hole-punched earlier, look
crooked, they are dug up and repositioned. A half-inch variation
can warrant a major correction. (The cups, to Dean's disdain, are
the 7-ounce size, not the preferred 9-ouncers.) Dean says he's
goofy that way. He's either totally into something or not at all.
This has become such tradition for him, such a part of him, he
can't help but put all of himself into it.
</P>
<P>
   Ronny drives by, waves and stops. He gets out and leans heavily
against the side of the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking good, Dean, looking good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know; I think it looks like hell,'' Dean answers,
critiquing his 16 days of work.
</P>
<P>
   A moment of silence passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronny, how did we get into this?'' Dean asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know,'' Ronny answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to be crazy,'' Dean says. ``You got to be crazy to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripping the lights Once the lights go on and Dean is finally
happy with the details, he crosses the street to admire his work.
The burden is lifted for another year. He smiles as he surveys his
yard. The green wires and hollow plastic icons create a beautiful
illusion of Christmas. A place where Santa smiles, frozen in a
wave. Nutcra-- kers stand in perfect formation, and baby Jesus
rests peacefully in a manger. This is the beginning of the
Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen minutes after Dean's holiday lights turn on their
magic,the first carload of parents and children drives slowly by.
As predicted, the little ones' faces are ``smooshed'' up against
the window. ``O Little Town of Bethlehem'' plays for the 11th time.
Dean nods his head toward the car. His dreams, and ours along with
them, have been fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
