<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRDWATCH-HITECH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bird watchers focus on high-tech aids
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Along with the familiar binoculars strapped
around their necks, bird watchers are increasingly going high tech,
carrying laptop computers and digital cameras into the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really kind of neat,'' naturalist Dane Mutter said.
``You can log on about noon and see pictures of birds around the
state that were observed that morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Computers are fast changing other aspects of bird watching as
well.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Christmas Bird Count, one of the largest events
every year for the Dayton Audubon Society, will be linked by
computer to BirdSource, a mapping and data basing project developed
by the National Audubon Society and the Cornell University
laboratory of ornithology.
</P>
<P>
   Observations from the annual count of early winter birds in the
Miami Valley will be added to sightings from bird watchers all over
North America. Last year 49,122 participants across the country
counted a record number of species (650). Fed into the Cornell
computers, the information is almost instantly available, showing
trends in bird populations and migrations.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Miami Valley Christmas Bird Count will be Jan. 3. It
involves groups of watchers from novice to professional who stake
out 15-mile sections and count the various species from midnight to
midnight on the chosen day. Watchers try to cover as much of the
area as possible and must stay out at least eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Local results will be compiled Jan. 5 at the Aullwood Audubon
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas Bird Count was started by conservationist Frank
Chapman on Christmas Day, 1900, as a reaction to an annual holiday
event called a ``side hunt,'' in which the team that shot the most
birds was the winner.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the 74th year for the Miami Valley bird count.
Sightings range from the rare, such as the common loon (one) to the
common, such as Canada geese (1,162).
</P>
<P>
   Mutter, who works the downtown corridor, usually spots the pair
of Peregrine falcons that nest in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   This past spring BirdSource at Cornell completed the task of
entering all of the Christmas Bird Count data back to 1900. With
animated maps on the BirdSource Internet site, individual species
are tracked for their abundance. The program has become a valuable
wildlife study tool.
</P>
<P>
   BirdSource noted the return of the American kestrel, which has
all but disappeared from much of North America in the 1950s.
Because the kestrel eats what humans consider pests, small insects
and mammals, scientists believe its return coincided with the
banning of the pesticide DDT in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have the Cooper's hawk, which we thought was gone
forever but now it's fairly common,'' said Mutter, who has been
part of the Christmas Bird Count for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
