<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-CATHOLICS29-COX     11-28 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-CATHOLICS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Baptist blacks finding faith, refuge in Catholic Church
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At age 19, Mary Johnson, reared as a devout black
Baptist, found a new faith.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Luke Baptist Church, she had heard the gospel choir
singing, swaying and shouting, the congregation stomping and
dancing about, the preacher belting out a vigorous, cadenced
sermon. All were the staples of black Protestant worship rooted in
the deep South. And they were all that Johnson knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always so confusing for me,'' she said. ``It was
distracting. The decibel level was really high. I never knew what
anyone was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one Sunday, her husband-to-be, Jerome Johnson, took her to
Mass. He had been raised Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   At St. John the Baptist Church, the solemn liturgy, the
flickering candles and meditative organ music moved her spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was quiet, serene adoration _ a direct contrast,'' said
Johnson, now 53 and a nurse who lives in Jefferson Twp. with her
husband. ``The music was beautiful and quiet. It was conducive to
contemplation, and at that time in my life that is what I needed. I
thought, `Hmmm, maybe this is where I belong.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She soon converted.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she is among the 2.3 million black Catholics in the
United States who celebrate November as Black Catholic History
Month. They hope that recognition of black contributions to the
Roman church will assist efforts to attract more blacks to
Catholicism. Bolstering their cause is the recent election of
Bishop Wilton Gregory of Illinois as vice president of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, the first black to hold an office
in that group, and rumors that Nigerian-born Cardinal Francis
Arinze is a possible successor to Pope John Paul II. He would be
the first pope of color since 496 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   The Archdiocese of Cincinnati's 500,000 Catholics includes 4,000
to 6,000 blacks, and about 10 predominantly black parishes. There
is one black parish pastor. The Rev. Freddie Washington leads the
merged Dayton parish of St. James and Resurrection Church.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, the two congregations will become St. Simon of Cyrene
Church and move into a new building.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelization is the major challenge facing blacks in the
Catholic Church, said George Findley, director of the archdiocese's
Office of African-American Ministries. Winning converts or inviting
strays back to the fold requires debunking an entirely different
set of stereotypes and myths about the Catholic Church, Findley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many African-Americans who do not believe that there
are black Catholics. Those who know there are wonder why they are
members of a white church,'' he said. ``The programs that I do are
designed to show that from the beginning of the Catholic church,
there were blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s and '50s, Catholic schools were a primary
proselytizing vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were blacks who moved from the South to the North and
sought out a better education for their children in Catholic
schools,'' said the Rev. Clarence Williams of the Archdiocese of
Detroit, which has about 30,000 black members. ``For example, in
1950 there were 8,000 blacks in Chicago. But by 1970, there were
80,000. ``
</P>
<P>
   But that avenue of conversion is waning, said Cecilia Moore, a
professor of religious studies at the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools in urban areas are having to close down because they
don't have the funding,'' Moore said. ``I think African-American
Catholics need to be concerned about things we can do to keep
Catholic schools in the inner city alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The pronouncements of Vatican II, which allowed cultural
integration with traditional Catholic liturgy, may have energized
evangelization.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the gospel music and expressive preaching that Mary
Johnson experienced in the Baptist church can be found in many
black Catholic services. They often are vibrant with the trappings
and traditions of African-American worship: kente cloth vestments,
drums, a choir with a saxophone. At St. James/
</P>
<P>
   Resurrection, Father Freddie is known as a singing preacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very ironic,'' said Mary Johnson, who attends St. James.
``I love the fact that worship is becoming more Afrocentric. At the
same time, I miss the quiet serenity that is conducive for me to
give over to complete prayer. I like the meditative prayer. . . . I
like the celebratory prayer. I think there has to be a balance in
worship.'' Black Catholics face the same shortage of vocations as
whites, says the Institute for Black Catholic Studies at Xavier
University. The United States has 14 black bishops but no black
cardinals. Among a handful of black Marianists in the United
States, the Rev. Paul Marshall is a member of the Cincinnati
province.
</P>
<P>
   But persons of African descent were present in the Roman church
centuries before the first black Catholics arrived in Florida with
the Spaniards in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   Saints of color include St. Apollonia, St. Anthony and St.
Martin de Porres of Peru, whom Pope John XXII declared the first
black American saint in 1962. And scholars still debate the hue of
revered St. Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   If Nigerian Cardinal Arinze succeeds Pope Jean Paul II, he would
be the fourth pope of color:
</P>
<P>
   Less than 200 years after the death of Jesus Christ, Pope Victor
I served from 189 to 199 A.D. Victor bore a Latin name like many
Africans of the time. He is buried at St. Peter's Basilica in
Vatican City.
</P>
<P>
   Miltiades, a black priest from Africa, was elected the 37th pope
in 311 A.D. Under Miltiades' reign, the Roman Emperor Constantine
was converted to Christianity and Roman persecutions of Christians
are believed to have ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Gelasius I served in the fifth century, from 492 to 496. He
was revered for his modest lifestyle and care of the poor. Gelasius
is also credited as the first pope to advocate separation of church
and state.
</P>
<P>
   Could there be an African pope in 2000?
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Williams of Detroit has considered the rumors
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard that the chances of having an African become pope
are very good. I've also heard the same is true for Latin
America,'' said Williams in a telephone interview from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument that I've heard is that the church is growing so
much in Africa right now and because the church is so vital in
Africa, that makes the possibility of having a pope from Africa
much greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Africa boasts 130 million Catholics, compared with 73.6 million
in North America, not including the Caribbean. Latin America has
about 60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Africa has no shortage of black priests, Williams said. In fact,
``the United States is a kind of mission again and Africans are
supplying priests and sisters to serve in our parishes here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Francis Tandoh of Ghana assists in Dayton's St.
James/Resurrection parish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you travel outside the United States,'' Williams said,
``you'll find that most persons of African descent who are
Christian are Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
