</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-PYREX29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kitschy classics hot on collector's lists
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Bette Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forget Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgic baby boomers are snapping up creamy green Anchor
Hocking Fire-King glass kitchenware from the '40s and '50s, nesting
Pyrex mixing bowls from the '60s, even pimento cheese/juice jars
from the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   For boomers, it's the call of the child. Or at least the
children they used to be. Buying a classic Fire-King custard cup is
like buying a little piece of their childhood, chocolate pudding
and all.
</P>
<P>
   On any given weekend, you can scour glass shows, antiques malls
and flea markets for these evocative items. They're especially hot
this time of year, thanks to holiday gift-giving and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the attraction is their affordability. Some rare pieces
cost several thousand dollars, but it's possible to begin building
a collection with a $15 cup and saucer in Fire-King's Jade-ite.
</P>
<P>
   But hurry. The stuff, especially anything Fire-King, is so
sought after that even the nation's top glass expert has trouble
keeping up with its popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything take off or its price go up as fast
as Fire-King,'' says Gene Florence, author of 65 collecting books,
including ``Anchor Hocking's Fire-King &AMP; More'' (Collector Books,
$24.95). ``I sold a Fire-King Jade-ite ball pitcher in '97 for
$125, another in February for $250.''
</P>
<P>
   Today they sell for $550 to $600.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, kitchen glassware was considered cheap,
even ugly, garage-sale fodder. Glass elitists still question its
merits. But a pristine set of oven-safe Pyrex casseroles is as
coveted by boomer glass fanatics as a Rembrandt is by art
collectors. Maybe more. After all, you can't pop a Rembrandt in the
oven, nor does it remind you of those great chocolate chip cookies
your mom used to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``People stand in my booth and say, `Ooooh, my mother had this
and my grandmother had that.' It reminds them of family and home,''
says Jo Henson, 52. She and husband Ronnie, 53, began amassing
Fire-King four years ago and now sell it at three metro Atlanta
antiques malls.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a large part of the appeal of kitchen glassware is
familiarity. Almost everyone has a few vintage pieces in their
kitchen cabinets, even if it's just a chipped Pyrex measuring cup.
</P>
<P>
   Add in the official seal of housekeeping diva Martha Stewart,
who featured her daughter Alexis' massive Fire-King Jade-ite
collection in Martha Stewart Living magazine, and _ boom! _ instant
feeding frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha personally shoved Jade-ite off the shelves,'' says
Terry Kovel who with husband Ralph writes antiques and collectibles
guides and a syndicated collecting column.
</P>
<P>
   Kovel credits Stewart for recognizing that a single piece of
anything is unimpressive. But, says Kovel, ``If you put together a
collection of almost anything, it fascinates people.'' Alexis'
Fire-King collection more than fascinated people, it was the
equivalent of Stewart saying, ``Beat this!''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen glass enthusiasts view the Stewart Fire-King article as
a watershed event, forever splitting them into two groups:
pre-Martha collectors who began acquiring Fire-King a decade ago,
and post-Martha collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-Marthas credit Stewart for bringing respectability to their
collections. ``The Depression glass people used to laugh at my
Fire-King. But who's laughing now?'' jokes Shirley Moore of Tulsa,
Okla. But they also take Stewart to task for making it scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply resent what she did to my glass,'' sighs Beckye
Richardson, 42, of Flower Mound, Texas, one of the nation's top
five Fire-King collectors. ``It's really hard to find now. And the
prices!''
</P>
<P>
   But like other die-hard ``dish people,'' as collectors are wont
to call themselves, she admits that part of the excitement of
collecting Fire-King and other glassware is not being able to find
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still pieces I haven't seen except in a book,'' says
Peter Hamilton, 33, an Atlanta graphic designer. ``But it's fun to
look for it and find the bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
