<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-STRESS-MASSAGE29-     11-28 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-STRESS-MASSAGE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A therapeutic laying on of hands
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Always wanted a professional massage but too
intimidated/shy/uncertain how to get one? Not sure how to separate
the lotion-potion parlors from the legitimate, trained massage
therapists?
</P>
<P>
   One way is to check with Atlanta's schools of massage. They can
refer you to graduates or sign you up for student clinics where
hourlong massages are about $30, half the going rate of standard
therapeutic massage sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent way for someone who's never had a massage to
come in and get one at one of the schools,'' said Sandy Jones,
director of admissions at New Life Institute School of Massage
Excellence in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, students at the clinics have completed their training
in basic technique and need practice perfecting their healing
touch. A bonus may include an instructor stepping in to demonstrate
so your muscles get a double dose of strokes and kneading out of
knots.
</P>
<P>
   The therapist you choose should be certified, meaning he has
attended an approved school of massage. In Georgia, the minimum
amount of hours for certification is 500. The state does not
require massage therapists to have a business or professional
license as many other states do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone could hang out their shingle, which is one of the
unfortunate aspects of massage in Georgia,'' said Maureen Marcus,
massage therapist in charge of staff training at Natural Body Spa
in Atlanta. One advantage of signing up for a massage through a spa
or health club is that they only hire certified therapists, Marcus
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asking friends is another way to find a trustworthy therapist.
``Referrals is basically how I built my business,'' said Barry
Guthrie, who specializes in deep-tissue massage at his Stone
Mountain, Ga., home studio. Guthrie, who began private practice
four years ago, said he did encounter the stigma the word
``massage'' sometimes elicits. ``Some people out there are still
not that educated about massage, so a big part of being a massage
therapist is to educate people.''
</P>
<P>
   At spas and health clubs, therapists say business booms during
the holidays as the working crowd has time off to luxuriate, and
many need a break from family gatherings and shopping till they
dropp. Massage gift certificates also make great stocking stuffers.
</P>
<P>
   Or if you're looking for a treat to give yourself during holiday
stress-out, have the massage therapist come to you.
</P>
<P>
   Many therapists in private practice such as Rebecca Thurman of
Atlanta will show up at your door with table, oil and music in
hand. The cost? Around $80 to $85.
</P>
<P>
   ``House calls are popular with some people,'' Thurman said.
``They don't want to fight the Atlanta traffic and afterward, they
can just take a shower or fall asleep in their own bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
