<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-CONSUMER29-COX     11-28 1584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-CONSUMER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survivng holdiay shopping
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Throughout November, the focus has been
Thanksgiving _ planning and execution. Who's coming for dinner? Who
isn't (thank goodness)? Where is the family recipe for chiffon
pumpkin pie? Which in-law is the most boorish? Today, get with the
gift-giving program in a climate-controlled setting.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Thanksgiving is the starting gun for those of us
who honor each holiday in its appropriate calendar month and muddle
through life _ quite nicely, thank you _ without a
Daytimerdayplanner. Start your purchasing engines, Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What if you just can't face the crowds?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you have survived DisneyworldDisney World in July andor
Six Flags Over Texas in August, any mall or shopping center should
be a snap. You gave your all yesterday on that turkey dinner thing;
today is your day.Q: Isn't everyone else marching to the mall
today?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure they are, but you have the edge. Attack shopping like
you would a jam-packed theme park _ go prepared and follow basic
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Arrive early _ before posted store hours. You get your pick of
parking places and have a moment to review your assault plan.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the mall or shopping center in a clockwise direction _ the
majority will follow a counterclockwise pattern.
</P>
<P>
   When given a choice (of registers, lines, whatever) pick the one
on the left _ the line to the right is favored by most.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the store farthest from your car first and work your way
back to the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Plan any meals at odd times _ have an early snack or a very late
lunch.Q: Don't I have a million other holiday chores to do?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but not on this unofficial national shopping holiday.
Put off other tasks that can be accomplished later.
</P>
<P>
   Buy stamps from the post machines in off hours. Begin saving the
comics to use for wrapping paper and raffia from flower bouquets
for ribbon. Forget about merry mavens who spend the afternoon
gold-leafing apples and dipping magnolia leaves in glycerin.
</P>
<P>
   Let the catalogs cool until the children are nestled all snug in
their beds, and address Christmas cards when you have the kitchen
table to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What family tree spawned the Mall of America?
</P>
<P>
   A: The shopping center has come a long way from its humble
roots. According to the New York Public Library reference desk, the
first urban shopping center was built in Baltimore, 1896; the first
suburban one in 1928 in Ardmore, Pa. This little center contained a
movie theater, two department stores, medical offices and 17 (count
'em) other shops.Q: Is it better to give than to receive if you
can't find the right gift?
</P>
<P>
   A: Do not waste time on hard-to-buy-forfind people today.
</P>
<P>
   Underbuy: A simple present can always can be augmented later.
</P>
<P>
   Consider gift ideas for groups: All sisters-in-law receive a
sweater; all teachers, a pen; all brothers, a soccer shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Donations make a great gift and are very much appreciated. Gift
certificates (to the movies, to a swanky grocery store) are fun and
flexible. Pick up several little gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Make a basket with wrapped gifts (presentation, presentation,
presentation) for the children to share with their friends.
</P>
<P>
   Insist that store clerks honor the customer in front of them
rather than the one on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for free wrapping (take it with you) _ gift boxes, tissue
paper, anything to make your wrapping life easier.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a hiding place.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to mail a gift, have the address written on an index
card to hand the clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the basics for storming the consumer's castle and
making the most of the day?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clear the decks.
</P>
<P>
   Remove every extra item from your purse to lighten the load.
Ditch the matchbox cars, the room-mother ``to call'' list and the
lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Plan to pick up take-out on the way home. No cooking, no
cleaning today.
</P>
<P>
   Make a list on an envelope (name, gift idea, price range). Use
it to store the receipts from today's purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Give yourself permission to meet a friend for coffee or lunch,
but don't shop with a friend _ it is distracting and
time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Check out what you have on hand _ any gifts you may have
purchased and hidden _ before you hit the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Dress appropriately: Dust off the walking shoes, don a comfy
sweater with pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Do without a coat if you can _ it just bogs you down.
</P>
<P>
   Do not be distracted by the perfect New Year's Eve dress or a
pair of shoes. Resist any temptation to head to a dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You load 16 tons and whaddaya get ... ?A: A backache.
</P>
<P>
   The lighter and the more centrally located on your body the
package or purse you carry, the better, says Dr. Randall Dryer of
the Central Texas Spine Institute. Try shifting your purse from one
shoulder to the other and carry it more toward the back of your
body than the front. (Safety dictates keeping your purse where you
can see it, though.)
</P>
<P>
   Lugging heavy packages and/or children in and out of the car and
the house can cause physical problems. ``Do not lift and reach,''
notes Dryer, as the shoulders should be in line with the hips when
lifting.
</P>
<P>
   Constant weight and improper lifting may cause some temporary
aches and pains that can be corrected with a change in posture or
habits as well as strengthening exercises.Q: Didn't Mama say
there'd be days like this?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Is the card still in your possession, and can you verify
the last three charges?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if you receive a call from your credit card
company after a day of heating plastic to the melting point. Judy
Miller of Chase Manhattan Bank says an early detection system
protects customers from the fraudulent use of their credit cards.
This electronic system looks at all card transactions and flags
unusual spending activity. Trained representatives review account
information to determine who should receive a follow-up phone call
to verify the account activity.
</P>
<P>
   Safe shopping
</P>
<P>
   The International Council of Shopping Centers advises shoppers
to remember the holiday season is the November sweeps for thieves.
So heed these tenets to keep you and your treasures safe:
</P>
<P>
   Remember where you are: Do not exit a store or mall uttering,
``Where did I park my car?'' Carry your keys in your hand.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be a target. Do not leave packages in plain sight on the
seat of the car. Lock your vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   When possible, walk to the parking lot with someone else (a
security guard or a friend who meets you at a prearranged time
inside the store).
</P>
<P>
   Glance in the back seat before you hop in. Avoid parking near a
large van that may obscure your view or contain a band of thieves
(easier said than done in Suburban country.)
</P>
<P>
   Be alert. Do not flash wads of cash or stacks of credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   _ Nordstrom is the only store I've heard of that turns its space
into Christmas overnight on Thanksgiving. No September Santas, no
October twinkle lights. Amen!
</P>
<P>
   Surviving holiday spending
</P>
<P>
   The holidays allow us all to be someone's fairy godmother _
don't let the ``someone'' be a credit card company. Enjoy the
thrill of giving and thinking about those on your list without the
guilt and interest rates. Here are some tips from the Consumer
Credit Counseling Service to help you.
</P>
<P>
   Plan ahead by saving money for the holidays (sage advice, but it
may be too late for this year).
</P>
<P>
   Split the cost of large gifts with someone.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a gift for an entire family instead of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Mail gifts early to avoid overnight charges.
</P>
<P>
   Walk around a store with a purchases to give you timea moment to
reflect on it.
</P>
<P>
   Pay with cash _ it is harder to spend cash than to use credit.
</P>
<P>
   Overspender's Punch Recipe: Cut top off a one-gallon milk carton
and fill with water. Add all credit cards. Place in deep freeze
until January. Thaw and serve warm with New Year's resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   For a free copy of the Consumer Credit Counseling Service
brochure ``Surviving the Holidays,'' call CCCS, a program of
LifeWorks, at 447-0711.
</P>
<P>
   Personal shoppers
</P>
<P>
   If making a list and checking it twice is making you a basket
case, then it's time for ``your people to call someone else's
people.'' Personal shoppers are veritable life savers for those
with long lists, impossible lists or lists of people you do not
really know. These wish-list wizards will consult with you,
suggest, select and shop for anyone. Need it mailed? No problem.
Need it delivered? Can do.
</P>
<P>
   Of course this type of service is a luxury (ask for prices), but
think of it as a gift to yourself _ and to your family. Cheaper
than therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise, surprise
</P>
<P>
   Black Friday, the shopping center industry name for the day
after Thanksgiving, is not the busiest shopping day of the year.
Its rank, according to the International Council of Shopping
Centers, is consistently below that of the Saturday before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Another holiday note: An average of 11,620 children per shopping
mall visited Santa in 1997 while listening to the two most popular
mall holiday songs _ ``Jingle Bells'' and ``White Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane S. Greig trolls for consumer questions, answers, tips, good
deals and discounts constantly. Contact her at P.O. Box 670, Austin
78767, 445-3697, 445-3968(fax) or jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
