<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CURRIE _ The next era in space exploration is set to begin Dec.
3, and a former Troy, Ohio resident _ astronaut Nancy Currie _ will
play a key role. On Dec. 3, Currie and her crewmates will blast off
on space shuttle Discovery to begin the biggest space construction
project in history, the International Space Station. Hailed as the
next step in human space exploration and denounced as a boondoggle,
the station will be bigger than a football field and house up to
seven astronauts for months at a time when it is completed about
six years from now. Since announced by President Reagan in 1984,
the program has been plagued by cost overruns, delays and
redesigns. The biggest problem now is Russia's economic crisis.
Russia is responsible for major parts of the station, but its work
is underfunded and behind schedule. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News).
30. WITH NASA GRAPHICS, PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BRADYLAW-GEORGIA _ Calls for instant background checks from gun
dealers are expected to quadruple in Georgia when the permanent
Brady law goes into effect Nov. 30. The new federal law requires
the buyer of any kind of firearm to undergo a background check.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENTS _ ATLANTA _ Several cities across the
country, including Chicago and Seattle _ have turned to
noneducators to operate their school systems. Atlanta Public
Schools, in its search for a superintendent, is also open to a
CEO-type person to serve as superintendent. We look at the track
record of several of these superintendents and update Atlanta's
quest for an innovative leader. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WILD-PIGS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ While hunters want the
season expanded, others are complaining about overwhelming numbers
of wild pigs. (Howard, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHIPPERS _ WASHINGTON _ When he was barely 30, David Schippers
slapped handcuffs on Sam Giancana, one of the most notorious and
elusive bosses of Chicago's mob. Nearly four decades later, the
bare-knuckled prosecutor faces a different kind of courtroom, a
courtroom of political intrigue as the chief counsel of the
Republican-led impeachment inquiry of President Clinton. (Carr,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 58. WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   w/IMPEACH-BOX _Upcoming schedule of House Judiciary Committee.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   ACCESS-CHARGE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A legislative fight over 12
cents doesn't sound like much at first. But those 12 cents add up
to about $800 million a year that flows from the pockets of
telephone customers to long-distance companies and, finally, into
the bank accounts of Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. (Hight, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AT&AMP;T will soon need every friend it can
find in the Texas Legislature for a backroom brawl with
Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. But in recent months, the
long-distance giant has shot itself in the foot _ with a machine
gun. (Hight, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   USA-FINANCIAL-NETWORK _ DAYTON, Ohio _ A federal judge has
ordered Dayton-based USA Financial Network Inc. and affiliated
companies to stop selling securities and insurance while an
independent consultant reviews the companies' operations. (Dillon,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
