<HEADLINE>
ULTRA-RICH BALLPLAYERS HAVE REINSDORF TO THANK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.Y., Mass., Calif., Wash.)  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What hath Jerry Reinsdorf wrought?
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox owner hasn't made a major free-agent
signing in two years, but the last one he did, Albert Belle,
triggered the escalating activity that reached a frenzy last week.
Bernie Williams and Mo Vaughn, not to mention Mike Piazza, can nod
in Reinsdorf's direction because his signing of Belle on Nov. 19,
1996, made their contracts possible.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball is hurtling toward its first $100 million
contract, and while salaries have been escalating since free agency
was created in 1976, the Belle contract thrust the salary scale
into a higher orbit.
</P>
<P>
   When bad Albert became a free agent following the 1996 season,
the highest-paid player in baseball was Ken Griffey Jr., who
earlier that year signed a four-year contract for $8.5 million a
year. To put in perspective what Reinsdorf did for baseball
contracts, it took four years to get from Ryne Sandberg's record
$7.1 million to Griffey's $8.5 million, an increase of 19.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If, in signing Belle, Reinsdorf had raised the scale by the same
percentage, Belle would have received just under $10.2 million a
year. But no reason to stop there. The White Sox owner asked Arn
Tellem, Belle's agent, what he wanted, then gave it to him _ $11
million a year _ sending the top of the scale soaring by 29.4
percent only 10 months later.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Reinsdorf agreed to a clause that enabled Belle to
become a free agent if three players had higher salaries. He is in
that position now and has until Wednesday to decide if he wants to
remain with the White Sox or go elsewhere. If it is elsewhere _
Baltimore _ he will do it for even more money than Reinsdorf gave
him.
</P>
<P>
   Tellem wanted the clause because he didn't know where the market
was headed, and he wanted to make sure Belle suddenly didn't become
underpaid. Any player who signs a long-term contract faces that
possibility. But Reinsdorf wanted Belle so he capitulated on that
issue, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now Belle is in position to sign with the Orioles for $13
million a year for five years, which, at least for today, would
place him in a tie for second for the highest annual average
salary. Piazza ($13 million) eclipsed Pedro Martinez of Boston
($12.5 million) with his Mets' contract in October, then was
supplanted himself last week when Vaughn ($13,333,333) signed with
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting aspect of the soaring, leapfrogging
salaries at the upper end of the scale has been the silence of
Griffey. Many consider him the best player in the game, but he has
plummeted from No. 1 to a tie for 12th and he has never suggested
that his contract be renegotiated to get him back to the top of the
scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't heard him say anything; that's not his style,''
Woody Woodward, the Seattle general manager, said. ``That's the way
he's always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's contract expires after the 2000 season, the same time
that his teammate, Alex Rodriguez, ends his contract. The Mariners
are warily watching the salaries soar onward and upward. By the
time Junior and A. Rod sign new contracts, they might own the
Mariners' new park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the two best all-around players in the game,''
Woodward said, ``looking at power, speed and defense, arms and the
positions they play. My position has been and continues to be both
of these fellows came through our system and I'd like to see them
both finish their careers with Seattle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
