<HEADLINE>
LITTLE IRON HORSES UPSTAGE THE FLORA AT BOTANICAL GARDENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Enveloped in the thick greenhouse humidity at the New
York Botanical Garden in the Bronx, 4-year-old Caleb Orange romped
along the conservatory pathways, ignoring fascinating plants like
the giant Burmese honeysuckle, otherwise known as Lonicera
hildebrandiana.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Caleb cocked his head heavenward and exclaimed with
delight as the red and green model train cars of the North Pole
Rail Company rolled across a bridge made of sticks and twigs high
above the conservatory floor. ``Wow,'' he said, as the electric
cars click-clacked over his head. ``Look at that one.''
</P>
<P>
   The bridge carries just a fraction of the nearly 1,000 feet of
model train track that runs through the Enid A. Haupt Conservatory
as part of ``A Victorian Holiday,'' the New York Botanical Garden's
seventh annual Christmastime display, which opened Friday and runs
through Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Another model train display opened Saturday at the Brooklyn
Botanic Garden, which is hoping to capitalize on the special
fascination people have with trains to boost winter attendance, as
its Bronx rival has done quite successfully.
</P>
<P>
   At the New York Botanical Garden, holiday season attendance used
to dip below 20,000, said John Rorer, the garden's executive vice
president and chief operating officer. Last year more than 65,000
people visited the train exhibit, and this year more than 100,000
are expected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the train displays have become increasingly
elaborate and expensive. This year's display, paid for by private
donations, cost about $135,000. It includes bridges, waterfalls and
models of historic New York City buildings, like a 1799 Gracie
Mansion, all made from plant materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holiday train show has sort of created a new season for
the New York Botanical Garden,'' Rorer said. ``What would have in
years past been a fairly small attendance has now become a growing
audience. The trains have really become the platform on which we
have built a whole new holiday season.''
</P>
<P>
   Several visitors admitted that they had not visited the gardens
except to see the train displays. Garden officials said the trains
held a particular interest for children that encouraged more
families to visit, a point that was reinforced by the dozens of
strollers whizzing through the Haupt Conservatory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Frank Conti, 4, who was with his parents, Carlo and Frances, was
jumping up and down in front of one track area. Like an undersize,
over-anxious commuter, he shouted, ``I want to see a choo-choo
train. I want to see a choo-choo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Contis, who live in Briarcliff Manor, N.Y., saw last year's
train display and delayed a visit to Grandma to see this one. ``He
got us up early to drive down here,'' Conti said of his son. ``We
asked him if he wanted to stop at his grandma's, he said, `Let's do
it after.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx display was designed by Paul G. Busse, a landscaper
and architect from Cincinnati, whose company, Applied Imaginations,
is one of the country's premier designers of garden railway
displays. Busse designed his first large display for the Ohio State
Fair in 1982. The trains and track for both the Bronx and Brooklyn
displays are on loan from Aristo-Craft Trains of Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   Garden railroading, which involves larger model trains known as
G-scale that can run both indoors and out (even in light rain), is
an increasingly popular hobby. Conventions now often draw thousands
of fans and Garden Railways, a hobbyist magazine, is celebrating
its 15th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Busse and his staff construct the miniature buildings, bridges
and other display components by hand, using natural materials like
leaves, bark and branches. Garden railroading, he said, combines
the traditionally distinct hobbies of gardening and train
collecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We touch the people who love miniatures,'' he said, ``we touch
the people who love trains, we touch the people who love gardens,
we touch the people who love waterfalls.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Morris Arboretum in Philadelphia, a train display helped
triple attendance, Busse said. ``Gardens are beautiful but I think
trains bring the sense of imagination and bring it alive,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The display in Brooklyn is the garden's first. Five trains roll
through tunnels, past model buildings designed to reflect the
borough in a wintry setting. There is a row of brownstones and a
replica of the Brooklyn bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Zuk, the president of the botanic garden, said she hoped
the display would grow in future years and would draw more
winter-time visitors. ``We want to encourage people to come out
here not just for the cherry blossoms and the lilacs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the two train exhibits raised the prospect of further
inter-borough rivalry. ``Look, we are great colleagues and friendly
competitors,'' said Karl Lauby, a spokesman for the New York
Botanical Garden, noting that all botanical gardens benefit from
interesting exhibits that draw attention and appreciation. He
added, ``Imitation is a sincere form of flattery.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
