<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: THOSE WACKY RED SOX; TALE OF TWO CONTRACTS;
DASHING THE BUCK-AND-BERNIE THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a new seven-year contract in his pocket, Bernie Williams
should finish his career with the Yankees. And every time he sees
the Boston Red Sox, he should express his gratitude because they
made it possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Boras wins again,'' an American League general manager
said. ``He had nothing until Dan Duquette.'' He referred to the Red
Sox general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duquette goes ahead and offers 87 and a half for Bernie on
Tuesday and Wednesday the Yankees matched his mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox offered Williams $87.5 million for seven years. Two
weeks earlier they offered Mo Vaughn $63 million for five years,
and when he rejected it, they said bye, bye to one of the most
popular athletes in Boston sports history, a player who had carried
them on his burly back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what's going through their heads,'' one general
manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any sense,'' said an agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox signing of Jose Offerman two weeks ago to a
four-year, $26 million contract outraged other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no accountability there,'' said an executive of a
National League club. ``They have no owner there. It's a trust.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive said he was told by the general manager of another
club that one of Offerman's agents, in talking to clubs about the
vastly improved infielder, sought less money than the Red Sox gave
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Leary, Wakefield, Garciaparra, Martinez, Offerman and he
almost did it with Williams,'' an American League general manager
said, rattling off names of players whose contracts other clubs
found to be unnecessarily inflationary.
</P>
<P>
   Short Term vs. Long Term
</P>
<P>
   The signing of Bernie Williams once again raised questions about
the Yankees' practice of not signing their good young players to
long-term contracts. The Cleveland Indians have followed the
opposite practice, prompting other teams, such as the Angels, to
sign their young players at least through the salary arbitration
years.
</P>
<P>
   A comparison between Williams and Jim Thome tells a revealing
financial tale.
</P>
<P>
   When Thome had between one and two years of major league
service, the Indians signed him to a four-year contract. Then
during the fourth year, in 1997, they signed him to a four-year
extension. In the past five years they have paid Thome a total of
$10.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had between one and two years of major league service
at the same time as Thome, entering the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   There was no multiyear contract for Williams then; nor was there
any until last week. Going year by year, the Yankees the past five
years have paid Williams $17,225,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some agents recommend that their clients shun multiyear
contracts early in their careers. Thome's agent, in fact, urged him
not to accept either contract. But the money and the security were
too great for Thome to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Yankees have Derek Jeter and Mariano Rivera eligible for
salary arbitration for the first time, and those players, as well
as Andy Pettitte, remain unencumbered by a multiyear contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some conversations last year and we agreed not to do
it,'' Casey Close, Jeter's agent, said. ``We couldn't agree on
preliminary stuff. I expect they'll bring it up this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Jeter and friends use the arbitration system, the
Yankees have committed $66 million for 17 players for next season.
They expect to have an opening-day payroll of about $81 million, up
from a season-ending payroll of $65.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The only teams close to them in present payroll are Cleveland
($67.2 million for 18 players) and Atlanta ($65.65 million for 13
players).
</P>
<P>
   No Conspiracy Theory
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the conspiracy theory espoused by some baseball
executives last February, Scott Boras did not have a deal with the
Arizona Diamondbacks to deliver Bernie Williams to them.
</P>
<P>
   That so-called deal was the subject of hot speculation after the
Diamondbacks signed Andy Benes, another Boras client, as a free
agent. The expansion team, the theory went, helped Boras by signing
Benes, and he, in turn, would make sure Williams signed with them
this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's logical for people to speculate in terms of Buck and
Bernie,'' Colangelo said at the time, referring to his manager,
Buck Showalter, who had been Williams' manager in New York. ``Now
there will be speculation because of the business I've done with
Boras.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo was interested in Williams this month but never got
serious enough with an offer to lure him to the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   In his effort to secure a record contract for Williams, Boras
prepared a 23-page booklet of data on the center fielder. On one
page, the agent got carried away. Citing his defensive ability,
Boras said Williams was ranked the major leagues' No. 1 center
fielder in the Elias rankings, which are used to determine
compensation for free agents. Williams was No. 1 all right, but not
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings use a complex formula based on a series of
statistics, and in the case of outfielders, they are all hitting
statistics _ plate appearances, batting average, on-base
percentage, home runs and runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   No fly balls caught or missed, no assists, no errors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 1656EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-NORWAY-DAEHLIE-NY     11-28 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NORWAY-DAEHLIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE OLYMPIC GOLD BECKONS SKIER DAEHLIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do Paavo Nurmi of Finland, Larysa Latynina of the former
Soviet Union and Mark Spitz and Carl Lewis of the United States
have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Each won a record nine Olympic gold medals during remarkable
careers, and each is in danger of being surpassed in February 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the cross-country skier Bjorn Daehlie has
concluded that he has not yet experienced enough burning in his
muscular legs or oxygen deprivation in his voluminous lungs in a
remarkable competitive career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit that it would be quite nice to pass Carl Lewis,''
the 31-year-old Norwegian said in a telephone interview earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Daehlie nearly passed out in his last Olympic race: the men's
50-kilometer event at the 1998 Winter Games in Nagano, Japan. The
instant he crossed the finish line, he pitched forward as if he had
been hit from behind by something blunt and heavy. He had already
set a Winter Olympic record in Nagano by winning his sixth and
seventh gold medals. Now he had his eighth, and he was as spent as
he had ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that was my hardest race ever,'' Daehlie said. ``I
saw the gold medal going away in the last two kilometers, and it
was hard to push myself because I was already completely
exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the months leading up to Nagano, Daehlie talked openly about
his plans to retire, saying he needed to spend more time with his
two young sons, Sivert and Sander, and their mother, Vilde. But
when he finally felt capable of speaking after what could have been
his final victory, he hedged on quitting. After discussing the idea
at length with his family, he has stopped bothering to hedge, and
the truth is that 31 might be old for a running back, but not for a
cross-country skier. In the 1994 Olympics, an Italian, Maurilio De
Zolt, won the gold medal in the men's relay at age 43.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of retiring was quite strong in me,'' Daehlie said.
``But the problem is, when you have been doing this for 10 years,
it's a part of your life, part of the way you're living. You don't
want to stop when you physically feel 100 percent. It might seem
difficult to understand when you see what skiing requires, but I
think I have a special connection with this sport. I dream about
the big events and all the pressure when everyone is trying to be
really fast. It's quite something to succeed when everyone has the
same goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwegians apparently agree. In a poll conducted last month by
the newspaper Verdens Gang, readers were asked to name their
``Norwegian of the 20th century.'' Daehlie came in third behind the
explorer and humanist Thor Heyerdahl and Norway's first female
Prime Minister, Gro Harlem Brundtland. In fourth place was Fridtjof
Nansen, a former Nobel Peace Prize winner and North Pole explorer.
Other notables were, in sixth, Roald Amundsen, the first man to
reach the South Pole and, eighth, Edvard Munch, one of the
century's foremost painters. Munch's most widely known work, ``The
Scream,'' is a fine approximation of how Daehlie looked at the end
of his 50K race in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Norway, there are a lot of children right now who would
like to be me; they are competing and falling over the finish
line,'' Daehlie said wryly.
</P>
<P>
   Daehlie's professional goal is to compete until the Winter
Olympics in Salt Lake City in 2002. But he has personal goals as
well, and so he no longer plans to train with the Norwegian
national team in the off season. Until this month, he was training
on his own near his home in Nannestad, and he also no longer
intends to compete for the overall World Cup title. After the World
Cup season begins on Monday, he plans to race regularly until
Christmas and then peak for the world championships in Ramsau,
Austria, in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being out with the team for 200 days a year in hotels is a bit
problematic for being a father,'' Daehlie said. ``So far, it has
been going very well, and if it works I will keep the same program
until Salt Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in Salt Lake City that Daehlie won his first World Cup
race in December 1989, and Daehlie said that the desire to come
full circle was part of his decision to ski on. So was financial
security, and Daehlie, unlike many a Norwegian skikonge (ski king)
of Olympiads past is increasingly secure. He has numerous sponsors
and his own clothing company, whose outfits the American Nordic
team will be wearing in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   What Daehlie wants is to convert Americans to his sport, which
is about as popular with spectators in the United States as cricket
or bullfighting and lacks a worldwide base and talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little hard for me to be famous in America I think, but
it would be nice to present cross-country skiing in America like
Stein Eriksen did with Alpine skiing,'' Daehlie said.
</P>
<P>
   Eriksen, a fellow Norwegian, won the giant slalom at the 1952
Winter Olympics in Oslo and three gold medals at the 1954 world
championships. He then directed ski schools at numerous American
resorts, playing a role in popularizing skiing with his worldly
manner and good looks.
</P>
<P>
   Daehlie recognizes that the pain etched on his face in
mid-effort and the icicles that form on his red eyebrows are not
necessarily the perfect pitch, but he is not really interested in
pushing weekend athletes beyond their limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want is to get more children out of the house and out
in the forest,'' he said. ``Because in Europe, the people,
especially the young people are more and more sitting still and
watching videos or using the Internet. It was quite different 10 or
15 years ago, and I am concerned for my sport and the way people
are living right now. We are not using our bodies the way we
should.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-country is maybe the greatest way to work out for
people. You know, in the United States, the Nordic Track machine is
a best seller, and it's a machine where you ski in your living
room. But the best way of doing it is in the nature. You need to
breathe the air, see the birds and the animals. That way the next
generation knows that the meat doesn't just come from shops.''
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of Daehlies already knows. Sivert, age 4,
began competing in cross-country races last winter. Sander, not yet
2, was recently given his first pair of skis. There are plenty of
other Norwegian children receiving the same treatment. Daehlie's
records could already be in danger, and he has no one to blame but
himself. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
