<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2970 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TEX-SCHRAMM-TEX     11-28 1769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TEX-SCHRAMM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO BUILT THE COWBOYS IS ALIVE AND WELL; JUST ASK HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was the father of football's instant replay. He hired Tom
Landry. He originated the cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury boxes. The helmet with the star. The hole in the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   Tex Schramm did all that.
</P>
<P>
   When he was fired/resigned/left-in-a-huff one April day in 1989,
Schramm left behind one of sports' greatest success stories. The
Cowboys enjoyed 20 consecutive winning seasons during Schramm's
reign as president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys became a Thanksgiving tradition. They rose to be
named America's Team.
</P>
<P>
   Tex Schramm did all that.
</P>
<P>
   In the autumn of his 78th year, Schramm sits in his north Dallas
home and, if you prod him, reflects on four decades of NFL
memories.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a good sitter. Never was.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm is a doer. A dreamer. A man whose unique vision helped
pave the way for the NFL's rise to prominence.
</P>
<P>
   His back aches _ he's had three surgeries _ but his mind remains
sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know enough about what the league's problems are
now,'' he said, issuing a disclaimer. ``I'm not like those people
who were outside of football who were always telling me what I
should do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I would do with the league now.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But since someone asked, Schramm wonders why instant
replay can't maintain a toehold. He thinks the salary cap is a good
idea gone bad. He thinks free agency will harm the game's
popularity. And don't get him started on the current commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Schramm always has spoken his mind, lest someone
speak it for him. Long before Jerry Jones fell in love with the TV
newsbite, Schramm was spin-doctoring the state of the Cowboys on
his weekly television and radio shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Tex Schramm'', the radio show was called.
</P>
<P>
   And you still can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I appreciate most, I think, is how lucky I was to
come along at the time I did,'' Schramm said. ``The National
Football League was undergoing its biggest boom, its greatest
growth. Television was doing the same thing. They almost came up
together and, in some ways, were responsible for each other's
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I look at it today, I don't see the same picture.
Today it's a different game, a different life.'' `Too much ...
business'
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change in the NFL, Schramm admits, is the money.
When the late Clint Murchison launched the expansion franchise in
Dallas in 1960, he paid the NFL $50,000 for the franchise and
$500,000 for the veteran players taken in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, Murchison's $550,000 investment would
be sold to Bum Bright for $60 million, who in turn would later sell
it to Jones for $147 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think today there is too much focus on the business aspects,
the money, than on the product, which is the game itself,'' Schramm
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up when people like George Halas and George
Preston Marshall were in the league, and their feeling was always
that the product _ the game _ had to be the No. 1 priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Without competitive balance, in other words, Schramm said he
believes that the NFL suffers. He cites the foundation-cementing
decision in 1961, when the league received its first network
contract, to share the TV revenue equally among all teams. Getting
the teams in New York, Chicago and Los Angeles to agree to the
deal, Schramm said, made the NFL what it became.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw where the New York Yankees signed a $500 million
cable contract,'' he said. ``They're going to get all the best
players. Is it any wonder why, in baseball, the teams with the
highest payrolls seem to have the best teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the theory of free agency cannot work in a team
sport. This isn't like boxing, where you have a heavyweight
champion, and everyone will pay to see someone fight the champ. In
football, you've got to have two people playing the game. You can't
have just a handful of good teams and the rest as a chorus line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make the competition. You have to have a system in
which teams have the opportunity to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Schramm is aghast at what he has seen free agency do to
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can have a sport and have somebody do what they did
to the Florida Marlins, that's a pretty bad commentary,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, Montreal sits up there, apparently with good
scouts and a good farm system. They bring them up, and as soon as
the guys show that they can play, they sell them for money.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, Schramm's own dynasty began to crumble, in the
mid-1980s. He himself could see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   He could see the age, not just in the veteran players but in
Landry's coaching staff. He could see the toll from so many years
of picking deep in the drafting order.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, according to others, Schramm was getting mixed
messages from Landry about the coach's quasi-impending retirement.
It was only after Landry suggested that Tex plan some sort of
orderly transition that Schramm, in 1986, hired Paul Hackett from
the San Francisco 49ers to be the Cowboys' new offensive
coordinator. Two seasons later, Hackett found his role being
increasingly diminished. One memorable Tuesday, Landry was standing
at his weekly news conference when he announced that, yes, he
planned to stay around for as long as it took to rebuild the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm has never made a secret of what his plans had been. At
Super Bowl XXIII in Miami in January 1989 _ only weeks before the
world-inverting sale that Schramm and Landry never saw coming _ the
Cowboys' official party watched the game with an up-and-coming
young coach Schramm thought would make a promising successor to
Landry: Jimmy Johnson. `You can't sit back ... '
</P>
<P>
   Change comes, Schramm knows now. Nothing is forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think things are always going to be that way,'' he said.
``In my time it was pro football, but 50 years from now, there may
be something entirely different that is the No. 1 thing. Like
NASCAR _ look at these tracks and stadiums that they're building
now and all the money involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a different set of people growing up now that have
been raised on technology. What I'm saying is, you can't sit back
and think you've got the world by the tail, because that's what
baseball thought.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Schramm worries that the NFL is not taking care
of the details. When he was the loudest voice on the league's
then-powerful competition committee, the group would meet days
ahead of the annual regular NFL meetings. If the average score of
the average NFL game was falling, the committee would react to it.
If the games were running too long, the committee would recommend
ways to speed things up.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm wasn't shy about asking the NFL to, in effect, reinvent
itself every few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought the worst mistake you could make is not
recognizing that the times are changing and the players are
changing,'' Schramm said. ``You need to realize that 15, 20 years
from now, it's going to be hard to beat what you're going to be
able to see in your own home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at a whole new generation. I don't think that
the youngster of today is going to tolerate some of the sports of
today. That's why you see things like skateboarding, rollerblading,
the X-Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you sit back and say that these are the major sports
today and it's going to be that way forever, you're just not
looking at history.''
</P>
<P>
   Tex Schramm need not worry, however, about his own place in
history. In 1991, he was selected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame,
the first, as he puts it, ``of my kind'' to be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, however, Schramm remains the only one of the Cowboys'
seven Hall of Fame inductees who is not also enshrined in the
club's Ring of Honor. Jones, who fired Schramm _ or forced him to
resign, depending on which version of the story you've heard _ has
the ultimate say in that.
</P>
<P>
   It has been ``months and months'' since Schramm and Jones last
spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea why he would have any bitterness about
me,'' Schramm said, ``but I guess he does. In the 10 years, I've
never said anything derogatory about him in the media or about
anything that has happened. Though a lot of people wanted me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Schramm still attends Cowboys games, sitting in the same box
suite that he occupied when he was with the club. As part of his
severance agreement with Jones, Schramm was allowed to retain the
box for 10 years. Those 10 years will expire at the end of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm and his wife, Marty, spend most of their time either
home or at their condominium in Key West, Fla. Tex appears happy,
but he confesses that there is a void in the couple's life.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Mardee Schramm Smith, died in June 1997, from a
rare form of cancer. Mardee was 52.
</P>
<P>
   Tex calls her death ``more difficult than anything else I've
been involved with. To a father, there's nothing like a daughter.
To lose one is a very, very difficult thing to accept.'' `I'm not
the only nut ... '
</P>
<P>
   Down in Key West, Schramm can get away and absorb himself in his
other passion: marlin fishing. He doesn't keep and mount the big
fish, preferring to tag and release them instead.
</P>
<P>
   His latest venture in marlin-hunting is vintage Schramm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to catch a marlin fishing off the beach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To do it, Schramm has picked out a kite that will travel the
quarter-mile from the shoreline and drop his bait. He has picked
out the island in the Bahamas where, when the southeast wind blows
just right, the kite and its hook can slip out beyond the coral
reef.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm the only nut doing this,'' he said. ``I'm trying to be
the first one to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schramm has never been a good sitter, not even when he fishes.
</P>
<P>
   In the autumn of his 78th year, he prefers to remember the good
things, rather than the foul memories that ended his time with the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you one thing that makes me feel great,'' he said.
``When I go somewhere, people always come up and say, `Tex Schramm?
All I want to do is say thank you for a lot of great seasons and
great memories.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happened hundreds of times. In airports, wherever. And
it's amazing. It obviously makes me feel very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Let it be recorded that, other than his weakening back, The Man
Who Built the Cowboys is very much alive and well these days.
</P>
<P>
   He can still talk a little football. He can still talk a little
life.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Tex Schramm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
