<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHIPPERS29-COX     11-28 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHIPPERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Culture clash: Chicagoan in Starr light
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ David Schippers is known as a bare-knuckled
attorney, the man who slapped handcuffs on Chicago mobster Sam
Giancana as a 30-year-old federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to asking independent counsel Kenneth Starr
questions about his investigation of President Clinton, Schippers
turned soft.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than establish facts in the case against the president,
Schippers last week asked Starr questions that allowed the
prosecutor to try to rehabilitate himself before a national
television audience that has grown tired of the whole scandal. At
the end of 30 minutes of questioning, Republican members of the
committee and some of those in the audience stood and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked out of the Rayburn Office Building that night,
Schippers turned and grinned. ``The highlight of the night was the
standing ovation for Ken Starr,'' said the born and bred Chicago
Democrat. ``The man deserves that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no disputing that the posh House Judiciary Committee
chamber on Capitol Hill is a far different forum from the
black-and-white world of the federal courthouse where Schippers
once took down mobsters or the county courthouse where Schippers
more recently has defended the likes of a serial killer and a porn
star named Seka.
</P>
<P>
   But as the committee continues its impeachment hearings Tuesday
to debate the consequences of perjury, the real question is: Can
Schippers pull it off?
</P>
<P>
   Can this salty Chicagoan, stocky in his signature drab brown
suits, beat back the polished presidential defense team?
</P>
<P>
   Friends defend the way Schippers questioned Starr and argue that
he brings a much needed outsider's perspective to Washington. He
has a finely tuned moral compass and a Midwestern directness for
the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows they trade horses for cows in Washington all the
time,'' said Peter Vaira, former U.S. attorney of Philadelphia, who
knows Schippers from Chicago when he ran an organized crime strike
force under the direction of former U.S. Attorney General Robert F.
Kennedy. ``He is going to tell them what he thinks. They might not
like it, but it will be the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Catholic world of Schippers, who spent five years
studying the priesthood before he met his wife, few things are
worse than lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes lying is a major transgression,'' said David
Schippers Jr., his eldest son, recalling a childhood episode in
which his father caught him lying about smoking cigarettes and was
more concerned about his not telling the truth than his smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could do anything wrong growing up, but if you lied, you
really had it,'' the younger Schippers said. ``To him, it requires
severe consequences when you lie _ and it doesn't matter if you're
a Democrat or a Republican doing the lying.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good because the other axiom the senior Schippers
instilled in each of his 10 children and 25 grandchildren is this:
``There are three things you should never bet against: God, the
Democratic Party and the Chicago White Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat with prosecutor's heart
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, who has voted for Clinton twice, is proud of his
Democratic lineage.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of northwest Chicago, Schippers was a regular at the
45th Ward Democratic headquarters, taking his children there to
celebrate election night with the same vigor he used to steer them
to Mass. Twenty years ago, he even ran on the Democratic ticket to
be Cook County sheriff, a job that for Chicago politicians is more
about patronage than law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is first cousin Tom Lyons, who runs the Cook
County Democratic Party, arguably one of the most powerful of the
party's strongholds given its storied machine-like way of turning
out the Democratic vote.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, it would seem odd that Schippers, a 68-year-old
Democrat at the twilight of a distinguished legal career, is
running an impeachment investigation for a conservative Republican
like Henry Hyde of Illinois, who heads the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Just how did Hyde lure Schippers to Washington in the first
place?
</P>
<P>
   The two began a casual friendship years ago when they served on
the Illinois Legislative Crime Investigation Committee when Hyde
was a state representative. They renewed that bond three years ago
when both were sworn in as papal knights in the Equestrian Order of
the Holy Sepulcher by the late Cardinal Joseph Bernardin.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing Schippers as lead counsel, Hyde may have thought he
was heading off charges of partisanship while bringing aboard a
lawyer with knowledge of the intricacies of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Schippers helped write an article that reviewed the
impeachment inquiry against President Richard Nixon and concluded
the evidence suggested that Nixon may have been guilty of
subornation of perjury (asking someone to lie under oath) and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   But, above all else, Schippers, who will be paid $130,000
annually in his government job, is a relentless prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave's a prosecutor at heart. He will follow the evidence
wherever it goes,'' said Lyons, his Democratic cousin. ``I just
don't happen to agree where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   `Nothing but the truth'
</P>
<P>
   When Starr's 445-page report arrived Sept. 9 on Capitol Hill,
Schippers told reporters the inquiry would be bipartisan and free
of the political tirades that commonly occur on Capitol Hill.
``This is going to be bipartisan,'' Schippers said. ``I'm a proud
Democrat, but I'm a lawyer and human being first. I will call it as
I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   One month later, Schippers announced there was ``substantial and
credible evidence'' that Clinton committed 15 impeachable crimes,
but Schippers did so without calling a single witness to confirm or
deny the 18 boxes of evidence accompanying Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone wondering what Schippers thinks about the merits of the
Starr report need look no further than what he told the Judiciary
Committee panel last month when he announced the 15 impeachable
offenses for which he believed there were grounds for
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle that every witness in every case must tell the
truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth is the foundation
of the American system of justice,'' Schippers said. ``If lying
under oath is tolerated and, when exposed, is not visited with
immediate and substantial adverse consequences, the integrity of
this country's entire judicial process is fatally compromised and
that process will inevitably collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Judiciary Committee Democrats argue that lying about sex
should not be placed in the same category as committing bribery,
treason or high crimes and misdemeanors. The Clinton case focuses
on lying about sex, not about state secrets, Democrats say.
</P>
<P>
   But Schippers sees it differently. ``The subject matter of the
underlying case, whether civil or criminal, and the circumstances
under which the testimony is given are of no significance
whatever,'' he told the committee. ``It is the oath itself that is
sacred and must be enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   As chief counsel, Schippers has said his role is to follow the
facts wherever they may lead. But Democrats contend he has
delivered his opinion long before the facts were known and
challenged. That can be seen, they say, in his final statement to
the committee, in which he paraphrased Sir Thomas More from the
famous play about his life. ``The laws of this country are the
great barriers that protect the citizens from the winds of evil and
tyranny,'' he said. ``If we permit one of those walls to fall, who
will be able to stand in the winds that follow?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if he were closing a case, Schippers looked hard at the
committee members. ``You are not being watched only by the
individuals in this room or even by the immense television audience
throughout the world. Fifteen generations of Americans, our fellow
Americans, are looking down on and judging what you do today,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, his friends say, is classic Schippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is exceptionally hard working and his integrity is
beyond reproach,'' said Raymond McKoski, the chief judge of Lake
County, Ill., who as a young state attorney prosecuted Larry Eyler,
a serial killer who was defended by Schippers. ``You could rely on
his word. He never tried to shade or color what he was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are times when Schippers' comments seem calculated for
effect. At a news conference after his speech to the committee,
Schippers joked to the Washington media that he wished his
Styrofoam cup had ``some gin in it,'' as he sure could use some.
(He neglected to say he is a teetotaler.)
</P>
<P>
   And even after delivering a speech so offensive to Democrats
that they had it stricken from the record, Schippers told reporters
he had no preconceived belief about the president's guilt or
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understood my role, it was to take the referral given to
me, examine all the evidence and then come up with an independent
judgment in what thaed with Schippers on the strike force.
``Washington isn't ready for Dave Schippers because Washington as a
whole is filled with corruption, it is a cesspool of corruption,
and Dave Schippers is going to go in and make mincemeat out of
these high-priced attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
