<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tossing coins
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The coin-toss blunder by referee Phil Luckett on
Thursday might go down as one of the biggest gaffes in league
history. But there have probably been more famous coin tosses in
the annals of professional football. In the '62 AFL championship
game, Dallas Texans tailback Abner Haynes opted to kick off after
winning an overtime coin toss. Pittsburgh owner Art Rooney won the
rights to quarterback Terry Bradshaw in the '70 draft via a coin
toss, and the Steelers won four Super Bowls under his direction. A
few years ago, New England linebacker Vincent Brown had to correct
the referee on the pregame coin toss. Just before the '63 AFL
season, the San Diego Chargers and Denver Broncos both claimed
rights to quarterback Tobin Rote, who was returning from a stint in
the CFL. Chargers coach Sid Gillman won a coin toss with
counterpart Jack Faulkner for Rote. He teamed with wide receiver
Lance Alworth to provide the Chargers an explosive passing attack
and they went on to capture the '63 AFL championship.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert to Seahawks?
</P>
<P>
   Seattle owner Paul Allen and team president Bob Whitsitt are
increasingly impressed by the work of vice president of football
operations Randy Mueller. That could mean the Seahawks won't pursue
Green Bay's Mike Holmgren for the combined post of coach-GM. Under
such a scenario, the man topping Seattle's wish-list to succeed
Dennis Erickson probably would be former San Francisco coach George
Seifert. With the odds improving on June Jones keeping the job in
San Diego, which is what GM Bobby Beathard hopes for, the position
that could most interest Holmgren now might be with the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe hurting
</P>
<P>
   Unless a fractured right index finger improves this morning, New
England quarterback Drew Bledsoe won't be able to start today
against Buffalo. Bledsoe was unable to work on Friday and
seventh-year veteran Scott Zolak took all the snaps with the No. 1
unit. Zolak has started only five games in his career, none since
1995. Embattled coach Pete Carroll had hoped a red-hot Bledsoe and
the return to health of wide receiver Terry Glenn might spark his
team during the December stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   Dripping with irony
</P>
<P>
   With owner Bob Kraft poised to move the Patriots to Hartford,
Conn., the media in the Boston area spent much of the week seeking
a quote from his past that might cast him in a bad light. They came
up with this childhood memory by Kraft, a Boston native, on the
relocation of baseball's Boston Braves to Milwaukee: ``They were my
team. To this day, I regret that they left. A part of me died on
that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Colts clobbered
</P>
<P>
   The Colts return to Baltimore today for the first time since
abandoning the city in 1984, and many former players from the
city's storied NFL history will be on hand to witness what they
hope will be sweet revenge. ``If (the Ravens) win by 100, it won't
be enough, but it will be some measure of vindication,''
quarterback Johnny Unitas said. Former Colts players insisted that
their ire is somewhat assuaged by the fact owner Robert Irsay has
died, but they still harbor a deep grudge. Hall of Fame defensive
tackle Art Donovan noted that the New York Jets will wear a decal
on their helmets in memory of coach Weeb Ewbank, who died two weeks
ago. ``Weeb coached the Colts, too,'' Donovan said. ``But that team
can't wear a decal honoring him. He was part of this city's
heritage, and he'd roll over in his grave if these Colts tried to
claim him as one of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Eric Allen (knee) for the season has ended the
experiment with Oakland corner Charles Woodson learning some
wide-receiver plays.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
