<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FEATURE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calls hardly heads-up
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For years, NFL coaches and talent scouts have had a
saying: The tape doesn't lie.
</P>
<P>
   The reference, of course, is to videotape, that celluloid stuff
that is to player analysis what Ace bandages are to sprained
ankles.
</P>
<P>
   But unless your name is Richard Nixon and Rosemary Woods is your
secretary, the audiotape usually doesn't fib, either. League
officials might keep that in mind when they begin to dissect the
Thanksgiving Day snafu now known as Coin-flipgate.
</P>
<P>
   The incredible gaffe by referee Phil Luckett at the beginning of
overtime in the contest between the Steelers and Lions imperfectly
culminated an afternoon of dubious decisions that infuriated both
coaches. In front of a national TV audience, Steelers fullback
Jerome Bettis called out, ``Tails!'' and Luckett somehow heard,
``Heads!'' For those who haven't yet seen replays, the coin landed
tails-side up.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrecting the old ``Heads-they-win-and-tails-you-lose''
routine, Luckett awarded the option to the Lions, victimized most
of the day by poor officiating calls. Detroit defensive end Robert
Porcher quit snickering long enough to decide that his team would
receive.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Pittsburgh radio station KDKA on Saturday denied
a report that it had an enhanced audio with an unidentified voice
saying, ``Heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lions took the kickoff, drove to Jason Hanson's game-winning
field goal, then hustled home to give thanks for the greatest
makeup call in league history. The Steelers, beneficiaries of at
least three questionable decisions, should have won in regulation
but still didn't deserve to lose on such an oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Even on Friday afternoon, Porcher had trouble stifling his
laughter. ``All I'm saying is, `Happy Thanksgiving, everybody,'''
Porcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Happy for everybody, that is, except NFL officials, who now must
deal with this holiday leftover. Even on a day off, NFL vice
president Greg Aiello was hounded at home Friday by reporters and
fans seeking answers and offering solutions. One fan suggested
using coin-flip flip-cards reading ``heads'' and ``tails'' that the
captain would hand the referee while the coin is in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Aiello confirmed that the coin flip will be reviewed but, with
supervisor of officials Jerry Seeman out of the office until
Monday, nothing is imminent. Aiello said, ``Just when you think
you've seen it all ...''
</P>
<P>
   What coaches, players and fans have seen too much of this season
is poor officiating. For the first time in several years, it's
possible to argue a viable case that officials have decided the
outcomes of some games.
</P>
<P>
   Already the mistake by Luckett has refueled the passions of
instant-replay advocates. But the coin toss would not have come
under the purview of any of their recent replay proposals. Instead,
for those who recall the movie ``The Conversation,'' figuring out
the Luckett error conjures up mental images of Gene Hackman huddled
in a nondescript van and wearing a headset.
</P>
<P>
   Given the poor performance of game officials, replay represents
only part of a solution. Officials must be held accountable,
sanctioned when necessary. Seeman, the mother hen who is so
defensive, also must be scrutinized. There is no quick fix, but a
game that's become too quick for some aging officials deserves a
remedy.
</P>
<P>
   League officials hinted Friday that Luckett faces sanction,
perhaps a one-game suspension, if a review upholds Bettis'
contention.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the attention on Luckett's call might reinforce
a notion shared by many coaches: Officials might be called
``zebras'' because of the striped shirts, but on Thanksgiving
afternoon they looked more like turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
