<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCNOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Packers search for coach
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After saying that Mike Holmgren probably will be
coaching elsewhere in 1999, Green Bay general manager Ron Wolf
conceded that at some point, he might have to begin looking at
Packers assistants and those around the league in a different
light. ``I guess there will come a time when I have to view them
(as possible replacements),'' he said. ``But before I do, I want to
convince myself we've exhausted every opportunity to bring Mike
back here.'' It's a good bet that Wolf already has compiled a short
list, and it probably includes current Packers aides Sherman Lewis
(offensive coordinator) and Andy Reid (quarterbacks), along with
Eagles coach Ray Rhodes. Rumored not to be on Wolf's wish-list is
San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci, who's negotating a contract
extension with the 49ers, and Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering no Moss
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his three-touchdown performance against Dallas on
Thanksgiving Day, the first chink appeared in the armor of
Minnesota wideout Randy Moss. The Vikings rookie star agreed to a
post-game interview with Fox analyst John Madden, then blew off the
rest of the media, many of them national reporters who covered the
game just because of him. Coach Dennis Green condoned the action,
rationalizing that Moss ``only caught three passes.'' Of course,
they were for TDs of 51, 51 and 56 yards. With wide receiver Jake
Reed (back) out for a month and tailback Robert Smith (knee) down
for at least two weeks, Moss figures to become even more central to
the offense. He'd better get used to attention, because quarterback
Randall Cunningham and coordinator Brian Billick are going to force
the ball to him.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves leads voting
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons' Dan Reeves, whose resurrection of a
moribund franchise figures to make him a prime contender for coach
of the year, already leads in one such poll. Since Nov. 1, the
league's Internet site (www.nfl.com) has been conducting balloting
for Staples coach of the year honors. Reeves holds a slight lead on
Green, Mike Shanahan (Denver), Jon Gruden (Oakland) and Chan Gailey
(Dallas).
</P>
<P>
   Secondary matters
</P>
<P>
   An already-ailing Green Bay secondary figures to be paper-thin
for today's matchup with Philadelphia. If neither Craig Newsome nor
Rod Smith can line up, Darren Sharper will move from free safety to
left cornerback. Pat Terrell would replace Sharper at free safety,
and Mike Prior, who has been ineffective lately, probably would
play in most nickel situations. ``We're into the cut-and-paste
mode,'' coordinator Fritz Shurmur said.
</P>
<P>
   Flying high
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly a half-season, but Arizona's Jake Plummer finally
has grasped the West Coast-style scheme installed by first-year
coordinator Marc Trestman and it could mean the Cardinals' first
playoff berth in a non-strike year since 1975. Plummer is more
relaxed now that Trestman has allowed him to use the no-huddle
more, and wide receivers Frank Sanders and Rob Moore are excellent
at reading his ad-lib moves. ``They're a scary offense when
(Plummer) starts drawing up plays in the dirt,'' Dallas defensive
coordinator Dave Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Steep price
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officials have indicated that they could have a tough
time paying tailback Jamal Anderson more than the $5.4 million a
year being earned by quarterback Chris Chandler. Getting a contract
extension, then, could be sticky. According to NFLPA figures, the
top six highest-paid tailbacks _ Curtis Martin (Jets), Terrell
Davis (Broncos), Dorsey Levens (Packers), Robert Smith (Vikings),
Emmitt Smith (Cowboys) and Barry Sanders (Lions) _ average about
$5.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
