<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ODDS-ENDS29-COX     11-28 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ODDS-ENDS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-minute drill with Vikings' Brian Billick
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Minnesota Vikings offensive coordinator Brian Billick.
</P>
<P>
   Topic: Scripting a game plan.
</P>
<P>
   Background: After 13 years as a college assistant, Billick
joined coach Dennis Green's staff in 1992 and was elevated to
coordinator midway through the '93 season. In his four full
seasons, the Vikings' offense has ranked No. 8 or better three
times and never been lower than 12th. Billick, 44, uses extensive
computer analyses to formulate the game plan and typically will
``script'' the first 15-20 plays.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does your scripting perhaps differ from that of Mike
Holmgren in Green Bay or San Francisco's Steve Mariucci?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many coaches who script the first few series will decide,
'OK, this is what we want on the first play (of the game), and then
we'll come back with this on the second snap.' We script more for
down and distance, with two or three plays for each scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the early stages of a game, how much does a variety of
formations allow you to ascertain what a defense is doing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Diversity of formation is a big key. We'll put, say, (wide
receiver) Randy Moss in the slot to see how the defense will react.
The next time, we'll have him out wide just to get a feel for what
the defense will do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you use that knowledge later in the game?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can look at the Polaroid shots and see how a defense
responds to a certain look. That may narrow or expand the range of
calls available to you. It affords you guidelines on situational
options.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON . . .
</P>
<P>
   Veterans: San Diego leads the NFL in defense against the run,
but it faces the ultimate test in Denver tailback Terrell Davis. To
contain Davis, the Chargers will need strong outings by linebacker
Junior Seau and strong safety Rodney Harrison, who will play up
close to the line.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie: Former Vanderbilt star Corey Chavous was drafted as a
safety by Arizona, but with oft-injured Tom Knight again sidelined,
Chavous starts today at cornerback. With Aeneas Williams on the
opposite side, Chavous figures to see plenty of passes thrown his
way by Kansas City quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent: The rumors are that Seattle quarterback Warren Moon
either will retire or be released after the season. Two-year
veteran John Kitna gets his second career start today, and it
serves in part as an audition for the future. He could battle John
Friesz for the starter's spot in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: The Ravens' Ted Marchibroda coached the Colts both in
Baltimore (1975-79) and Indianapolis (1992-95). Today, he's under
pressure from fans with long memories to vanquish the much-despised
Colts, who under the stewardship of late owner Bob Irsay exited
Baltimore in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   TIP SHEET
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Schiller of Turner Sports and Dick Ebersol of NBC should
announce within two weeks that their new football league will begin
play in June 2000. ... One AFC West team mulling a coaching change
has begun gauging interest of Florida's Steve Spurrier. ...
Tailback Lawrence Phillips, a two-time loser in the NFL, will try
to resurrect his career in the World League. ... University of
Washington quarterback Brock Huard, a junior who nearly left after
the '97 season, already has filed the papers to make him eligible
for the '99 draft. ... Falcons backup quarterback Steve DeBerg was
pulled over for speeding recently on I-85, but his blood-alcohol
level was barely under the state's .08 limit for DUI. ... Kansas
City insiders insist that coach Marty Schottenheimer will be back
in '99, but they aren't so sure about linebacker Derrick Thomas.
... St. Louis personnel director Charley Armey is under even more
fire than coach Dick Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   Former Vikings coach Jerry Burns has offered to be a bone-marrow
donor for Iowa aide Bob Elliott, who suffers from a clotting
disorder. Elliott is son of longtime Hawkeyes AD Bump Elliott and,
before his illness, thought to be a possible successor to Hayden
Fry.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Not even being under the thumb of Jets coach Bill Parcells could
halt the bad behavior of linebacker Bryan Cox. Cox was fined
$10,000 for roughness against Oilers quarterback Steve McNair,
then, typically, charged the NFL with racism.
</P>
