<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banks hobbling but game
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ His career has been a flash of brilliance one week,
a glimpse of ineptitude the next. But one thing that can be said
about St. Louis Rams quarterback Tony Banks: He always shows up for
work.
</P>
<P>
   Banks will start his 41st consecutive game this afternoon at the
Trans World Dome against the Falcons, a streak that places him
fourth among active quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   With 104 straight appearances opening games, Brett Favre of
Green Bay leads the list. Next is Tampa Bay's Trent Dilfer with 59
and New England's Drew Bledsoe with 44. And then there is Banks.
</P>
<P>
   His availability for the Atlanta game was questionable because
of a sore right ankle suffered in last week's loss to the Carolina
Panthers. However, Banks practiced with the team Thursday,
prompting optimism from coach Dick Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked fine,'' Vermeil said. ``He threw the ball well.
He'll start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't ask him to move a lot, but he did all his drop-back
stuff and roll-out stuff. He's a tough guy.''
</P>
<P>
   With an offensive line that is young and inconsistent, Banks has
taken a beating from aggressive pass rushers. ``He's taken probably
more shots than all of them,'' Vermeil said.
</P>
<P>
   Banks did not practice Wednesday, but did during a light workout
on Thanksgiving Day. He reported some stiffness and tenderness when
making some moves. Still, it's not enough to keep him from
starting.
</P>
<P>
   However, with his mobility limited, Banks, a fleet-footed sort
who can break off a big run with his deft ability to escape the
pocket, said he'll be more of a pocket passer against the Falcons
than a roll-out one. The game plan doesn't call for as many
rollouts and bootlegs. ``Atlanta took that away from us last time
we played them anyway,'' he said. ``So they're ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the Falcons certainly would like to put
pressure on Banks as much as possible, the thinking being to make
him run or make a decision while hobbling. Still, Banks insists he
will not force the ball into coverage just to get rid of it before
a sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my ankle's bothering me, probably I will have to change
some things,'' Banks said. ``But if it's just a little pain and I
can play through it, I'll try to make some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Backup Steve Bono, a former 49er, will play if Banks can't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
