</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-PHILOSOPHY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Reeves difference: Quality upgrade
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Whenever he's on his way to a road game, Atlanta
Falcons coach Dan Reeves always flies first class. This season,
he's trying to make sure that players get an upgrade, too.
</P>
<P>
   At Reeves' urging, John Knox, administrative assistant/finance
for the Falcons, ordered bigger planes for most of this season's
road trips, a concession to the average size of NFL players and an
attempt to reward them for their work.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the Falcons would charter Boeing 727s for most
games, and move up to a Boeing 757 _ which is more expensive _ for
long trips to the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Both planes have three seats on both sides of the aisle, but
seats in the 757 are wider by a few inches, and there are more of
them. Also, there are 24 first class seats in a 757, to 12 in a
727.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference,'' linebacker Cornelius Bennett
said. ``Those couple hours we spend on the plane are valuable time.
You get somebody with a sore shoulder or something and you get
cramped up on a plane and something can swell up.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Reeves decided a long time ago to try to make life
easier on the road, and, for that matter, at home.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the few coaches who doesn't require players to
check into a hotel the night before home games. Also, whether at
home or on the road, he schedules no meeting the night before
games, when almost every other team meets. Instead, those meetings
are held the morning of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought (staying in a hotel the night before home
games) accomplished anything,'' he said. ``For a family man, that's
tough. These guys don't see their kids much, and their family
really suffers during the season. One of the only chances to do
something quality with your family would be the night before a game
(at home).''
</P>
<P>
   Having a few hours of free time on road trips is a great thing
for players. For example, when the team made two trips to New York
in October, some players went into the city for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they need it, but the NFL's Collective Bargaining
Agreement calls for each player to get a $37 dinner allowance on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives guys a chance to get in town, get a good meal, and
not rush around,'' said Bennett, who had 7:30 p.m. meetings the
night before games when he played with Buffalo. ``It's very
professional. (Reeves) treats us as men, and it's up to us to
behave that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of cities, the team is using different hotels this
year than in the past. In St. Louis, for example, the Falcons
stayed at a Marriott near the TWA Dome. But this year, they spent
Saturday night at Adam's Mark because it has enough space on one
floor to accommodate the team's pregame meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a conscious effort to stay in nice, newer properties
with good meeting space,'' Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   Although players have most of their time to themselves the night
before road games, there is an 11 p.m. hotel curfew and bed check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's nice for them on the road to be able to go out
and get themselves a nice meal,'' Reeves said. ``As long as they're
paying attention during the week, I don't think it's a big deal.
I've never fined a person for being out the night before. If I had
a problem with it, then we've got the wrong kind of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel operator is instructed not to let calls through to
players' rooms after curfew, and a security guard is posted on the
same floor as the players. It's his job to make sure that only
players are on the floor and to report player movement to team
security chief Doug Worthan, who usually stays in the room closest
to Reeves' suite.
</P>
<P>
   Players sleep two to a room, although they can have a single as
long as they pay for the difference in cost.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is the same on every road trip, and it's always served
four hours before game time at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The drink offerings are orange juice, apple juice, grapefruit
juice, grape juice, cola and diet cola, low-fat milk, two flavors
of sports drink and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   To eat, players choose from scrambled eggs, pancakes and French
toast with hot syrup, grits, sausage links, baked potatoes (with
sour cream, butter, grated cheese and bacon bits), spaghetti, hot
blueberry muffins, croissants, and cornbread, four kinds of cereal,
sliced apples, bananas, peaches, and strawberries, grilled boneless
chicken breasts and a build-your-own sandwich bar.
</P>
<P>
   And that's nothing compared to what players eat and drink _ no
alcohol allowed _ on the flight home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more food than you've ever seen consumed in two hours,''
Knox said. ``All kinds of meats, pastas, vegetables, salads. You
name it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, tonight's trip home from St. Louis will be a bad
example of the Falcons' new ways. They're flying one of the smaller
727s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta has been very good about (changing the team charters),
but because it's Thanksgiving weekend, and busiest travel day of
the year, they couldn't change it this late,'' Knox said. ``But
otherwise it's worked out great.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Terance Mathis said, ``Sometimes we get rewarded
with the bigger planes, and that's great, but it really doesn't
make a difference to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, though, is 5-foot-10 and 185 pounds. Defensive end
Lester Archambeau is 6-5, 275. He'll take the bigger planes, thank
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan always talks about how little things matter,'' he said.
``If you can stretch out on the plane, you won't be as stiff when
you arrive. Maybe that helps you play better.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT REEVES HAS BROUGHT TO THE FALCONS
</P>
<P>
   _ BIGGER PLANES: By upgrading to larger 757s from 727s, players
feel less cramped.
</P>
<P>
   _ FAMILY TIME: Reeves is one of the few NFL coaches who does not
require players to check into a hotel before home games.
</P>
<P>
   _ EARLY MEETING: Reeves will not hold a team meeting on the
night before a game, allowing players a few hours of free time to
hit the town when on the road.
</P>
<P>
   _ HOTEL UPGRADES: The team looks for ``nice, newer properties''
with ample space for team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
