<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM KEATING, 55, ART DEALER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Keating, a London-based art dealer who was born in the
United States and who helped the Australian financier Alan Bond put
together a collection of Australian artworks, died on Nov. 4 at his
home in London. He was 55.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, said his wife, Angela
Nevill-Keating.
</P>
<P>
   It was Keating who placed Bond's successful $53.9 million
telephone bid for van Gogh's ``Irises'' at Sotheby's in 1987.
Keating was also known for rediscovering the work of Paul Helleu,
the Belle Epoque artist.
</P>
<P>
   Keating was born in Savannah, Ga., and attended Benedictine
College in Savannah and the University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   After college he moved to London. In the late 1960s, he met
Angela Nevill while he was in Amsterdam one weekend attending a
Rembrandt exhibition. The couple eventually went into partnership,
forming Nevill Keating, private art dealers. They were married in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
