u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-JOHNSON-NYT &LR;      11-28 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLAN JOHNSON, 82, FORMER SAKS CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Minn., Calif., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Allan Raymond Johnson, a former chairman of Saks
Fifth Avenue who helped shepherd the elegant department store
through an era of rapid expansion, died on Thanksgiving Day at the
Mary Manning Walsh nursing home in Manhattan. He was 82 and had
lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from a stroke, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   During his years at Saks, Johnson was involved in the renovation
or addition of nearly two dozen stores, said his daughter Susan
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the son of a Saks executive, joined the store as
personnel director in 1945 and held a variety of senior executive
posts until he was named executive vice president in 1961. In 1969,
when his mentor, Adam Gimbel, retired, Johnson became the store's
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, he was given the added title of chief executive;
he held that job until 1978, when he was named a senior vice
president of Brown &AMP; Williamson Industries, then the store's parent
company.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to serve as chairman of Saks until 1979, when he
was appointed chairman of the Batus Retail Division, then the
corporate owner of Saks Fifth Avenue and Gimbel Brothers. Saks
Fifth Avenue was run for four decades by the Gimbel family, until
1969.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a popular executive who maintained a warm, familial
atmosphere at the store, said Helen O'Hagan, a former vice
president of public relations. He organized a glee club for
employees and held dinners to honor longtime employees, she said.
``It was really like a very big family,'' Ms. O'Hagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's personal touch _ what might be considered paternalism
today _ was credited with helping prevent his employees from
unionizing despite several organizing drives.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement in 1981, Johnson served on corporate
boards, including those of Viacom International Inc. and Shearson
Lehman Investments (now Salomon Smith Barney). He also served as
chairman of the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau, the
National Retail Merchants Association and the Fifth Avenue
Association. But his family said the organization he was most
devoted to was the Boy Scouts of America.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was divorced three times and is survived by his fourth
wife, Maria Toia Johnson, whom he married in 1980. In addition to
Ms. Johnson, who lives in Riverdale, the Bronx, he is survived by
three other daughters, Jane Fell of Rochester Hills, Minn., Kathy
Jones of Los Angeles and Barbara Hobin of Worcester, Mass.; a
brother, Patrick Raymond Johnson of Boston; seven grandchildren,
and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
