<HEADLINE>
EMIL REYNOLDS, 93, WORLD WAR II PHOTOGRAPHER  
 ANTHONY SALVATORE, 77, RECORDING ENGINEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ariz., Calif.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Emil G. Reynolds, a globe-trotting press photographer who
covered World War II and other events, died Nov. 22 at Monmouth
Medical Center in Long Branch, N.J. He was 93 and lived in Long
Branch.
 &HT;    Reynolds was born in Vienna but grew up in Newark, N.J. He
started his career with the old Newark Ledger before supplying his
work to United Press International, The Associated Press and
various newspapers in the United States and Mexico.
 &HT;    In World War II he covered nearly all fronts, working in the
China-Burma-India theater, the South Pacific and Europe and at the
Yalta Conference. His fluency in German came in handy at the
Potsdam peace conference and the war trials at Nuremberg. He
photographed Israel's war of independence and several Arab League
conferences.
 &HT;    His photographs appeared on the front pages of Newsweek, Time
and Life magazines, among others. A picture he took minutes after
the 1946 bombing of the King David Hotel in Jerusalem was published
around the world.
 &HT;    Reynolds is survived by a son, Paul, of Tempe, Ariz., and two
grandsons. His wife, Clara Silverman Reynolds, died in 1991 after
62 years of marriage.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony Salvatore, a Grammy-winning recording engineer, died on
Nov. 18 at Hackensack University Medical Center in Hackensack, N.J.
He was 77 and lived in Hasbrouck Heights, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Salvatore worked with RCA Records from 1955 to 1993, and then
retired to work independently. He won Grammys for recordings of
``Lohengrin'' (1966), ``Sweeney Todd'' (1979) and ``The Heifetz
Collection'' (1995), and was credited with having supervised more
than 1,000 recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists he worked with were the conductors Fritz
Reiner, Sir Thomas Beecham and Leopold Stokowski; the
instrumentalists Artur Rubinstein, Vladimir Horowitz and Van
Cliburn, and the vocalists Robert Merrill and Placido Domingo.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked on recordings by the Boston Symphony Orchestra,
the Royal Philharmonic, and the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Mary Jo; a daughter, Penny Salvatore
Shepos of Somerset, N.J.; a son, Jack, of Los Angeles; two
brothers, Gerald and Alfred, both of Parlin, N.J.; a sister, Palma
Salvatore Mallory of New York, and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
