<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-NEWHOUSE-NYT &LR;      11-28 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NEWHOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 THEODORE NEWHOUSE, 95; HELPED BUILD A COMMUNICATIONS EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Theodore Newhouse, who began a lifelong career in
publishing as a manager of a family-owned newspaper, The Long
Island Press, and helped his brothers assemble one of the nation's
biggest communications conglomerates, died Saturday at the Hebrew
Home for the Aged in the Riverdale section of the Bronx after a
long illness. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse was the last of the founding brothers who turned from
hawking newspapers on the street to buying newspaper companies. The
Newhouse holdings now include 26 newspapers; Conde Nast
Publications, which publishes The New Yorker, Vogue and Vanity
Fair; the Sunday newspaper supplement Parade, and interests in
cable television programming and cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   As the associate publisher of Newhouse newspapers, Newhouse had
kept up an active involvement in the family business until his
health began to fail about 12 years ago, said David Starr, the
senior editor of Newhouse newspapers. Newhouse moved into the
nursing home in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a hands-on, shirtsleeves manager and he knew more about
newspaper production than anybody,'' Starr said. ``He was the elder
person in the family and in the business. He was the consultant on
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse was raised in Bayonne, N.J., one of eight children of
impoverished immigrants. His father came from Russia; his mother
was from Austria. As a child, Newhouse helped the family by selling
newspapers on the street.
</P>
<P>
   His eldest brother, Samuel I. Newhouse, who died in 1979, got
the family into the publishing business when he bought The Staten
Island Advance, a financially troubled paper, in 1922. Newhouse,
then 19, was recruited to help out and get what he would later call
``on the job training,'' as was another brother, Norman, who died
in 1988. That fraternal management style came to characterize the
Newhouse family business.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Newhouse maintained a strong interest in
the arts. Even as he was working at the family's first newspapers,
he took night courses at several New York City universities in
opera, music and art, and studied dance in the summers.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Caroline H. Newhouse, whom he married in 1956
after the death of his first wife, Beatrice, Newhouse was a patron
of several arts organizations, including the New York City Opera
and Career Transition for Dancers, a nonprofit organization that
helps professional dancers after they retire.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Newhouse is survived by two
granddaughters, Julie Lobel and Amy Bermant Adler, both of New York
City, who are the children of his daughter, Jane Berman, and six
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
