<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mind over matter crucial for Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Maybe the question here today when Atlanta plays the
Rams is not whether the Falcons can win without Chris Chandler at
quarterback, but if they think they can win with someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's ankle is sprained badly enough that he almost
certainly won't play after not practicing this week. Second-year
man Tony Graziani took most of the snaps with the No. 1 offense
late in the week, and it appears he'll get the second start of his
career. A chance also remains that 44-year-old Steve DeBerg could
get his second start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves hasn't said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (9-2) are good when Chandler starts and finishes,
amassing a 14-4 record dating back to last year. But when he
doesn't play _ and he's missed or been injured of one of every
three games since joining the Falcons _ Atlanta is just 2-7,
including 0-3 when he's out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   When he missed the Oct. 25 game against the Jets, Atlanta got
smoked 28-3. A few days later offensive players admitted they went
into that game thinking they could win _ if everything went perfect
with DeBerg at quarterback. Instead, the offense was universally
lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   So what's more important? Who's at quarterback, or the passion
of players around him?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time there was more of an emphasis of playing
without Chris,'' said wide receiver Terance Mathis. ``This time, I
think this team has more confidence we can win no matter who is in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani's mobility could come in handy against a Rams team with
37 sacks, but perhaps just as importantly, being last year's
seventh-round draft choice year may make it imperative he play.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious, hopefully, DeBerg, 44, isn't going to be around
next year to back up Chandler. The Falcons need to figure out if
Graziani should be back.
</P>
<P>
   If they lose to their NFC West opponent today, the Falcons could
lost their grip of first place, and allow the 49ers (8-3) to gain a
tiebreaker edge. Lost today and Atlanta will have two division
losses to San Francisco's one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's overdue,'' said Graziani. ``We haven't won when
(Chandler) hasn't started. (Through more than a year of practice,
preseason, and the cameo role against the Jets) your reads get
faster, your drops get quicker. I feel I've improved a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg said, ``This team is good enough to win without Chris.
Maybe not against the elite teams in the NFL, but we have an
outstanding defense and a good running game.''
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't sound reassuring, consider the matchup of
Anderson versus the Rams, who've lost Atlanta three straight times
and 12 of 16.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed for a career-high 172 yards and two touchdowns in a
37-15 win four weeks ago, and 162 yards in a 34-31 win last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not worrying about (quarterback) because Jamal is
the guy right now,'' said St. Louis middle linebacker Eric Hill.
``I don't want to take anything away from him, but we're a lot
better than we showed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
