<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-ALMANAC29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safe stand ensures hunting success
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell and Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK'S TIP
</P>
<P>
   Bob Shumaker of Dawsonville bagged a trophy 10-point, 160-pound
deer last week in Madison County. One of the keys to getting it,
says Shumaker, a jokester, is staying in the tree stand. Or not
falling out. ``Every time you hunt, inspect your stand and make
sure it's safe,'' he said. ``And don't ever climb into it carrying
a rifle.'' Shumaker recommended tying a line on the rifle and
pulling it into the stand after you are seated and secured with a
safety belt.
</P>
<P>
   BRAGGING RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Native Atlantan Bill Carson, 41, has hunted since he was 12, but
never before has he taken such a magnificent buck as the 220-pound
11-pointer he took Nov. 21 on a 5,000-acre farm in Dooly County,
one of the Wildlife Resources Division's quality-management
counties, near Lake Blackshear.
</P>
<P>
   It shows what the program can do. By setting a minimum on antler
size, deer have time to grow and mature into such specimens, which
scored 138-plus on the Boone &AMP; Crockett big-game system.
</P>
<P>
   Deer already are rutting in the area. Carson said there was a
scrape under almost every oak limb that hung over a service road
bordering the hay field.
</P>
<P>
   Deer that big are wary, and Carson had more than his share of
luck. He decided at 6 a.m. to move his stand and had just finished
setting it up when he heard a noise _ other than what he was
making.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my disbelief, (there) was the buck, walking fast down one
of the rows of pine trees paralleling the hay field (near his
original setup),'' Carson said.
</P>
<P>
   He took the deer with one shot at 80 yards. Carson was using a
Browning .30-06 bolt action with a Leopold 3x9 Veri-X II scope and
was using 135-grain Nosler ballistic tip bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-point rack has a 19-inch spread. All tines were more than
seven inches long, and two were more than 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   UNBREAKABLE RECORD?
</P>
<P>
   It's been so long since George Perry caught the world-record
largemouth bass (22 pounds, 4 ounces in 1932) that access to the
lake where he caught it _ Lake Montgomery, an oxbow of the Ocmulgee
River _ is nearly impossible unless the river level is up or you're
willing to hike through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The same has been said about the chances of the next record
coming out of Georgia, according to a report in the
December-January issue of In-Fisherman magazine. It's nearly
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The report, entitled ``The Golden Age of Giant Largemouth
Bass,'' takes an informative state-by-state look at trophy
largemouth fishing and takes a guess at which state has the best
odds. Georgia has a one-in-150 chance of producing the next record,
according to the magazine. Like most Southeastern states, Georgia's
biggest bass _ 13 to 15 pounds _ mainly come from private ponds.
</P>
<P>
   The best chance of breaking a record? California, where stocked
Florida bass are making trophy lakes out of Castaic, Casitas and
Clear lakes. California's odds stand stand at 4-1, mainly because
of the number of fish of more than 17 pounds caught in the past
decade. Bob Cruppi's 22.01-pounder caught on Castaic in 1991 still
stirs talk, but large catches there have trailed off. Casitas is
producing the state's bass the past few years. Also, although not
officially recognized, a 24-pounder caught and released in a Spring
Lake, is further evidence that there's big bass out West.
</P>
<P>
   Other top odds: Florida (7-1), Texas (10-1), Louisiana (30-1).
Thirty-two states were given no line, meaning no chance at all.
</P>
<P>
   HITS AND MISSES
</P>
<P>
   The popular wintertime technique of spoon jigging has been
knocking the hybrids dead on Lake Allatoona, according to Ted
Gambrell of the Dugout in Marietta. Allen Brooks caught and
released 75 hybrids last week using the lure, mostly on long
points. ... The bombing run on Lake Lanier _ throwing Long A
Bombers to the shoreline and slowly retrieving _ has not been very
explosive this fall, as the moody stripers are still acting
finicky. Live bait, especially trout, have been effective, however.
Stripers also have been striking jumbo shiners, bucktails, Super
Flukes and Zara Spooks, among other lures and baits. A 24-pounder
was weighed in at Hammond's Fishing Center, while a 26-pound caught
by Randy Dover of Buford came in at the Dam Store.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE NEWSSTAND
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial subject a Georgian can bring up in a
crowd _ other than politics and religion _ is what is the best
rifle for hunting deer. The December issue of Field &AMP; Stream
magazine has its opinion on the rifle, plus 25 other items picked
by a panel of the magazine's editors from around the country that
should keep the conversations warm around campfires, bait shops and
marinas until January. The panel's choice for a rifle: Marlin's
Model 1895 Guide Gun.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE BIRDS
</P>
<P>
   The return of the seagulls and loons to Lake Lanier is a good
sign for even the less knowledgable angler. Find the birds and
you've got a good chance of finding fish and bait, according to
guide Bill Vanderford. Signs indicate that striper fishing on the
lake may be picking up, too. Schools of stripers can be seen
chasing baitfish on or near the surface from around Lake Lanier
Islands to as far north as Wahoo Creek and Little River. They'll
hit bucktails, Fluke-type plastic minnows, or most any large, live
baitfish within 10 feet of the surface. Early morning or during the
evening hours, one can try a topwater lure like the Zara Spook.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
