u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-RDP29-COX     11-28 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-RDP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 die while hunting in 1998
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell and Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Rangers have recorded 36 hunting accidents and
two fatalities so far in 1998, according to the Wildlife Resources
Division of the state Department of Natural Resources. Figures
include the current deer and waterfowl seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five accidents and one fatality involved deer hunters
falling out of tree stands. The other fatality was an accidentally
self-inflicted wound.
</P>
<P>
   The state has had six shooter-victim accidents.
</P>
<P>
   One involved a father shooting his son. The father was hunting
alone and wasn't aware his son was coming into the woods.
Obviously, he didn't see his target clearly and must have been
shooting at movement, a violation of one of the basic rules of
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Without tree-stand accidents, however, hunting looks relatively
safe, with 11 accidents and one fatality among a group of 400,000
people in the woods with guns.
</P>
<P>
   Give a plant this season Holiday shopping for the person who has
everything got easier with the Georgia Wildlife Federation's
WingSong Gift Certificates program. The WingSong nursery features
only native, Georgia-grown plants, raised without the use of
harmful pesticides. Proceeds from WingSong sales go to the GWF,
Georgia's largest conservation organization. The nonprofit GWF
probably is best known as producer of the Buckarama, Fisharama,
Turkeyrama and Duckarama, but it also works effectively as a
conservation watchdog when the Georgia Legislature is in session.
For information on WingSong, call 770-929-3350.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling geese
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's beleaguered lake-dwellers and golfers might learn from
Oregon how to control the Canada goose. Beginning next month, the
Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife will give farmers a list of
hunters willing to come onto their fields and shoot the offending
birds, which do considerable damage to wheat. They are trying to
steer geese off croplands and into wildlife refuges. ``Geese aren't
dumb,'' said Chris Vandenberg, the program coordinator. ``When they
fly into a field and get shot at a couple of times, they are a
whole lot less likely to come back.'' Oregon's problem is with
wintering geese. Georgia's Canadas are homegrown and the problem is
year-round and growing. Geese are grazers and they eat like sheep,
yanking plants out of wet soil and trampling seedlings.
</P>
<P>
   Record footage?
</P>
<P>
   You can get a chance to see a possible record bow-and-arrow
whitetail deer kill tonight on the Outdoors Channel's ``Outdoor
Adventures with Denny Guerink'' (7 p.m.), which will show footage
of what is believed to be the biggest buck ever taken by bow and
arrow. Mitch Rompola's 12-point Michigan whitetail dressed at 263
pounds and was estimated to be 6 years oldBass class
</P>
<P>
   The Bass Anglers Sportsman Society is offering a series of BASS
fishing classes beginning in January. Thirty-six two-day seminars
are scheduled, including one Jan. 23-24 hosted by Kennesaw State
University. The class, to be held at Wyndham Garden Hotel in
Kennesaw, will be taught by pro anglers on various aspects of bass
fishing. The registration fee is $89, with a fee for a spouse or a
child under 16 of $44.50. For information, call 770-423-6765.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
