<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-TEXAS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Clemson coach off to rough at Texas
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia faced Texas twice in the opening month of
last season, but the Bulldogs will play a vastly different
Longhorns team in Austin, Texas, today.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Longhorns, who lost both games to the Bulldogs
last November, are off to their worst start since going 0-6 in
1974-75. Texas, under first-year coach Rick Barnes, formerly of
Clemson, has dropped games to Houston, South Florida and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns are struggling to adapt to Barnes' defensive
style, shooting just 36.8 percent from the floor and committing 19
turnovers per game. Barnes replaced longtime coach Tom Penders, who
resigned in April after a well-publicized player revolt. Penders is
now at George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one area that we don't need to improve at,''
Barnes said. ``We have to learn to play hard all the time. I'm
going to do a better job of substituting players, getting guys to
play hard two, three minutes at a time. We've got to learn to play
defense. We'll find a way to score points. I'm the kind of guy who
wants to challenge every shot, win every possession, run teams out
of their offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' first task was instilling discipline. In a team meeting
on the day he was announced as coach, Barnes banned all facial
hair, earrings, wearing hats in buildings and wearing headphones on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has been hurt by the departure of two players _ highly
regarded wing man Luke Axtell, who transferred to Kansas, and guard
Bernard Smith, who left for Houston. Axtell was suspended by
Penders last season for academic reasons, and Axtell then quit the
team after a former assistant released his grades to a local radio
station.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was expected to start at point guard before he left in
August. The situation worsened when highly regarded recruit
Nathaniel Bailey didn't academically qualify. Junior William Clay
has taken over at point, allowing senior DeJuan Vazquez to move to
shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns are led by forwards Gabe Muoneke, who is averaging
18.7 points and eight rebounds, and Kris Clack, a senior who's
averaging 14.3 points and nine rebounds. Sophomore center Chris
Mihm is among the nation's top shot blockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got great athletic ability,'' Georgia coach Ron Jirsa
said. ``Between the two forwards, they're getting almost 30 points
a game. Clack is a sure NBA prospect on the wing. They're at home
and they're 0-3. Their backs are against the wall, so we've got to
realize that they're going to play extremely hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia faces a tough three-game stretch. The Bulldogs won't
return to Athens until Monday morning, leaving them just one day of
practice to prepare for West Virginia. After playing in Morgantown,
W.Va., on Wednesday, the Bulldogs face Furman in Stegeman Coliseum
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really only got one day to turn it around and (play West
Virginia),'' Jirsa said. ``It's going to be important for us to
realize how vital these games are for the entire season outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTING REPORT: GEORGIA AT TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   When, where: Today, 7 p.m., Erwin Center, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   TV, radio: Fox SportSouth, WSB (750 AM), WNGC (95.5 FM).
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Ron Jirsa is 23-16 in second season at Georgia; Rick
Barnes is 0-3 in first season at Texas, 202-137 in 12 years
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Georgia 3-1; Texas 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   Series: Georgia leads 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Last meeting: Georgia won 94-76 in Athens on Nov. 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Texas update: The Longhorns have struggled in Barnes' first
season, dropping their first three games to Houston, South Florida
and Arizona. Texas is shooting just 36.8 percent from the floor and
committing 19 turnovers per game. In the Longhorns' 73-57 loss at
Arizona on Wednesday, they shot only 33 percent and committed 20
turnovers. Forward Gabe Muoneke is leading the team with 18.7
points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Probable lineups: Georgia _ Guards, G.G. Smith (Sr., 5 feet 10)
and Ray Harrison (Sr., 6-2); center, Robb Dryden (So., 7-1);
forwards, Jumaine Jones (So., 6-7) and Michael Chadwick (Sr., 6-4).
Texas _ Guards, DeJuan Vazquez (Sr., 6-4) and William Clay (Jr.,
6-2); center, Chris Mihm (So., 7-foot); forwards, Gabe Muoneke
(Jr., 6-7) and Kris Clack (Sr., 6-5).
</P>
<P>
   Injuries: Georgia _ guard Adrian Jones (foot) is out for season.
Texas _ none reported.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
