<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK29-COX     11-28 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaches miss season more than fans
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe the fans don't miss the NBA _ every survey
confirms it _ but there's no question that absence from the game is
driving the league's top coaches crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lenny Wilkens said the lockout has colored his view
of retirement. Although it's four years away, the Hawks coach
already dreads the free time he can have at age 66. Now, add the
Celtics' Rick Pitino and the Heat's Pat Riley to the number that no
longer can imagine life without a team to coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said up until this point that I'm going to coach
until I'm about 52 or 53 and then look at some front-office
stuff,'' Pitino said. ``Now that I realize what it's like being
out, I want to coach until I'm about 62 or 65. Definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino had dabbled in horse racing, TV and played golf, but it
cannot obscure his love for coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always questioned guys like Mike Fratello,'' Pitino said.
``They have a great TV job, so why did they get back into coaching?
And now I realize (that) when you don't have it, it kills you not
to be a part of it. So this taught me a lot. For me, it's a great
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, 'Why don't you go into TV commentating some day?'
But coaching's my niche, and I would miss basketball too much to be
away from it. That's what this has taught me. I can't be away from
it. I can't live without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley spent a year away from coaching as an NBC analyst after he
left the Lakers. ``I hated it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And although Riley said last season he did not think he could be
a coaching lifer like Bill Fitch, he has changed his mind. He is in
the business for the long haul, probably with the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you get to a point where you get sort of
comfortable,'' Riley said. ``I've been in for 17 years now. I don't
have any anxiety anymore. Since I've come here, I feel a love to
coach more than ever. Maybe it's the age. I'm just sort of settling
in. I like it here. To build this organization, it's a different
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Door's open
</P>
<P>
   Hawks rookie Roshown McLeod was on the court at Duke in
September when Christian Laettner tore his Achilles' tendon. ``He
got a pass, went to make a move to the basket all by himself and
went down,'' McLeod recalled. ``He said I think, 'I tore my
Achilles`.' None of us believed him because he didn't show any pain
on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   While Laettner, a free agent, recuperates, agent Lon Babby
protests the assumption that he's locked in for Detroit.
``Christian hasn't ruled out any team, and he certainly hasn't
turned his back on the Hawks. He's still very interested in
returning to Atlanta and, remember, Atlanta can do more for him
than any other team, under the current rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Laettner, by the way, saved money when he dumped agent Herb
Rudoy, who takes 4 percent of his client's contract. Babby bills by
the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bad air
</P>
<P>
   Here's NBA attorney Jeffrey Mishkin's unpromising view of labor
negotiations: ``We can't agree on the shape of the table. We can't
agree on what we have agreed to, and that's not a conducive
atmosphere for productive negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Mishkin's take on the death of Saturday's
negotiations differs from the union's. According to the league's
chief counsel, Billy Hunter became inflexible on key points, thus
making talks so unpromising they were canceled. Specifically, it is
alleged that Hunter said the players would not take less than 57
percent of the pie.
</P>
<P>
   Money
</P>
<P>
   Under the NBA's proposed system of capping the highest salaries,
the league would never again see a $100 million contract. They
would take Kevin Garnett's six-year, $126 million deal from
Minnesota and put it in a museum for foolishness. Assuming the
salary cap is $32 million this season, here are the maximum deals
available to players in three categories, under the owners'
proposal. The two sets of figures represent the contracts players
could sign with their originating teams as ``Larry Bird
exceptions'' and what they could get on the open market:
</P>
<P>
   Contract pct. of cap Old team New team
</P>
<P>
   10-plus years 35 $92.65M $66.3M
</P>
<P>
   7-9 years 30 $73.1M $53.0M
</P>
<P>
   0-6 years 25 $61.725M $44.2M
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Spurs' David Robinson says he's opposed to
the concept. ``Nobody is going to accept that,'' Robinson said.
``It would be a huge mistake to limit the top guys' salaries. If
you say (to Tim Duncan), 'Tim, you can only make $9 million on your
next contract,' what happens then? You immediately restrict
salaries of guys in the lesser category than Tim. You say if you're
an owner, 'Well, Avery (Johnson), we're paying Tim $9 million, you
should get about $1.5 million. All the salaries will fall.
Everything is really measured according to the top salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson cleared $75,000 doing an autograph show in Detroit
last weekend. Oh, but he didn't do it because he needed the money.
</P>
<P>
   According to Darren Prince, one of Johnson's booking agents,
Johnson periodically puts out fresh signatures so that his
collectibles will not fall prey to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people out there ripping these guys off with phony
signatures,'' Prince told the Detroit News. ``If you see a Magic
autograph going for $20 or $30, you know it's a fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Unity
</P>
<P>
   Taking an optimistic view that there will be a season, the
Pacers are emerging as the favorites in the East. Among the reasons
is team unity. You might have heard that as many as 11 players from
last season's team have been working out together. That includes
free-agent center Rik Smits, who is expected to re-sign with the
Pacers. ``We don't have the coaches pushing us,'' Antonio Davis
said. ``We're pushing ourselves. The guys want to be as ready as
possible. The only way we can savor anything is to get together and
work out as much as possible.'' Call it another ``Larry Bird
exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
