<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping Oilers ahead
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The best architect in hockey is doing it again. He
lost his starting goalie to free agency. He lost his best offensive
weapon twice, first to a contract holdout, then to knee surgery. He
has long since lost his ammunition to a shrinking economy that
finds ``Canadian dollar'' a contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   But Glen Sather still wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Edmonton Oilers started last week in first place in the
NHL's Northwest Division. It has helped that the Colorado
Avalanche, a team with double the Oilers' payroll, limped out of
the gate; but that the Oilers are even above .500 is a credit to
Sather's eye for young, inexpensive talent and his ability to stay
a step ahead of most other NHL executives in the direction of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, I'd like to have more money to spend,'' said the
general manager of the Oilers, whose payroll of $21.938 million
ranks 23rd among 27 teams. ``But even if I had been in Atlanta and
I had the budget that team may or may not have, I still would not
have paid (goalie) Curtis Joseph $24 million for four years. I
think you're a lot better off getting a group of young guys
together, teach them about the game and about life and bring them
along. You're much better off than trying to hit a home run with a
bunch of 30-year-old free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   When the week started, the Oilers had twice as many wins as the
New York Rangers, whose payroll of $39.783 million was
third-highest in the NHL and 81 percent higher than Edmonton's.
Sather was GM of five Stanley Cup champions _ he also coached four
of them _ with a group of kids who eventually found riches
elsewhere. They include Wayne Gretzky, Mark Messier, Paul Coffey,
Grant Fuhr, Jari Kurri, Glenn Anderson and Kevin Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers upset Colorado in the playoffs last season, then lost
Joseph to Toronto. Forward Doug Weight, the team's leading scorer,
will have played only four games by the time he returns to the
lineup in late January, having torn up a knee a week after
returning from protracted contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But Edmonton continues to get strong play from Bill Guerin, whom
Sather stole from New Jersey in a trade last year, and has received
surprisingly excellent goaltending from Mikhail Shtalenkov, who
cost Sather only a fifth-round pick in a trade with expansion
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   At times this past offseason, some people wondered if Sather
would be back in Edmonton. Rumors long had swirled that the
franchise, in financial straits, would be moved, while owner Peter
Pocklington had sold the team to a group of 26 owners. Even after
new owners vowed to keep the team in Alberta, Sather, who earns
approximately $1 million, was uncertain of his role.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers were among a few clubs that approached Sather,
although his conversations were with team vice president Dave
Maggard, not president Harvey Schiller. The Thrashers were
uncertain how serious Sather was about the job and thought that he
wanted to stay in Edmonton. They hired Don Waddell instead.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sather admits, ``The first thing I thought of was loyalty
to the city of Edmonton. I didn't want to seem like a carpetbagger
at this stage. I was responsible for this franchise for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Thrashers concluded that Sather wasn't gettable, they
were mistaken. Sather said he would have ``loved the chance'' to
build a team from scratch _ if the conditions were right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of working for Ted Turner would have been very
exciting for me,'' he said. ``He's one guy I've always had great
esteem for. I've read a lot about him. He's an interesting guy.
I've always liked Atlanta as a city. They'll have a great building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to them a couple of times. It just seemed a little, I
don't know, restrictive. I report to a board of directors here. But
they know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Sather was assured he would remain in control of the
Oilers, he didn't believe he could get the same situation in
Atlanta. Sather's comfort level is such that he occasionally takes
brief respites at his offseason home in Palm Springs, Calif.,
during the season, usually when the Oilers are on a West Coast
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Sather defends the practice. He can talk on the phone and catch
just as many games on a satellite dish in Palm Springs as he can in
Edmonton. Besides, he said, ``It's just as easy to fly some place
out of Palm Springs as it is Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
