<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beanie Babies, bad bank statements plague Penguins
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A woman attending a Beanie Baby giveaway at a recent
Penguins game tried to obtain one of the stuffed animals on the
pretense it was for her infant son. She was denied _ after it was
determined that the ``infant'' she had wrapped in a blanket was a
Teddy bear.
</P>
<P>
   If that had been Pittsburgh's only off-ice headache last week,
things wouldn't be so bad. But there's more in bankruptcy central.
The latest:
</P>
<P>
   _ Co-owner Roger Marino admits in recent depositions what others
have suspected, that he has been in contact with other cities about
moving the team as early as the end of this season. The hit list:
Cleveland; Houston; Kansas City, Mo.; Little Rock; Milwaukee;
Portland, Ore.; Salt Lake City; Seattle; and Las Vegas. ``Nobody
wants to leave,'' team attorney Michael Kaminsky said. ``We just
want to ... compare the Civic Arena lease with other leases.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Details of the Penguins' $127 million debt include $3.8
million in signing bonuses to 10 current players in the minors or
juniors and $5.99 million in deferred payments to six roster
players, as well as $33 million to Mario Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   _ The next 10 paychecks to players on the current roster will
come courtesy of a bank in France, after a $20 million loan was
secured by the team and approved by a U.S. bankruptcy judge.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is speculation the team might leave high-priced goalie
Tom Barrasso unprotected for the Thrashers in June's expansion
draft. Behind Barrasso, the Pens have three young goalies _ Peter
Skudra, Jean-Sebastian Aubin, Craig Hillier _ and the veteran is
making $2.7 million per year. He is scheduled to become an
unrestricted free agent after the 1999-2000 season, which might
dissuade the Thrashers from pursuing him.
</P>
<P>
   Capital punishment
</P>
<P>
   The most startling development in last week's free-for-all
between Washington and Boston _ which resulted in 44 penalties
totaling 270 minutes _ was the decision by referee Mark Faucette to
eject all 12 players participating in a first-period brawl. ``I
suppose if you go strictly by the rules, the ejections were
proper,'' Bruins general manager Harry Sinden said. ``But suppose
you have the same thing happen in the next period? Do you call off
the game? The officials have to use some common sense.'' Caps left
winger Craig Berube also was suspended for three games for ``abuse
of officials'' when it was determined he pushed a linesman to get
to a Bruins player. Such suspensions are issued by the game
officials, not by the league. Boston and Minnesota combined for 406
penalty minutes on Feb. 21, 1981, the NHL record. An amusing
postfight comment came from Caps goalie Olaf Kolzig, who squared
off with friend Byron Dafoe, Boston's goalie: ``It's tough fighting
your best friend. He went after one of our guys. I went after one
of their guys. We ended up getting together.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Overkill? Doctors let Montreal's Mark Recchi extend his ironman
streak to 561 even though he was in the early stages of pneumonia.
... Buffalo killed off 78 of 85 penalties (90.6 percent) in its
first 16 games, and it's no secret why. ``We have the best penalty
killer in the league _ Dominik Hasek,'' forward Curtis Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
