<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Goon Squad' rates hockey's aggressive players
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Journal-Constitution presents the first
``Goon Squad'' ratings, taking into account total penalty minutes
(PM), fight penalties (FP), numbers of games suspended this season
(Sp.) and goals scored (GS). The more goals scored, the more a
player drops in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Rank Player Team PM FP Sp. GS
</P>
<P>
   1. Bob Probert Chicago 80 10 0 1
</P>
<P>
   2. Patrick Cote Nashville 67 9 0 0
</P>
<P>
   3. Denny Lambert Nashville 51 5 4 1
</P>
<P>
   4. Matt Johnson Los Angeles 49 2 12 1
</P>
<P>
   5. Tie Domi Toronto 75 9 0 1
</P>
<P>
   6. Krzysztof Oliwa New Jersey 57 9 0 1
</P>
<P>
   7. Sean Brown Edmonton 68 4 3 0
</P>
<P>
   8. Peter Worrell Florida 63 8 3 0
</P>
<P>
   9. Paul Laus Florida 66 8 0 0
</P>
<P>
   10. Jeff Odgers Colorado 72 8 0 1
</P>
<P>
   11. Gino Odjick N.Y. Islanders 113 5 0 4
</P>
<P>
   12. Ken Baumgartner Boston 54 6 0 1
</P>
<P>
   THRASHERS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville Predators did not play a home exhibition this year
so that their season opener against Florida would be the team's
first game in the new Nashville Arena. Don't expect the Thrashers
to do the same. ``We'll do some preseason games here,'' team
president Harvey Schille said. ``We want to make sure everything is
ready with the arena for the season, and it has promotional value
for the people. Ticket prices also will be lower, so it's a chance
for people to come down and get a taste of things and a feel for
it, without (it) costing a lot.'' ... General manager Don Waddell
will try to use his connections with Detroit, where he served as
assistant GM, to bring the Red Wings in for an exhibition. ...
Reason for the delayed release of Thrashers jerseys: Team officials
are having trouble finding a manufacturer who can get the dark blue
and copper colors right. Expect the jerseys to be released in early
January. . . . Schiller conceded that the team is not close to
negotiating a deal for construction of a practice site, and it is
becoming more likely the team will rent ice time from an existing
rink for practices, as well as use the new arena when it's
available.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE BLOTTER
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt that new NHL vice president Colin
Campbell was on a record-setting pace for handing out suspensions,
here are the numbers. Campbell already has suspended 20 players _
four in the preseason, 16 in the regular season _ for everything
from throwing a water bottle at a fan (Chicago's Reid Simpson,
suspended one game) to cross-checking an opponent in the face
(Tampa Bay's Andrei Nazarov, seven games). Former league VP Brian
Burke suspended 27 players all of last season. League officials say
they do not keep records on suspensions for a season, but Campbell
could surpass last year's total before the All-Star break. Campbell
is defending his moves and the job Burke did last year. ``Brian is
being unfairly criticized for (being too soft),'' Campbell said.
``But he did the job that was asked of him.'' Campbell said he was
given a different mandate than Burke, which was to crack down on
hits to the head.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   Evidence indicates that rule changes finally are increasing
scoring. The overall average of 5.2 goals per game remains low, but
consider the 50-game breakdowns: 4.7 average in games one to 50;
5.0 in 51-100; 5.3 in 101-150; 5.7 in 151-200. The trend could
continue now that the NHL mandated changes in between-periods
activities beginning this past week. The ice must be resurfaced
three minutes earlier than before, allowing for more time for the
water to freeze and less time for entertainment. Players coming out
of the dressing room before the start of the period must go
directly to the bench instead of skating around, except for those
who will open the period. The goal: a faster ice surface and
quicker, more action-filled starts to the period.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Dallas right winger Mike Modano is blaming his scoring slump _
five goals in 16 games _ on the fact that his six-year, $43.5
million contract is creating financial management problems for him
off the ice. ``You try as much as you can not to bring that to the
rink. But it's tough when it weighs on you the 22 hours you're not
at the rink. Then the other two, you try to focus on hockey.'' Hey,
here's a solution: Give some of it back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
