<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLWEST29-COX     11-28 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicholls tries to fend off Shark attack
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For a guy who ranks 26th on the NHL's all-time scoring
list with 1,209 points and is one of only eight players to score 70
goals in a season, Bernie Nicholls deserved a better exit than the
one he got last week.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose general manager Dean Lombardi and coach Darryl Sutter
met with Nicholls after a home game against the New York Rangers
and told him that he would not accompany the team on a four-game
trip the next day. They also told him that he had played his last
game for the Sharks, period, and suggested he retire.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi shouldn't be expected to carry Nicholls on the roster
if he doesn't think the probable Hall of Famer can play anymore.
But how is that determination made six weeks into the season and
not before the year starts _ especially after Nicholls was given a
new contract for one year plus an option?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it was awkward in terms of timing, but we'll work
through it and get it right,'' Lombardi said.
</P>
<P>
   The team has approached Nicholls about staying on in some
capacity, but it has yet to create a job description. Nicholls is
open to the idea but wants a long-term commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made up their mind that I'm not in their plans (as a
player) and they're going to take a different route,'' Nicholls
said. ``I can respect that part. But I don't agree. I feel I can
still play. My agent said he could call teams and find a spot for
me to go. But what's best for me in the long run? If I take a job
here and it's for the long run, then it's in my best interest to
stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Cha-ching
</P>
<P>
   Many general managers and players have whined this season after
league vice president Colin Campbell handed out suspensions. But
when Campbell banished Los Angeles left winger Matt Johnson for the
year's longest punishment _ 12 games (and $95,121.95 in salary) _
Johnson was silent and Kings general manager Dave Taylor was as
meek as a puppy. After Johnson attacked New York's Jeff Beukeboom
from behind with a punch to the head, leaving him with a
concussion, Johnson alibied that he was retaliating for Beukeboom
kicking out the feet of a Kings teammate. Campbell disagreed,
because he didn't suspend Beukeboom. Johnson also qualified as a
``repeat offender,'' having been suspended four games last year for
a slashing incident.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings might consider having A&AMP;W cater their pregame
meals. In the middle of their 2-6 slump, things seemed to get worse
for them when they had to bus nearly four hours from Calgary to
Edmonton because their plane, ``Redbird One,'' had a hole in the
fuselage. A fuel truck had backed into it. ``We drove from Calgary
to Edmonton and stopped on the way for burgers and fries at A&AMP;W,''
assistant coach Dave Lewis said. ``I think it reminded all of the
guys of their junior days, when they just played the game for the
love of it. Everybody kind of got back to basics.'' No kidding. The
Red Wings that night played one of their best games of the season,
beating the Oilers 6-2. ... Rumor mill: The Kings are talking to
Ottawa about acquiring center Radek Bonk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
