<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 11/28/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BEDFORD HILLS, N.Y. -- Nov. 28, 1998 -- NY-CASTLE, 11-28
-- Donald Lehman and his wife Barbara, bought the Darlington Castle
and 30 acres in Bedford for $1.5 million, a relatively low price
because of a working radio tower mounted to its roof and an
iron-clad lease that insures it will remain there until 2006. The
Lehmans now complain that Kenny G has become the soundtrack to
their lives because the station, WZZN at 106.3 FM, comes through on
every channel on the radio dial and meddles with the reception on
other equipment. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KANKANI, India -- Nov. 28, 1998 -- INDIA-HUNTING-SUIT,
11-28 -- Kankani elders like Prahlad Ram, are among those accusing
Salman Khan, a young movie idol in India, of having poached two
antelopes. Khan's lawyer says that some villagers' love of animals
``twists their thinking.'' Ram says that his people, Bishnoi
villagers, have a duty to serve as ``protectors and nurturers of
all living things.'' Now, the Bishnoi have become national heroes
in an ecological morality play that pits simple farmers against an
Indian movie idol. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROWE, N.M. -- AMERINDIAN-PREP-SCHOOLS-2, 11-28 -- Sven
Husaby, the headmaster of the Native American Prep School, on his
porch in the Pecos River Valley, near Rowe, N.M. The boarding
school prepares gifted Indian students from 32 different American
Indian tribes and 11 states, most of whom grew up in poverty on
reservations, to walk in two worlds, tribal and academic. ``The
atmosphere is almost like a Native American United Nations,'' says
Husaby. (Steve Northup/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ROWE, N.M. -- AMERINDIAN-PREP-SCHOOLS-1, 11-28 -- Two
11th-grade students, Tom Vallo, left, of Acoma Pueblo, N.M., and
Fredericka Brandon, a Navajo-Hawaiian from Rowe, N.M., in their
chemistry class at the Native American Prep School. The boarding
school prepares gifted Indian students, most of whom grew up in
poverty on reservations, to walk in two worlds, tribal and
academic. It will graduate its first class in June, and has already
drawn recruiters from more than 30 colleges, including Harvard and
Cornell. (Steve Northup/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 28, 1998 --JEWS-SETTLE-DISPUTE, 11-28 --
Estelle Sapir, 73, a Holocaust survivor who sued Swiss banks on
behalf of her father, who died in a Polish camp, says all funds
left over after payments to the heirs of Swiss account holders
should go directly to survivors, ``not the organizations, not the
lawyers.'' In recent months, competing lawyers from the U.S. have
barnstormed across Europe soliciting clients, publicly castigating
one another and privately maneuvering to oust their adversaries.
(Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GLASGOW, Scotland -- Nov. 28, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-NATIONALSIM, 11-28 -- The Union Jack still flies over
Edinburgh Castle, but if the Scottish Nationalist Party has its
way, it could be replaced by the blue-and-white Cross of St.
Andrew. The Nationalists have been gaining support in Scotland.
Much of the enthusiasm for the Nationalists could have to do with
the party's attentions to local problems at a time when many Labor
district councils are notorious for corruption and complacency.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 28, 1998 -- TEENS-PLASTIC-SURGERY, 11-28
-- Dr. Gerald Pitman, discussing the possibility of cosmetic
surgery with a teen-aged girl, right, and her mother. A generation
ago, it was not unusual for youngsters to have their noses
straightened or ears pinned back, procedures that doctors say are
appropriate for those with ungainly features. But these days, more
controversial procedures, like breast augmentation and liposuction,
are gaining popularity in this impressionable age group. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
