<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY CHEERS? NOT THIS PAST WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thank goodness Thanksgiving week ends today. Local sports teams
couldn't take any more of this holiday abuse _ some of it
self-inflicted, some of it Moss-produced.
</P>
<P>
   There was but one confirmed winner _ the Mavericks, who have no
game or games at the moment. With nothing to screw up, they won by
not being involved.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, from the Dept. of Opinions, here's a slanted view of
the story:
</P>
<P>
   Within the Cowboys ranks, there seemed to be genuine surprise,
starting with Jerry Jones, that Nine-Toed Deion took the scratch
for Thursday. But why the surprise?
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, ego prevented Sanders from participating in a
national spotlight matchup. Say the toe-sprain reduced him to 90
percent _ if Randy Moss burns Deion, he loses luster and face.
</P>
<P>
   Did you think this was about the team? Instead, focus on
reputation, a new contract and Being Deion. Then again, Sanders
will now have had two full weeks to recover, setting him up for the
December stretch run, and maybe a January rematch with the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Not all bad, frankly.
</P>
<P>
   Gall-of-the-week winner was easily the Rangers. Talk about no
shame in jacking up 1999 ticket prices another 20 percent _ the
third consecutive off-season for a price increase, all of them in
the 20 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   When club officials were begging for stadium votes seven years
ago, they successfully sold that Arlington election with one key
point: the new ballpark would be so prosperous it would absorb
growing players' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, fan-gouging is yearly and rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Score this as the first negative P.R. for the Tom Hicks
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Honk, Doug Melvin, if you're still alive. What a nice Rangers'
scam _ shut out in free agency thus far while also reaching into
the fans' hip-pocket.
</P>
<P>
   That hip-pocket reach works both way. The Stars are stealing
Hicks' money.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the good NHL teams normally half-skate through November,
but there's a difference between that and loafing. Too many times
lately, the Stars have appeared disinterested in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Darryl Sydor, for publicly citing ``arrogance,'' and
``a lack of respect'' for the opponent. Someone in the Stars'
locker room needed to say it.
</P>
<P>
   According to several players, Chan Gailey's postgame locker room
comments to the team centered on ``next time.'' In other words, he
voiced confident eagerness about trying the Vikings again in the
playoffs. But health or no health, the Cowboys will lose again if
the stupid offensive penalties and dropped passes don't cease.
</P>
<P>
   How confused was the Cowboys' makeshift secondary on
Thanksgiving? Consider one critical third quarter play: With the
Vikings facing third-and-18 from their own 38, Dave Campo called
for the dreaded three-man rush (it never works, Dave.) That meant
eight pass defenders as Randall Cunningham heaved the ball deep and
up for grabs. Incredibly, Kenny Wheaton still ended up singled
against Moss, and drew the pass interference at the 12-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   That set up the game-turning touchdown. The Cowboys were down
24-19 when Wheaton took that penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Birth of a receiver. My, my, what have the Cowboys found in
Patrick Jeffers? The son of an Arlington gynecologist who prepped
at Fort Worth Country Day, Jeffers was picked up for nothing from
Denver late in the summer. Troy Aikman, for one, has privately said
Jeffers, tall with speed, is a ``player,'' and that was before the
past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Credit receivers coach Dwain Painter with the acquisition of
Jeffers. Painter was on Denver's staff last season.
</P>
<P>
   One good theory on the Stars. With 11 of the first 18 games at
Reunion, and with two five-day breaks in the schedule in the first
six weeks, it's a team that has spent way too much time at home.
</P>
<P>
   Tee times, wifes, kids and girlfriends tend to limit hockey
concentration. A test for the homebody theory is coming quickly.
Ten of the 15 games in December are on the road, followed by eight
of 12 in January.
</P>
<P>
   How do the Rangers explain higher ticket prices if they don't
sign Randy Johnson? Even if they do, while the explanation will be
easier, that doesn't make it valid.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting sight of the week: Moss, with his head down, and a
ballcap also pulled tight on his head, mumbling into the Madden
turkey after Thursday's game. Pat \RSummerall\S and John \RMadden\S
had their postgame questions, but Moss had few answers and little
interest in talking on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that was still more than he wanted to say to the
media in the locker room. Moss snarled and cursed at TV reporters.
Greatness on the field is one thing. Acting like a punk is another.
</P>
<P>
   December is coming and the Mavericks remain unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   (Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
