<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Nov. 29. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CREDIT (undated) _ Free money! A new tax break is like a winning
lottery ticket for some Arizona schools. Too bad everyone's not a
winner, say the critics. The windfall could easily add up to tens
of millions of dollars, thanks to a law that allows taxpayers to
donate up to $200 for extra-curricular activities and subtract the
full amount from their state income tax bill. By KATHLEEN INGLEY
and CATHY CRENO. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CACTUS (undated) _ This was supposed to be a story about the
world's fattest cactus, a really obese specimen rooted near Picacho
Peak. Based on a reliable tip, momentous journalism plans were set
in motion. The monster would be dubbed El Gordo and crowned the
Sumo of Succulents. The thing would be declared an Arizona
landmark. Roseanne would do a show about her botanical soulmate . .
. Oops. It turns out El Gordo is not the world's most corpulent
cactus. Nor is it the heaviest, tallest, happiest or ugliest.
Barrel cactuses grow taller and wider in Mexico. So forget about El
Gordo. This story is about the whole world of spiny succulents.
It's a compendium of facti about cacti, drawn from experts and
books. By DENNIS WAGNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NIGHT-CHILD (undated ) _ When night falls, the Collin Cassinat hour
begins. As other children take cover from the darkness, Collin's
playtime is just beginning. Under the moonlight, he races his bike,
catches frogs, hunts bugs and exhilarates in his freedom. Sunshine
is no friend to Collin. Exposures of just minutes would cause his
skin to redden, burn and blister. An overdose would kill him.
Collin, 9, is a child of the night. Born with a genetic disorder
called xeroderma pigmentosum, in which the cells of the body lack
the ability to repair DNA damage from ultraviolet rays, Collin's
best chance for survival is to avoid all sunlight. By BARBARA YOST.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ Elizabeth ``Trudy'' Calabrese's murderer
stood in open court last week and told a judge, ``Regardless of
what my family thinks, I deserve the death penalty.'' Trudy's
husband, Rosario, widowed father of two children, sat quietly
nearby, and disagreed. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the
``A'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 1905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
