<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATT-MISSING29-COX     11-28 3621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATT-MISSING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home for troubled kids causing problems for teen's loved ones
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ There are troubled kids, kids who break
the law and lie to their friends and make their parents cry.
</P>
<P>
   There are kids who slip quietly into invisibility, who are
wallpaper at school and ghosts around their peers, whose names
nobody can remember.
</P>
<P>
   There are kids who shrivel up and drift away because the right
people don't care.
</P>
<P>
   By almost every account, Matthew Grise is none of those kids.
</P>
<P>
   He is serious around adults and silly around his friends, a
straight A student and an athlete who can pitch 13 strike-outs in
seven innings. By almost every account, he's the student teachers
want in class, the guy people want for a friend, the 15-year-old
adults actually like.
</P>
<P>
   Because of who he is, his friends are showering politicians in
three states with letters pleading for help, local preachers are
including him in their prayers over the pulpit and his 70-year-old
grandmother, Joan Grise, is currently in Independence, Mo., trying
to do something - anything - for Matt.
</P>
<P>
   Since July, Matt has been incarcerated at the New Bethany
Baptist Church juvenile compound near Arcadia, La., a facility run
by the controversial and secretive Rev. Mack Ford. A
self-proclaimed proponent of corporeal punishment based on his
interpretation of the Bible, Ford has been accused of child abuse
many times in the 27 years he has run juvenile compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Matt has no documented history of illegal, violent, antisocial
or even disruptive behavior, and is not legally required to be
there.
</P>
<P>
   But Matt's father and step-mother, Vincent and Tami Russo,
reportedly told Matt's friends and family that he is a ``bad seed''
and a ``pathological liar'' and sent him to New Bethany allegedly
to be reformed. Friends say nothing is further from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt is a delightful child,'' said Cindy Bentley, whose son,
David, became Matt's close friend when the two were students at
Scenic Elementary School. ``To say he is troubled or a liar or a
bad kid is absolutely ridiculous. He's a wonderful boy and he
shouldn't be where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   None of his friends or extended family can tell him that,
though, because the only people allowed contact with Matt under
Ford's strict rules are Vincent Russo and the people who run the
New Bethany compound.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ford or his staff declined interviews with The Daily
Sentinel on four occasions, but accounts from various people who
have been to New Bethany describe it as a well-maintained juvenile
compound with a school, a working farm and 10-foot chain-link
fences topped by razor wire.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Haynes, an employee of the Hope Youth Ranch in nearby
Minden, La., who has been to New Bethany, said guards with German
shepherds patrol the grounds and ``I got the feeling they (the
people who run New Bethany) were kind of cultish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got their own people and they don't like anybody from
the outside on their grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's not the kind of place where you just walk in and say,
'Hi, I'm Uncle Payson and I'd like to talk to Matt,' `` said Payson
Grise, Matt's uncle. ``I have no idea what he's doing there except
Vince and Tami think he should be there. We're all really worried
about what could be happening to him, and Libba, well, this would
be her worst nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to agree on that: Sarah Elizabeth ``Libba'' Grise
feared nothing as she approached death except that something would
happen to her son to lessen his happiness or tangle the path of his
life. She died in October 1995 at age 46 after an extended struggle
with cancer, having first made arrangements she thought would see
Matt through to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Walker, Libba's close friend, said Libba worried only
that Matt's father, Vincent Russo, might do something to complicate
Matt's life. Russo, after four requests for an interview, agreed to
talk to The Daily Sentinel, but then failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   When Libba and Russo met in Snowmass in 1982, Libba had already
lived in Colorado for 10 years and was ready to settle down, her
friends said. She moved to Snowmass from Ohio in 1972, maybe
looking for adventure, her brother, Payson, said. She worked as a
housekeeper, housekeeping supervisor and daycare provider in Aspen,
Snowmass and Carbondale, making friends, learning how to ski and
having fun in her free time, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were instant friends,'' Walker said of Libba. ``She was a
happy woman. I never heard her raise her voice except at baseball
games. There's a picture of her in the front of the cookbook she
helped put together for her church and when I see that smile I
think, 'That's Libba, that smile on her face.' ``
</P>
<P>
   She loved children, Walker said, and met Russo, who was a
construction worker, in Carbondale in 1982 because she was taking
care of his two daughters. In 1983 she became pregnant with Matt
and had him Nov. 9. She told friends that was the best day of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with Russo, whom she never married, was rocky,
Payson Grise said, and ended when Matt was still a toddler. Before
that, though, when Matt was barely a year old, Libba was diagnosed
with cancer after seeing her physician about a lump on her neck.
</P>
<P>
   The financial strain of radiation therapy added to the expense
of raising a child on a limited income was almost overwhelming,
``but Libba was one of the most stubborn people I've ever met. She
was determined to make things work,'' Walker said, adding that the
Grise family is very close and pulled together around Libba.
</P>
<P>
   About a year later, Libba entered a remission that lasted almost
five years. While she was still healthy, she and Matt moved to
Grand Junction, where Matt started school at Scenic Elementary and
she started a day-care business.
</P>
<P>
   Libba and Matt had a good relationship, friends said: They told
each other corny jokes, went to the park and double-checked Matt's
homework. Libba taught Matt to say please and thank you and excuse
me and that he still would have to mow the lawn despite his
grumbling. He showed her he could match her work ethic by bringing
home straight A's and pitching shutout games for his baseball team.
To Libba's pleasure, her son was tall and sandy-haired like her.
</P>
<P>
   They were good together, Bentley said, ``but I can remember one
time when I was volunteering in his first-grade class, seeing him
at his desk with his hands over his eyes, crying. I asked him what
was wrong and he said they'd just drawn pictures of their families
and he told me he was the only one in the class without a father.''
</P>
<P>
   That probably wasn't quite true, but Matt was very aware of not
having a dad. Walker said Matt had only occasional contact with
Russo, even after Libba's cancer returned several years after she
and Matt moved to Grand Junction.
</P>
<P>
   As Libba's health got worse - she eventually had to have her
voice box removed as a last-ditch effort to slow the spreading
cancer - she willed herself to be strong for her son, friends said,
and Matt did the same for his mother. She and Matt remained active
at Redlands United Methodist Church and she helped organize a
church cookbook to raise money for a building project. Kathy
Carlson, who during that time was Christian education director for
the church, said church members became an extended family for Libba
and Matt.
</P>
<P>
   Matt still got good grades and did normal boy stuff as he
watched his mother die, staying with the Bentleys when she had to
go to Denver for treatment. When there was nothing left to do and
she knew she was shrinking into a person Matt wouldn't recognize,
Libba took a deep breath and hugged her son tight and sent him to
live with his Uncle Payson and Aunt Sharlene in Rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Before she died, Libba asked her friend, attorney Martelle
Daniels, to draw up a will for her. In it she specified that she
wanted Matt to live with Payson and Sharlene Grise, but chose not
to pursue formal guardianship for them because she feared Russo
might take that as his cue to seek custody, Payson Grise said.
</P>
<P>
   The only effect of designating a guardian in a will rather than
through legal action is to state the preference of that person in
future court proceedings, Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   Russo came to Libba's funeral but didn't have much contact
afterward, Payson Grise said. Matt started building a life with his
aunt and uncle in Rifle, earning a spot on the honor roll each
quarter and making friends. He started building a life without his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Then in November 1996 Russo called Matt and asked if he would
like to come to Independence, Mo., where Russo lives, for Christmas
vacation. Because Matt wanted to know his father, Payson and
Sharlene agreed Matt could go. At the end of the vacation, Matt and
Russo called Payson and Sharlene in Rifle and said Matt was going
to stay in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Payson and Sharlene, distraught over the decision, did what they
believed was right for the nephew they love: They let him stay with
the father he'd always wanted, ``hoping Vince had changed and
thinking how it would hurt Matt if we refused,'' Payson said.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting stories started several months after Matt began
school at Raytown Middle School, said Sandy Playter, a guidance
counselor at that school whose son, Jay, became one of Matt's
closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   Playter's husband, Mike, was putting together a youth baseball
team and Jay said Matt was an excellent player. Mike Playter
contacted Russo about Matt playing on the team and Russo said Matt
might be going to Colorado. He called again a week later and Russo
said he still didn't know, so Mike Playter suggested Matt could
practice with the team and be in shape if he wanted to play in
Colorado, Sandy Playter explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince and Tami didn't provide any transportation for him to
practices or games, so either my husband or I or my mom picked him
up and took him home, and that's how we got to know him,'' Sandy
Playter said.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri he continued earning straight A's and earlier this
year placed third in a regional math competition. Playter said one
of Matt's English teachers bought new shoes and clothes for Matt to
wear to the math competition.
</P>
<P>
   He also continued excelling in baseball, football and track, but
last year several of his teammates on the track team individually
went to a school guidance counselor to confide that Matt frequently
felt faint at practice, possibly from not eating breakfast or
lunch. When the counselor approached him about it he replied that
he could prepare lunch if he chose, but he just chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was suspicious,'' Sandy Playter said. The other
guidance counselor arranged for Matt to eat school lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Playter said Matt frequently was grounded or confined to the
basement because Vince and Tami Russo said they thought Matt had
lied to them. Because the Russos refuse to comment, nobody knows
what happened inside the home, but Playter said she never caught
Matt in a lie and found him to be a sensitive, kind and intelligent
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Vince Russo became a fundamentalist Christian
and started attending an Independence church that preaches a
literal interpretation of the Bible and strict adherence to it.
While he lived with his father, Matt attended that church and was
active in the youth group, and occasionally carried a Bible to
school.
</P>
<P>
   In January of this year Vince Russo called Payson and Sharlene
Grise and said it wasn't working out for Matt to live in Missouri,
so the Grises called Daniels and asked her to draw up papers for
Vince to relinquish custody of Matt to them. Daniels sent the
papers to Russo to sign, but he never returned them. The Grises
continued asking Russo for the papers and thought it would be good
for Matt to finish the semester in Missouri before actively
pursuing custody.
</P>
<P>
   In June the school year ended and one day none of Matt's friends
knew where he was.
</P>
<P>
   Playter said she called the Russo residence and asked to speak
to Matt and Vince told her Matt didn't live there any more. She
then called Payson and Sharlene Grise to ask if Matt was in Rifle
and they didn't know where he was. Playter called Russo again and
he said Matt was at a ``really neat place'' in Louisiana, so the
Grises asked Daniels to investigate and through contacts Daniels
was able to trace him to the New Bethany compound. Bienville Parish
Sheriff Joe Storey, whose jurisdiction includes Arcadia, was able
to confirm Matt was there.
</P>
<P>
   The Arcadia New Bethany compound is billed as a fundamentalist
Christian facility and a last hope for very troubled youth that
Ford has run for at least 14 years. Because he infrequently talks
to reporters, little is known about Ford or the compound.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 Ford told a United Press International reporter that he
had been a missionary in Australia and came back to the United
States in the early 1970s to open a home for troubled youth and
raise his seven daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's first compound for youth was in Longstreet, La., where he
began taking in the ``extremely troubled'' boys and girls parents
and guardians from across the country sent to him. Louisiana state
officials shut it down in 1981 amid allegations of abuse. In 1982
Ford relocated the compound and school to Walterboro, S.C., again
taking in ``troubled'' kids and some day students. In 1984 three
employees of the facility faced charges of kidnapping and child
neglect but were not convicted. At the time Ford said the charges
were motivated by a grudge.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of beatings, neglect and other forms of abuse
continued swirling around the facility. In the 1984 UPI story, Ford
admitted to confining an ``uncontrollable'' child in a small room
and replacing the child's mattress with a chair because Ford said
the child tried to sleep all the time. South Carolina authorities
raided the facility that year and closed it. Ford then opened the
compound near Arcadia.
</P>
<P>
   In several June 1984 New Yrk Times stories, people who formerly
lived at Ford's compound told about being beaten, handcuffed and in
other ways abused by Ford and other compound workers. Ford
adamantly denied the allegations and defended the use of corporeal
punishment for kids he said were so troubled that his compound was
their last chance before jail. He said the corporeal punishment
used there was limited to ``paddlings'' and ``licks'' and no staff
member is allowed to administer more than 10 ``licks'' at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1988, Louisiana state officials raided the New Bethany
compound and took 28 of the 52 girls aged 12 to 17 from the
compound amid renewed rumors of abuse. Ford never was convicted of
a crime and has continued operating the compound, which is not
licensed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the Louisiana Department of Human Services removed
all of the children in its custody from the New Bethany compound,
according to Paul Brown of the Louisiana Volunteers for Youth
Justice. He said the department deemed it an inappropriate location
for youth in foster care on the heels of Ford's repeated refusals
to allow inspections of the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Storey said Ford also has refused to allow state officials to do
fire inspections and welfare checks and has at various times filed
lawsuits against state agencies waving the banner of separation of
church and state. He has claimed the compound is a church and not
subject to state laws, particularly since the compound is run
entirely by donations, and so far the state has supported his
arguments, said Walter May, Jr., district attorney for the
Louisiana Second Judicial District.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a church facility down there and of course we are
state,'' Storey said. ``He refuses us entry down there, he has
refused us entry even when we've had legal papers.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, much is unknown about the compound. Haynes said
his visit there was brief because he was returning a child to the
compound who had been there previously, then transferred to Hope
Youth Ranch but, at the child's mother's decision, returned to New
Bethany.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real peculiar about outsiders there,'' he said. ``They
basically tried their best to get me out of there as quick as
possible. They're real short with you, and usually when you do an
intake there's quite a bit of paperwork but they didn't require me
to sign any papers. They did ask me what kind of problems we'd had
with the boy, but that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's not a bad place. They do have the tall fence around
it with razor wire and the German shepherds run free within the
facility and they're constantly barking, which could be
intimidating. But I'd gone down to see the facility and if I'd had
a problem with it I would have brought the boy back with me. The
razor wire may be been a little extreme, but I can see why he has
it. These are troubled kids, kids with problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes said he saw well-maintained grounds amid the scrub pines
of north-central Louisiana, two-story dormitories for boys and
girls, a gym, a church and a small, tidy farm at the back of the
compound. There are separate living facilities for the staff
members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have lived at the compound have said the rules are
extremely strict, which Ford has said is necessary to maintain
discipline for troubled youth. In addition to corporeal punishment
Ford has said he believes is mandated in the Bible, students have
extremely limited access to the outside world. They can have
contact only with the parent or guardian who sent them there.
</P>
<P>
   That is what bothered Joan Grise. She said she couldn't call
Matt and had no way of knowing how he was doing at New Bethany. She
could only send letters to Matt by way of Vince Russo. So she went
to Missouri to see what she could do for her grandson.
</P>
<P>
   She said her attempts to ask Russo what was going on were
fruitless, so she donned a sandwich board bearing Matt's picture
and the words ``Missing!'' and picketed in front of Russo's house.
He called the police and she told them she was too old to be
intimidated. She said she'd beaten cancer into submission for three
years and was tough enough to see this through, too. She wanted to
see her grandson.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is worried, and she's not the only one. The Grises,
the Playters, the Walkers, the Bentleys, all have had no contact
with Matt since July. They don't know if he's happy, if he has
enough to eat, if he still has straight A's or ever gets to play
baseball. And they all want him out of there but they don't know
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Legal counsel in Colorado, Missouri and Louisiana have come up
with different answers. Daniels said Colorado really has no
jurisdiction in this case since it has been almost two years since
Matt has lived here. May said this most likely is a civil rather
than criminal issue because it revolves around custody of Matt and
who can make decisions for him. And since it is a custody issue,
the case would be handled by the state with the most information on
the case - in this case, Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys in Louisiana have told the Grises and the Playters
there is little they can do at this point because Vince Russo is
Matt's legal guardian and is allowed by law to make decisions for
Matt and send him to the New Bethany compound.
</P>
<P>
   Storey said Louisiana at this point could do nothing criminally
because there is no documented evidence of abuse at New Bethany. He
said if Matt ran away and sought the sheriff's department's help,
Storey would have to call Russo and see what he wanted done. And if
Russo said he wanted Matt back at New Bethany, Storey would have to
take him there.
</P>
<P>
   So Payson Grise and Sandy Playter and Joan Grise and many of
Matt's other friends said they don't know what to do now, which
makes them feel helpless and fearful of the worst.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, they said they fear brainwashing and that they've lost
the boy they love in the most awful sense. They fear what happens
to a boy who loses his mother to lingering, ugly cancer then is
sent away by his father. They fear that the boy they love is scared
and hurting and feeling awfully alone because the people he loves
haven't called or written.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys have told family and friends their best hope is to
begin an expensive custody battle or somehow convince Russo to
bring Matt back. Bentley set up a fund at Norwest Bank to take
donations for legal fees to get custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how this can happen,'' Walker said. ``How
can this happen in America? And why can't the state of Louisiana do
anything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a straight A honor student, a wonderful athlete,''
Payson Grise said. ``He's a wonderful kid. He shouldn't be there,
he doesn't need to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of every kid I know, Matt is the one with the most places to
go,'' Bentley said. ``There are so many people who would love to
have him, that I don't know why Vince thought this was the only
option.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grises want him, Bentley said she would love to have him
live with her and David, Playter said despite having four sons of
her own, she and her family would be honored to have Matt live with
them. ``I'm scared he doesn't know that,'' Playter said. ``When
this whole thing started I began keeping a journal of what happened
that day and who called to ask about Matt. It's at least 30 pages
now and I'm keeping it for him to have when he gets out. I want him
to be able to read it and know people prayed for him and fought for
him and thought about him every single day. I want him to know how
much so many people love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
