<HEADLINE>
SINN FEIN'S ADAMS WARNS OF SNAG ON ARMS ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ The Sinn Fein leader, Gerry Adams, warned that the
political settlement in Northern Ireland could collapse unless the
British and Irish governments stop focusing on the fate of
paramilitary weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview with the Globe, Adams expressed both
concern and optimism. He said the stalled peace process was in
danger of becoming hopelessly bogged down over one issue _ weapons.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged that he and other leading members of his
party, which is the political wing of the Irish Republican Army,
have been trying to persuade skeptical members of the IRA to stay
committed to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem at the moment is that the agreement is losing
credibility. So that means we have to convince people, Sinn Fein
and I have to convince people, that the agreement isn't the
unionists having their way again,'' Adams said Friday over
breakfast in a Dublin hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process is stalled over the refusal of Protestant
unionists to allow Adams and the Sinn Fein negotiator, Martin
McGuinness, to sit in the Cabinet of the new government, which was
created under the Good Friday agreement.
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, the Northern Ireland Assembly's first minister,
and the leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, says Sinn Fein cannot
take part in the government until the IRA begins turning in some of
its vast arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   But Adams says there is nothing in the agreement that links Sinn
Fein's participation in government with IRA disarmament. Under the
agreement, Irish republican and British loyalist paramilitary
groups are supposed to begin turning in their weapons within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, who with nationalist leader John Hume was awarded the
Nobel Peace Prize last month, is fighting a rear-guard action in
his party by those who are bitterly opposed to the agreement.
Unionists are especially opposed to the parts that call for the
release of paramilitary prisoners and reform of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, which is 93 percent Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he appreciates Trimble's political difficulties,
``but that doesn't mean he can rewrite the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said it was up to British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, to make it clear that arms
decommissioning is only part of the settlement, and that the issue
should not be allowed to marginalize Sinn Fein and a party linked
to loyalist paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the governments,'' Adams said. ``While I'm worried,
I also share Tony Blair's optimism in that we all have come too far
to let it go back. The governments need to step up their ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Unionists say the IRA must give up its weapons to prove it is
seriously committed to the democratic process. But the IRA says
previous incarnations of Irish revolutionary groups were allowed to
enter the democratic process without giving up their weapons.
Loyalist groups, meanwhile, have said they won't turn in their
weapons even if the IRA does.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the seriousness of the impasse, Blair traveled to
Belfast last week to seek a compromise on the arms issue. Ahern is
scheduled to do the same this week. Both leaders, who held talks in
Dublin on Wednesday and Thursday, said they hoped to announce soon
the establishment of cross-border authorities that would oversee
areas of mutual interest on the island of Ireland. That part of the
agreement is seen as crucial by Irish nationalists because it
involves the Irish government in the administration of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Blair became the first British prime minister to
address the Irish parliament in Dublin. Adams was in the
distinguished visitors' area as he watched Blair's address, further
evidence of the gradual emergence into the mainstream of a man who
in the 1970s was an IRA commander.
</P>
<P>
   Later on Thursday, Adams spoke to a group of 400 business
leaders here, outlining his party's economic policy. Adams was
applauded by the industrialists, another milestone in Sinn Fein's
transition from pariah to ordinary political party.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he was not trying to be alarmist, or use hyperbole,
but he said he was worried that too many people were becoming
complacent about the peace process. He said it could collapse if
the impasse is allowed to drag on indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is serious,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
