<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-SPECIALT     11-28 2285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-SPECIALTEAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNERS ARE RUNNING UP THE SCORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This has been a wild season for special teams coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Through the season's first 12 weeks, 10 kickoff returns and 13
punt returns have gone for touchdowns, a total of 23 that is
unprecedented for 12 weeks since the advent of the 16-game schedule
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The punt-return total of 13 matches the 12-week total in 1994
and 1997, the two years with the most combined punt and kick
returns for scores in NFL history. In 1994, 32 kicks were returned
for scores, and last year 29 were brought back. The record is in
jeopardy, and Dante Scarnecchia, the Patriots' special teams coach,
is not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of returners is as high as it's ever been,'' said
Scarnecchia. ``Every week, it's `Oh, my God.' There are a lot more
return guys who can pull the trigger now than there used to be in
the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarnecchia does not support the theory that the advent of free
agency and hence the constant movement of players who in the past
might have formed the core of a consistent special teams unit is
part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed emotions about that,'' Scarnecchia said. ``It's
nice when you've got the same guys year in and year out like we
used to have, but they all hit the wall. They become starters and
don't want to do it anymore or they're close to becoming a starter
and so focused on that they've forgotten about playing special
teams. And, frankly, you can do that job for only so long before
you can't make yourself do it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I like new faces. It's painful sometimes until you
get them coached and you find yourself emphasizing the same stuff
every year, over and over, but that's coaching. What it gives you
is enthusiasm. I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When  &UR; Doug Flutie  &LR; arrives at Foxboro Stadium Sunday, he will
bring with him the second-highest third-down conversion rate of any
NFL quarterback this season; he is second only to Minnesota's
 &UR; Randall Cunningham &LR; . The importance of this is obvious by the fact
that thequarterbacks with the five highest third-down percentages
are a collective 29-11 as starters. Flutie is 37 of 72 (51.4
percent, 5-1 as a starter). The others in the top five are  &UR; Steve
Young  &LR; (47.3 percent, 7-3),  &UR; Vinny Testaverde  &LR; (46.9 percent, 7-1),
and  &UR; Steve Beuerlein  &LR; (46.6 percent, 2-5) ... Cunningham told an
interesting story last week about how his comeback began on a golf
course in Santa Barbara, Calif., during the year he exiled himself
from the NFL. Cunningham was playing in a foursome with  &UR; Michael
Jordan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and at one point Jordan pulled out a cigar. Someone asked
what it was, and Jordan said, ``It's a championship cigar.
Cunningham wouldn't know anything about this.'' Although Cunningham
laughed at the time, he also said it ``opened my eyes.'' Soon he
accepted the backup role to  &UR; Brad Johnson  &LR; in Minnesota and now,
with Johnson out until at least Dec. 6 with a broken thumb, he's
the comeback player of the year ... Just for the record, the Bills
and Jets have the easiest finishing schedules in the AFC East. Both
face opponents with an aggregate winning percentage of .491. The
Patriots' opponents are .582, while Miami's are .709 ... Dolphins
rookie  &UR; John Avery  &LR; comes from a tough household. Twice last Monday
night, he missed adding to those kick-return totals when he was
tackled or tripped by New England kicker  &UR; Adam Vinatieri &LR; . It was
no surprise to learn that Avery's teammates were on him about that,
but apparently he had a harsher critic. Avery claimed his mother
called and said, ``How do you let a kicker take you down from
behind? I thought I raised you better than that.'' Such
close-to-home criticism is nothing new to him, however. ``When I
ran a 4.3 at the combine,'' said Avery, ``My father told me, `I can
do that.''' ... Dolphins wide receiver  &UR; O.J. McDuffie  &LR; has been on
a tear. In his last three games, he nearly doubled his season
receiving yardage, catching 24 passes for 314 yards. In the first
half of the season, McDuffie had 32 catches for 345 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When the undefeated Broncos wend their way into Qualcomm Stadium
Sunday to face the 5-6 San Diego Chargers, an oddity of history has
a chance to repeat itself. On Nov. 18, 1984, the 11-0 Dolphins went
to San Diego to play the 5-6 Chargers. By the end of the day, San
Diego had ended that Dolphin team's quest to match its undefeated
1972 brethren, beating Miami, 34-28, in overtime. Among the
Chargers players that season was former Patriot safety  &UR; Tim
Fox &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who said that week, ``The way our season is going, we'll
probably win.'' If history repeats itself Sunday, no one will be
happier than  &UR; Dick Anderson  &LR; and  &UR; Nick Buoniconti &LR; , &UR;  &LR; two mainstays
of the 1972 Miami team that went 17-0. They and several other
members of that team gather each season after the last remaining
undefeated team is beaten to toast themselves with champagne. That
recently prompted another former teammate,  &UR; Manny Fernandez &LR; , &UR;  &LR; to
comment: ``I wish them and their psychoanalysts well.'' ... Denver,
by the way, has won its last seven road games, dating back to last
year's playoffs ... Here's how quickly things can change in the
NFL. Not a single one of the teams that won a division title last
season is leading a division this week ... These could be flush
times for  &UR; Fred Taylor &LR; . The Jaguars rookie running back has rushed
for 806 yards and 10 touchdowns and is within hailing distance of
several big-money incentive clauses in his contract. Taylor will
earn an extra $150,000 if he rushes for 1,000 yards and $200,000
more if he scores 12 touchdowns. If Taylor reaches 1,200 yards,
it's worth $200,000, and for 1,300 yards he would be paid an
additional $500,000 ... Taylor, by the way, has one more touchdown
than Minnesota rookie receiver  &UR; Randy Moss  &LR; and four more than
Patriot rookie running back  &UR; Robert Edwards  &LR; ... There are many
reasons why the Packers have struggled this year, but a glaring one
has been the absence of the big plays that characterized their
recent seasons. This time a year ago, Green Bay's offense had
produced 50 plays of 20 yards or more. This year, the number is 30.
Worse, their running backs had 12 such plays in 1997. They have
none this season.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jets coach  &UR; Bill Parcells  &LR; came up with a most innovative
explanation for why he kept the locker room closed to the media _
in violation of league rules _ after last Sunday's victory over the
Oilers. He said it was for ``safety reasons'' because the visitors'
locker room at Vanderbilt Stadium was so small. Parcells didn't
specify, but it seems fair to assume he was talking about his
players' safety, and not the media's. Either way, it cost the Jets
$10,000 ...  &UR; Rick Terry &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a defensive tackle whom Parcells drafted
in the second round last year and cut this year, was asked by the
Carolina media for a one-word assessment of Parcells. ``Dictator,''
said Terry, who is now a backup with the Panthers ... When
Arizona's  &UR; Jake Plummer  &LR; rushed for three touchdowns last Sunday,
he became the first quarterback to do so since  &UR; Archie Manning  &LR; in
1977. Plummer has been impressive enough in his second season to
lead Dallas cornerback  &UR; Deion Sanders  &LR; to comment, ``He's the kind
of quarterback you don't want to see in the fourth quarter.'' ...
Quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf  &LR; continues to sit on the bench in San Diego,
and his bar tabs continue to sit on the wall of The Coug, a popular
watering hole in Pullman, Wash., near the Washington State campus.
Apparently Leaf is a legendary cheapskate, which is why they have
his bills _ with tip _ posted. One of the best of the worst is a
$90 bill with a $5 tip ... When head coaching vacancies open up
this winter, don't expect to see many senior citizens filling them.
 &UR; Bryan Cox  &LR; may not be right about everything he said last week,
but it's hard to argue with his position on the success rate of
resurrected head coaches in the NFL. Four current coaches are over
60 _  &UR; Dick Vermeil &LR; , &UR; Jim Mora &LR; , &UR; Bobby Ross &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Ted Marchibroda &LR; 
_ and their combined record is 14-31. Vermeil has said he would
never resign, despite a two-year record in St. Louis of 8-19, and
Marchibroda is 14-28-1 since taking over the Ravens _ the
second-worst record in the league during that period. Who was
worse? Indianapolis (14-29), the team that fired Marchibroda ...
Speaking of the Colts, they're 29th in the NFL in yards allowed
(367.5), rushing yards allowed (159.4), and points allowed (27.1)
per game, and with good reason. Of their 25 defensive players, only
five were drafted in the first three rounds, and, because of
injuries, as many as five of Sunday's starters could be undrafted
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are taking few chances with 1,000-yard rusher  &UR; Jamal
Anderson &LR; . Last week they asked his agent to submit a proposal for
a contract extension that would make Anderson one of the league's
top five paid backs. Anderson, who has a year to run on his present
deal, has rushed for 1,000 yards three straight seasons and will
earn $1.2 million this year and is due to be paid $1.6 million in
1999. No deal is imminent, but the Falcons seem committed to
re-signing him long before he gets into the position  &UR; Curtis Martin
 &LR; was in last March with New England ... Troubled ex-Bears defensive
end  &UR; Alonzo Spellman  &LR; has resurfaced around Chicago and is talking
about wanting to return to the NFL next season. Spellman recently
did a round of TV and print interviews while appearing at a
children's center he helped finance. Although he has been diagnosed
as manic-depressive, he said he would refuse to take his prescribed
medicine, even if it was a requirement for returning to the NFL.
``If it comes down to that _ and I don't think it's going to come
down to that _ it's definitely something I will not do,'' Spellman
said. ``I know everything's all right with 'Zo.'' ... Patriots
coach  &UR; Pete Carroll  &LR; said he had never heard of a call as bizarre
as the botched coin flip in the Pittsburgh-Detroit game Thursday in
which Steelers running back  &UR; Jerome Bettis  &LR; was heard calling
``tails'' yet referee  &UR; Phil Luckett  &LR; insisted he'd called heads and
thus allowed the Lions to receive the kickoff. Detroit marched
downfield to kick the winning field goal. Luckett later claimed
Bettis first called heads and then changed it to tails, even though
replays indicated Bettis called ``tails.'' ``I've never heard of
that happening,'' Carroll said. ``I don't know how that could have
happened. Heads-tails? I've never heard of that happening. That's
pretty unusual.'' Let's hope so ... Former Carolina quarterback
 &UR; Kerry Collins  &LR; believes he has a kindred spirit in his new boss,
Saints coach  &UR; Mike Ditka &LR; . ``He talked to me about second chances
and the fact that he got a second chance and that it saved his
career,'' Collins said. Ditka didn't disagree, citing how he went
from being a Pro Bowl tight end in Chicago to a disgruntled player
when he was traded to the Eagles. ``I became a very bad guy,''
Ditka said. ``I was a complainer. I was all the things you don't
want to be. I spent a lot of time in bars and told my story to any
poor sap that would listen.'' Now Ditka is counseling Collins, and
it may be paying off. Last Sunday Collins not only threw for 328
yards in a 31-20 loss to San Francisco but also pulled a child from
a car involved in a smoky accident on his way to the airport. The
Saints are hoping to sign Collins to a new deal at the end of the
season but realize that if he plays well, they could lose him to
cap-friendly Cleveland. ``We'd love to sign him, but we won't
overpay for him, either,'' Saints GM  &UR; Bill Kuharich  &LR; said.
``Cleveland is in a position to do that because they have all that
cap room, but we're hopeful if he plays well the rest of the season
we'll have a chance to re-sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Owner  &UR; Al Lerner &LR;  decided that his new Cleveland team would wear
the same logo-less helmets as the old Browns, even though NFL
Properties came up with several dramatic possibilities. After
seeing them, Lerner said, ``Good. If they want to use them, let
them buy a team.'' Lerner said the helmets will remain plain ``for
at least as long as my life expectancy.'' ... San Francisco
executive  &UR; Dwight Clark  &LR; is expected to be released from bondage by
the 49ers this week and could be in his new office in Cleveland
next door to  &UR; Carmen Policy  &LR; before next weekend ... Good wishes
and a prayer go out to Saints salary cap consultant  &UR; Terry
O'Neill &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former network executive, who is recovering from
cancer surgery at home in Greenwich, Conn. The play of his Saints
this season should help cheer him, since he helped figure out how
to re-sign  &UR; Joe Johnson  &LR; and  &UR; Mark Fields  &LR; ... Speaking of the
Saints, since they signed Fields to a multimillion-dollar extension
a month ago, he has gone wild. Fields has made 11, 10, and 11
tackles in his last three games and has a sack in each one ... Poor
 &UR; Priest Holmes. &LR;  If he could play the Cincinnati Bengals every
week, he'd be the high priest of NFL running backs. The Ravens
runner rushed for 227 yards vs. the Bengals last Sunday and has 400
in their two meetings this year, averaging 6.3 yards a carry.
Holmes has the Ravens' only three rushing touchdowns and all came
against Cincinnati. If Holmes could keep up the same pace against
the rest of the league, he'd rush for 3,200 yards ... Here is the
difference Parcells has made in the Jets. In the last 27 games, the
Jets are 16-11 under Parcells. In the 27 games prior to that under
 &UR; Rich Kotite &LR; , &UR;  &LR; they were 3-24. For those of you following at home,
that's a 13-game swing.
</P>
</TEXT>
