<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-ZOLAK-     11-28 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-ZOLAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOLAK MAY HAVE CAREER OPPORTUNITY ON HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ He has been careful not to talk about it through
his long, six-day wait, but Scott Zolak knows what could be at
stake for him this afternoon at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   If Zolak is pressed into action for Drew Bledsoe, as appears
likely, this could be his chance of a lifetime. After nearly eight
years of patient waiting, Zolak's moment may be arriving at the
best of times for him and in the worst of times for his team.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots cannot afford a slipup Sunday against the Buffalo
Bills if they want to keep their playoff hopes off life support.
There is no margin for error, which is why the notion of playing
Bledsoe with a broken right index finger is courting disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The game is likely to be a close one, as was the first battle
between these teams two weeks ago. It very well could be decided by
a key play or perhaps a turnover. And what more likely way to tempt
fate than to ask your quarterback to take 60 or 70 snaps from
center with a broken finger on his throwing hand? Or to ask him to
throw 30 or 40 passes with it?
</P>
<P>
   That is why it makes sense to play Zolak despite the fact he has
not started a game since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are financial incentives for Zolak to do well.
</P>
<P>
   Next February, he becomes a free agent. As things were going, he
was due to enter the market as a backup quarterback who had not
started a game in more than three years and had thrown fewer than
25 passes in that time. In other words, he wouldn't have much to
sell but eight years as a loyal soldier.
</P>
<P>
   But if Zolak comes through Sunday, or in one or two other games
this season, the perception of him could change radically in a
league starving for quarterback talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about that right now, because at the time
you're thinking about things like that, you can float off and get
out of control,'' Zolak said. ``But I understand what this is. I
understand this game could do a lot for me. I also understand I
could end up not even playing.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does play and performs well, however, one can only
speculate about what it could do to his market value.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Rob Johnson was in a similar situation last year,
after having sat for three seasons behind Mark Brunell in
Jacksonville. He replaced an injured Brunell in the team's 1997
opener against Baltimore and completed 20 of 24 passes for 294
yards while throwing for two touchdowns and running for a third.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson never started another game, but the NFL did not forget
him. During the offseason, there was a scramble to pry Johnson away
from Jacksonville, a team for whom he was not going to play as long
as Brunell stayed healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were so enraptured by his one start and several relief
performances that they traded their first- and fourth-round draft
choices for him and then signed him to a lucrative contract that
included an $8 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will be watching from the bench, having lost his job to
Doug Flutie only months after he was awarded it, while Zolak will
likely be getting his chance to hit an NFL jackpot with an
outstanding performance.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak's agent, Ralph Cindrich, was reluctant to talk about all
that, in part because he is not sure his client will even play and
in part because no one knows how ready Zolak is to take advantage
of what could be a very advantageous position.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cindrich understands the negotiation game as well as
anyone. He knows what this opportunity could mean in the open
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not where Scott's focus is,'' Cindrich said. ``He's not
thinking about things individually. He has a lot of respect for
Drew and a lot of confidence in his own ability. He's just excited
at the prospect of possibly getting to play. Because Drew has been
such a durable guy, he hasn't had that chance very often.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the rest of it, I don't know that one or two good games
would do it for Scott, although certainly it makes sense that if he
gets this opportunity it could be important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   As important to his long-term future as it is to his team's
short-term fate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
