A3045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-SUGARSHA     11-28 1825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-SUGARSHANE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE OF SUGAR MAY GO UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; There is only one Sugar Ray, and the same may be true of Sugar
Shane.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the great skill Sugar Ray Leonard showed throughout
his distinguished career, when you say ``Sugar Ray'' in boxing
circles what follows next is ``Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   If things continue along for another five or six years the way
they've been going lately, if anyone says ``Sugar Shane'' in
another decade or two, the only thing you'll hear after that is
``Mosley.''
</P>
<P>
   It is always dangerous in boxing to put Sugar in your system,
because most fighters wilt in comparison to the greatest boxer in
history, but Mosley has made a strong case for his right to borrow
the name since first winning the lightweight title.
</P>
<P>
   His most recent victory was a surprisingly one-sided destruction
of former World Boxing Council super featherweight champion James
Leija, and with it the International Boxing Federation champion did
more than keep himself undefeated. He also arguably moved one step
closer to a father's seemingly odd goal for his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Shane Mosley to become the cash cow of his division,
the way Roy Jones is in his division and Oscar De La Hoya is in his
division,'' Jack Mosley said. ``He is the best lightweight in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the thought of your son becoming a cash cow might make
some parents cringe, if you work in the often bizarre world of
big-time boxing, such a goal is not as demeaning as it might sound,
because prizefighting is as much about the prize as the fighting,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley got the first of those prizes a day after beating Leija
silly when he signed a seven-fight deal with HBO that includes the
possibility of at least one pay-per-view match. Such a contract is
the Holy Grail of the sport, for that is where the money is, and
where the money is is where Jack Mosley wants his son to be, and
his right to be there will never be disputed by James Leija.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets more respect from me every time I watch him,'' Leija
said.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Mosley and his father are seeking now. The respect
not only of boxing's cognoscenti, who have long known him as the
fastest and most gifted fighter in the lower weight classes, but
also the respect of the general sporting public, because from there
comes the real cash.
</P>
<P>
   To earn the kind of money De La Hoya, Jones, and Prince Naseem
Hamed command, Mosley must stay busy even though he seems unrivaled
in his weight class, but he must do something more. He must do
something far more difficult than fighting.
</P>
<P>
   He must blow his own horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cesar Bazan said in some Spanish newspapers he wanted to unify
the (lightweight) title,'' Mosley said after some prodding from his
father. ``I've always wanted to do the same. We're going to get
that straightened out in his mind so we'll all know who's the best
lightweight in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley didn't seem to indicate that he thought that lightweight
was the current WBC champion, but he also didn't seem comfortable
doing what he has steadfastly refused to do most of his life _
boast.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mosley understands if such a fight can be made (and it might
be, because promoter Bob Arum has a piece of Bazan and a
relationship with HBO, which wants the fight) he could solidify his
dominance at 135 pounds by beating Bazan and then giving a shot to
Stevie Johnston (another Arum fighter the public was just beginning
to recognize when Bazan upset him). If he wins those fights on HBO,
Mosley's name would be more widely known and he could move up to
140 pounds and immediately challenge for a title with the full
knowledge that he was out of legitimate lightweights with which to
make a payday.
</P>
<P>
   He would then be free to hunt down the likes of hard-hitting
Kostya Tszyu, relentless Vince Phillips, two-time world champion
Miguel Angel Gonzalez, and perhaps even a young lion named Zab
Judah, who is 17-0 and has looked good building that record in the
140-pound class.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever direction Mosley takes, his father believes there is
only one route to follow. The loud one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane is trying to become cocky but he's always been a quiet,
laidback guy,'' his father-trainer-manager said. ``He's trying to
be more assertive outside the ring to let everybody know who he is
because he can back up what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jones said recently, ``I love the father-son relationship they
have,'' when asked about the Mosleys because his own attempts at
that failed so miserably that he and his hard-bitten father now
barely speak after years of training together. Jones said Mosley's
father came to him to discuss the problems of a
personal-professional relationship between father and son and Jones
advised him to give his son room to be a man. ``He realized he was
losing Shane, and he changed,'' Jones said ... Just for the record,
here's your faithful commentator's latest pound-for-pound Top 10
list: (1) Jones; (2) Mosley; (3) De La Hoya; (4)  &UR; Mark
Johnson &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (5)  &UR; Felix Trinidad &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (6)  &UR; Evander Holyfield &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (7)
 &UR; Tim Austin &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (8) Naseem Hamed; (9)  &UR; Ike Quartey &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (10)  &UR; Johnny
Tapia  &LR; and  &UR; Saman Sorjnturong  &LR; (tie). Any quarrels, please send
them along ... Just for the record, here's old friend and top
trainer  &UR; Teddy Atlas's  &LR; all-time best pound-for-pound ratings: (1)
Robinson; (2)  &UR; Henry Armstrong &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (3)  &UR; Muhammad Ali &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (4)  &UR; Benny
Leonard &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (5)  &UR; Sam Langford &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (6)  &UR; Harry Greb &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (7)  &UR; Mickey
Walker &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (8)  &UR; Roberto Duran &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (9)  &UR; Gene Tunney &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; (10)  &UR; Carlos
Monzon  &LR; and  &UR; Joe Louis &LR; . What makes his list most interesting is
that Atlas included three heavyweights. Often, they are ignored by
less knowledgeable observers. Any quarrels, please send them to him
... HBO had hoped to find a way to replace the injured Gonzalez
with Mosley last night but he was unable to make such a quick
turnaround two weeks after his last title defense. So HBO settled
for putting in Cuban  &UR; Diosbelys Hurtado  &LR; with original Gonzalez
opponent Tszyu because WBC president  &UR; Jose Sulaiman  &LR; agreed to
sanction it for one of those dreaded ``interim'' titles that so
often come back to haunt everyone. The winner of the interim WBC
junior welterweight title had to agree to fight _ or sign to fight
_ Gonzalez within 90 days. It was Hurtado's second fight in 15
days, as he went the distance Nov. 13 vs.  &UR; Manuel Gomez  &LR; in Miami
on a card that included fellow Cuban exile  &UR; Eliseo Castillo &LR; . Those
bouts were broadcast on Radio Marti back to Cuba, marking only the
third time a sporting event was broadcast from the US to Cuba since
 &UR; Fidel Castro's  &LR; takeover. The others were the 1997 and 1998 World
Series pitching performances of  &UR; Livan Hernandez  &LR; and his brother
 &UR; Orlando Hernandez  &LR; ...  &UR; Dino Duva's  &LR; promotional company, Main
Events, tied the can last week to four fighters, including
undefeated but reluctant heavyweight prospect  &UR; Chris Byrd  &LR; (26-0)
and two Cuban defectors who were originally signed with great
fanfare at the Atlanta Olympics after a heated battle for their
services with rival promoter  &UR; Bob Arum &LR; . Duva dumped both junior
lightweight  &UR; Joel Casamayor  &LR; and cruiserweight  &UR; Ramon Garbey  &LR; ...
Now that the deal has been done between promoter  &UR; Don King  &LR; and
TVKO, HBO's pay-per-view arm, for the March 13 unification fight
between Holyfield, the World Boxing Association-IBF heavyweight
champion, and WBC titleholder  &UR; Lennox Lewis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; King will take the
two champions on a publicity tour, which hits Boston Tuesday ...
Next Saturday night, King will make his first promotional
appearance in New Jersey since Dec. 8, 1990, when he stages the
first title defense of new WBA welterweight champion  &UR; James Page
 &LR; against mandatory challenger  &UR; Jose Luis Lopez &LR; , &UR;  &LR; as well as World
Boxing Organization junior bantamweight champion Tapia's quest for
the bantamweight title vs. WBA champion  &UR; Nana Konadu  &LR; at the
Atlantic City Convention Center. King had been banned from
promoting in New Jersey when he was indicted by the US government
on insurance fraud charges, but he has twice beaten the charges ...
The problem in announcing the  &UR; Mike Tyson &LR; - &UR; Frans Botha  &LR; fight has
been solved. The MGM Grand will host the event as planned Jan. 16,
but it had been seeking a multi-fight option while offering no site
fee. That meant the casino would provide no guaranteed money to the
promoters but simply supply the building, with the promoter keeping
the gate and taking all the financial risk. Those demands were
altered this past week, and an announcement on an agreement will be
made in Los Angeles this week.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 8 at the Roseland Ballroom in Manhattan, promoter  &UR; Cedric
Kushner  &LR; will stage another of his Heavyweight Explosion shows on
US Satellite Broadcasting, with  &UR; Kirk Johnson  &LR; (26-0, 19 KOs) in
the main event vs. former IBF cruiserweight champion  &UR; Al  &LR; ``Ice''
 &UR; Cole  &LR; (30-3, 15 KOs). Byrd faces  &UR; Jeff Wooden &LR; , &UR; Obed Sullivan
 &LR; fights aged  &UR; Jesse Ferguson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and former NFL running back  &UR; Alonzo
Highsmith  &LR; continues his quest for boxing glory on the same card
... Jones took a solid shot at King during a recent press
conference called to publicize what turned out to be another
one-sided victory for him over WBO middleweight champion  &UR; Otis
Grant. &LR;  While talking about the benefit screening of an HBO
documentary on Robinson held to raise money for the children of
crippled former middleweight champ  &UR; Gerald McClellan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Jones said,
``It was interesting to see HBO take a Showtime fighter (McClellan)
and run a benefit for him. (Promoters)  &UR; Murad  &LR; ( &UR; Muhammad &LR; ), Cedric
Kushner, Bob Arum, and Dino Duva were all there, but the guy who
did promote him (King), I didn't see. I'm sure I wouldn't miss that
hair if it had been there.'' In fairness, King did buy a table at
the event but declined to attend after a daylong negotiating
session with Duva over the Holyfield-Lewis contract ... The best
woman fighter in the world,  &UR; Lucia Ryker &LR; , &UR;  &LR; approached fading
former champion  &UR; Terry Norris  &LR; in a West Coast gym not long after
his lackluster performance against  &UR; Dana Rosenblatt  &LR; and, as
respectfully as possible, asked him to consider the possibility
that he was staying too long in the most dangerous sport. The story
goes she told Norris he is no longer the same person he once was,
physically or mentally, and should consider retirement. Norris has
agreed to fight  &UR; Laurent Boudouani tomorrow &LR;  in Paris for the WBA
junior middleweight title, so apparently he did not heed her
heartfelt warning ...  &UR; Salvador Jasso  &LR; has a unique perspective on
the upcoming De La Hoya-Quartey matchup because he has served as a
sparring partner for both. His opinion: ``Ike will knock you out
with two or three punches, but Oscar, he's fast and turns his hands
at the last second so it hurts. Oscar surprises you and then
explodes in your face. Ike can win with the jab and the hook, but
Oscar will go over the top if Ike drops his hands.''
</P>
