<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-LEFTOVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUCK WITH THANKSGIVING LEFTOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Scott Boras, the man who almost delivered Bernie Williams to
the Red Sox before George Steinbrenner perished that thought,
stated the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet Dan Duquette is taking a lot of heat in Boston,'' said
Boras, ``but he was darn close to getting the guy. I think instead
of criticizing him, the fans in Boston should be happy that the
club was as competitive as it was trying to get Bernie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were under the impression that there was every chance
Bernie was not going to be a Yankee when we went to Atlanta (last
Sunday) to meet with the Red Sox. Truthfully, there was nothing
more Dan could have done other than substantially overpaying the
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great empathy for them, knowing how important the
player was to them, and knowing how close they were to getting him.
They were that close.''
</P>
<P>
   That is of little consolation, of course, to Red Sox fans, who
only see a gaping hole where Mo Vaughn used to be. The Sox not only
lost out on Williams, but bailed out on negotiations for Albert
Belle, who apparently has come to terms on a five-year, $65 million
deal with the AL East rival Orioles. That's about the same kind of
money the Sox offered Vaughn, so it apparently wasn't economics
that killed their interest in Belle, but character issues, though
no Sox official, including CEO John Harrington, will stand up and
say that's the reason.
</P>
<P>
   The dollars did steer the Sox away from Rafael Palmeiro, who
reportedly has received a five-year, $45 million offer to remain
with the Orioles. Duquette was not comfortable being tied that long
to the 34-year-old first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Where do the Sox go from here? Duquette's initial response was
that the team would pursue pitching. He said that neither Randy
Johnson nor Kevin Brown was interested in Boston, though Boras, who
represents Brown, said his client has never indicated that. Brown
will cost somebody more money than Pedro Martinez's six-year, $75
million deal, and Brown probably would choose Boston only if the
Sox outbid such well-heeled contenders as the Rockies, Dodgers,
Orioles, and Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Take away the top-of-the-line free agents, and the pickings for
pitching are slim. The Sox could sign a Tim Belcher or a Bob
Tewksbury, or perhaps trade for a Pedro Astacio, but none of those
names is a fit for the No. 2 starter sought by the club. Roger
Clemens? A nice fantasy, but the Blue Jays will eventually move him
elsewhere for more than they could get from the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   On the offensive side, Duquette has explored a trade for Expos
outfielder Rondell White, but Montreal officials have indicated
that, so far, it's not a good match. The Sox could inquire about
the availability of the Big Hurt, Frank Thomas, who was on the
market at the end of last season, but it's unclear the White Sox
would move him, especially with Belle not coming back to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, only 30, is an intriguing thought, especially since it's
likely that last season's .265 average was an aberration for a man
who began 1998 with a lifetime average of .330. He's also a first
baseman, albeit a reluctant one who prefers to DH, and the White
Sox picked up another first baseman, Paul Konerko, this fall from
Cincinnati. During the summer, the Red Sox had floated a
Vaughn-Thomas swap past the White Sox, and while club sources
insist the teams have not talked recently about Thomas, it would
seem to be a logical avenue to revisit.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers would move $10 million man Gary Sheffield, who has
been erratic and hurt the last couple of years, and might even
consider dealing outfielder Raul Mondesi, about whom the Red Sox
inquired last winter. With Jay Buhner most likely having to move to
first, slick-fielding David Segui could be available from Seattle,
for whom he posted some of the best offensive numbers of his career
last season (.305, 19 home runs, 84 RBIs).
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman's Kansas City teammate, Johnny Damon, could
attract some interest from the Sox. Damon, 25, has yet to show the
star quality the Royals anticipated when he broke into their
lineup, but while his offensive numbers remain modest (.277, 18,
66), his power numbers have jumped over his first two seasons and
he could be on the verge of a breakout year. The Sox could also
take a run at the Marlins' Cliff Floyd, a lefthanded-hitting first
baseman/outfielder who hit 22 home runs and drove in 90 runs for
baseball's weakest team.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's winter meetings begin a week from Friday in
Nashville, where Duquette is expected to be one of the most active
players in Music City. He has little choice.
</P>
<P>
   How hectic have recent days been for Boras? He called home at
one point, only to discover that his wife and three kids had moved
into their new house in Southern California. Boras knew the move
was in the works but had lost track of time and didn't realize the
vans would be coming while he was away.
</P>
<P>
   Boras was asked how he would respond to the charge that he
played Duquette as a means of driving up the price for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is so clear that wasn't the case,'' he said.
``But even if we did do that, that's the market. The Boston Red Sox
made a fair-market offer, and the fans should be more upset if the
team's ownership hadn't been competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras spent an hour Friday night on the telephone, explaining
the series of events that ultimately led to Williams becoming a
Yankee and the Red Sox being left with an empty plate on
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, when Duquette flew to Atlanta to meet with Williams
and Boras, the Yankees had made just one offer to Williams, a
five-year deal for $60 million that Boras would not even
acknowledge. The other team most interested in Williams was the
Arizona Diamondbacks, whose manager, Buck Showalter, is very close
to Williams from their days together with the Yankees. Boras would
not confirm what Arizona was prepared to pay, but he did say there
was one team in the Williams sweepstakes willing to guarantee the
center fielder more than $90 million for seven years, and
presumably that was Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette initially had made a run at Belle when talks broke off
with Vaughn, but when it became evident to him that there really
was a chance Williams would leave the Yankees, he made a powerful
presentation to the American League batting champion, bringing in
manager Jimy Williams on Monday to reinforce his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy and Dan made a very positive impact on Bernie,'' Boras
said. ``Dan, I'm telling you, really handled the situation well. I
thought his timing was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy and Bernie had a delightful three- or four-hour
conversation. And I've been around many GMs in these situations,
and they're very uncomfortable with the player. Dan was not like
that at all. This guy impressed me. He did a great job on Bernie.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in their conversation, according to Boras, Duquette
asked Williams point-blank why the center fielder of the World
Series-winning Yankees would want to leave. Boras said that both he
and the player responded by telling the Sox GM that if the Yankees
were willing to pay him his fair-market value, he wouldn't be going
anywhere. They never told the Red Sox otherwise, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees had not done so, and instead were in the hunt
for Belle as well as exploring a trade for Montreal's White.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Duquette not only made a seven-year offer, Boras said,
but the sides discussed all the other details that go into a
contract of this magnitude: incentive clauses, performance bonuses,
and the like. The Sox balked at a no-trade clause, but in the end,
they even gave some ground there, putting in an additional $2
million payment if Williams was traded in the fifth year of the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Boras said Williams was prepared to choose Boston over Arizona,
mainly because he had questions about how long it would be before
the expansion Diamondbacks would be competitive. But then late
Monday night, Yankees GM Brian Cashman called Boras, asking for
another chance to talk. And, at Boras's suggestion, Williams called
Cashman, and a meeting was set for the next day in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Williams and Steinbrenner, who takes a far more
proactive role in such matters than a Harrington, met face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them not to talk about money,'' Boras said, ``but talk
about whether they were prepared for life without one another.''
</P>
<P>
   They had a frank discussion, Boras said, and when it was over,
the agent said he told Steinbrenner where the market was for his
client, and what it would take to keep him. Steinbrenner, he said,
asked for more time. Boras said he would need an answer by the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told George that was D-Day,'' Boras said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, Boras said he could tell by the morose
expression on Williams's face that he didn't want to leave the
Yankees, the team with which he had grown up. He'd run into
teammate Derek Jeter at the Yankees' complex and clearly was torn
about leaving. Boras advised the player that he could take more
time on a decision, but Williams replied that he was prepared to go
to Boston if the Yankees didn't come across with a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees officials, including Cashman, said they were convinced
that Steinbrenner would not go to seven years. And, as Peter
Gammons describes elsewhere on these pages, that afternoon, the
Yankees were rebuffed on an attempt to make a deal for the Expos'
White.
</P>
<P>
   Boras was in Denver, meeting with Rockies officials about Brown,
when Steinbrenner called. At first, the Rockies executive who took
the call was reluctant to interrupt the session, perhaps fearing
that Steinbrenner wanted to place a bid on Brown. But eventually,
Boras was summoned, and after a 40-minute conversation with the
Boss, a deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   And the Sox were left out in the cold. Duquette, who had hoped
to be receiving a call saying Williams was Boston-bound, instead
received the same news as the Diamondbacks, that Williams was
staying put.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   They're already making jokes in Baltimore about who will wear
No. 8, Belle or  &UR; Cal Ripken  &LR; ... Sox catcher  &UR; Jason
Varitek &LR; , &UR;  &LR; contrary to what club officials had said initially, will
require surgery on the index finger of his throwing hand, which he
fractured playing winter ball in Puerto Rico. The surgery is no
different from that which  &UR; Steve Avery  &LR; required when he fractured
his left index finger playing football, according to Boras, who
represents both players ... The Blue Jays are reeling from manager
 &UR; Tim Johnson's  &LR; forced confession last Monday that he'd lied about
doing a tour of duty in Vietnam, when, as a member of the US Marine
Reserves, he never left the States. Johnson's imagined war stories
to his players included tales of having to shoot women and
children, according to published reports. He also lied about having
been an All-America high school basketball player and rejecting a
scholarship to play hoops at UCLA. GM  &UR; Gord Ash  &LR; praised Johnson's
``tremendous character and courage'' for coming clean, but what
choice did he have after the lies became public knowledge? Johnson
was well-liked by Sox players when he served as  &UR; Kevin Kennedy's
 &LR; bench coach in Boston, and he led the Blue Jays on their run at
the Sox last September, but once someone in his position has lost
his credibility, how can he be expected to retain a job in which
the trust of his players and the public is so crucial? Imagine the
outcry among veterans groups if Johnson were managing in a US city.
Even Ash's credibility was affected. He initially dismissed reports
about Johnson's deceit as tabloid-style journalism. Johnson, who
underwent counseling in the team's employee assistance program, was
asked by  &UR; Mike Rutsey  &LR; of the Toronto Sun why he had lied. ``It's
not like I told a lot of people,'' Johnson said. ``There are times
where I said some things I shouldn't have said. Why? Who knows?
Guilt? Maybe. I don't think it was to impress them. I think it was
more guilt (about having not gone to Vietnam) and, you know,
sometimes it's not knowing what the reason was. Maybe I feel I
should have been there with the buddies who went and I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Remember  &UR; Andy Yount &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former Sox No. 1 draft pick whose
career appeared to have come to a tragic end when he severed the
tendon of the middle finger of his pitching hand? Yount sustained
the injury when a glass, or glass bottle, shattered in his hand at
the gravesite of a friend killed in a car accident. The tendon
would not stay in place, and reportedly Yount has had nine
operations on the finger. The Red Sox released him (according to
Baseball America, he found out when his father read the news in the
transactions), but after a tryout in which he was throwing in the
low 90s, the Tigers signed him for $60,000 and invited him to the
instructional league. If Yount can develop another pitch to go
along with his fastball, Tigers officials said, he could succeed in
his improbable comeback ... Rockies infielder  &UR; Mike Lansing
 &LR; learned that he is afflicted with Bell's palsy, which affects
facial nerves but is believed to be a temporary condition. Team
trainer  &UR; Thomas Probst  &LR; said the condition is unrelated to the
numbness Lansing felt last spring in his left leg, from his knee to
his toes, which affected his play early in the season. Lansing said
there is still a slight numbness in his foot. Lansing, who signed a
four-year, $23.25 million contract after being acquired from the
Expos last November, hit .276 in his first year with the Rockies
with 12 home runs and 66 RBIs. However, he was hitting only .239
with three home runs and 17 RBIs as late as June 18 ... There has
been little rest this offseason for National League MVP  &UR; Sammy
Sosa &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but he's not worried. ``If I had time, I would be on
vacation,'' Sosa said. ``But I'm taking care of the people of my
country. The MVP is great. Sixty-six home runs are great. But when
I go home (to the Dominican Republic), I know a lot of people don't
have anything. No house, nothing. They only have one hope and I'm
trying to come through for them.'' ... Good news for the Cubs on
the  &UR; Kerry Wood  &LR; front. The National League Rookie of the Year, who
missed the last month of the season with a sore elbow, apparently
has been given a clean bill of health after an MRI on his elbow
just before the holiday. GM  &UR; Ed Lynch  &LR; said Wood should be ready
for the start of spring training ... Finally, just whom do you
think this quote refers to? ``He's one of those guys who makes a
team better in a lot of ways. He gives us that big horse in the
middle of the lineup and that takes some of the pressure off the
other guys. We still have a lot of young players who were suddenly
on the firing line in September. He is not afraid to stand up and
say, `Let's not be intimidated, we're as good as anybody.'
Leadership in the clubhouse is very important if done the right
way. He prepares right and plays right. He carries credibility.''
Mo Vaughn, of course. The speaker? Angels manager  &UR; Terry Collins &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
