<HEADLINE>
INSIDE STORY ON OUTDOOR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Why did Edmonton land the 2001 world outdoor track and field
championships instead of Stanford? There were government guarantees
worth $80 million. Alberta promised to pay travel and
accommodations costs for all athletes and officials and offered a
fat Canadian TV deal.
</P>
<P>
   Though Stanford, which has been spurned thrice in a row, had an
attractive package, it couldn't match what amounted to full public
underwriting, and won only two of 24 votes. That was a body blow
for USA Track and Field, which was counting on the event (which the
US has never hosted), to boost the sport's sagging spectator
interest here.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Just to make sure there's no repeat of Atlanta's high-wire
financing for the 2002 Winter Games, the Salt Lake City organizers
and the Utah state government have agreed that no more than 60
percent of the $1.45 billion budget will be spent or committed
before next October, that the committee will always keep a reserve
fund of at least $100 million in the bank, and that the state
auditor will continue to have continuous access to the books ...
After basking in their Golden Girl glow for 10 months, the US
women's ice hockey team will be in action for the first time since
Nagano against Canada and Finland in next month's Three Nations Cup
in Finland. Eleven Olympians, including  &UR; Cammi Granato &LR; , &UR; Karyn
Bye &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and &UR; Sara DeCosta &LR; , &UR;  &LR; are on the squad, which will be directed
by Wisconsin head coach  &UR; Julie Sasner &LR;  ... No surprises in the
men's ice hockey relegation tournament for the A pool at next
year's world championships in Norway. As expected, the US and host
Austria breezed past Estonia and Kazakhstan. The Yanks, who sent
over a patchwork crew of off-duty German League pros and golden-age
volunteers, won all three of their games ... The US men's doubles
team stayed on its Nagano roll in the first two World Cup luge
events. It grabbed three of the top four places in the Innsbruck
opener, with  &UR; Christian Niccum &LR; - &UR; Matt McClain  &LR; and  &UR; Mark
Grimmette &LR; - &UR; Brian Martin  &LR; going 1-2.  &UR; yesterday &LR;  in Altenberg,
Germany,  &UR; Chris Thorpe  &LR; and  &UR; Gordy Sheer  &LR; took the bronze.
Rebuilding season for the men's and women's singles, who haven't
come close to the podium yet. Rough start, too, for Somerville's
 &UR; Erin Warren &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who figured to be the top US woman but has yet to
crack the top 20 ... Looks like there'll be a minimal US presence
at the Grand Prix figure skating final in Russia in March. After
four of six events, only  &UR; Michael Weiss &LR; , &UR; Nicole Bobek &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and the
pair of  &UR; Kyoko Ina  &LR; and  &UR; John Zimmerman  &LR; figure to qualify. With
 &UR; Michelle Kwan  &LR; and  &UR; Todd Eldredge  &LR; sitting out the circuit and
 &UR; Jenni Meno &LR; - &UR; Todd Sand  &LR; (pairs) and  &UR; Elizabeth Punsalan &LR; - &UR; Jerod
Swallow  &LR; (dance) turned pro, the Yanks are thin. Not so the
Russians, who'll be favored to win all four titles and could sweep
the men ... After years of looking at thousands of empty seats
inside Detroit's Joe Louis Arena, the US Figure Skating Association
has switched next year's Skate America to the new 8,000-seat World
Arena in Colorado Springs ... Home cookin' paid off for the US
bobsledders, who finished second ( &UR; Brian Shimer &LR; ) and fifth ( &UR; Todd
Hays &LR; ) in Friday's World Cup two-man event on the Olympic run at
Salt Lake City after a sluggish debut at Calgary. Winchester's  &UR; Jim
Herberich  &LR; has been 12th and 14th in the two-man races, 14th in the
first four-man ... The US short-track speedskaters keep cruising on
the World Cup circuit _ both  &UR; Amy Peterson  &LR; and Brookline's  &UR; Dan
Weinstein  &LR; set American records in the 500 at Heerenveen and
 &UR; Apolo &LR;   &UR; Ohno  &LR; won the 1,000 in Hungary. Nice start, too, by
long-tracker  &UR; Christine Witty &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won a silver and a bronze in
the first two 1,500s of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   How far have the US men slipped on the global weightlifting
scene? Only junior  &UR; Oscar Chaplin III  &LR; met the qualifying standard
for the recent world championships in Finland, and he placed 13th.
Better showing by the US women, who got a bronze from  &UR; Robin Goad
 &LR; at 53 kilograms, a fourth from  &UR; Cara Heads  &LR; at 75 kg, and a sixth
from  &UR; Tara Nott  &LR; at 48 kg. The Greeks dominated the men's event,
winning three of eight golds and five medals in all. The Chinese
and Taiwanese grabbed six of the seven women's titles ... ``Mind
Over Water,''  &UR; Craig Lambert's  &LR; lovely new book on rowing and its
life lessons, includes some intriguing Olympic-related nuggets,
most of them involving the mystical  &UR; Harry Parker &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who both
sculled and coached in the Games. A terrific read, even if you
can't tell a pair from a double ... Looks like it'll be a long road
back to the medal podium for the rebuilding US men's and women's
volleyball teams, who both got spiked at the world championships in
Japan. The men, who won the bronze medal last time, were bounced in
the quarterfinal round and are playing for ninth-12th place this
weekend. The women didn't win a game in their preliminary pool.
Worse yet, the US males were fined $3,000 (along with six other
teams) for a fashion faux pas: loose-fitting shirts.
</P>
</TEXT>
