<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-VICTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GOING IN RIGHT DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the tail end of the Bruins' Western swing in October, there
were signs that the club was far from a cohesive unit. The team
defense was porous and the goal scoring was inconsistent.
Fortunately, the goaltending was terrific, but Boston still went
through a 1-5-1 stretch from Oct. 19-Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 games since then, the Bruins have rolled along at a
6-1-3 clip, their most recent victory a 5-1 thrashing of Montreal
Friday afternoon. Why the turnabout? There are a number of factors:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Defenseman Kyle McLaren and forward Anson Carter, who were
embroiled in contract disputes and missed the first 15 and 12
games, respectively, have looked more and more effective.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Center Jason Allison, who missed all but one exhibition game
because of a contract squabble, is back to 100 percent after a bout
with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Right wing Dmitri Khristich, who was up and down last year
partly because of a distraction over his contract, has been the
team's most consistent forward and is on a scorching scoring pace,
with 25 points in 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Sophomore forward Sergei Samsonov is benefiting from playing
with Allison and Khristich, and even though opponents are targeting
him, he's finding a way to score.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Defenseman Darren Van Impe, who looked tentative at times
last year, is playing with a great deal more confidence and has
been the missing ingredient on the power play, which is among the
league's best.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Byron Dafoe has embraced the starting goalie job he earned
last year, and after the snubbing on the All-Star ballot, he has
played with an even more pronounced ``Take that!'' mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, don't think for a minute that coach Pat Burns
will allow his players to become complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet, we're far from being there,'' said Burns
after the win over the Habs. ``We have a lot of work to go. We have
a lot of things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the dimensions the team is missing is the one brought by
center Tim Taylor, who has been sidelined for 18 of 22 games
because of a balky ankle that he sprained Oct. 14 in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris (Taylor, Tim's brother) is doing a fabulous job, don't
get me wrong,'' said Burns. ``But we do miss Tim. Kyle is finding a
way to compensate for the training camp he missed. He's playing
much better every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we didn't say it was going to be a
one-year-and-two-month changeover. We're still going to get our
butts kicked some night, we know that. There are going to be a lot
of highs and some lows. (Last) week has been a high for us. Two
weeks from now, we might have a low. I'm not that dumb, I'm not
going to tell you we're there yet. I hope we're not there yet. We
have a lot of things to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Rob DiMaio, who expressed acute frustration earlier
in the year when so many free agents were out of the lineup, said
he can see the club coming together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased,'' said DiMaio. ``Just one guy is missing.
When Timmy gets back, it will be a big boost. We don't have to
change anything. We're going pretty much with a lot of confidence.
We're not trying to do too much. We're just keeping it simple. Our
power play is working real well, the penalty killing is working
real well. If we can do that for another 60 games, we should be
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is an area DiMaio would like to see improved, it is his
line's offensive output, which has been hampered by the absence of
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been creating too much,'' said DiMaio. ``I've been
frustrated as well as (P.J. Axelsson) and Chris. If the rest of the
team wasn't scoring, then there would be real cause to worry but
we're still shutting other team's lines down as much as we can and
we've done our job. When Timmy gets back, we kind of jell a little
bit more. We understand the way each other plays and we get our
offense from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who is champing at the bit to get back, said that when
he was with the Red Wings, the players felt the pressure to win.
The pressure isn't as intense in Boston, since it's understood that
the Bruins are a young club. But he doesn't see any reason why the
expectations here shouldn't be high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was the most realization I had at how close we were
because the team that barely knocked us out is a team that went to
the Stanley Cup finals,'' said Taylor, referring to the Washington
Capitals. ``You look in our division and it's pretty tight because
teams are playing really well. We're one of the top teams (in the
East).''
</P>
<P>
   As positive as the attitude has been around the club _ winning
has a way of doing that _ no one is jumping the gun. After all,
only 22 games have been played.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just say automatically that now we're a Stanley Cup
contender,'' said DiMaio. ``We just have to play consistent and
play within ourselves every night and let our confidence build. We
are young and the better guys play, the more confidence we're going
to have and the better we're going to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking this season in quarters and we're at the end of
the first quarter. We've got a lot of hockey left to play. Maybe
toward the end we can start talking like that a little bit more but
not now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
