</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BUFFALO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIPPING QB DRAMA ABOUT TO UNFOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ When Bob Kraft arrived at Foxboro Stadium Friday
following a Thanksgiving Day respite, he wanted to know two things.
(1) Would Drew Bledsoe play against the Bills. And (2) Where did
all of those mail bins with thousands of letters come from?
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, there was no conclusive evidence as to whether Bledsoe
would start or not as the team went through its walk-through
practice at the stadium. According to team spokesman Stacey James,
Bledsoe only handed the ball off to his backs and did not throw.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe certainly will be active Sunday and will test his broken
finger in pregame warmups. His status will be a game-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If at that point he can't throw the ball with accuracy or
authority, he won't go,'' said James.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's right index finger was broken in two places during the
game-winning drive last Monday night against Miami. He has been
wearing a brace on it and said he would not be able to play if it
was in the same condition it was on that dramatic drive, even
though he did not come out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mail, it contained letters and checks from more than
20,000 fans who want their names put on a season-ticket waiting
list, tripling the number on the list from 10,000 to 30,000 in
about a week since Kraft announced he was moving the team to
Hartford in 2001. Approximately 30 percent of the additions are
from Massachusetts fans, mostly from the western suburbs, while the
remainder are mostly from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing to see it all,'' said Kraft. ``It just
reaffirms what great fans we have in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the fans rallied around the team in the 26-23 win over
the Dolphins, one of the best games the stadium has ever hosted.
But with Doug Flutie making his return to Foxborough, where he's
10-0, will the locals become Bills fans in a hurry if the Patriots
don't stay in the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that will happen,'' said coach Pete Carroll.
``Our fans will support us and root for us. I can say that with
certainty based on the way the fans responded last week. They will
be respectful of Doug and applaud him because of all the great
things he's done in this area, but they'll be rooting for us to win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bledsoe's status in doubt, teammates mustered something of
a rallying cry for Zolak in the past week. Kraft noticed it Friday
when several of them came to him and said they could win with
Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Johnson seemed to start it early in the week when he said,
``If Drew can't play, there's nobody I'd rather have in there than
Scott, he's so fiery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think players feel very comfortable with Zolak,'' said Shawn
Jefferson. ``He brings that attitude that we like to see. He's a
winner. He'll do anything to win. If he can't find anyone open,
he'll still try to find a way to make a play. I think we'll be all
right with Scott in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is a change in quarterbacks, the Patriots aren't
expected to change much of what they planned. The spread-out
offense that worked so well against Miami will be seen at times,
but the Patriots want to reestablish the running game. Robert
Edwards has disappeared the past five weeks, and that must change
as the Patriots head into a bad-weather month.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, of course will be sky high. He was hoping to go
head-to-head with Bledsoe in a marquee matchup, with the two teams
jousting for position the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think last week's game was a signature game for Drew,'' said
Flutie. ``It may change the way a lot of people view him there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
