<SLUG> BC-FBC-BRADLEY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kick completes Chambers' odyssey
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Brad Chambers figured he'd been to ``every Georgia
Tech-Georgia game since I've been alive.'' He wasn't alive in 1957,
but he knows who Theron Sapp is: ``The guy who scored the touchdown
against Georgia Tech.'' And he knows one thing more: ``Something
about Georgia always gave me the creeps.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day Brad Chambers gave the Bulldogs something in return:
The drought-ending, pride-rending blues. His field goal at 0:02
hoisted Chambers into Yellow Jacket lore. And just who is Brad
Chambers? Here, as they say in Hollywood, is the backstory:
</P>
<P>
   He learned to kick in his Toccoa backyard, booting a ball over a
neighbor's power lines. ``It didn't matter if it was straight or
not; it just had to get over.'' He got serious about kicking not
because he foresaw the day when he'd fell the Dogs between the
hedges, but because he got tired of his sister showing him up.
Ginny Chambers was, her brother said, ``the only girl in the
neighborhood, and she was the best kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to Tech as a walk-on. (His sister went to Auburn, not as
a placekicker. She works in Nashville now.) Chambers was issued a
scholarship after his freshman season. Having worn No. 31, he asked
for a different uniform. Only No. 13 was left. He took it. On the
first day of practice, Chambers said, ``All the coaches said,
`We're not having a kicker wearing 13.' But they never took it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say that Chambers' collegiate career was all good
fortune. He kicked a 20-yard winner against Clemson last season but
missed four of five field goals at Maryland on Halloween 1998. He'd
been bad in practice this week, he said, and his first try Saturday
clanked off the left upright. Even a later success, a career-long
49-yarder with 5:01 left, earned none of its three points for
style. ``Ugly,'' Chambers called the line drive.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Tech within a point. The Bulldogs went
three-and-out. Tech proceeded downfield, Chambers ducked behind the
bench to kick into a net, monitoring events on the big screen. When
finally he was summoned, five seconds remained.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia called one timeout, then another. ``That didn't make me
nervous,'' Chambers said. ``The only thing was, my mouth got
completely dry.''
</P>
<P>
   He received this sage counsel from coach George O'Leary: ``Just
make it, son.'' Afterward O'Leary opined that the timeouts had
actually helped his kicker: ``He started getting the color back in
his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Basquin, the holder, told Chambers: ``Don't worry about
the laces _ you won't see them.'' Basquin had another viewing tip:
``He told me to keep my head down the whole time,'' Chambers said.
``He said, `You'll know it's good if I jump on top of you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Duly prepped, Chambers stepped forward and swung his leg. He
didn't see the ball rise above the leaping Champ Bailey, didn't see
it arch toward the goal posts and the sea of Tech fans beyond,
didn't see anything but ground and then sky after his holder flung
him to the turf. Other Jackets followed forthwith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a bruise right here,'' Brad Chambers said, touching his
sternum. He'll take it. Better a celebratory bruise than a
continuing case of the creeps.
</P>
<P>
   Email:markb(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
