<HEADER>
A3054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-DEFENS     11-28 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-DEFENSE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech D's big day: Stops at end set stage
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It started with the Georgia team stomping its own
logo at midfield. It ended with the Bulldogs bickering among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Georgia Tech staged a remarkable fourth-quarter
comeback after trailing 19-7, ending a seven-year drought by taking
a last-second, 21-19 win.
</P>
<P>
   As many Tech offensive heroes as there were, the unsung, often
maligned Yellow Jackets defenders finally stood up and demanded to
be counted. In three hours and 13 minutes, Tech erased seven years
of frustration and ensured itself state supremacy and a top-15
ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's defense had given up 399 yards per game this season, next
to last in the ACC. Saturday, the Bulldogs managed 384, but only 5
of them came on Georgia's last two possessions. Tech sent the
Bulldogs off the field with back-to-back four-and-out sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of trash-talking,'' said defensive end Felipe
Claybrooks, who had a sack and two pass breakups. More important,
Claybrooks stayed in Bulldog quarterback Quincy Carter's face much
of the afternoon. The two have known each other since Claybrooks
played at Decatur and Carter at Southwest DeKalb. ``We talked the
whole game,'' Claybrooks said. ``I'd say `Hey, don't blame me for
you getting hit. Blame your offensive linemen.' Stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior defensive end Jesse Tarplin called his defense together
in the late going when it became apparent Tech had a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them we needed a four-and-out,'' he said. ``We hadn't
had one all day. I told them we needed to get the ball back to our
offense fast. We knew we had a chance because they were rattled (on
their last two possessions). They were arguing back there among
themselves. Quincy was on his linemen and the linemen were accusing
each other, telling each other to block.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarplin had five tackles and often accompanied Claybrooks into
the Bulldog backfield. As he left the field, a fan dumped a Coke on
his head, but his mood was too good to be dampened by a soft drink.
``That comes with the territory,'' he said. ``I told (my teammates)
not to get mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Claybrooks said the Tech defense knew what to expect when they
went out on the Bulldogs' last two possessions. ``(Defensive line)
Coach (Lance) Thompson called the front four together and told us
to remember their tendencies. We knew Quincy would have the ball in
his hands, so Coach Thompson told us to pressure him. He told us to
make plays, pressure Quincy, stay with your man. I think we worked
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lineman Nate Stimson perhaps put the afternoon in
perspective, recalling last year's 27-24 loss in the last 48
seconds to the Bulldogs. ``It's worse to lose a game by one point
than by 50. I hope they feel bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
