<HEADER>
A3055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-MAIN29     11-28 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-MAIN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doggone good kick
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The drought is over.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's seven-year misery against Georgia ended Saturday
on Brad Chambers' 35-yard field goal with two seconds left, which
gave the No. 17 Yellow Jackets a 21-19 upset of the No. 12 Bulldogs
at Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was Tech's first win over the Bulldogs since its co-national
championship season of 1990, breaking the second-longest losing
streak in the series. Georgia Tech finished the regular season at
9-2, its best mark in eight years, and will play an undetermined
opponent in Jacksonville's Gator Bowl on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which fell to 8-3, must wait to learn its postseason
fate, most likely an invitation to the Citrus or Outback Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time for them to feel like we've felt for the
last seven years, especially last season,'' Georgia Tech
quarterback Joe Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   The final minutes of Saturday's game probably seemed familiar to
much of the sold-out crowd of 86,117. Three hundred and sixty-four
days after Georgia won on an 8-yard touchdown pass with eight
seconds left in Atlanta, the Yellow Jackets put together their own
game-winning drive in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This year's edition of the intrastate rivalry also ended with
some controversy _ Georgia's players felt they'd recovered a fumble
during Tech's final drive, and that Dogs quarterback Quincy Carter
crossed the goal line on a failed two-point conversion attempt
earlier. Last year's game ended after a controversial
pass-interference call against Georgia Tech in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 19-18 with less than four minutes remaining, Tech
started its final drive at its 30-yard line. The Jackets reached
Georgia territory on Hamilton's 14-yard run. The junior quarterback
appeared to fumble, with Dogs safety Larry Mann recovering at the
Georgia 31, but officials ruled Hamilton was down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he fumbled, but I'm not the one making the call,''
Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Tech faced third-and-11 at the 32. Following
a timeout, Hamilton hit senior Charlie Rogers with a short pass in
the right flat, which Rogers turned into a 13-yard gain to the 19.
Tech split end Mike Sheridan picked off Georgia cornerback Champ
Bailey on the play, allowing Rogers to break free down the
sideline. After a 1-yard run and a pair of timeouts by Georgia,
Chambers nailed his game-winning field goal through the uprights in
the west end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Chambers) looked spaced out walking onto the field,'' Georgia
Tech coach George O'Leary said. ``I think those two timeouts helped
him. He got some color back in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 19-7, the Yellow Jackets finally found life
at the start of the fourth quarter. After converting on fourth
down, freshman Joe Burns scored on a 10-yard run to make it 19-13.
O'Leary chose to go for a two-point coversion, and Hamilton
succeeded on a run around right end, cutting the Dogs' lead to
19-15 with 13:00 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, a senior from Toccoa, kicked a career-long 49-yard
field goal with 5:01 left to cut Georgia's lead to 19-18.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's offense, which produced 278 yards and 19 points in the
first three quarters, went dormant in the fourth. The Bulldogs had
only nine offensive plays and 14 yards on their final three drives,
allowing the Yellow Jackets to hold the ball for more than 10
minutes in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tech) didn't do anything differently,'' Georgia offensive
tackle Matt Stinchcomb said. ``We just didn't execute. It's our job
to put them away. We didn't, and gave them the opportunity to come
back down the field and put the game away.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's defense also had its problems in the fourth quarter,
allowing Tech to gain 163 yards on 30 plays in its final four
series. The Yellow Jackets rushed for 241 yards, the second-highest
total the Bulldogs have allowed this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inability to slow them down really bothered all of us,''
Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``They converted too many third-down
plays and some fourth downs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
