<HEADER>
A3056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BISHER-COLUMN29-C     11-28 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BISHER-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Give the boot to series' latest drought
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Another drought has been broken, but this time the
shoe was on the other foot, so to speak. Georgia had lost to
Georgia Tech eight times in a row when Theron Sapp, a solid but
plodding fullback from Macon, planted his brogans in the end zone
at Grant Field and Georgia earned its third victory of the 1957
season, 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Drought Is Broken,'' they cried in a delirium that spread
across the state. Sapp still lives in the hearts of Bulldogs as
``The Man Who Broke the Drought,'' today a restaurant operator in
his 60s in Augusta. Now Georgia Tech has a match for him.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Chambers is a 22-year-old senior, tall and lean, from just
up the road at Toccoa, playing his last game against Georgia. When
he put his shoe to the football in Sanford Stadium Saturday
afternoon, five seconds remained in the game. The distance was 35
yards. He stood there alone while Georgia called two timeouts, to
``freeze'' him in the term of gamesmanship. The number ``13''
glistened on his shirt in the lowering sun. Would it be the symbol
of foul luck, or would it be one to be revered in Tech's football
memory? He had kicked one from 49 yards earlier, a wobbling liner,
ugly but good, the longest of his college life.
</P>
<P>
   His kick was true and with Chambers' field goal Georgia Tech had
broken a drought of its own, seven seasons of defeat by Georgia,
and delirium of another sort broke out, this one in the color of
Gold and White. There was no time left for rebuttal, two ticks left
on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   As the college game goes, this was one for the museum. Old
rivalries are known to fade and die away, with the intrusion of
television and the rupture of conferences, and this one had been on
the wane. Georgia Tech had split from the Southeastern Conference
and the same spirit of vengeance just wasn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of George O'Leary in Atlanta and Jim Donnan in
Athens, however, the tempest thickened. The ``good old-fashioned
hate,'' as my friend Bill Cromartie has labeled it, was welling up.
A crucial officiating call in the last 30 seconds had slugged Tech
in the chops last year, robbed the Yellow Jackets of a game they
were already taking to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   So here we were again, this time in Sanford Stadium, stuffed to
the gills with 86,117 spectators of one denomination or the other.
This was college football rivalry as it's supposed to be, the way
it used to be when Harvard played Yale. The tension was thick.
There was a personal thing between the two quarterbacks, Joe
Hamilton at the position Quincy Carter might have been playing had
he not turned his back on Georgia Tech, first to pro baseball, then
to the Bulldogs. That sore had been festering.
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly possible for two teams to be more evenly matched.
It was supposed that Tech had an edge in the kicking game and
moving the ball on foot, Georgia on defense. True, a kick made the
difference, and while Rodney Williams' punting average was 45.8,
freshman Wynn Kopp, a kind of desperation choice, a local kid, had
himself a day kicking for the Bulldogs. He got good rolls and good
coverage when they needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Proof that not all such augury works out on the field, it looked
as if Georgia had put the game away on a grinding drive of 65 yards
on which running back Olandis Gary, a senior from Washington, D.C.,
was the workhorse. In between Carter strikes to Tony Small,
Georgia's surest catcher, and Larry Brown, Gary carried the load
and scored the touchdown that made the score 19-7, and at that late
stage of the third quarter, the Bulldogs must have felt pretty
cozy.
</P>
<P>
   But, as you may now have reasoned, it was not to be. They had
scored their last point. Joe Burns put another touchdown on the
board for Georgia Tech, followed by Hamilton's two-point run, and
the rest was left to the foot from Toccoa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
