A3057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTES29-C     11-28 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loss to Tech may cost Dogs trip to Citrus
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Only time will tell, but Georgia may have played
its way out of the Citrus Bowl with Saturday's 21-19 loss to
Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   With Florida (9-2) still a possibility for the Orange Bowl, the
Citrus would have given strong consideration to matching a 9-2
Georgia with the No. 2 team from the Big Ten on Jan. 1 in Orlando,
according to Chuck Rohe, the game's executive director. At 8-3,
Georgia's bowl options are not quite so clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's really hard to say,'' said Georgia coach Jim
Donnan. ``When you lose your last one, you pretty much have to take
what they give you.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia might still get into the Citrus, which gets the No. 1
pick of remaining SEC teams after the Bowl Championship Series
makes its selections. If Tennessee and Florida both get into the
BCS, it appears Arkansas (9-2) would go the Cotton Bowl to play
Texas. That would leave the Citrus to choose among Georgia,
Kentucky (7-4), Alabama (7-4) and Mississippi State, which would be
8-4 if it loses in the SEC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   By rule, the Citrus could pick any of those teams, regardless of
record. If Georgia does not go to the Citrus, it appears the
Bulldogs are headed back to the Outback Bowl in Tampa, where they
beat Wisconsin last Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   More controversy
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's 27-24 win over Georgia Tech last year in Atlanta had a
controversial pass interference play that kept the Bulldogs'
winning drive alive. This one ended with a fair share of griping
from the Georgia side.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays caused the most reaction. Television replays showed
that Georgia quarterback Quincy Carter had apparently crossed the
goal line on a two-point conversion try with 3:13 left in the third
quarter. The ACC officiating crew, however, ruled that Carter was
stopped short. Those points were the difference in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Georgia Tech's winning drive, quarterback Joe Hamilton
appeared to have fumbled on a 14-yard run along the Yellow Jacket
sideline. But officials ruled him down and Tech maintained
possession at the Georgia 31-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind it was a fumble,'' said Georgia's
Larry Mann, who fell on the loose ball. ``But I don't make the
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan would not get pulled into the controversey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refs didn't make any difference in this game,'' said
Donnan. ``They just whipped us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just thinking
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia wide receiver Michael Greer threw the first pass of
his college career Saturday, a 68-yard touchdown bomb to senior
tight end Larry Brown on the game's third play. Greer catches every
ball that's thrown to him, returns punts, and now throws it for
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brown posted his career high in receiving with 106 yards on
three catches. Brown has started 44 of 46 possible games in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   _ With Tommy Tuberville taking the job at Auburn on Saturday,
the odds are greater that assistant coach Rodney Garner will remain
at Georgia. If Bill Oliver had gotten the job, there would have
been a full-court press to hire Garner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia cornerback Champ Bailey passed the century mark in
total plays for the fifth straight game and sixth in the last
seven. Bailey was in the game against Tech for a total of 102 plays
(30 offense, 63 defense, nine special teams). He had four catches
for 38 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech notes
</P>
<P>
   _ Tech's nine victories are the most in a season since 1990,
when the Jackets went 11-0-1 and won the UPI national title.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tech has rushed for 560 yards over the last two games while
holding both opponents, Wake Forest and Georgia, to under 100 yards
on the ground. Tech's 241 yards rushing was the most given up by
the Georgia defense all season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Freshman Kelly Campbell had only 10 catches for 76 yards this
season when he beat Georgia's Cory Robinson in the second quarter
for a 55-yard touchdown pass to tie the game at 7-7. That same pass
also gave Hamilton the school record for touchdown passes in a
season at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia notes
</P>
<P>
   _ Saturday's capacity crowd of 86,117 set an average attendance
record for Sanford Stadium. The total attendance for six games this
season was 513,710, an average of 85,618. That record surpasses the
old mark of 83,948 set in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
