<HEADER>
A3058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-CLASS2     11-28 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-CLASS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bummer cum laude
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The stunned faces of former Georgia stars Randall
Godfrey and Hines Ward as they left Sanford Stadium on Saturday may
have said it all. The Bulldogs' senior class, left with the annual
assignment of beating archrival Georgia Tech, failed to accomplish
the feat.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's senior class of 15 scholarship players would have been
the fifth straight to graduate with an unblemished 4-0 record
against the Yellow Jackets. Instead, they're the first to lose to
Tech since 1990, the year before record-setting quarterback Eric
Zeier arrived on the Athens campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that it came on your watch, so to speak, makes it even
worse,'' senior offensive tackle Matt Stinchcomb said. ``That's
probably the best way to put it. It's not the way it happened, it's
just that it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   How it happened _ on Brad Chambers' 35-yard field goal with two
seconds left, which gave the Jackets a 21-19 win _ made it worse
for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to get out of here without ever losing to them, but
these things happen,'' senior defensive tackle Paul Snellings said.
</P>
<P>
   Said senior safety Kirby Smart, ``It wasn't the perfect scenario
at all. It definitely puts a damper on the season. Looking back, if
you had told me we'd be 8-3 and going to a bowl game, I might have
been satisfied. Right now, this definitely dampens our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter hurt
</P>
<P>
   Georgia quarterback Quincy Carter missed postgame interviews
while getting X-rays on his hand. The X-rays were negative. Carter,
a former Parade All-American from Southwest DeKalb High who once
signed with Georgia Tech, got the hand stepped on during the fourth
quarter. Carter completed 16 of 31 passes for 225 yards with no
touchdowns or interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Carter left the field at the beginning of the first half to get
fluids intravenously. He was hampered by the flu during Friday's
workout.
</P>
<P>
   Another Dog commitment
</P>
<P>
   Georgia picked up another verbal commitment on Saturday, this
one from Jackson High athlete Tavares Morgan, a preseason Super 11
pick by the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, a 6-foot-1, 180-pound quarterback at Jackson, rushed for
500 yards and nine touchdowns, while throwing for 1,300 yards and
eight scores. He's expected to play defensive back or wideout at
Georgia. Morgan's brother, Montez Morgan, played at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
