<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-DRIVE2     11-28 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-DRIVE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The final push
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For all the frenzy with 86,117 fans in Sanford
Stadium, a seven-game Georgia Tech losing streak to Georgia on the
line, and 70 yards to go to the end zone and the sweetest of
redemptions for the Yellow Jackets, their huddle was a relatively
quiet place to be.
</P>
<P>
   About all tailback Phillip Rogers remembers hearing from Tech
quarterback Joe Hamilton other than play calls was a quick ``ball
security'' reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew what we had the opportunity to do,'' sophomore
receiver Dez White said. ``Everybody had fire in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 19-18 with 3:47 left, Hamilton started the Yellow
Jackets from their own 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 10 guys in there and me, playing Georgia with three
minutes left and a field goal to win, there's not much you need to
say,'' Hamilton said. ``All I said was `Relax, we've got a lot of
time. There's no rush.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Tech started rushing, but only in the football sense, with
six consecutive running plays.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton started it off with a bootleg run to his left for 6
yards. Then he handed off to Phillip Rogers on a pair of runs of 13
and 6 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got the ball I was going to run people over,'' Rogers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton carried again up the right side for a 14-yard gain and
came near disaster. He was tackled by linebacker Adrian
Hollingshed, who jarred the ball loose. Georgia safety Larry Mann
came up with the loose ball, but the officials ruled Hamilton was
down. Tech resumed its assault at Georgia's 31 with 2:22 left.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of a timeout, tailback Charlie Rogers got thrown for
a loss by Georgia nose guard Josh Mallard in the backfield. But two
plays later he caught a short pass on a crossing route and turned
it into a 13-yard gain on third-and-11 to set up the field goal
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Ralph Friedgen said Tech had used the play
once before in the game. It was drawn up to have receiver Mike
Sheridan run his route right in the path of Georgia's best
defender, Champ Bailey, who would be shadowing Rogers across the
field. Sheridan did his job and sealed Bailey off with a
basketball-style pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd been trying to pick me all day on that play,'' Bailey
said. ``I followed (Charlie Rogers) all the way and then I got
smacked. I don't know who it was, I just remember somebody saying
to me `gotcha.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Taking Bailey out of the key play on the drive was sweet for the
Yellow Jackets, who had been haunted by memories of Bailey for a
year. It was his 28-yard reception on a screen pass that set
Georgia off on its final drive in the Bulldogs' last-second 27-24
win over Tech last season.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Yellow Jackets have a drive of their own to savor. Ten
plays, 52 yards, Brad Chambers from 35 yards. Good. Tech wins
21-19.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs were the ones left without much to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know how they felt last year,'' Georgia safety Kirby
Smart said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
