<HEADER>
A3066 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     11-28 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Fry's retirement drains color from coaching ranks
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Hayden Fry accepted the Iowa football coaching job in 1978,
he found himself reminiscing about his roots, his college days at
Baylor, when an athlete received room and board and $15 a month in
what was called laundry money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that big a deal,'' Fry said. ``You could find a
little dumplin' to do the wash and then take her out to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden was swamped with mail and phone calls from women's groups
in Iowa and elsewhere, offering to run him through the presoak and
rinse cycles. The lesson raised his sensitivity to a level Phil
Donahue would have envied.
</P>
<P>
   The young Hayden Fry was brash and uninhibited, nice qualities
in a quarterback, but sometimes a liability for a coach. It isn't
easy to picture him as an elder statesman, announcing his
retirement this week after 20 years as the coach of the Hawkeyes.
At 69, he had spent more than half his life in the business. Now it
was time, he said, his eyes puddling up, to call it a career. His
was one of the less likely sleigh rides college football has ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   He was just three years out of Baylor, a novice coach at his
alma mater, when SMU named him as a surprise choice to revive a
program that had fallen on hard times. He did it, too, leading SMU
to its first Southwest Conference title in 1966. The previous
season, SMU ended a six-year losing streak to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   His players tried to carry him off the field after that 31-14
upset, but Hayden wrenched free and raced through the crowd. In the
Cotton Bowl tunnel leading to the locker rooms, he caught up with a
dejected Darrell Royal.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning close to the renowned Texas coach, he blurted out:
``Darrell, you whipped my rear end like a drum the last few years,
and I just wanted you to know how good it feels to finally beat
yours.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not always diplomatic, a quality other coaches found easy
to resent when Fry was establishing himself. But his teams played
hard and in defeat won respect. It was after watching a feisty SMU
team lose to heavily favored Michigan, in 1963, that Lee Iacocca
walked into the visitors' locker room and announced Ford's new
sports car would be named the Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   Fry integrated the Southwest Conference in 1966 with Jerry
Levias, who as a sophomore made the winning plays in four games and
led the Ponies to the Cotton Bowl. This decision did not exactly
start a stampede to recruit black athletes, but suddenly the phrase
``social justice'' became popular among other coaches and athletic
directors. As a receiver and runner, the exciting Levias evoked
comparisons to Doak Walker himself.
</P>
<P>
   Texas teams had been famous for their aerial circuses, dating to
Sammy Baugh at TCU and Gerald Mann, the Little Red Arrow of SMU.
Later, the Mustangs kept the tradition alive with Fred Benners and
Don Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Fry who in 1967 unveiled the most unusual offense of
all, the Flea Circus, featuring a 5-4 quarterback named Ines
(pronounced EE-ness) Perez. He was quite a sight, Perez, so small
that part of his jersey number had to be tucked inside his pants.
Levias, at 5-7, was the game-breaker, and the fullback, Pinky
Clements, stood 5-9, maybe. Pinky's dad would become the governor
of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While winning only three games, the '67 Mustangs upset the
eventual conference champions, the Texas Aggies, on national
television, and won the hearts of underdogs everywhere. Fry had
tried to build a better mousetrap by using real mice.
</P>
<P>
   They went to three bowls but had only three winning seasons
under Hayden, and he was fired after finishing 7-4 in 1972. He
swallowed his pride and moved to the outback, taking a small-time
program at North Texas State, beating with regularity teams its own
size and knocking off the occasional national power.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he went, Hayden brought a certain unguarded charm and
energy. A North Texas booster named Newton Rayzor introduced him to
the actor Dabney Coleman, and they became friends. In the movie, 9
to 5, Coleman ad-libbed a line: ``As my old coach, Hayden Fry, used
to say. ''
</P>
<P>
   A high school star at Odessa, a Texan to his toes, Fry easily
made the transition to America's breadbasket. His nature grew less
brash, and more settled, but he continued his pattern of taking
doormats and giving them a reason to roar. Iowa won three Big Ten
titles and three trips to the Rose Bowl. The '90s were not kind to
the Hawkeyes, but Fry leaves as the winningest coach in Iowa
history.
</P>
<P>
   When he started his run in 1962, the big-name coaches were
Royal, Bear Bryant, Woody Hayes, John McKay, Ara Parseghian, Duffy
Daugherty and Frank Broyles. Hayden Fry was an unlikely candidate
to stay on the job for 37 years, but he never put much stock in
being predictable. And now college football will be a little less
fun, a little less colorful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
