<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CURRIE29-COX     11-28 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURRIE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New era starting with shuttle launch
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS, NASA GRAPHICS
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Thursday's launch of the space shuttle Endeavour
will mark the start of the next era in America's human spaceflight
program, the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   The first space station element is in orbit, launched Nov. 20
from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan on a Proton rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's 12-day mission will be to mate the Unity connecting
module in its cargo bay with the Russian-built element, the Zarya
control module. Astronaut Nancy Currie, a former Troy resident,
will play a key role as the operator of the shuttle's robotic arm
which will grab Zarya and position it for docking with the Unity
module.
</P>
<P>
   The embryonic station will not be ready for occupancy, but it
will be powered up and tested, and U.S. and Russian astronauts will
enter it to set things up for future assembly flights. The third
element should be added in July, and the first station crew should
take up residence in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the station is assembled _ sometime in the year
2004, according to the latest timetable _ the station will be the
largest, most complex human object put into space. It will cover an
area larger than a football field, weigh 460 tons and contain
46,000 cubic feet of volume _ as much as two Boeing 747 jumbo jets,
according to Boeing, which is also the main contractor for the
space station.
</P>
<P>
   NASA says the nation will open new doors to knowledge as
astronauts from the United States and other nations do research in
the station's barrel-shaped research modules. Its microgravity
environment _ the near total absence of gravity _ will allow
experiments that can't be done on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be the biggest and costliest space project ever
attempted, involving 16 nations and 43 rocket launches from the
U.S. and Russia. Cost estimates have soared from the original $8
billion pricetag in 1984 to a recent government estimate of nearly
$100 billion, including operating costs and resupply flights.
</P>
<P>
   After years of designing and redesigning the station, fighting
for funds and negotiating with 15 international partners, NASA
hopes the American public will start taking notice of the project
itself, rather than the funding debates that have drawn most of the
media attention so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real excited about what's coming, and I'm hoping that
you all share our excitement,'' Frank Culbertson, space station
operations manager and a former astronaut, said to reporters this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Now that hardware is flying, the project is bound to attract
more attention.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has failed to ignite public enthusiasm the way the
Apollo moon-landing program did, the space station will involve
more flights, more space activity, and in many ways, more technical
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Just for starters, the space station can't be assembled and
tested on the ground. Several countries are responsible for the
production of various elements. Thirty-four U.S. shuttle flights
and nine Russian rocket launches will be required to complete it.
</P>
<P>
   Many more astronauts will be working in space. Seven assembly
crews and four space station ``expedition'' crews are in training,
said Bonnie Dunbar, crew director and former astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with a three-person crew in January 2000, the station
will be continuously occupied for 10 years to 15 years, she said.
The station is designed to house up to seven astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   But the schedule is full of perils. Each element launched will
be critical to the rest of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single one of them would have big impacts on the
program'' if it failed to work or didn't make it into orbit,
program manager Randy Brinkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's experience with its Mir space station has shown the
potential problems and dangers. Crews, including U.S. astronauts,
have had to repair broken steering, power and breathing systems,
sometimes with emergency spacewalks. In June 1997, a seven-ton
cargo ship accidentally sideswiped the station, damaging a solar
panel and puncturing one of Mir's pressurized modules.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, Mirs two-man Russian crew retreated into their
Soyuz landing capsule to ride out the Leonid meteor shower,
although no meteor strikes on the station were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest issue isn't technical, but financial.
Brinkley said NASA won't know until next year whether the Russian
government will give its space agency the funding it needs to meet
its commitments for space station hardware and the rockets for its
share of assembly and supply flights.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical item Russia is to provide as a space station
partner is the Service Module, scheduled for launch in July. It's
needed to control the station's attitude and periodically reboost
its orbit to counter the slight but steady drag from the outer
fringes of Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   So critical is this piece that NASA has chipped in $60million _
in exchange for some research time and resources Russia would have
had on the station _ and made contingency plans to launch an
interim module and be ready to build its own replacement module.
Failure by Russia to deliver the Service Module could delay the
station's completion by a couple of years, Brinkley said. He
declined to estimate the cost to the United States of building a
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial problems have added to the station's
financial woes. In June, the General Accounting Office, the
auditing arm of Congress, upped its cost estimate for the station
from $93.9 billion to nearly $95.6 billion, counting operating
costs and shuttle flights. Its report said the cost could well go
higher if the schedule slips further or more shuttle flights are
required.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
