<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-BROWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN REFLECTS ON SUCCESSFUL SEASON AT TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A record-setting season in the history books and a heaping
helping of Thanksgiving leftovers in his belly, Texas football
coach Mack Brown joined the tourists in celebrating a season-ending
upset of [ No. 6 ]Texas A&AMP;M. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown and his wife, Sally, took a celebratory drive by the UT
tower late Friday night to see the campus landmark awash in orange
lights. Normally, only the top portion is lit after victories. But
when the Longhorns win a conference championship or knock off the
Aggies, every inch glows orange, from the ground floor to the top
of the observatory deck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As hard as these kids had worked to light that tower up, I
thought I should go down and pay tribute to it,'' said Brown, whose
team's 26-24 triumph over A&AMP;M allowed Texas to finish with an 8-3
record, doubling the Longhorns' victory total from 1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he drove by and watched fans pose for pictures, Brown said he
began to grasp the significance of what his initial Texas team had
accomplished: an NCAA career rushing record for tailback Ricky
Williams (6,279 yards), who will learn Dec. 12 if he wins the 1998
Heisman Trophy; 15 additional NCAA career records set or tied by
Williams; renewed enthusiasm in fans, .MDBU/with crowds of more
than 80,000 at Royal-Memorial Stadium [ who filled Royal-Memorial
Stadium with more than 80,000 fans ].MDBR/.MDNM/for each of the
team's last three home games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Brown could point to two victories over top-10
opponents: Friday's upset of A&AMP;M, ranked sixth in The Associated
Press poll, and a 20-16 triumph over then-No. 7 Nebraska that broke
the Cornhuskers' 47-game home winning streak Oct. 31. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, we got as much from this football team as we
could get, from the first day of spring practice right through the
A&AMP;M game,'' Brown said. ``It couldn't have been much better. It's
been a dream year for us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victories over A&AMP;M and Nebraska marked the first time since
1990 for Texas to defeat two top-10 foes in the same season. By
comparison, the Longhorns were a combined 1-8-1 against top-10
opponents in six seasons under Brown's predecessor, John Mackovic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of Williams' myriad records, perhaps the most incredible is that
he surpassed Navy's Napoleon McCallum as the NCAA career leader in
all-purpose yards, with 7,206. Williams did so without ever
returning a kick in his college career. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the A&AMP;M game, Williams lobbied Brown for the chance to
return a kickoff if it would help him accumulate the 234 yards he
needed to surpass McCallum. Brown laughed and urged him to
concentrate on getting the 63 rushing yards he needed to surpass
Tony Dorsett as the career rushing leader among Divison I-A
players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You're not getting 234, bud. Their defense is too
good,''' Brown said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Williams finished with 259 rushing yards and 36 yards on
five pass receptions, he tapped Brown on the shoulder and said: ``I
guess I won't need that kickoff return, after all.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown laughed as he recounted the exchange, using it as a
fitting summation for a player and team that exceeded expectations
throughout 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What Ricky did would have to be the best performance under
pressure I've ever seen by a great player against a great
defense,'' Brown said. ``It was a fitting end to a great year for
us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
