<HEADER>
A3081 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     11-28 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTCARDS FROM THE LEDGE: FRANCHIONE KEEPS OPTION UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What I'd love to hear, what I think all of Fort Worth would love
to hear, from TCU coach Dennis Franchione is that he's not going
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ever. Never. No way. No how.
</P>
<P>
   We want him to tell us that he'll bleed purple till the day they
cart him away, singing the TCU fight song and flashing the Frog
sign on his way out the door.
</P>
<P>
   But the man's not stupid.
</P>
<P>
   If you've gotten the idea Franchione is keeping his options
open, while continually denying that he's had any contact from
anyone at Oklahoma, despite all the media rumors, you're right. He
is, as quietly and carefully as possible.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that Franchione, fresh off a 6-5 season in
the first year of a six-year contract, is looking to put Fort Worth
in his rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Fort Worth a lot,'' Franchione says. ``I'm excited
about TCU and what we got accomplished the first year. I'm excited
about the future and the facilities. I'm kind of tired of this
being a media topic because it shouldn't be. It creates uncertainty
for fans and recruits and I don't seem to have any control over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, TCU athletic director Eric Hyman's policy in which he said
he would not ``confirm or deny'' whether he'd been contacted by OU,
asking for permission to talk to his head coach, and a couple of TV
interviews in which Franchione seemed to act ``honored'' to be
considered by OU aggravated rather than helped the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of took it lighthearted at first, so I may have come
across a little indecisive or open, and I didn't mean to do that,''
Franchione admitted. ``This has all been somewhat amusing to me
because nothing official has happened. I've had all kinds of media
overtures but nothing from anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione has shown, not surprisingly, that he knows what the
coaching game is all about. He knows that Oklahoma is the big time,
a step up in class from TCU (sorry, but it's true). He could win a
national title at OU. Look me in the eye and tell me he has a
realistic chance of doing that at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any coach goes into a situation thinking it's
not going to be a long-term thing,'' Franchione said. ``I never
have. But here's Mack Brown, he's at a great school in North
Carolina, and he leaves and goes to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would listen to what people have to say ...''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Fran, so keep your ears open. No one can blame you for that.
And if somebody wants you bad enough to pay off your reverse buyout
clause and you decide to leave, I suppose that's the way the game
works, as distasteful as it is to watch grown men break contracts
they expect the players they recruit to keep.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd like to believe, though, is that the guy who said, upon
his arrival, that he'd be happy if TCU was the last coaching stop
on his resume, plans on sticking around for at least a couple of
years. ...
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as Randy Moss was in the Vikings' 46-36 victory
Thursday against the Cowboys at Texas Stadium, his postgame,
head-down, who-gives-a-flip appearance on Fox for the traditional
John Madden turkey leg presentation was equally unimpressive. In
the locker room later, when a newspaper reporter approached, Moss
shook his head. ``You're not TV,'' he said, declining to speak to
the pen-and-notebook crowd. Fine, Randy. Nice to see you. Hope you
freeze your earlobes off up there in Minnesota. ...
</P>
<P>
   And for those who keep crying about how the Cowboys passed on
taking Moss with the eighth pick in the draft, at least they have a
rational alibi (whether you buy it or not) in not choosing to mix
Moss' rapsheet with an organization frantic to clean up its image.
What about the other 18 teams who passed on him, too? What's their
excuse? ...
</P>
<P>
   Most prevalent feeling to emerge from the Cowboys' locker room
after the game was not a sigh of relief that they'd almost kept up
with the Vikings' offensive firestorm, despite a multitude of
injuries. Instead, the Cowboys were legitimately disappointed that
they'd put themselves in position to win the game in the third
quarter and let it get away again. ...
</P>
<P>
   Anybody doubt that cornerback will be high on the Cowboys' list
for next year's draft? Believe it or not, that fits in with coach
Chan Gailey's draft philosophy anyway. He may be the offensive
coordinator, but he believes in taking defensive linemen and
cornerbacks high in the draft. ...
</P>
<P>
   To the many who wrote or called to point out the inconsistency
of my position on Ken Caminiti's passing up lots more loot from
Detroit to return to Houston (Revo's Rimshots last week), all right
already. It was a cheap and easy rip, I took it and I regret it.
You're right, everyone of you. Caminiti did the right thing and
should be applauded for not making money the most important issue.
Case closed. ...
</P>
<P>
   And while we're getting the record straight, former Mavericks
operations director Marty Faulkner writes to say that he left the
organization to pursue another opportunity, not because of any
problems with president Terdema Ussery, as mentioned as a
possibility here, so apologies to both parties in that case, too.
...
</P>
<P>
   All-time NFL career TD man Jerry Rice, apparently ticked off
about catching just three passes (none in the first half) in the
49ers' ragged victory over New Orleans last week, hinted afterward
that he might consider retiring, then soft-shoed away when Bay Area
columnists pointed out that his attitude might be construed as a
bit selfish.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said he's just frustrated that the 49ers' offense hasn't
played like it can and should.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not playing that way, it's not fun, and if it's not
fun, I've got to think about retiring,'' Rice told reporters. ``I
talked to Michael Jordan, and he told me the same thing. He thought
about retirement because he was not having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying, guys, is if this drags on for a while, you
would have to consider that, think about it, if you're not having a
good time.'' Yeah, that's always been the No. 1 criteria about
keeping a job for me, too. Right. ...
</P>
<P>
   The ``Chicago Tribune's'' Bernie Lincicome said it best as he
bemoaned not being able to watch the Bulls' Dennis Rodman play
regularly: ``A day without Dennis is like an overpass without
graffiti.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
REVO'S RIMSHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Billups? Reese? Jeffers? Ogden? What, was it tryout day at Texas
Stadium on Thursday or Jerry's new law firm?
</P>
<P>
   Jets wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson was asked about the death of
former Jets coach Weeb Ewbank, who led the franchise to its only
Super Bowl victory back in 1969. ``He was a coach or something,
right?'' Johnson asked, as he stood outside the Jets' practice
facility, officially named Weeb Ewbank Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this: The Rangers find themselves hoping to lure
Randy Johnson to town or face the prospect of crawling back to
Kevin Brown, checkbook in hand, to beg for his services. If they
strike out on both, maybe Son of Sam's available.
</P>
</TEXT>
