<HEADLINE>
`IT PROBABLY HAS OPENED A FEW DOORS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Terry Baker sometimes feels as if he won an
Academy Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's actually a pretty good description of it,'' says the
former Oregon State quarterback. ``The only difference is, the
Heisman is more exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, they give out a lot of those \RAcademy Awards\S,
but they only award one Heisman.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker won it in 1962, providing a couple of historical
footnotes. Among other things: He is the last Heisman winner to
have begun his career as a single-wing tailback, although the
Beavers switched to the Wing-T prior to his junior year. And, he is
most assuredly the only Oregon State player who has even come
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we had a pretty good year in '62,'' says Baker, whose
99-yard run in the Liberty Bowl provided a 6-0 victory against
Villanova and capped a 9-2 season. ``And we also had a publicity
machine. Nothing like what they do today, but our guy on campus was
pushing me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a coach, Tommy Prothro, who guided the Beavers into
the limelight with two Rose Bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief pro career, Baker went back to school and got a
law degree at Southern Cal. For the past 28 years, he has been a
partner in a Portland law firm that he helped start.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, in 1970, he served on the President's Commission
on Campus Unrest and Kent State Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right after the bombings in Cambodia and the killings
at Kent State,'' he says. ``A very volatile era, and we spent a
year traveling around the country studying an issue that was having
a major impact on American society. It was a very useful
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, however, few who have met the state's only
Heisman winner have asked about campus unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you win that award,'' he says, laughing, ``it's almost as
if it becomes a part of your body. Everybody knows your name, and
it probably has opened a few doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I once briefly considered running for governor, but
fortunately my political period passed fairly quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   No one at Oregon State has worn Baker's No. 11 jersey since he
left, but it wasn't officially retired until last week _ during the
Beavers' stunning upset of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   So, does he still follow those battling Beavers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' he says, ``you know that game last week where we beat
Oregon? It was the greatest football game I've ever seen in my
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
