<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GRIFFIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT WAS AN EVEN GREATER THRILL THE SECOND TIME'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As the 1975 season approached, Ohio State
running back Archie Griffin found himself in a severe quandry.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the '74 campaign had been a pretty good one for
Griffin. In fact, he won the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through pre-season drills, I could only think of one
thing,'' he recalls, ``and that was what Woody Hayes always said:
every day, you either get better, or you get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that settled it. Griffin was left with no choice ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what I was bringing down on myself,'' he says,
``but I actually played that whole season hoping I would win a
second Heisman. Toward the end, I realized what a ridiculous notion
that was, and I was convinced they would never give it to the same
guy twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Proving that Griffin _ now an associate AD at his alma mater _
was a better football player than prophet. In '75, he became the
only man in the 63-year history of the award to win it twice.
</P>
<P>
   Was he maybe a bit blase by then?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Lord no,'' he says. ``It was an even greater thrill the
second time. When they give you that award they call you the
greatest player in America, and it's just such an honor ... it's a
humbling moment. It was a high point in my life, and it's something
that everybody identifies you with from then on.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thing you have to remember is that I played on one of
the most powerful teams in history. We had a lot of great players,
and without them _ my teammates _ I would have never won anything.
And that's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin also says he ``loved playing for Woody Hayes,'' but does
have one regret _ a Rose Bowl loss to a UCLA team the Buckeyes had
beaten by three touchdowns early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most disappointing loss I ever had,'' he says.
``They were a fine team, but I think we may have taken that game
for granted because we had beaten them earlier. I think we may have
gotten distracted by Hollywood and Disneyland _ that'll happen to
guys from the Midwest out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, in any case, was fated to play for the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he says, ``I was born in the hospital right here on
campus. I grew up here, played here, and then went just a little
ways up the road to Cincinnati when I was in the NFL. I've been
back here since '84, and now I oversee 17 of our 34 sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the best thing of all is, we finally beat Michigan this
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981128.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3085 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BERWANGER-TEX     11-28 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BERWANGER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST HEISMAN WINNER HAD NO IDEA AWARD WOULD BECOME A HOLY GRAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Jay Berwanger received the news that he
won the first Heisman Trophy, he was, of course, thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``A letter came to my fraternity house at the University of
Chicago, telling me I had won this award,'' he recalled. ``Enclosed
with the letter were two plane tickets, for me and my coach to fly
to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest thrill of my life. I had never been on an
airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Jay ... how was the flight?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful,'' he said. ``We took off, and after a while, we
landed. That's what I call a good flight.''
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1935, and that flight would carry Berwanger into
the pages of history as the first recipient of a then-obscure award
that would one day become the Holy Grail of college football. This
year's edition will be awarded by the Downtown Athletic Club in New
York on Dec. 12. Texas' Ricky Williams is the leading candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Berwanger's flight took him to an award he had never heard of.
But he knew about the silver football.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the award you got from the /Chicago Tribune'' if you
were named the player of the year in the Big Ten,'' said Berwanger,
84. ``It was a very coveted award, and they gave you a trophy with
a big silver football on it. The really big thrill for me that year
was winning that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning that placed him in the company of players such as Harold
``Red'' Grange of Illinois and Francis ``Pug'' Lund, the acclaimed
Minnesota running back whom Berwanger had faced during the previous
season.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Heisman got Berwanger and his coach, Clark
Shaughnessy, ``a very nice dinner with about 400 to 500 people, and
a swell tour of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoyed ourselves thoroughly, but at the time, I had no
idea about what this award would become.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What it has meant to me is, all my life, I've had people
coming up to me and asking for my autograph,'' he added. ``It's
kind of amazing _ they still do it, after all this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing I've gotten out of it is that ... I kind of
joined a fraternity. I enjoy going back to New York for the
ceremony ... I think most of us do. We get together and tell lies,
and we all get better every year. It's been a lot of fun, a very
enjoyable part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The award was also an occasion of remarkable irony; within five
years, the school that produced history's first Heisman winner
would disappear forever from the landscape of major-college
football.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1930s, the once-powerful Maroons were marching
resolutely toward oblivion. Berwanger _ a classic triple-threat
tailback in the single-wing era _ was the school's last
All-American. The team's final Big Ten victory came in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Depression, the school dropped its football
program after the 1939 season. It was resurrected 30 years later,
at the Division III level.
</P>
<P>
   When Berwanger arrived as a freshman in 1932, the coach was Amos
Alonzo Stagg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his last year there,'' Berwanger said. ``He was a fine
person, and a great coach. His teams had legendary battles with
Fielding Yost's teams at Michigan, and he was winning championships
when Knute Rockne was a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, when I was there, I think Chicago had still won more
Big Ten titles than any other school. But they hadn't won one in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   They won none during Berwanger's career, either, finishing at
.500 (3-3-2, 4-4, 4-4) during each of his three years (1933-35) on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we were in the middle of the Depression then,''
Berwanger said, ``and that had a lot to do with what happened to
the school, and with my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Dubuque, Iowa, and I normally would have tried to
go East to school, because I had high grades. But there was no
money to send me away that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago wasn't far away, and there was a guy in my hometown
named Ira Davenport who had been an Olympian from the school in
1912. He had played for Stagg, and offered to take me up for an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stagg was a wonderful man, and one thing that I noticed was
that his players had great respect for him. Ira loved cigars, and
he also smoked a pipe, but not around Stagg, because the old man
wouldn't allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Berwanger, described in news accounts of the day as ``Chicago's
one-man gang,'' was a runner-passer-kicker who finished with 22
career touchdowns, 1,839 yards divided almost equally between
running and throwing, and a 38-yard punting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the first real notice I got came from playing
defense when we held Minnesota to six points in the first half in
'34. They rolled us under in the second half, but Walter Camp put
me on his All-America team after watching that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, I played defense, did all the passing and
punting, and a lot of the running. In my senior year, I also had to
call the signals, because right before the season, our quarterback
got married and quit school.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the season highlights was a 20-13 loss to a powerful Ohio
State team, coached by Francis ``Landslide'' Schmidt. The week
before, the Buckeyes had been upset, 18-13, by Notre Dame in what
remains one of history's most famous games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were actually a bunch of really good guys, and we had a
good game with them,'' Berwanger said. ``I had an 85-yard run, but
it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   As a reward for an outstanding season and career, Berwanger
received national acclaim, the silver football _ and another
now-famous trophy of which he remains slightly skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I know it's documented that they used some players in
New York to pose for that trophy,'' he said, ``but I've always
thought it looks a lot like a picture of me that ran in the Dubuque
paper one time. But I've never pushed it.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other rewards as well, but a fat pro contract was not
among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, the pros didn't make much money,'' he says. ``It
was a big deal if somebody got $5,000, and most guys were playing
for a few hundred bucks for a season _ or on a per-game basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it wasn't too bad in comparison to everything else
during the Depression. Someone figured out one time that for the
people in my graduating class who went into the business world, the
average starting salary was $17 a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that happened was that all of us who made
All-America went out to Hollywood and made a movie. Then I went
back to the school and coached the freshmen, and I also wrote a
column for the Chicago Daily News. I finally went to work for a
sponge rubber manufacturer.''
</P>
<P>
   Berwanger became acquainted with the Fort Worth-Dallas area
during the war, most of which he spent as a flight instructor at
the naval air station in Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got out, I discovered that they had sold the company I
was working for,'' he said, ``so I started my own _ Jay Berwanger
Inc. I still own it, but you could say that right now my position
in the firm is, I'm in charge of golf. Actually, we're in the
process of selling it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being the first man ever to win the now-famous Heisman,
he says well, it's been nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it really didn't get to be such a big deal until
television came along,'' he says. ``After that, it kinda took
off.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the massive hype that now surrounds the award he won 63
years ago, Berwanger manages a loud chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There sure is a lot of it, and they find new ways to do it
every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no matter how thin you slice it, it's still baloney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
