<HEADLINE>
BREWERS AND CLARK _ A PERFECT FIT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Will Clark should sign with the Milwaukee
Brewers. It would be the perfect match.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers, having grown weary of John Jaha, need a first
baseman. Clark needs a team. Bud Selig could use some advice.
</P>
<P>
   Clark could run baseball by day and play first base by night,
providing both baseball and the Brewers with his invaluable
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, by mutual need, he will be back with the Rangers.
Both sides have few other options, especially if Rafael Palmeiro
returns to the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Clark would then have nowhere else to go. The best teams in
baseball are set at first base. After the Rangers, the best teams
looking for a first baseman are the Brewers and the Pittsburgh
Pirates. Kevin Young can play first base for Pittsburgh, but they
would like to move him to third.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would also have few other options at first base. One
would be a platoon of Lee Stevens and Mike Simms and sign a
front-line designated hitter like Jose Canseco or Rickey Henderson.
Another would be to sign Robin Ventura and move either him or Todd
Zeile to first base. But Rangers officials don't believe Ventura is
worth $7 to $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could trade for a first baseman. Kansas City would like
to move Jeff King, but again a trade would mean giving up valuable
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But getting Clark back would be the path of least resistance,
providing the Rangers don't try to low ball him. Or his attorney,
Jeff Moorad, doesn't try to point out the obvious _ that Clark is
much more deserving of $26 million than Jose Offerman. Random
observations Baseball has some umpiring problems _ as a national
magazine proclaimed during the playoffs _ particularly with an
inconsistent strike zone. But their umpires are absolutely
infallible when compared to NFL officials, who absolutely stink.
The most incompetent people in all of sports are those zebras whose
job it is to call pass interference or not. They have absolutely no
clue.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn obviously gives the Angels a dangerous bat in their
lineup. But perhaps more important, he gives the Angels their own
``sheriff,'' a hard-nosed leader who will reinforce manager Terry
Collins intense, aggressive approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox, having been badly used by Bernie Williams
and his agent Scott Boras, have messed up royally. They've lost
Vaughn, missed out on Albert Belle and Williams, and are left with
nothing but Jose Offerman and his absurd contract. They have one
great player in Nomar Garciaparra and one great pitcher in Pedro
Martinez. The rest of the team is thoroughly mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   An all-Cy Young rotation is available for any team willing to
spend the money: Randy Johnson, Doug Drabek, Dennis Eckersley, Jack
McDowell and Orel Hershiser. It's a marketing executive's dream. Or
how about five left-handers available who have all had an 18-win
season: Steve Avery, Jim Abbott, Jimmy Key, Mark Langston and Pete
Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an interesting thought: Belle and Cal Ripken Jr. on the
same team.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin and his family spent
Thanksgiving week skiing in Canada. They were joined by Cardinals
general manager Walt Jocketty, Blue Jays GM Gord Ash and their
families. Asked if Ash is trying to move Clemens, Melvin said that
``he hasn't made up his mind yet. I think they may wait until July
to see if they're in contention.'' The Diamondbacks are totally
convinced they're going to get Johnson. But Johnson may eventually
be swayed by the Angels after they signed Vaughn and the
Diamondbacks failed to get Bernie Williams.]
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers eventually must throw some money at a left-handed
reliever: Mark Guthrie, Mike Magnante, Mike Munoz or Jim Poole.
</P>
<P>
   Never underestimate the power of the Yankees to throw a dollar
at anybody they deem necessary. They're talking about a payroll of
$85 million next year and don't doubt one thing: They'll have no
trouble affording it.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos had a payroll of just over $8 million last
year. Now there are 25 players in the major leagues with an average
annual salary of $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't appear as if the Indians will get the No. 1 starter
they were hoping to get, after they failed to interest Kevin Brown.
With an All-Star at every position, it's the one thing that
franchise is missing, but there is still hope Jaret Wright or
Bartolo Colon could develop into one.
</P>
<P>
   Why should owners in Montreal, Oakland, Kansas City and
Minnesota even try. Just throw a team out there for $10 million,
collecting your share of the national television contract and
everything else is pure profit. You have no chance anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Stunning development: The Toronto Blue Jays have negotiated a
new lease with SkyDome, rather than making good on their threat to
play in Exhibition Stadium next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are faced with one sad truth: They're stuck paying
Randy Myers $12 million over the next two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
