<HEADLINE>
`IT STAMPS YOU AS THE BEST'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Following a distinguished career with the
Dallas Cowboys, Roger Staubach received perhaps the ultimate
reward: induction into the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   But when the man who directed the Cowboys to two Super Bowl
titles throws a party, the guests usually arrive with something
else in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of entertaining at home,'' he says. ``Almost
invariably, the first question people ask is, `Do you have your
Heisman Trophy here? Can we see it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   For Staubach, who won the award as a junior at Navy in 1963, it
has become something akin to a lifelong friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect it has on people is unprecedented,'' he says.
``It's by far the most recognized award any football player can
ever receive. Rightly or wrongly, it stamps you as the best _ and
that's the way people view you for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the event unfolded 35 years ago, Staubach was not
completely thrilled by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great team,'' he says, ``but it was because of a lot
of people, not just me. Even back then, there was a lot of
publicity surrounding it, and Navy was definitely pushing me for
the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty much a quiet type of person, and I really just
wanted to do my part and kind of fade into the background. All the
hype was kind of embarrassing to me then.''
</P>
<P>
   Staubach was the fifth _ and last _ player from Army or Navy to
win the award, as the two schools reached the end of a long reign
as national powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat Michigan in Ann Arbor, and we were the last Navy team
to beat Notre Dame,'' he says. ``Our nemesis was the Cotton Bowl,
where we lost twice _ to SMU in the regular season and Texas in the
bowl game. It was a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   Now president of his own company, Staubach has adjusted to fame,
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's such a great honor,'' he says, ``and even back then,
I was excited by it, especially because my parents got to go to New
York for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that over the years the Heisman has transcended all
criticism, and it has brought nothing but good things to most of
those who won it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it seems the Heisman can even transcend one of
football's most ancient rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every so often,'' Staubach says, laughing, ``We even have
reunions of the guys who won it from Army and Navy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 2119EST &QL; 
