<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT BECOMES A PART OF YOUR NAME'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As the 1957 season reached its conclusion,
Texas A&AMP;M coach Paul ``Bear'' Bryant made a brief address to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't give the Heisman Trophy to John David Crow,'' he
rasped, ``They oughta just quit giving out the danged thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus spoke the Bear. And presto, Harry and Velma Crow of
Springhill, La., were taking the first plane ride of their lives _
all the way to New York with their baby boy for the award
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess a lot of people have heard that story,'' Crow says,
laughing. ``Coach Bryant didn't compliment anyone all that often,
so I guess it started people thinking, `This guy must really be
good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I probably wouldn't have won the Heisman if he hadn't
said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that Crow _ a dramatically physical two-way player
winding up an outstanding career _ would have won it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Often compared to Bronco Nagurski, he did not make many
swivel-hipped runs _ but within 10 yards of either goal line, he
was the player who usually determined whether or not somebody
scored a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   His performance earned him a coveted award that he was unaware
of as a college senior ... and has thoroughly enjoyed ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what it was,'' he says, ``until one day our
publicist, Jones Ramsey, called me into his office and started
asking me questions for a bio, like what was my favorite movie
star. I remember I told him it was Debbie Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the wall was a photo of a trophy, and I said, `That's real
nice-looking, what is it?' And he told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't long after that that Carolyn \Rhis wife\S and I were
on our way to New York for the ceremony. My folks went with us _
their first plane ride _ and it was really neat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carolyn and I are still making that trip, each year. It's been
a wonderful part of our lives. It's kind of like you joined a
fraternity, and you have this great group of friends to go visit
with every so often.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the award itself, it's almost as if it becomes a part
of your name. For the rest of your life, wherever you go, it goes
with you. It has brought me continuing recognition I never would
have dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Crow, who rushed for 5,000 yards and had over 3,500 yards in
pass receptions in an 11-year NFL career, does have one gripe,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``It upsets me when people run some of these guys down because
they never had big NFL careers,'' he says. ``The Heisman has
nothing to do with pro football. It's a reward for what you
achieved in college, and that's all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
