<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO MAKES PITCH TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Rafael Palmeiro understands that the Rangers
need pitching. He also understands why they have made Randy Johnson
their No. 1 priority.
</P>
<P>
   He just points out one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that I see it, if they were to get Randy Johnson and
myself, with the team they already have in place, it would be a
very strong team,'' Palmeiro said. ``They could take two big steps
toward making it a championship team.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said yesterday his first choice still is to return to
the Baltimore Orioles, and he said the two sides are close to
working out a new five-year contract. But Palmeiro makes his home
in Colleyville and still is tantalized by the possibility of
returning to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live 15 minutes from The Ballpark,'' Palmeiro said. ``It
would be nice to play there. But I've enjoyed Baltimore also. If I
can work something out with Baltimore, that would be great. If I
had the opportunity to come back to Texas, that would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' plan is to see if Johnson will accept their
four-year, $50 million offer. Johnson's agent Barry Meister said
yesterday he has received the final offers from the Rangers,
Anaheim Angels, Los Angeles Dodgers and Arizona Diamondbacks. All
of them are for four years and approximately $50-51 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meister said Johnson and his wife, Lisa, will spend today going
through the offers and likely will announce their decision
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers have been very gracious,'' Meister said. ``They
understand Randy and Lisa just need to sit down and decide between
the three cities and four clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching and shortstop Royce Clayton have been the Rangers' top
priorities this off-season, but they are also without an everyday
first baseman under contract since Will Clark is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has spoken with Palmeiro's agent, Jim Bronner, but has
not made an offer. He also plans to talk with Clark's attorney,
Jeff Moorad, again this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hopeful they would be interested,'' Palmeiro said. ``At
this point, I've got to do what I've got to do. At this point, I'm
moving forward with the Orioles.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who has also received interest from the Boston Red
Sox, hit .296 with 43 homers and 121 runs batted in for the Orioles
this past season, winning the Silver Slugger award for best
offensive first baseman. Clark hit .305 with 23 homers and 102 RBI,
helping the Rangers win their second division title in three
seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
