<SLUG> BC-FBO-COLBYFREEMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINCE SOPHOMORE YEAR, BROWNWOOD STAR A HOT PROSPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK HERRIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNWOOD, Texas _ Sitting in the office of Tom Osborne,
Nebraska's legendary former coach, Colby Freeman's eyes widened.
</P>
<P>
   The glass-enclosed case with national championship trophies. The
coach. The conversation.
</P>
<P>
   That was Freeman's star-struck initiation into college
recruiting. That was two summers ago, when Freeman was Brownwood
High School's quarterback preparing for his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that Nebraska summer camp that Freeman became such a
commodity that Osborne tried to talk him into a Cornhuskers career.
By the end of the week, Freeman was offered a scholarship by a team
that was one year removed from consecutive national championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my first contact with any type of college,'' said
Freeman, the son of Class 4A Brownwood coach Steve Freeman. ``With
not even knowing about Nebraska and having never met the coaches,
and by the end of the week they offered a scholarship. What they
told me was that I had acquired the skills they were trying to
teach their guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons later, Freeman (6-foot-3, 205 pounds) is one of the
nation's most coveted quarterback recruits.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Freeman special is his combination of running and
throwing ability with size and speed (4.48 40-yard dash). He is the
state's top quarterback recruit and is ranked among the top 10
quarterbacks in the nation by several recruiting services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one unique factor is his rushing capability,'' said
Steve Freeman, who played linebacker at Abilene Christian
University. ``He's had the ability to run the wishbone and any form
of option. And throwing schools like the fact of his mobility.''
</P>
<P>
   Colby Freeman said he has narrowed his wish list _ in no
specific order _ to Texas, Texas A&AMP;M and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of officially said that's where the visits are going
to be,'' Freeman said in his polite Texas drawl.
</P>
<P>
   He did say that A&AMP;M is his leading choice and that it would be
hard to leave the state for Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``A&AMP;M is in the lead right now because of the comfort reason,''
Freeman said. ``I have been around them quite a bit more. And
thinking about the actual day I get in the car and drive up there
\Rto Nebraska\S, and not having my dad see me play, I don't know if
I want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As a four-year starter, Freeman has become almost as well known
throughout Texas as former Brownwood coach Gordon Wood. The
Freemans helped turn Brownwood's proud program into a winner again.
With Colby Freeman at quarterback, the Lions went from 1-8-1 his
freshman season to three consecutive 10-win seasons and two
district championships. Brownwood finished this season 10-2 and
reached the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman showed his versatility by finishing this regular season
as the Fort Worth area's top Class 4A rusher (1,498 yards) and one
of its most accurate passers (58 for 98 and one interception). It
was the second consecutive season Freeman surpassed 1,000 yards
rushing and passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they \RNebraska\S could tell about Colby was that
he was a good-sized player and has good speed,'' said Bobby Burton,
managing editor of the ``National Recruiting Advisor''. ``Those are
two things you can't lose, barring injury. And he is dedicated to
becoming a great player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
