<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTRECRUIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN GETS HEAD START ON REAPING TALENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MILLER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mack Brown can finally return to his style
of recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   When he took over as the Texas Longhorns' football coach last
December, Brown found himself playing catchup in the recruiting
game. He was two months from national signing day with no recruits.
During a frenzied eight weeks, Brown signed a class of 18 recruits
that was competitive with any in the state.
</P>
<P>
   That was not how Brown did things in his last years at North
Carolina and that's not the way he's doing things in his first full
recruiting season with the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know that you have a group of young men who fill
certain needs for you, then you also know what positions you need
to get commitments for,'' Brown said. ``In my early days, we would
be in a position where we were waiting on five players until the
very end, and if the five went somewhere else, then in a sense, we
lost five scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of such national powers as Penn State,
Michigan and Ohio State, Brown has made Texas the first Big 12
school in the state to seek oral commitments from high school
players before their senior season.
</P>
<P>
   Commitments aren't binding until national signing day, Feb. 3,
the first day letters of intent for scholarship agreements can be
signed.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thanksgiving, Texas easily leads Texas A&AMP;M, Baylor and
Texas Tech _ the other Big 12 schools in the state _ with 17 oral
commitments from Texas high school players and one from Denver.
Four players have committed to play for the Aggies, three to Baylor
and one to Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is no question that they have some blue-chip
players committed to play for them next season,'' Bobby Burton,
editor-in-chief of ``The National Recruiting Advisor'', said of
Texas. ``I think that if everything holds their course, they have
the definite makings of a very strong class.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, Texas A&AMP;M and Texas Tech choose to wait to make their
big recruiting push, as Texas did before Brown arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many good players in the state of Texas, we just
feel like it is in our best interest to sit back and evaluate the
kids during their senior year,'' Baylor coach Dave Roberts said.
``It \Rwhat Texas is doing\S certainly won't affect what we do.
They have taken some players out of the pool, but there are still
plenty of good players available.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes agreed, even seeing benefits for
the Red Raiders by having Texas pick up early commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can do in a recruiting battle is finish
second,'' Dykes said. ``Now we know the people \Rwho\S have
committed to Texas. They are guys who probably would have anyway.
That saves us a lot of time. The sooner you find out that you're
not going to get a player, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting also eliminates some of the risks associated with early
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   A player who is offered a scholarship and makes a commitment to
a school could suffer a career-ending injury during his final high
school season. Then there is the problem of players who change
their minds. On several occasions, a recruit has committed to
several schools before finally signing with one.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly why Texas A&AMP;M prefers a more conservative
approach to early commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a good situation if that player is truly committed
to the university,'' said Tim Cassidy, associate athletic director
in charge of football operations for Texas A&AMP;M. ``If it is someone
\Rwho\S has reservations, then we don't want him to commit until he
is sure. We tell them that it is like being engaged. Once you get
engaged, you can't go out on two or three more dates to make sure
it's what you really want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown started going after recruits early four years ago while at
North Carolina. It is the same style first-year TCU coach Dennis
Franchione brought to the Horned Frogs from New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just two different schools of thought on recruiting,''
Burton said. ``Florida State does not really go after the early
commitments, yet they have been very successful. Michigan, on the
other hand, goes after early commitments and they have also been
very successful. Who is to say which way is better than the
other?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been successful at signing the players who make
commitments. Only one of his North Carolina recruits who committed
early did not sign. That case had the unusual circumstances of a
death in the family shortly before national signing day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very surprised if any of the kids \Rwho\S have told
us they are going to sign with us don't do so on signing day,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown started reeling in commitments in June when Texas held a
football camp for upcoming seniors. At the end of the camp, on June
3, Coppell High School offensive lineman Robbie Doane became
Brown's first oral commitment for this recruiting season. That was
six months before Texas picked up a commitment last year and eight
months before signing day.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was going to try to wait and see what happens,''
said Doane, who is considered one of the nation's top offensive
linemen by recruiting evaluators. ``But when I went down there, I
liked the way they ran things and I liked the coaches. I also
wanted to concentrate on my senior season.''
</P>
<P>
   The commitments kept rolling in. By the time the Longhorns
opened their season on Sept. 5 against New Mexico State, they had
14 oral commitments.
</P>
<P>
   If all 18 sign, Texas will have seven scholarships to give
between now and Feb. 3 to reach the annual limit of 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a foolproof philosophy, and there is some risk,''
Brown said. ``But if you see a young man who fits your school, not
just as a football player, but in all the other ways as well, and
if he wants to come to your school and seems committed to playing
for your team, why not go ahead and make the commitment, no matter
what time of year it is?''
</P>
<P>
   It appears many players in the state agree with Brown. At their
present rate, the Longhorns could be wishing for a few more
scholarships to give out for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   (CHART:) Recruiting primer
</P>
<P>
   KEY QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Once a recruit commits to a school, can he change his mind?
</P>
<P>
   All commitments are non-binding and a recruit is free to change
his mind at any time before signing the national letter of intent.
</P>
<P>
   How many college visits can a recruit make?
</P>
<P>
   Recruits are limited to five official visits, meaning the school
pays for the trip. However, recruits are free to make other visits
if they pay for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   How many visits can a head coach make to a recruit's home?
</P>
<P>
   A head coach is limited to one calendar day to make an in-home
visit.
</P>
<P>
   KEY DATES
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 1: Coaches can start making in-home visits with recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 13: Quiet period: a coach can write and call a recruit, but
cannot meet with a recruit off the university campus. A recruit can
visit the coach on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 14-17: Dead period: a coach can write or call a recruit,
but there cannot be any face-to-face interaction between the coach
and recruit.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 18: Quiet period
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 24-Jan 1: Dead period
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 10: Quiet period
</P>
<P>
   Jan 11-13: Dead period
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 14: Quiet period
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 1-4: Dead period
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 3: National signing day. First day recruits can sign
binding national letters of intent.
</P>
</TEXT>
