<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Dec. 6.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ABUSE OF POWER: THE NEW NIXON TAPES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Stanley I. Kutler. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17.
Transcripts of Watergate tapes released in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ADIRONDACKS: A HISTORY OF AMERICA'S FIRST WILDERNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Schneider. John Macrae/Owl/Holt, $12.95. A tour of New
York's 6-million-acre Adirondack Park.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICAN EXODUS: THE ORIGINS OF MODERN HUMANITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Christopher Stringer and Robin McKie. Owl/Holt, $14.95. A
case for the ``out of Africa'' model of human origins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALL OVER BUT THE SHOUTIN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Rick Bragg. Vintage, $14. How a dirt-poor child became a
prize-winning journalist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICAN SCRIPTURE: MAKING THE DECLARATION OF INDEPENDENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Pauline Maier. Vintage, $14. A feisty and highly original
perspective on our most treasured national relic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEAR AND HIS DAUGHTER: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Stone. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12.
Testosterone-rich fiction by a most distinctive novelist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEGINNING OF SPRING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Penelope Fitzgerald. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12. A lovely
comedy of manners set in Russia in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BELIEVERS: A NOVELLA AND STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Baxter. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. Eloquent tales
focusing on ordinary Midwesterners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIG TROUBLE: A MURDER IN A SMALL WESTERN TOWN SETS OFF A
STRUGGLE FOR THE SOUL OF AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By J. Anthony Lukas. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17. Capital
vs. labor in turn-of-the-century Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLACK JACKS: AFRICAN AMERICAN SEAMEN IN THE AGE OF SAIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By W. Jeffrey Bolster. Harvard University, $14.95. Two centuries
of rousing, and fascinating, nautical lore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOB THE GAMBLER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Frederick Barthelme. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12. Fiction
about gambling's toll on a middle-class family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOOK OF FAMOUS IOWANS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Douglas Bauer. Owl/Holt, $12. A novel about a scandal in a
small Iowa town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BOOK OF MEMORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Nadas. Translated by Ivan Sanders. Penguin, $14.95. A
complex Hungarian novel about communist Europe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOYHOOD: SCENES FROM PROVINCIAL LIFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By J.M. Coetzee. Penguin, $11.95. A South African novelist's
gritty memoir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOYS: THE UNTOLD STORY OF 732 YOUNG CONCENTRATION CAMP
SURVIVORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Martin Gilbert. Owl/Holt, $16.95. A remarkable group of
mostly Polish Jews recall their childhood ordeals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRIGHT COLLEGE YEARS: INSIDE THE AMERICAN CAMPUS TODAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Matthews. University of Chicago, $14. A look at
university life after the end of the canon wars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BURNING THE DAYS: RECOLLECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By James Salter. Vintage International, $13. A novelist revisits
his varied careers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BYRNE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Burgess. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $10.95. An audacious novel
told entirely in rhymed verse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CALIFORNIA'S OVER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Louis B. Jones. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. Fiction about
the foibles of a hippie family in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLD MOUNTAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Frazier. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. A novel that
recasts the ``Odyssey'' during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COMPLETE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Bernard Malamud. Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $16.
Fifty-five tales of enormous variety about Jews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A COUNTRY OF STRANGERS: BLACKS AND WHITES IN AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David K. Shipler. Vintage, $15. An engaging book on the
United States' uneasy racial divide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DARK SIDE OF CAMELOT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Seymour M. Hersh. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $15. A dirt-filled
tour exposing the warts of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DIARIES OF DAWN POWELL, 1931-1965 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Tim Page. Steerforth, $19. Journals written during the
last half of the novelist's life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINOSAUR LIVES: UNEARTHING AN EVOLUTIONARY SAGA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By John R. Horner and Edwin Dobb. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13.
Fascinating speculation about how dinosaurs lived.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DJINN IN THE NIGHTINGALE'S EYE: FIVE FAIRY STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By A.S. Byatt. Vintage International, $12. Eloquently told tales
of magic and quests.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOO-DAH! STEPHEN FOSTER AND THE RISE OF AMERICAN POPULAR
CULTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ken Emerson. Da Capo, $16.95. The life and times of a
pioneering songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DREAMS OF MY RUSSIAN SUMMERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Andre Makine. Translated by Geoffrey Strachan. Scribner,
$7.99. A French novel about a youth coping with Soviet life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EGGS FOR YOUNG AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Katherine L. Hester. Penguin, $12.95. Assured stories by a
provocative Southern writer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIRST MODERNS: PROFILES IN THE ORIGINS OF TWENTIETH-CENTURY
THOUGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By William R. Everdell. University of Chicago, $16. How
discontinuity has affected math, physics and art.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GAY METROPOLIS: 1940-1996 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Kaiser. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14. A social history
of homosexual life in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLASS, PAPER, BEANS: REVELATIONS ON THE NATURE AND VALUE OF
ORDINARY THINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Leah Hager Cohen. Doubleday, $12.95. Meticulous reflections
on three common objects.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOD OF SMALL THINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Arundhati Roy. Harper Perennial, $13. A first novel about the
decline of an Indian family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREAT APES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Will Self. Grove, $12. A satire in which chimps are at the
top of the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROOMING, GOSSIP, AND THE EVOLUTION OF LANGUAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Robin Dunbar. Harvard University, $14. How gossip is the
human version of primate grooming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HISTORY OF THE SIEGE OF LISBON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jos Saramago. Translated by Giovanni Pontiero.
Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13. A novel by a Nobel Prize-winning
Portuguese author.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOTEL EDEN: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Carlson. Penguin, $12.95. Confiding tales with
self-deprecating narrators.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW WE LIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sherwin B. Nuland. Vintage, $14. A surgeon explains how the
human body works.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUNGRY GHOSTS: MAO'S SECRET FAMINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jasper Becker. Owl/Holt, $14.95. A chilling re-creation of
the 1959-61 Chinese famine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ILIAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Homer. Translated by Robert Fagles. Penguin, $15.95. A
forceful, direct translation of Homer's classic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INGENIOUS PAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Miller. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13. A novel about a
brilliant surgeon who cannot feel pain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE MEMORY OF THE FOREST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles T. Powers. Penguin, $12.95. A moral novel about a
Polish village's Jewish population.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE KENNEDY TAPES: INSIDE THE WHITE HOUSE DURING THE CUBAN
MISSILE CRISIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Ernest R. May and Philip D. Zelikow. Belknap/Harvard
University, $16.95. A scholarly transcription revealing a resolute
president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LARRY'S PARTY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Shields. Penguin, $12.95. A novel that shows what it's
like being a man in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIGHTNING SONG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lewis Nordan. Algonquin, $10.95. A coming-of-age novel with a
goofy 12-year-old hero.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIVING AFTER MIDNIGHT: A NOVELLA AND STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lee K. Abbott. Ohio State University, $16.95. Fiction about
ordinary people fascinated with language.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOST MAN'S RIVER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Matthiessen. Vintage International, $14. An ambitious
novel set in the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVE AND LONGING IN BOMBAY: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Vikram Chandra. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $13. Five tales of
glitterati and gritty policemen in India.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LUCKY YOU &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Carl Hiaasen. Warner Vision, $7.50. Fiction about wacky
Floridians and a lottery prize.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKING WAVES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Mario Vargas Llosa. Edited by John King. Penguin, $14.95.
Essays charting a Peruvian writer's intellectual growth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEMOIRS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sir Georg Solti. A Cappella, $15.95. A zestful book by a
renowned conductor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO: BIOGRAPHY OF POWER. A HISTORY OF MODERN MEXICO,
1810-1996 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Enrique Krauze. Translated by Hank Heifetz. Harper Perennial,
$18. An ambitious study of the nation's colonial past.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MOORING OF STARTING OUT: THE FIRST FIVE BOOKS OF POETRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By John Ashbery. Ecco Press, $18. Rich, complex verse from a
celebrated poet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY BROTHER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jamaica Kincaid. Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $10. An
Antiguan author's bold account of her brother's life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY NAME ESCAPES ME: THE DIARY OF A RETIRING ACTOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alec Guinness. Penguin, $12.95. A charming journal by a
charming actor begun at 80.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NAKED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David Sedaris. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $12.95. Funny, sharp
essays about a writer's odd experiences.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NAPOLEON OF CRIME: THE LIFE AND TIMES OF ADAM WORTH, MASTER
THIEF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ben Macintyre. Delta, $12.95. A portrait of the Victorian
era's most notorious crook.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO MERCY: A JOURNEY TO THE HEART OF THE CONGO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Redmond O'Hanlon. Vintage Departures, $14. A wild travelogue
about a search for a living dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONCE A DANCER ... &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Allegra Kent. St. Martin's, $16.95. A ballerina surveys her
life and career.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONE OF US &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David Freeman. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $11.95. A novel of clashing
cultures set in grand colonial Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANDAEMONIUM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Leslie Epstein. St. Martin's Griffin, $14.95. A Hollywood
novel featuring dreamy European exiles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PEACEABLE KINGDOM: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Francine Prose. Owl/Holt, $12. Mordant forays into the weird
jungle of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PERFECT STORM: A TRUE STORY OF MEN AGAINST THE SEA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sebastian Junger. Harper Paperbacks, $6.99. A fishing boat's
harrowing encounter with a nor'easter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRESENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alfred Corn. Counterpoint, $13.50. Poetry that links
disparate cultural figures and forces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUBLISH AND PERISH: THREE TALES OF TENURE AND TERROR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By James Hynes. Picador USA, $14. Postmodern novellas of
contemporary academe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PUTTERMESSER PAPERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Cynthia Ozick. Vintage International, $12. A novel about a
New York Jew and her imaginary life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REALITY AND DREAMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Muriel Spark. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12. Fiction about a
spoiled film director tempted to play God.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEX ON THE BRAIN: THE BIOLOGICAL DIFFERENCES BETWEEN MEN AND
WOMEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Deborah Blum. Penguin, $13.95. Clear-headed reporting on the
war between the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPIN CYCLE: HOW THE WHITE HOUSE AND THE MEDIA MANIPULATE THE
NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Howard Kurtz. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14. The media's
bad marriage to the Clinton spinmeisters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SPIRIT CATCHES YOU AND YOU FALL DOWN: A HMONG CHILD, HER
AMERICAN DOCTORS, AND THE COLLISION OF TWO CULTURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Fadiman. Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $13. The tale
of an immigrant child's medical crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUMMER FOR THE GODS: THE SCOPES TRIAL AND AMERICA'S CONTINUING
DEBATE OVER SCIENCE AND RELIGION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Edward J. Larson. Harvard University, $14.95. A Pulitzer
Prize-winning account of the ''monkey trial.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOWARD THE END OF TIME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By John Updike. Fawcett Columbine, $12.95. A ``Walden'' gone
haywire, set in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNDERWORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Don DeLillo. Scribner, $16. A sprawling fictional wake for
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAIT TILL NEXT YEAR: A MEMOIR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Doris Kearns Goodwin. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $13. A
woman's childhood passion for the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHITTAKER CHAMBERS: A BIOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sam Tanenhaus. Modern Library, $16. A copious life study of a
famously enigmatic figure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WHOLE SHEBANG: A STATE-OF-THE-UNIVERSE(S) REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy Ferris. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14. A skillful
and arresting status report on cosmology.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WIND-UP BIRD CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Haruki Murakami. Translated by Jay Rubin. Vintage
International, $14. A big, bold Japanese novel with lots on its
mind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOE IS I: THE GRAMMARPHOBE'S GUIDE TO BETTER ENGLISH IN PLAIN
ENGLISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia T. O'Conner. Riverhead, $11. An irreverent and
surprisingly useful Baedeker.
</P>
</TEXT>
