<HEADLINE>
IT'S AN EARLY SPRING  
 STRENGTH COACH KEEPS D-BACKS FIT IN OFF-SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Below ground, in the cool concrete tunnels of Bank One
Ballpark, the snakes are not hibernating.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks already are preparing for next spring and
summer, their second in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of strength and conditioning coach Jeff
Forney, about 10 players come in virtually every day to mold
themselves into shape. And players who live outside Arizona aren't
gathering mold. They know what is expected of them.
</P>
<P>
   They have general programs geared to their positions, and most
have specific routines that are tailored to fit their individual
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they weren't doing it, it would definitely show when they
reported to camp,'' Forney said. ``My wrath has little to do with
it. A lot of these guys could lose a job if they're not prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the end of the season, Manager Buck Showalter sat
down with Forney and members of the training and medical staffs to
discuss each player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where Jeff's job starts,'' Showalter said. ``In many
ways, his job is more important now than it is during the season.
Baseball is such a stamina sport . . . the fact that we play every
day makes it essential that these guys build and maintain
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Forney played as an outfielder in the Cincinnati Reds chain for
six years and was a coach at Notre Dame and Arizona State before
joining the Diamondbacks organization in 1996. That experience
makes him valuable, Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can identify with what the players are going through,''
Showalter said. ``He knows when to back off and when to push.''
</P>
<P>
   The local players coming in include pitchers Andy Benes, Ben
Ford, Bryan Corey, Willie Banks and Chris Michalak. Recently signed
middle reliever Greg Swindell has joined the group. Third baseman
Matt Williams and first baseman Travis Lee participate.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Bernard Gilkey, who is recovering from corrective
laser surgery on his eyes, has been in but went back to his home in
the St. Louis area. He is expected to return shortly after the
first of the year, and others such as infielder Jay Bell are
expected to arrive. Showalter said Forney has gone to Tampa on two
occasions to work with Bell, and Bell is considering a permanent
move here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is strong in April. We want to try to make sure that
these guys have something left in September and October,'' Forney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players took the month of October off and started to
work back into shape about three or four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Damian Miller, who lives in LaCrosse, Wis., said he
tries to follow Forney's program as closely as possible. He lifts
weights, rides a stationary bike for cardiovascular exercise and
plays an occasional game of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   These days, much of his time is spent building a new home for
his wife and young daughter, helping his uncle with whatever is
needed. Miller also has done some hunting, which helps the legs, or
so one would think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were deer hunting and this buck practically jumped right
out in front of us,'' Miller said. ``I was running, chasing him up
a small hill and I thought I was going to have a heart attack. That
shows how quickly you can get out of shape. But I'm getting back
into it now. It's exciting for us catchers because we've added a
few quality pitchers (Swindell, Todd Stottlemyre and Armando
Reynoso) that should help us out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's running mate behind the plate, Kelly Stinnett, is
excited, too, but he has to maintain a more deliberate pace as he
recovers from arthroscopic surgery to remove debris from his right
knee. The surgery was performed shortly after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do some (weight) lifting and a little bit of running for
about two hours and another hour of rehabilitation,'' said
Stinnett, who lives in Lawton, Okla. ``Jeff sent us some videotapes
reminding us of the proper way of doing the exercises.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett also is maintaining dexterity in his hands by changing
diapers for his second son, Alex, who was born a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Forney said the pitchers concentrate on working their lower back
and legs, using dumbbells, power cords and medicine balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``And although people might not think that pitchers work much on
their upper body, we believe in working that, too, not necessarily
with muscle mass, but with strength,'' Forney said.
</P>
<P>
   Position players use a little heavier weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a good core, abs (abdominal muscles), lower back and
legs,'' Forney said. ``This is one of the more rotational of the
sports. You need to be explosive as a hitter. We can have 'em go
heavy now because we've still got a lot of recovery time.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as running is concerned, there are a lot of short bursts
and longer sprints, but not a lot of distance work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to repeat (the shorter work and weights) over and
over and over. To me, that's more taxing than running 10 miles,''
Forney said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
