<SLUG> BC-RAC-TURF-SECURITY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRONS OF `SPORT OF KINGS' DON'T ALWAYS ACT LIKE PRINCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Bruce Denneny, a retired Chicago police officer and
detective, begins the walk each day at about the same time and
place.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be a hurried walk, but because of shrinking Turf
Paradise crowds, due to off-track betting expansion, Denneny no
longer needs to be a Carl Lewis in loafers.
</P>
<P>
   At age 62, Denneny can afford a more leisurely pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock on wood, but we don't get the kind of clientele we used
to get,'' said Denneny, who has been Turf Paradise chief of
security for the past 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Clientele is Denneny's nice way of describing the rip-off
artists that lurk in the shadows at many racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   Before Turf Paradise began expanding its OTB network several
years ago, Denneny usually could count on a thick file full of
unsavory characters by the end of an eight-month meet. Denneny now
estimates an average of only 10 such incidents a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that feed off honest gamblers stick out more
because (on-track) crowds are smaller and they are more easily
identified,'' said Denneny, who reported no such incidents last
Saturday during Breeders' Cup Day, which attracted a record crowd
of 4,734.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of people?
</P>
<P>
   ``Stoopers,'' ``10-percenters,'' ``odds changers,'' ``clippers''
and other scam artists and schemers looking to make a quick buck
off a racetrack's patronage.
</P>
<P>
   Stoopers sneak around searching for discarded tickets, picking
them off floors and digging them out of garbage cans. Although
stooping isn't a crime, most racetracks have regulations preventing
it.
</P>
<P>
   One argument for such regulations is that discarded tickets pick
up dirt, which in turn jam parimutuel machines. To prevent such
occurrences, Turf Paradise employ floor sweepers after every race.
</P>
<P>
   Another argument is that some horseplayers unknowingly throw
away winning tickets, some of which are lottery sized.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about five years ago, Maureen Boskon of Carefree,
whose adventure was chronicled in the ``National Enquirer,''
inadvertently threw away a winning twin trifecta ticket worth
$18,000.
</P>
<P>
   When she realized the mistake, she appealed to sympathetic
racetrack employees, who immediately began to search for the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She threw it on the floor and it ended up in a garbage can,''
Turf Paradise spokesman Vincent Francia said. ``Three of us,
including (former Turf Paradise President) Bob Walker, started
digging through trash bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, Mr. Walker found it.''
</P>
<P>
   Denneny can count on one hand the number of stoopers he has
apprehended the past several years, and none is a recent case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give them one warning and tell them to go home,'' Denneny
said. ``If we catch them again, we ban them from the racetrack and
take a picture of them. We send the photograph to all the OTB
outlets and to the (greyhound) tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   So crafty have some stoopers become, they earn nicknames.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work at Delaware Park, and there was this one guy we
called `The Toe,' '' Francia said. ``He had these black pointed
shoes and he could somehow stick the toe of the shoe underneath a
ticket and flip it over without having to stoop to read it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, there were times when we'd be standing watching him
from a few feet away and he'd do it without us even knowing it.
He'd flip it over and nonchalantly glance down to see if it was a
winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there six years and I think we only caught and threw him
out four times.''
</P>
<P>
   Clippers, Denneny said, tear off the corners of $10 or $20 bills
and paste or tape them on the corners of $1 bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any of that anymore, either,'' Denneny said.
``About the only time you see it is at the concession stands. But
we have ways to check to make sure they're legal bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Denneny also produced a sheet of confiscated counterfeit bills,
some of which are extremely phony appearing, including an obvious
photocopy of a $1 bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-percenters attempt to cheat tax laws by offering to cash in
hefty winning tickets for 10 percent of the ticket's worth.
Gamblers with winning tickets worth more than $600 must sign an IRS
form. If a ticket is worth at least $1,500, it is subject to an
immediate tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have one (pari-mutuel window) for people cashing in
large tickets,'' Denneny said. ``Now you can go to any window.
That's why you don't see the 10-percenters here anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, we recognize a lot of these people. They've been
regulars for a long time, and with the smaller crowds, we spot them
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds changers, or jinglers, attempt to gain favorable odds by
dumping large amounts of money on a particular horse, then
canceling the bet at the last moment in order to make a second bet
at better odds.
</P>
<P>
   But because of advances made in electronic wagering, it's more
difficult to complete the scam.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine with Denneny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem we have these days is with the automatic
pari-mutuel machines,'' Denneny said. ``Somebody will put $20 into
the machine, make a $5 bet and forget to punch the return balance
button.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time that is going on, someone else will be watching
this from several feet away. As soon as the gambler walks away from
the machine, the other people will come up and hit the return
balance key and walk away with the money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``See that man over there,'' said Denneny, pointing to a
sloppily dressed, bearded man standing next to a table. ``I caught
him a while back and threw him out. I told him if it ever happened
again, he's be banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a good boy since then. And that's the way we like
it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
