<HEADLINE>
THE OUTER LIMITS OF FORGIVENESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
Trudy Calabrese's murderer stood in open court last week and told a
judge, ``Regardless of what my family thinks, I deserve the death
penalty.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trudy's husband, Rosario, wid owed father of two children, sat
quietly nearby, and disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he should die,'' Calabrese told me.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' he said, ``the Bible tells me so.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he paused, and added, ``Also, this is a thing Trudy would
not want. I'm sure about it. She was not such a person.''
</P>
<P>
   One day last February, the Living Springs Assembly of God
church, near 123rd Avenue and Camelback Road, got a call from a man
named John Sansing.
</P>
<P>
   He told them he and his wife, Kara, and their three children
were going through hard times and needed food. He'd heard the
church had a program that might help. &QL; 
Later that night, Trudy Calabrese arrived at the Sansings' home
carry ing a box of groceries.
</P>
<P>
   As she walked through the front door, Sansing clubbed her over
the head. The couple had been smoking crack cocaine. They bound
Trudy with electrical cord and dragged her into a bedroom. She was
sexually assaulted and stabbed, her body dumped in a shed behind
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the food, Trudy had $1.25 in her pocket.
</P>
<P>
   They took that, too.
</P>
<P>
   All the terrible details of the crime are known to Rosario Cala
brese. The suspects were quickly arrested, the knife found under a
sofa cushion.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you marry,'' he said, the sharp edges of English smoothed
over by his Sicilian accent, ``you make a commitment. I do this
same thing with the Lord. He tells me, you need to forgive, and I
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't, I would be so angry inside, and it's no way to go
through the day with all the anger. So, I tell the Lord, `I'm
giving it to you.' And I try to go on best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days of Trudy's murder, the congregation at her church
had gathered clothes and toys for the suspects' four children. Even
now, they pray for Sansing and his wife, who's expected to strike a
deal soon with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In court last week, Sansing said, ``To you, Mr. Calabrese and
your kids, I'm very sorry. I wish I could change it, but I
can't.'' &QL; 
Rosario met Trudy in Germany. He'd moved there from Sicily to work.
She was in the Air Force. They came to the Phoenix area in 1996,
settling on the western edge of the city, in Avondale, where
Rosario plans to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our life is here,'' he said. ``We must go on. When I see this
man (Sansing) in court, I'm glad about what he said. He knows what
he did. His family is broken like my family. It's not easy for him
to go through his life with this.''
</P>
<P>
   As if it should be easy for him.
</P>
<P>
   There are times in this business when you can't help but put
your self in the place of the person you're writing about.
</P>
<P>
   I think of Rosario, a man with two kids, and myself, a man with
two kids, and I know if I was in his situation I'd spend every
spare moment plotting to kill the SOB who did this in a way more
gruesome than even he could imag ine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't forgive, the Lord may not forgive you,''
Rosario said.
</P>
<P>
   So what? he is asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you never forgive,'' he said, ``you may never find any
joy. And your kids, maybe they will have no joy also.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosario and Trudy have a daugh ter and a son. The girl was 10
when her mom died. The boy only 6.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario said he hasn't spoken to his daughter about Sansing or
his punishment. He learned recently, though, that she had written a
letter to the sentencing judge, asking that Sansing's life be
spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mother would be proud,'' he told me, his voice rising with
an unexpected but easily identified emotion _ joy. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8978 or at ed.monti
 &UR; ni &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
