<HEADLINE>
WINNING IS NO CURE-ALL IN DALLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They entered the weekend trailing the Coyotes by a single point
in the Pacific Division, but trouble is brewing in ``Big D.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Dallas Stars Coach  &UR; Ken Hitchcock is in danger of
losing control of the players, if he hasn't already, and that one
of them confessed he wanted to take a swing at him during a recent
game.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them apparently said they don't think Hitchcock is the
coach who can take them to the next level and privately have
complained to General Manager  &UR; Bob Gainey. Their biggest gripe is
that Hitchcock has been getting outcoached and seems out of touch
when it comes to match-ups during the flow of the game. That's
debateable, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to blow up pretty soon down there if they're not
careful,'' said a source familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock is a good guy, and if a handful of renegades try to
run him out of town, it would be a mistake. But something has to
change if the problems are as bad as insiders claim.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Hitchcock to duck and cover, though. He has slammed
him team publicly more than once this season and he won't be afraid
to trash a player or two to send a message. &QL; 
Crashing by design &QL; 
The ``National Post,'' Canada's new national newspaper, recently
brought together a five-member panel of experts from the fashion
world and had them rate the best and worst looking sweaters in the
NHL. The standard was based on ``chicness.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, Philadelphia and Los Angeles' new purplish crown logo
sweater drew the top ratings. The worst were the Mighty Ducks, the
San Jose Sharks and your Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the panelists said of the Coyotes sweater: ``It looks
like a Power Rangers shirt. Far too cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina Hurricanes didn't get good reviews either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in a hurricane before and I prefer the hurricane, to
tell you the truth,''  &UR; Suzanne Boyd, editor in chief of ``Flare''
magazine, said of Carolina's whirlish, red, black and white logo.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, consumers in North America spent $1.5 billion on
NHL-licensed merchandise this past year. That's up $150 million
from the previous year. The Coyotes, by the way, had the ninth-best
selling sweater in the league. Detroit was first. &QL; 
Who's No. 1? &QL; 
When a backup goalie is hot and gets a chance to start a few games
in a row, it can be tough for a coach to put him back on the bench.
Just ask  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld of the Coyotes, although his two goalies _
 &UR; Nikolai &UR; Khabibulin and  &UR; Jimmy Waite _ have been so hot that it
really doesn't matter who plays.
</P>
<P>
   That being said, it still can be tough on a backup. Just the
name itself implies some sort of inferiority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never put a lot of stock into No. 1 and No. 2. You're the
No. 1 guy the night you play and that's it,'' Florida goalie  &UR; Kirk
 &UR; McLean said. ``When I'm not playing, I'm definitely the No. 2 guy
because I'm not starting. But the next night, I might be the No. 1
guy again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole No. 1 and No. 2 thing gets blown out of proportion.
It always has and it's unfair. It's a tough enough job being a
goaltender, but when you get labeled as the No. 2 guy, it's an
awful feeling. You feel like you're not part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Panthers were winning like the Coyotes, McLean might feel
a little better. &QL; 
Andrei the Giant &QL; 
One of the reasons the Edmonton Oilers are flying high _ despite
the loss of center  &UR; Doug Weight to a knee injury _ is because of
the rejuvenated play of  &UR; Andrei Kovalenko.
</P>
<P>
   He has nine goals in 20 games, including a game-winner Friday
over Calgary. This is after scoring only six goals in 57 games last
season, a year in which he was a multiple healthy scratch and came
dangerously close to being an ex-Oiler.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, he scored 32 goals and we called him `The
Tank,' '' Edmonton Coach  &UR; Kevin Low said. ``Last year, he was `The
Baby Carriage.' '' &QL; 
Pouting Coyote dealt &QL; 
Left wing  &UR; Andrei Vasilyev, whom the Coyotes assigned to Las Vegas
of the International Hockey League during training camp, was traded
by the Thunder last week to the Grand Rapids Griffins for future
considerations. The Coyotes approved the move, which might be the
best thing for the struggling 26-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   He had three goals and six assists in 15 games for Las Vegas and
hadn't been happy since Day 1 there. He felt the Coyotes didn't
give him an honest look in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very, very disappointed,'' Thunder Coach  &UR; Bob Bourne
told the ``Las Vegas-Review Journal.'' ``I'll never forget that
first practice I saw him skate for us. He did everything at
half-speed. He just didn't care. It took him a few games to get
over that and, in fact, I think he never got over it.'' &QL; 
The first to fall? &QL; 
It's getting to that point in the season when owners and general
managers of sub-.500 teams usually start huddling to discuss the
fate of their head coaches. Surprisingly, no bench boss has gotten
the boot yet in the coach killing-happy NHL, although a couple
firings could be right around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not,  &UR; Paul Maurice's job might be on the line,
even though he has the Carolina Hurricanes in first place in the
Southeast Division. The 'Canes, however, had dropped three straight
entering the weekend and six of their past eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always pressure on a coach when a team is going
through a slump,'' Carolina GM  &UR; Jim Rutherford said. ``People tend
to look around and speculate. December is a crucial month for the
whole team, not just the coach. It's time for us to start making a
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Said an upbeat Maurice: ``Everybody should have to live with a
noose a little bit. I think it brings out the best in people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches on the hot seat include Chicago's  &UR; Dirk Graham and
the Sutter brothers, San Jose's  &UR; Darryl and Calgary's  &UR; Brian. &QL; 
Loose pucks
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix artist Todd McFarlane, creator of the Spawn comic book,
is a minority owner in the Edmonton Oilers and has shown some of
the players sketches he did for a potential third jersey the team
can wear.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, the players loved it. General Manager Glen Sather
didn't sound overjoyed. ``I'd like to see it first,'' he sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   Kaj Linna, a 27-year-old defenseman in the expansion Nashville
Predators organization, announced his retirement after suffering
his third concussion, the latest of which led to bleeding in his
brain. ``It's very disappointing,'' Nashville Coach Barry Trotz
said. ``He's someone who we felt could play for us at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot? Paul Kariya of the Mighty Ducks is on an 11-game
scoring streak, during which he has seven goals and nine assists.
He's on pace to finish with a 113-point season.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not? Carolina center Ron Francis had only four goals and
four assists through 22 games and was a minus-7. Former teammate
Jaromir Jagr of Pittsburgh, meanwhile, had no goals in eight games
entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   What's this? Brett Hull backing off a controversial comment?
That's right. The newest member of the Dallas Stars said the media
got it all wrong a couple weeks ago when it was reported Hull was
upset about the lack of ice time he was receiving from Coach Ken
Hitchcock. ``I didn't (complain) and moan about ice time,'' Hull
said. ``I've played more this year than I did in my last two years
in St. Louis. I'm having the time of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rumors are rampant that Colorado's Claude Lemieux will be
dealt before the trading deadline in March. An unrestricted free
agent, he would make the perfect pickup for a team wanting to
strengthen itself for a run in the postseason. Are you listening,
Coyotes? ``I don't worry about that,'' said Lemieux, who always
seems to turn it up about a dozen notches in the playoffs. ``If it
happens, it happens. I just take it day by day.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek on ending his four-game shutout
streak against the Rangers last week during a 4-2 win: ``I'm kind
of glad it's over. Now I can just forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Defenseman Eric Weinrich, recently traded from the Blackhawks
to the Canadiens in a six-player deal, comparing his minus-13
rating in the fall in Chicago to April at Augusta National: ``It
looked like I was going for the green jacket.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
