<HEADLINE>
BRAVES ADD OFFENSIVE BEEF, STILL HUNGRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Atlanta Braves, fresh off their sixth non-World
Series championship season in seven years, truly seem to have
bought into the idea that they need more offense in order to win a
second World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing they were going to lose out on  &UR; Brian Jordan last week,
Atlanta General Manager  &UR; John Schuerholz bumped the Braves offer
from four to five years, matching what Baltimore agreed to offer
Jordan and essentially securing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who have one of the best pitching rotations in the
game, bowed out of the National League Championship Series for the
second consecutive time when they lost to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a few innings here and there, Atlanta's
offense did not show up in the best-of-seven series, which led to
the Padres advancing to their first World Series since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves took criticism from many corners, including from
within their own clubhouse, for placing too much of an emphasis on
pitching. This time, Schuerholz seems to be listening.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta added Jordan, who should bat fifth behind  &UR; Chipper Jones
and &UR; 
 &UR; Andres Galarraga, giving the Braves a much better one-two-three
punch in the middle of the lineup than they've had in years.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Jordan on board at a hefty $40 million salary over
five years, and second baseman  &UR; Bret Boone acquired from
Cincinnati, the Braves insist they are not through retooling the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz would love to add a bona fide leadoff hitter. One
player who might be dangled as trade bait is left fielder  &UR; Ryan
Klesko, who has not seemed to improve through the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't necessarily mean we're at the end of anything
that we're doing,'' Schuerholz said. ``We'll continue to look at
things that might help us.'' &QL; 
Close call &QL; 
Unable to sleep at 1 a.m. (Eastern time) Tuesday night/Wednesday
morning,  &UR; Bernie Williams telephoned New York Yankees General
Manager &UR; Brian Cashman, who was staying at the same Tampa hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had turned down a five-year, $60 million offer
just days earlier, wanted to know if there was any way the club
would be willing to increase its offer. Cashman assured him there
was no way.
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, Williams asked if Yankees boss  &UR; George
Steinbrenner might be willing to be a bit flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Having been told no, Williams hung up and eventually fell
asleep, albeit discouraged and frustrated, believing his brilliant
Yankees career was truly over. After Williams woke up, he even told
a friend he believed he would sign with Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, at day's end Wednesday, Steinbrenner
capitulated and offered Williams a seven-year deal for $87.5
million, which brings the pair's tumultuous relationship full
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it, Williams came perilously close to moving north to
Boston. &QL; 
Everywhere an All-Star &QL; 
Talk about star-studded: The addition of  &UR; Roberto Alomar to
Cleveland's everyday lineup means the Indians now have All-Stars at
every position.
</P>
<P>
   Having been selected nine times for the midsummer classic,
Alomar leads the Indians' All-Star parade. Next is catcher and
brother  &UR; Sandy
 &UR; Alomar (six), center fielder  &UR; Kenny Lofton (five), third baseman
 &UR; Travis
 &UR; Fryman (four), left fielder  &UR; David Justice (three), first baseman
 &UR; Jim
 &UR; Thome and right fielder  &UR; Manny Ramirez (two apiece) and shortstop
 &UR; Omar
 &UR; Vizquel (one). &QL; 
Strained relationship &QL; 
Reliever  &UR; Jeff Brantley, recently traded from St. Louis to
Philadelphia, didn't leave the Gateway City without taking a few
jabs at Cardinals Manager  &UR; Tony La Russa and pitching coach  &UR; Dave
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I'm happy to be away from Tony La Russa, but
I'm happy to be away from the situation,'' Brantley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My relationship with Duncan was absolutely terrible. Whether
it was my fault or his fault, I don't know. I had a long talk with
Duncan on the last day of the year, and that was the only time
anybody said anything to me the last month and a half. I said, `Why
did you guys not pitch me for the last two months?' He said, `We
didn't purposely not pitch you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, generally considered the best pitching coach in the
majors, responded, ``All I can say is that it was not an ideal
working relationship. It wasn't because I didn't try to make it
work. The circumstances Jeff pitched under were very difficult for
him. The failures he had were very difficult for him to accept. And
naturally, when you have a year like that, you're not going to be
happy with a lot of things.'' &QL; 
A family affair &QL; 
The Boone family became the fourth to have at least four members
hit home runs in the major leagues last August when  &UR; Aaron Boone
slammed a shot off  &UR; Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron joined brother  &UR; Bret, dad  &UR; Bob and grandfather  &UR; Ray as
Boones who have gone deep in a big league game. The other families
with four home run hitters are the  &UR; Alous ( &UR; Felipe,  &UR; Matty,  &UR; Jesus
and  &UR; Moises); the
 &UR; Delahantys ( &UR; Ed,  &UR; Frank,  &UR; Jim and  &UR; Joe) and the  &UR; O'Neills ( &UR; Jack,
 &UR; Jim,  &UR; Steve and  &UR; Mike). &QL; 
On his way &QL; 
Store the name of  &UR; Mike Zywica away: It should come up again soon.
The Texas Rangers outfield prospect became the seventh batting
champion from the Arizona Fall League.
</P>
<P>
   The previous six winners _  &UR; Steve Pegues,  &UR; Scott Pose,  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Grudzielanek,  &UR; Robin Jennings,  &UR; Kevin Orie and  &UR; Brad Fullmer _ all
made it to the majors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Wonder whether he knows something the rest of us don't: New Houston
third baseman  &UR; Ken Caminiti will not wear his customary No. 21 next
season. He's making it available in case Houston trades for another
No. 21,  &UR; Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Omar Vizquel sends his thanks: Cleveland, which just signed
 &UR; Roberto Alomar, has used 15 second basemen since trading  &UR; Carlos
 &UR; Baerga during the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback:  &UR; Dan Schatzeder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Imagine if Roberto Clemente or Willie Stargell had
 &UR; played in this era: Pittsburgh's four-year, $16 million offer to
 &UR; B.J.
 &UR; Surhoff is the largest in franchise history. The Pirates would like
to play Surhoff at third base, a position he has manned for five
innings in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trivial nonsense: The Cincinnati Reds, the oldest club in the
major leagues, have not had a Cy Young Award winner. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
San Diego, intent on keeping starter  &UR; Kevin Brown, increased its
offer to the premier free agent pitcher from four years and $44
million to five years and $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs pitcher  &UR; Kerry Wood, National League Rookie of the
Year, was given a clean bill of health on his previously sore right
elbow last week. Wood is expected to start spring training on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles General Manager  &UR; Kevin Malone has switched his
stance, declaring that only one Dodger is off limits in a trade.
Starting pitcher  &UR; Chan Ho Park, who won 15 games and struck out 191
while holding opponents to a .244 average, is the man Malone will
not trade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jorge Fabregas, the first Diamondbacks catcher, will have
$500,000 of his $1.85 million salary paid by the New York Mets, who
traded him last week to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs have offered unspecified contracts to outfielder  &UR; Henry
Rodriguez, third baseman  &UR; Gary Gaetti and pitcher  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Clark. It is unclear whether the club will offer salary arbitration
to them by Dec. 7. If not, none can sign back with the Cubs before
May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Remember  &UR; Josh Booty, the high school phenom from Louisiana who
took Florida's then-record $1.6 million signing bonus instead of
playing quarterback at Louisiana State? The Marlins took him off
the 40-man roster last week. Worse yet, none of the other 29 clubs
claimed him. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
 &UR; Robin Ventura seems intent on getting a five-year, $40 million
contract. Seattle has talked with him and he may be willing to take
a one-year offer and re-enter free agency next year. The primary
suitors for Ventura are Boston, St. Louis and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore is offering free agent first baseman
 &UR; Rafael Palmeiro a four-year contract in the $32 million range.
Palmeiro, eyeing deals signed by  &UR; Mo Vaughn and  &UR; Bernie Williams,
is entrenched, wanting at least a five-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Do not expect embattled reliever  &UR; Bobby Ayala back with Seattle
for a sixth season. Manager  &UR; Lou Piniella all but ruled out Ayala's
return recently with this statement: `Bobby's career would benefit
from a change of scenery. He's pitched his last game for us, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis, Toronto and the Chicago White Sox are considering
signing free agent catcher  &UR; Terry Steinbach. If Steinbach, who
played for years under  &UR; Tony La Russa, joins the Cardinals, it will
be strictly as backup to  &UR; Eli Marrero.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Kansas City closer  &UR; Jeff Montgomery is in a sticky
situation. Soon to be 37, does he remain with the Royals and notch
another eight saves to reach the exclusive 300-save level or take
an offer from another club to become a set-up man and have a shot
at a World Series?
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays have been asking what other clubs are willing to
give up in exchange for  &UR; Jose Cruz Jr., a onetime top prospect
whose star is mysteriously fading. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
