<HEADLINE>
WAITING GAME BEGINS FOR UA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - Some players clenched them between their teeth.
Others held them aloft. They were flamenco dancers in shoulder
pads.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Athletic Director Jim Livengood had the symbol of one
attached to the lapel of his coat.
</P>
<P>
   Roses, roses everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But were they just a bouquet for a rosy season or symbolic of a
bowl to come?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can be certain.
</P>
<P>
   There are mounting reports that Arizona, 11-1 for the first time
ever, will get a Rose Bowl bid if UCLA beats Miami convincingly
enough Saturday to stay ranked among the Bowl Championship Series'
first two teams. If UCLA falls to No. 3 or further in the BCS, it
is headed to the Rose by virtue of its victory over Arizona on Oct.
10.
</P>
<P>
   If it stays at No. 2, the Rose is open to Arizona, because UCLA
would be headed to the Fiesta Bowl's championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Notre Dame lurked as an obstacle Friday night after
Arizona's 50-42 victory over Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish played the University of Southern California Saturday
night at Los Angeles. A USC victory presumably would have
eliminated the Notre Dame possibility. Or, in Arizona's case, the
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the news reports. The Wildcats are always suspicious of
Notre Dame's influence.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Notre Dame's national following was a key reason that
ABC decided to televise the Irish victory over ASU at Sun Devil
Stadium on Oct. 10 instead of UCLA's victory at Arizona Stadium.
ABC will televise the Rose.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the suspicions are built on Arizona's history of never
having been to the Rose. The Wildcats are the only Pacific-10
Conference team without a postseason trip to Pasadena in their
record book.
</P>
<P>
   A rose is a rose is elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Bowl Committee members at Arizona Stadium Friday night were
impressed with the Wildcats, who probably are headed to the Holiday
Bowl if UCLA drops in the BCS ratings or Notre Dame gets the nod.
But they weren't making any commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Arizona would be a great representative,'' Rose Bowl
Committee member Ron Okum said. ``We would be excited to have them.
But there aren't guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is left with the speculation. The Wildcats have to hope
it is accurate. There are a couple of theories:
</P>
<P>
   There's talk that the Rose Bowl will honor its historical tie to
the Pacific-10 Conference. If it didn't, the Rose would anger
schools that have been longtime partners.
</P>
<P>
   There's further speculation that Arizona's rise in the polls
will make the Wildcats difficult to snub. They figure to jump a
spot, from No. 7 to No. 6, because of Texas' victory over Texas
A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   For Arizona, empty seats at home are a continuing negative. Not
even the annual feud with ASU filled Arizona Stadium. The crowd was
announced at 57,953. It was the smallest Arizona Stadium crowd for
an ASU game since 1990, when the game drew 57,112. In 1992, the
number was 58,095. In 1994, it was 58,810. In 1996, it was 59,920.
</P>
<P>
   The slight decline in crowds is tough to evaluate as a potential
factor in Arizona's chances at the Rose. It, too, is a subject for
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's game at Miami is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we have to be UCLA fans,'' said Arizona quarterback
Keith Smith, who sounded as if he would prefer a rematch with the
Bruins to wearing their colors.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins figure to be favored over Miami. They were able to
rest and heal some bruises over the last seven days, a bye week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rose Bowl needs to look at us,'' Smith said. ``I think we
showed some weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sugar Bowl, one of four in the BCS' mix, also had
representatives in Tucson Friday night. But Arizona's chances at
reaching the Sugar appear very unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Coach Dick Tomey believes the Sugar, in addition to the
Orange, will probably opt for regional favorites such as Florida or
Florida State. Notre Dame also has been mentioned as a possibility.
Of course, the Irish probably had to beat USC to stay eligible for
the BCS at No. 12 or above. The Irish were eighth last week.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the Wildcats are conceding nothing if they get
the chance to play an established national power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved that we're one of the best teams in the country,''
Arizona offensive guard lineman Yusuf Scott said. ``We hope the
bowl committees see that and give us one of the best bowl games in
the country.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
