<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS SEE PROMISE FOR '99 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Minutes after his team's defeat, Arizona State
safety Mitchell Freedman waited patiently for Trung Canidate to
finish media interviews on the Arizona Stadium field.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman, standing on the two bad knees on which he played much
of the season, wanted to congratulate the Arizona tailback and
Central High School graduate for his 288-yard, three-touchdown
effort.
</P>
<P>
   It was a defining moment. For much of the season, the battered
Sun Devils have watched teams with better health, and in some cases
better talent, steal the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to think about now, but this team's going to be in
good shape for next season,'' senior linebacker Joe Cesta said. ``A
lot of the young guys got experience this year, and that's going to
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 50-42 loss Friday to the Wildcats that knocked ASU out
of bowl contention, the Sun Devils remain upbeat. The game was
indicative of their 5-6 season: plenty of promise but not enough to
close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the story of our season,'' linebacker Adam Archuleta
said. ``Both teams had momentum, but we came up short in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are optimistic because they feel the game gave a
glimpse into their future. The most encouraging sign: The old Ryan
Kealy is back.
</P>
<P>
   He completed 33 of 56 passes for 511 yards, four touchdowns and
two interceptions. In his past three games, he has put up these
numbers: 64 for 103 for 947 yards, nine touchdowns and two
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   He appears to be playing with more confidence and seems more
demanding of himself and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's game, he was unimpressed that his passing yards
were the third most in school history, as were his attempts and
completions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of how many yards you've thrown, if you don't win,
it doesn't mean (expletive),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy, whom Snyder oftens refers to as a tough quarterback, was
coming off arthroscopic knee surgery 2{ weeks before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty courageous,'' quarterbacks coach John Pettas
said. ``He was able to suck it up and play through the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy's performance came on the heels of Chad Elliott's
dismissal from the team. ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said he made the
decision after it became evident that the redshirt freshman's
interests weren't with the team anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The move will force the Sun Devils to rethink their recruiting
strategy. Home visits with recruits begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's game also confirmed that tailback J.R. Redmond still
hasn't recovered from a severe ankle sprain. Although he gained 74
yards and scored a touchdown, he clearly is not the tailback that
started the season.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond reaffirmed after the game that he intends to return for
his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder expects to fill approximately a third of his next
recruiting class with junior college transfers, and many of those
could be on defense. The Sun Devils gave up 607 yards of total
offense Friday and demonstrated a propensity this season for giving
up big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ASU allowed four touchdowns on plays of more than 45 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defensive struggles, ASU countered with an offense
that hung in until the end. The Sun Devils had a chance to tie the
score in the final seconds, but Kealy and wide receiver Tariq
McDonald couldn't connect in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave everything they had,'' Snyder said. ``You learn a
lot about a team by how they respond when something goes poorly. I
think we iterally responded every single time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Snyder hopes the Sun Devils have the same fire next season
to rebound from a disappointing 1998. &QL; 
Quick hits: &QL; 
Freedman is scheduled to undergo arthroscopic knee surgery Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Cody Price had two tackles for losses, his first of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Other than 52 points by UCLA, the 42 that ASU scored Friday were
the most the Wildcats had allowed this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
