r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CHIEFS-COLLAPSE-A     11-28 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHIEFS-COLLAPSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS HIT WALL IN BIG WAY  
 SEASON FALLS APART FOR MANY REASONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY - The world's sexiest athlete was supposed to have
the Kansas City Chiefs Super-Bowl bound and 11-0.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Grbac was going to make the maniacs from America's
midsection forget Joe Montana and finally exorcise the quarterback
ghosts of Mike Livingston, Jackie Lee, Bill Kenney, Steve Fuller,
Todd Blackledge, Steve DeBerg, Mike Elkins and Matt Blundin.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Donnell Bennett was going to step in for the owner
of Marcus Allen's North Oak Toyota and keep the Chiefs' running
game going.
</P>
<P>
   It has worked out so badly that Grbac, 1-4 as a starter, and
Bennett, demoted for Bam Morris, will be on the bench for today's
game against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be joined there by All-Pro defensive end Derrick Thomas,
who returns today from a one-game suspension but won't start. The
last time the nation saw Thomas, he was called for three
personal-foul penalties in the fourth quarter of a Nov. 6 loss to
Denver on ``Monday'' ``Night Football.'' Twice, he yanked Broncos
tight end Shannon Sharpe's face mask. He also threw a forearm at
quarterback Bubby Brister's head.
</P>
<P>
   Don't put all the blame on Grbac, Bennett and Thomas for the
team's six-game losing streak, the longest in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' said offensive lineman Glenn Parker, an
Arizona product. ``It's confusing. I've never been through this in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Chiefs Coach Marty Schottenheimer, known for playoff
failures and regular-season triumphs. He was 94-49-1 in the regular
season entering this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the 4-7 season ranks in his coaching career,
Schottenheimer said, ``The fact that it's right now, and we're
enduring it or working our way through it, it certainly has to rank
at the top or the bottom, whatever the case may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Where did the Chiefs go wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Their talent was oversold. ``Sporting News'' predicted the
Chiefs would return to the Super Bowl for the first time since
1969. ``Kansas City Star'' columnist Jason Whitlock wrote the team
would finish the regular season 16-0.
</P>
<P>
   He only missed by at least seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, we aren't as good as we thought we were,'' Chiefs
linebacker Donnie Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Chiefs went 13-3 and had home-field advantage in
the AFC playoffs. But they lost at home to Denver, the second time
in three years they had the AFC's best regular-season record but
lost their first playoff game at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people predicted this year we'd go 8-8,'' Parker said of
``Sports Illustrated.'' ``We'd be happy with 8-8.''
</P>
<P>
   They lack chemistry. The additions of defensive linemen Leslie
O'Neal and Chester McGlockton, both of whom have had
well-documented problems on previous teams, didn't mesh with a
locker room that already had controversial figures in wide receiver
Andre ``Bad Moon'' Rison, Simmons and Morris, who has returned from
a suspension for substance-abuse violations.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this season the Chiefs have set team records for
penalties. They enter today's game with an NFL-high 112 penalties
for 953 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Things have gotten so bad in Kansas City, where pro football is
treated almost as a religion, players are worried that the
staunchly loyal fans might turn on them if they fall behind the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   During the 10 years of the Schottenheimer regime, the fans,
nearly 80,000 strong, are known for their ``Tomahawk Chop'' chants
and making the noise level the highest in the NFL, but seldom have
they booed.
</P>
<P>
   They also aren't used to watching the Chiefs lose three
consecutive home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things don't go well early and the performance is not what
the fans expect it to be, the crowd could get on us,'' quarterback
Rich Gannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Radio talk shows are lit up with calls from fans saying that
Schottenheimer has lost control of the team and should be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it. Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt said he's not
thinking of replacing Schottenheimer, whose contract runs through
2001, or General Manager Carl Peterson, who is signed through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very, very capable guys,'' Hunt said. ``Six games does
not change a career. I think they're among the tops, and I
certainly consider them that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be kind of silly to go from when we were 4-1, when we
had tied the best start in team history, you would say, `Boy,
that's pretty good.' So six weeks later, you can't say that undoes
10 or 15 years of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitlock, the most powerful media voice in Kansas City, blames
Schottenheimer for the franchise's demise but hasn't spared
assistant coaches from criticism. He refers to offensive
coordinator Jimmy Raye as ``Dis-A-Raye.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not ``Dis-A-Raye's'' fault that Grbac suffered a separated
right shoulder in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Grbac, meanwhile, never boasted of his sex appeal. ``People''
magazine gave him that title.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, a fifth-year pro, was supposed to be chairman of the
running back by committee. But he didn't tell the team to bypass
signing free agents Robert Smith, Natrone Means or Raymont Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The running game is 24th in the league, four spots behind the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had a meltdown against the Broncos, but he wasn't alone.
Linebacker Wayne Simmons was fined $7,500 by the NFL for slamming
Brister to the ground with unnecessary force. A day later, he was
released.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Schottenheimer cried in the locker room, said he
was embarrassed and humiliated and apologized to the community.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs fullback Tony Richardson told ``USA Today,'' ``I've been
here four years, and this is the first time I've ever felt like
just crawling out of this locker room.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-98 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
