<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-28 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-PLUMMER-AZR     11-28 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-PLUMMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER BECOMES THE TALK OF THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY - The crowd at Arrowhead Stadium might have risen
and cheered him as Jake Plummer ran onto the field this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It no doubt would have been an emotional afternoon for him,
starting for the Kansas City Chiefs against the team that leases
the stadium where Plummer played in college.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs wanted Plummer. And he felt very much at home with
their coaching staff, whom he got to know when they coached his
team in the Senior Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ```Leading up to the draft,'' Plummer said last week, ``I
thought they would be the team I'd go to. They were definitely one
of the teams I wouldn't have minded going to play for.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Chiefs had a change in plans. They signed
unrestricted free-agent quarterback Elvis Grbac for the 1997
season. They already had Rich Gannon, who has emerged as their
starter.
</P>
<P>
   So the Chiefs became another team that really liked Plummer but
didn't pull the trigger in the 1997 draft. San Francisco is
another.
</P>
<P>
   And the rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer likely will get a rather frosty reception when he runs
onto the field this afternoon as the starting quarterback for the
6-5 Cardinals, who have won three of four and are in the middle of
the playoff race, to face the 4-7 Chiefs, who have lost their past
six and surprisingly aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has a quarterback controversy. The players seem more
comfortable with Gannon. The coaches like Grbac. Gannon is back in
the lineup today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cardinals, who jumped at the chance to draft
Plummer in the second round in 1997, have no quarterback
controversy, although it took a turnaround by Plummer in the past
four games to head one off.
</P>
<P>
   He was struggling early while getting to know new offensive
coordinator Marc Trestman and his offense. Plummer made bad reads,
threw interceptions, took sacks. Worse, the trademark qualities
that made all those coaches salivate over Plummer before the draft
disappeared. He was lost, and many fans believed the Cardinals
might be better served by benching Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Since halftime of the Nov. 1 game at Detroit, though, both
Plummer and the offense have thrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having put this offense in at Detroit last year, I'd gone
through the same process,'' Trestman said. ``We were very slow to
start, but as the season went on, it kicked in, and we got better.
At San Francisco, we were notoriously slow starters, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the difference has been Jake's familiarity with the
offense, being more relaxed, more sure of himself on the field.
That has enabled all his intangibles to come out more.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came during the bye week. The Cardinals got
injured left guard Chris Dishman back. That helped the running
game. The threat of the run enabled the line to give Plummer better
protection. Plummer has made the most of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake has just been Jake,'' said offensive tackle Lomas Brown,
one of the team's co-captains. ``He's been making plays, doing
things to get us over the hump, doing what it has taken for us to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people blamed him for our slow start. But you have to
realize that he was in another new offense, and there was a lot of
pressure that was put on him _ everything from building a stadium
and saving the NFL for an entire city to taking us to the playoffs.
That's a lot on anybody, especially a young guy like Jake.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown gives Plummer credit for not making excuses along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now things are starting to jell,'' Brown said. ``He's looking
more and more like the quarterback everyone wanted him to be, and
we're looking more and more like the team we thought we were going
to be at the beginning of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer threw a club-record 15 successive pass completions in a
comeback win over Washington three games ago. The next week, his
465 passing yards nearly pulled the Cardinals out of a 28-0 hole in
a 35-28 loss to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Plummer directed the Cardinals to a 31-0 first-half
lead and a win over the Redskins in a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   In the month since the bye, the Cardinals have taken the league
lead in red-zone scoring, validating both Plummer and an offensive
line that many believed was among the league's worst.
</P>
<P>
   Trestman was confident enough in the group to add a no-huddle
wrinkle to the repertoire. Plummer took the Cardinals on touchdown
drives in both series that it was used.
</P>
<P>
   Now, people around the league are sitting up and taking notice,
not of the defense that is loaded with first-round draft picks and
was drawing the early-season raves, but of Plummer and his
production with the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to be right in foreshadowing or whatever,'' Redskins
Coach Norv Turner said. ``But you knew Jake was going to come out
of it. Young players go through some peaks and valleys. I would
prefer for him to wait another week until after we played him. He's
a heck of a football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a talented group of football players with him, too. The
receivers, the runners, the quarterback, the offensive line played
extremely well in our game, played well against Dallas. So you knew
the ability was there. You just wait for them to come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they've added the no-huddle. It's a great change-up.
Obviously, it does fit Arizona's personnel because they can spread
you out and throw the ball around.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo, the Cowboys' defensive coordinator, was the first to
be victimized by Plummer in the no-huddle. Campo breathed a sigh of
relief after Plummer shredded Campo's secondary in the comeback
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're better because their quarterback is better,'' Campo
said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders came away describing Plummer as
``a special quarterback'' who has many traits that Hall of Famer
Fran Tarkenton had.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins cornerback Darrell Green is equally impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my own guys on the sideline when we were playing them,
`This young guy is just incredible. He is just such a competitor,'
'' Green said. ``I have always been a player who appreciates my
opponent. I'm going to fight as hard as I can to beat him, but I
enjoy the competition. And I respect great competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they used to say, `Darrell Green is fast.' Well, OK,
I am, but there's more to my game than that. They say Jake is a
scrambler, but it's not just scrambling. You have to have a head on
your shoulders to understand what's happening around you when
you're scrambling. Not many can do that. This kid has a knack for
scrambling and keeping the rest of his team in the game. But he is
more than just a scrambler, he is a complete ball player. And he's
only a kid. I think the future looks good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans believe Plummer is better on the move, but his
long-term future is dependent upon becoming an efficient pocket
passer. That doesn't have to be at the expense of his innate
abilities, according to Trestman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake is a very diligent guy,'' Trestman said. ``He listens to
everything you say. Yet sometimes the best coaching is not
coaching. There is a chemistry involved there. I don't think any of
us want to see him as a guy who plays his career just running
around not knowing what the heck is going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of an ongoing process and we're in such early stages
in the development. I know the public perspective and perception is
that we ought to have the all-encompassing quarterback here. Right
at this moment that's not fair to Jake. He'll still go through his
days where he is not going to look like the guy he has in the last
three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of it, Trestman doesn't want to place a limit
on how good Plummer can be, or how quickly he can get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations are that he plays very well on a weekly
basis,'' Trestman said. ``We also have to be realistic. He has been
able to develop over the last few weeks. He's starting to
conceptualize. He knows where he is protected. He knows where he is
not. He knows where people are on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that has enabled him to go back and bring out some of
the qualities that the people who have watched him play over the
years down here know that he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the first to know it was Schottenheimer, the Chiefs'
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake had a tremendous air about him, a confidence about him,''
Schottenheimer said. ``I had him rated quite high. Mechanically we
thought he was very talented. The comparisons that were frequently
drawn were to (Joe) Montana _ the quickness of Jake's setup and the
quickness of his delivery, not great arm strength but extremely
accurate, and the anticipation that I think is so important in
quarterback play _ those were the qualities that we saw in him.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that Plummer has played nearly two seasons in the
league?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were right on,'' Schottenheimer said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
