<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS CAN'T HESITATE TO PAY BEST PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All along, the Cardinals' plan for making the playoffs this
season has been pretty simple.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to come out of November around the .500 mark,
knowing they would play three of their final four games at home
against weaker competition.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens today in Kansas City, the plan has
worked almost to perfection for the Cardinals, who are 6-5 and in
line for the third wild card spot in the NFC playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But as young as the Cardinals are, the team shouldn't be a
one-year wonder, even though next year's schedule won't be loaded
with fifth-place weaklings.
</P>
<P>
   They have a second-year quarterback in  &UR; Jake Plummer, whom one
national publication described this week as the best player to come
into the league at that position since  &UR; Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   They have the NFL's youngest defense, and it should only get
better, especially once the right cornerback and free safety spots
are stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's draft should pay big dividends because the Cards
have two first-round picks (their own and San Diego's) and could
have several compensatory picks after losing  &UR; Michael Bankston,
Eric Hill,
 &UR; Kevin Williams, Brent Alexander and  &UR; Jeff Feagles through free
agency during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   But some dark clouds are hanging over them because of the lack
of foresight by the front office.
</P>
<P>
   Outside linebacker  &UR; Jamir Miller should have been signed to an
extension last spring. It would have cost the team about $4 million
a year. Now, it will cost $5 million to $5.5 million a year, plus a
signing bonus as high as $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals won't lose Miller. They will slap the franchise
tag on him if they don't re-sign him before mid-February. If he's
still unsigned when free agency begins, things could get messy.
Miller will hold out, as will middle linebacker  &UR; Ronald McKinnon, a
restricted free agent, if they don't get fair-market deals.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon's contract already should have been done. The same goes
for wide receiver  &UR; Rob Moore, who will be in big demand if he's
still available as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 players have signed extensions or renegotiated
deals since the beginning of the season. Unfortunately, the
Cardinals haven't participated in the signing frenzy. It's not for
a lack of trying. They just don't get serious until a gun is
pointed at their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few other suggestions to make the team a consistent
winner:
</P>
<P>
   Re-sign left offensive tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown as protection until a
young tackle is groomed to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Spend two of your first three draft picks on offensive linemen.
Use the other on a speedy wide receiver or a cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Go after a defensive back in free agency and make sure you get
him. Finishing runner-up for  &UR; Brock Marion and  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Carrier the past two years won't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be chintzy in re-signing defensive tackle  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Smith. He's the most underpaid starter on the team and deserves
more than just the tender. Sure, you hold his exclusive rights, but
that doesn't mean he should be deprived of a fair deal.
</P>
<P>
   Find a blocking fullback in the draft. How many years are you
going to vow to get one?
</P>
<P>
   Get all of this wrapped up by mid-April, just in time for a vote
on a new stadium. &QL; 
Aiming for perfection &QL; 
Finally, a member of the Denver Broncos has acknowledged he is
thinking about an unbeaten season.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker  &UR; Glenn Cadrez said it is on his mind as the
Broncos try to improve their record to 12-0 tonight at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to fool anybody,'' Cadrez said. ``I'm looking at
undefeated, and I want it. I want it bad. I want this roster in
Canton (Ohio, the site of the Pro Football Hall of Fame) as the
only 19-0 undefeated team. There's no avoiding it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I sit here and blow smoke up your nose and say,
`Oh, we're not thinking about it'? Of course, we're thinking about
it. I can't see anybody on this team not thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing something that is beyond expectation right now.
We've won 11 games. We have a perfect record. What's next? You're
always looking for something. We won the Super Bowl last year. That
was great, but what's our next step? We want greatness. Everyone on
the team wants that.'' &QL; 
Strange homecoming &QL; 
Fourteen years ago, Colts owner  &UR; Jimmy Irsay's father,  &UR; Robert,
ordered moving vans to sneak out of Baltimore in the middle of the
night and move the franchise to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Irsay doesn't know whether he should return to Baltimore
in disguise for today's game between the Colts and the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' Irsay said. `` &UR; Paul
McCartney one time attended a Rolling Stones concert, third row
center in 1966, dressed as a 90-year-old man. Maybe he'll lend me
his outfit.''
</P>
<P>
   The game isn't big to most of the players on the two teams. But
it's huge to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be rooting for the Ravens as much as we're
rooting against the Colts,'' said one fan,  &UR; David Houseknecht. ``I
think the (Ravens) band should play the Colts song, just for the
hell of it. We just hope they (Colts) get their butts kicked. You
never want them to win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   One Ravens player,  &UR; Larry Webster, a native of Elkton, Md.,
knows how important today's game is to Baltimore fans. His
godmother has ordered him to ``kick the Colts' butts.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore football fans watched the Colts not have a winning
season their final six years there. They've seen the Ravens lose
the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People act like it's a tragedy,''  &UR; Art Donovan, a member of
the Colts' 1958 league championship team, said of the team leaving
Baltimore. ``A tragedy is going to a hospital and seeing a sick
kid. Kids with cancer, that's a tragedy. You can always get a lousy
football team back.'' &QL; 
They said it &QL; 
San Francisco wide receiver  &UR; Jerry Rice has been portrayed as
selfish for complaining that he isn't getting the ball enough and
is pondering retirement. The more he talks, the worse it looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Minnesota, and the go-to guy is  &UR; Cris Carter,''
Rice said. ``You look at Dallas, and the go-to guy is  &UR; Michael
Irvin. I don't think I'm still the go-to guy. I feel like this is a
totally different team. It's up to  &UR; Steve ( &UR; Young, quarterback) to
choose who's going to get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Chicago Bears defensive lineman  &UR; Alonzo
 &UR; Spellman wants back in the NFL but refuses to accept medication,
which doctors prescribed last spring, for manic depression. ``I
know everything's all right with 'Zo,'' Spellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Eagles Coach  &UR; Ray Rhodes on being 2-9: ``I just try
to make sure I don't have glass objects and razors and stuff like
that laying around in my house.'' &QL; 
ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; San Diego Chargers: Interim Coach June Jones is a good guy doing a
good job. He's 3-2 since replacing Kevin Gilbride. They are playing
the best defense in the NFL, allowing teams only 255.7 yards per
game. They haven't led the league in defense since 1965, and that
was in the American Football League. They already have 30 sacks
after finishing with 27 last season. If quarterback Craig Whelihan
keeps winning, rookie Ryan Leaf might stay on the bench. They've
even survived a season-ending injury to running back Natrone
Means. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Cincinnati Bengals: Let's see if we have this right. Coach Bruce
Coslet brings in quarterback Neil O'Donnell to replace Jeff Blake.
Then, when O'Donnell struggles, he skips Blake and promotes former
Arizona State quarterback Paul Justin. What's next? The Bengals are
going to use a practice team quarterback if Justin doesn't start
winning. They have too much offensive talent to be 2-9. Don't you
think running back Corey Dillon and wide receivers Carl Pickens and
Darnay Scott could start for many teams? &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
 &UR; New York Giants owner Wellington Mara, on the New England
 &UR; Patriots' move to Hartford, Conn.: ``I don't like to see the league
moving this way, especially moving out of the big cities. Now this
means Los Angeles, Houston and Boston would be without teams.'' &QL; 
ARE BOLTS DOLTS? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Chargers (5-6) are only a game behind the
Cardinals, who own their draft pick. That pick isn't looking so
good right now. Earlier in the year, the Cardinals thought they
might have a top-10 pick. Now, the choice could be in the teens.
It's all Leaf's fault. If he hadn't gone up to Pullman, Wash., and
terrorized the town, he'd still be playing and throwing
interceptions. The Chargers would be losing and the Cardinals would
be celebrating. Now, Jones' success leaves General Manager Bobby
Beathard with two options: Give him the job full time or try to
hire George Seifert. &QL; 
SHORT SHOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe has a new touchdown dance he is
calling the ``Bucking Bronco.'' He describes it this way: ``It's
just like if you were on the back of a bull or a Bronco, and he's
bucking you and you're going back and forth. I don't really expect
to see people in the street doing it, but maybe some of my
teammates will pick it up and try it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven quarterbacks are 35 or older, and seven have been regular
starters _ Seattle's Warren Moon (42), Denver's John Elway (38),
Miami's Dan Marino (37), Buffalo's Doug Flutie (36), San
Francisco's Steve Young (37), the New York Jets' Vinny Testaverde
(36) and Minnesota's Randall Cunningham (35).
</P>
<P>
   Under Coach Bill Cowher, the Steelers are 13-1 at home in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina defensive lineman Rick Terry, a second-round pick of
the Jets in 1997, was asked to describe Jets Coach Bill Parcells in
one word. He paused 12 seconds and then said, ``Dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' Young, on Thanksgiving growing up in Greenwich,
Conn.: ``Some of the best Thanksgiving football ever played was in
my back yard _ no helmets, lots of bloody noses.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 444-8334, or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
