<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN, O'MEARA CASH IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA, Calif. _ Tom Lehman said he can't throw a baseball
and has trouble lifting his right arm above shoulder level, but he
can play golf.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, Greg Norman and Fred Couples found out just how
well he can play during Saturday's first day of the Skins Game at
Rancho La Quinta Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman and O'Meara tied with $150,000 in winnings; Norman and
Couples were shut out.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who said he separated his right shoulder while playing
with his children during the British Open last July, will have the
shoulder operated on Monday morning in Los Angeles. He said he
can't do ``a lot of the little, every-day things'' and his shoulder
hurts even when he gets out of bed in the morning, but golf still
is not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Extended golf, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play good rounds, but not good tournaments,'' said
Lehman, who birdied the par-3 third hole for $75,000 and the par-4
fourth for $25,000. He ended Saturday's round with a two-putt
birdie on the par-5 ninth for another $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who has played in only 23 events this year, has saved
some of his best golf for the Skins Game, which rewards aggressive
play. Counting last year, when he pocketed $300,000, the defending
champion has 15 birdies in his last 27 holes.
</P>
<P>
   He had five more Saturday. O'Meara had two and Couples and
Norman had two and one, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing,'' Couples said. ``I felt like I had some
good opportunities. If you weren't going to get any skins, today
was a good day not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's back-nine skins will be worth $700,000, including
$200,000 on the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's front nine, which was worth $300,000, was a
particularly frustrating day for Norman, who hit two balls in the
water and didn't even finish the par-5 ninth hole, when he dumped
his two-iron second shot into a lake. Norman, who recently returned
to competitive golf after shoulder surgery and teamed with Steve
Elkington to win the Franklin Templeton Shark Shootout two weeks
ago, said his game is rusty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to get back in the groove,'' he said. ``I have to
get the timing and rhythm back... get back in the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to jump back in the saddle.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy for O'Meara, who also found the water with his
second drive of the day, but he had a great equalizer _ his
putting. O'Meara is trying a new prototype putter from Taylor Made
and has shelved his trusty Ping Anser 2 for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very close by, trust me,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara forced a carryover on the second hole when he saved par
from 50 feet, and dropped a 20-footer for birdie on the par-3
eighth hole to win a $150,000 skin, the largest ever on a Saturday
of this competition.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara also was at the center of a minor controversy on the
par-3 sixth hole, when he mistakenly picked up Couples' marker,
which was six inches away from the hole, and conceded the putt.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, just off the green and preparing to chip for a possible
birdie, asked for a ruling and Couples' coin was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I fell asleep,'' O'Meara said. ``I assumed the guys were
going to give him that putt. It was obviously going to change how
Greg was going to play the hole... he wanted to make sure the putt
was good. If not, he could be a little more conservative with his
chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling is an outside agency moved his marker, so it was
put back in its original position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I messed up. It's not the first time I've messed up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
