<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-SAT-SCORE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH ACHIEVER DISSATISFIED WITH PREVIOUS SAT SCORE ACES EXAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN F. SHERRY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A few weeks ago, Calabasas High School senior
Yashih Wu stood in the suburban school's college resource center
and called an automated number to learn the results of her SAT.
</P>
<P>
   Yashih had hoped to improve on her previous high score of 1,480,
but could not believe her ears when the computer told her she had
scored 800 in verbal and 800 in math: a perfect score of 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Burnam, the school's college counselor, watched as Wu
burst into tears and fled her office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid she had gone down,'' Burnam said. ``She couldn't
say anything. She just started to shake.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu, 17, said her reaction was due to shock and fear that it was
a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might have dialed the wrong number or something,''
she said. ``I replayed it and replayed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, Wu still could not say the number aloud and
swore Burnam to secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weeks before she let us tell anybody,'' the counselor
said. ``She really didn't believe the recording. She waited for
paper confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   Other students have achieved perfection in the standardized
Scholastic Assessment Test, which is used by colleges in their
admissions process. But Wu's accomplishment is all the more
impressive when paired with her scores in the subject-specific SAT
II tests in chemistry, advanced math and English writing: 800, 800
and 800.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a true perfectionist,'' Burnam said, ``but she handles
it beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of full disclosure, Wu did score a mere 770 on
the history SAT II test and a 750 in biology. Burnam wonders if the
score sheet Wu sends to universities will give admissions
counselors pause, because every score is marked as the maximum
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like you made a mistake,'' Burnam said.
</P>
<P>
   Wu, a resident of suburban Agoura Hills, credits Burnam and her
teachers with helping her score so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote them thank-you cards after I found out,'' she said.
``(Burnam) was just always very supportive of me. She probably had
more confidence in me than I had in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu said she has no secrets to test-taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy in taking tests is hope for the best and expect
the worst,'' she said. ``Taking practice tests was the biggest help
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu particularly wanted to improve upon her previous verbal
score, so she studied flash cards of vocabulary words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I came across a word I didn't know, I'd write it down
and look it up later,'' she said. ``I crammed a lot the last few
days before the test.''
</P>
<P>
   And for that extra bit of help, Wu prayed to her ancestors
before every test and wore good-luck charms for good measure. An
incentive to do well came from a bet with her friend Steven about
whether either of them would score more than 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to take me out to dinner,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wu's younger sister is jokingly mad at her for setting an
unbeatable family standard, and her grandparents wanted her to make
a bumper sticker touting her perfect scores.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to racking up amazing test scores, Wu also serves as
treasurer of the Associated Student Body, president of the
California Scholarship Federation and as a member of several other
campus clubs. Twice a week, to let off steam, she heads to a local
karate studio and attacks a punching bag with side and roundhouse
kicks. She has been kick-boxing since the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great way to get rid of stress, tension,'' she said.
``My form of relaxation is kind of keeping busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her scores, Wu is not ready to rest on her laurels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I just have to worry about college applications,'' she
said. ``I'm still nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she remains undecided, Wu is applying to nine
universities, including elite private institutions like Harvard,
Northwestern, Princeton and Yale. She is leaning toward a career in
the medical field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grades and test scores aren't that important,'' she said.
``I'm really proud that I do get these scores. It's not an end in
itself. There's more to come.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
