<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CACTUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CACTUS STORY DIED, BUT WOW, WHAT A THORNY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a story about the world's fattest
cactus, a really obese specimen rooted near Picacho Peak.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a reliable tip, momentous journalism plans were set in
motion. The monster would be dubbed El Gordo and crowned the Sumo
of Succulents. The thing would be declared an Arizona landmark.
Roseanne would do a show about her botanical soulmate . . .
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out El Gordo is ``not'' the world's most corpulent
cactus.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it the heaviest, tallest, happiest or ugliest.
</P>
<P>
   Barrel cactuses grow taller and wider in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   So forget about El Gordo. This story is about the whole world of
spiny succulents. It's a compendium of facti about cacti, drawn
from experts and books.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know, for example, that saguaros are not really the
world's tallest cactuses?
</P>
<P>
   Or that John Wayne's tip _ chopping off the top of a barrel
cactus and drinking the juice _ is a recipe for swollen throats and
diarrhea, rather than survival?
</P>
<P>
   Or that the prickly pear, exported to Australia, overwhelmed the
outback, causing an environmental disaster?
</P>
<P>
   We thought not. Because few people really get to know the lowly
cactus, up close and personal.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, you like to take sunset snapshots or drive through
Organ Pipe National Monument during the bloom.
</P>
<P>
   But there aren't many who embrace cactuses, figuratively
speaking, with the affection displayed by Kent Newland, former
president of the Central Arizona Cactus and Succulent Society.
</P>
<P>
   Newland's favorite is known as ``trichocerus,'' and he raises
150 of the little spikers in a Carefree shadehouse. The attraction:
This humble plant produces the most glorious bloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're kind of like hedgehogs on steroids,'' Newland says,
proudly. ``I check on them weekends, except in spring when they
flower. Then I check 'em every day. If you miss the day, then you
miss the year. . . . They're to die for.''
</P>
<P>
   Newland talks to his spiny friends. He takes snapshots. He
nurtures them. ``People almost get fixated,'' he adds. ``It's not
drugs or cigarettes, it's cacti. Beauty is in the eye of the
beholder.'' &QL; 
SCIENCE STUFF
</P>
<P>
   Now, a brief primer.
</P>
<P>
   Cactuses are native only to the Americas, with 1,500 to 2,000
species from Canada to Chile. While most are confined to deserts,
varieties thrive in rain forests and on 14,000-foot alpine slopes.
There are more than 100 varieties in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The tallest tops 80 feet; the shortest is under a silly
centimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe the botanical origins go back 20,000 years,
though evolutionary roots remain a mystery because no fossils have
been found.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks think the cactus is unique because of prickers and
pulp. But researchers say the big difference is sex.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this inscrutable definition offered by Del Weniger,
author of ``Cacti'' ``of the Southwest'':
</P>
<P>
   ``A cactus is always a dicot, and its two seed leaves will
distinguish it at once from all those members of the lily family so
often called cacti, since they are monocots and have one seed
leaf.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Cactus flowers have a weird ovary deep within the
flower, and the stems are loaded with unique bud points which
produce spines and arms.
</P>
<P>
   If you lived in desert sand where the surface temperature may
reach 175 degrees, you'd need an edge. And evolution has provided
cacti with a lot of evolutionary tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Weniger put it this way: ``The key to understanding why the
cactus is such a strange plant is the understanding of its major
problem and how it solves it. This is the water problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Mazier, superintendent of horticulture at the Desert
Botanical Garden in Phoenix, says the pad of a prickly pear is 137
degrees on a hot Arizona afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine yourself standing in the sun 14 hours. Hey, you'd get
hot,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   To cope with that, Mother Nature provided waxy cactus skin to
retain moisture. Spines shade the stem and defend the juicy flesh
from invaders. Pleated stems work like an accordion, contracting in
drought and expanding to store water during rainy seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In dry weather, the barrel cactus may have a moisture content of
just 20 percent. But an adult specimen can drink up to 20 pounds of
rain in a day, and increase its water content to 90 percent after a
monsoon.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider ``crassulacean acid metabolism.''
</P>
<P>
   Books and botanists use that phrase to describe how succulents
retain moisture in summertime. They inhale only at night, when the
air is cool, to reduce evaporation. Then they hold their breath
during the day, sustaining themselves on reserves. &QL; 
NATURAL HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   All of which may be very boring and technical to casual
observers who realize that a cactus is like pornography: We may not
be able to define it, but we know one when we bump into it.
</P>
<P>
   That may have occurred to Chris Columbus after he rowed ashore
at Hispanola and became the first European to encounter nature's
pincushions. And it undoubtedly occurred to subsequent
conquistadors who traipsed through Arizona cholla.
</P>
<P>
   Native Americans were undoubtedly amused. They had foraged on
cactus for centuries. They prepared tea from the flowers, wine from
the fruit. They used dry saguaro ribs for hut walls.
</P>
<P>
   One of the White man's first ethnocentric moves, upon landing in
the New World, was to toss aside Native American plant names in
favor of Greek terms such as ``kaktos'' (thistle) and
``Ellchinocactus xeranthemoides'' (whatever that means).
</P>
<P>
   By any name, they soon became a subject of European delight.
</P>
<P>
   Early explorers, ever on the lookout for treasure, were amazed
to learn that little cochinillo bugs create a royal red dye as they
suck the juice from prickly pears.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Crosswhite, curator at Boyce Thompson Arboretum near
Superior, explained the importance during a recent tour. It seems
red dye was so hard to find in Spain, and so expensive, that only
nobility had magenta clothing. After American Indians showed the
Spaniards the cochinillos, mashed bug juice became a hot item on
the shipping lanes.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1700s, New World expeditions were being launched
just for the study of cactus specimens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest in these strange new plants grew and soon
amounted to a `cactus craze,' '' notes Weniger. ``The extent of the
`craze' is hard for us to comprehend today. By 1800 businesses were
being set up by French, Belgian and German importers to sell cactus
sent by professional collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Cactophilia rivaled the devotion to orchids among wealthy
Europeans. But cactuses are a hardier lot, and prickly plants soon
adorned window ledges of even common folk from England to Japan. &QL; 
CACTUS NUTS
</P>
<P>
   Cactomaniacs struggle to explain the intrigue, but they seem
awed by the idea that God's most forbidding flora produce such
spectacular flowers. And they marvel at the incredible survival
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think, `Cacti? Yuck!' '' Crosswhite says. ``But
once you stop and really look at them _ even without flowers _ they
have a beauty all their own. You have to get to know them
personally. The best thing you can do is get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosswhite calls them ``plants of iron with flowers of silk,''
and wonders why Americans take their native greens for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of cactus research has been done by Europeans. The
Cactus Society of Tokyo boasts 5,000 devotees. The London society
has 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arizona's Cactus Center Club _ one of the nation's
largest groups _ claims just 500 members.
</P>
<P>
   David Eppele, club president, says the cactus is like a prophet
_ without honor in its own land.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to concentrate on the absolute beauty,'' he adds.
``And the toughness. They wrote the book on survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Eppele, director of Arizona Cactus &AMP; Succulent Research Center
in Bisbee, is a self-proclaimed nut about cactuses. He's written
several books on the subject, not to mention an essay describing
his personal mania.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls boyhood days using a cactus spine to catch fish, and
spends his adult life raising succulents and experimenting with
prickly pear as cattle forage.
</P>
<P>
   Eppele views bulldozers as the great Satan to succulents,
scraping away cactus forests to make room for homes and businesses,
oleander and eucalyptus. He is one of many naturalists crying out
for desert plants, condemning the spread of mulberry and lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big misuse of our water,'' he complains. ``It doesn't
say one damned thing about the state of Arizona. We're just going
to have to change our plant pallet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Paul Nabhan, another dedicated cactophile and author,
penned an anthem in honor of his beloved ground-huggers:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us now raise the banner of the Spiney Revolution, one that
gives both cacti and cactus-lovers their due. And let us now praise
famous prickly pears, barrels, hedgehogs . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Reg Manning, late editorial cartoonist for ``The Arizona
Republic,'' became so smitten with desert denizens that he wrote
the book on 'em: ``What Kinda Cactus'' ``Izzat?'' Among Manning's
scientific observations:
</P>
<P>
   ``A jumping cactus cannot jump _ all evidence to the contrary
notwithstanding. It is simply a painful illusion _ the thorn is
quicker than the thigh.'' &QL; 
CACTUS USES
</P>
<P>
   Cactus aficionados like to talk about how useful the plants are.
But let's be honest: As a natural resource, they seem pretty dang
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, prickly pear slime eases the pain of sunburn, and
backpackers use cactus spines as toothpicks. But, since the advent
of Fry's and Bashas', only the prickly pear seems to have real
mercantile value. Though not yet part of the U.S. diet,
``nopalitos'' _ sliced or diced prickly pear pads, minus the spines
_ are a staple in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   David Morris, a Native American instructor at Central Arizona
College, says efforts are under way to revive the prickly pear as
an Indian food source. And Eppele says his experiments suggest that
prickly pear could become an Arizona cash crop one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proving that we can grow that plant in Cochise County and
you could make a business of it,'' Eppele says. ``We could open a
canning factory.''
</P>
<P>
   While desert rats and horticulturalists may get carried away,
even the most effete city dweller admires the bloomin' beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Each spring, botanical gardens set up phone hotlines to update
callers on blooming times. More than 2 million people visited
Saguaro National Monument last year, mostly in March and April.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they bloom,'' Crosswhite notes, ``it's the final,
ultimate, absolute, mind-blowing reward. They're show stoppers.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
