<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX CREDIT HELPS RICH SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHRYN CRENO AND KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free money!
</P>
<P>
   A new tax break is like a winning lottery ticket for some
Arizona schools. Too bad everyone's not a winner, say the critics.
</P>
<P>
   The windfall could easily add up to tens of millions of dollars,
thanks to a law that allows taxpayers to donate up to $200 for
extra-curricular activities and subtract the full amount from their
state income tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's footing the bill for field trips to California for some
kids in north Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A Flagstaff elementary school is offering all-day kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Some students are in free after-school homework clubs in north
central Phoenix's Madison schools.
</P>
<P>
   To educators such as Matt Devlin, principal of Madison Richard
C. Simis School, the money offers ``a wonderful opportunity,''
especially for helping students at risk of failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky's the limit out there for things we can do after
school for kids,'' he said, ``everything from chess clubs to
small-group reading programs.''
</P>
<P>
   But low-income districts are having trouble cashing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not good public policy,'' objected Penny Kotterman,
president of the Arizona Education Association, the state's largest
teachers' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only a stop-gap funding opportunity that will make the
inequities between rich and poor schools even worse. It is
ridiculous that the Legislature isn't providing the dollars it
takes so all schools can provide decent programs in sports, music
and fine arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona ranks near the bottom in state spending per pupil, and
in 1996-97, it spent nearly one-third less than the national
average, according to Arizona Education Association figures.
</P>
<P>
   So eager parents, teachers and administrators have a long
shopping list, ranging from computer clubs to field trips. It
includes items, such as extracurricular sports in middle schools,
that districts could once afford.
</P>
<P>
   And creative folks realize that equipment bought for
after-school use _ software for the math club, for instance _ can
be used during school hours, too.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the credit works: Suppose your state income tax is
$300 for 1998. You donate $200 to a public school for
extracurricular activities. Your tax credit comes right off the
bottom line _ now your tax for the year is $100.
</P>
<P>
   Any individual taxpayer can claim the credit. Here's the pitch:
Why pay money to the state when you can give it to a school?
</P>
<P>
   Some districts have swung into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandler Unified School District and Phoenix Elementary
School District have payroll deduction programs for employees and
any area businesses that want to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Public Schools have raised more than $105,000, with its
program barely rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The district makes it easy, with donation cards and postage-paid
envelopes available at every school, so people can just pop a check
in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Special software lets Mesa issue receipts almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Paradise Valley Unified School District have
donated $150,000 to their tax credit fund so far. Officials of the
34,000-student district in north Phoenix expect that amount to
double next month, when many parents will make end-of-the-year
donations.
</P>
<P>
   The money will help revive sports in Paradise Valley middle
schools, which lost their interscholastic programs to budget cuts
two years ago. Counting on support from the tax credits, the
district has a new ``festival sports'' program for any student who
wants to play.
</P>
<P>
   Many schools, though, have yet to see a dime.
</P>
<P>
   At Silvestre Herrera School in central Phoenix, Principal Evelyn
Sanchez would dearly love a few thousand dollars so more of her
elementary students could play in an after-school music program
with a member of the Phoenix Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 30 or 40 kids interested who don't have the $18 a
month it takes to rent a violin,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   In south Phoenix, Principal Gloria Henderson just wants $1,000
or so for an after-school reading program at her Martin Luther King
School. She's hoping donations will start to trickle in next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Isaac School District in the southwest Valley is still
waiting for donations, too. Superintendent Jose Leyba was amazed to
hear how much money Paradise Valley expects to raise:
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred thousand dollars? What we could do with just
$10,000 _ after-school classes, after-school day care, tutorial
programs. The problem in low-wealth districts like ours is that we
don't have enough staff to free up to even research something like
this. And our PTAs aren't sophisticated enough to get such a
venture going.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so in districts like north central Phoenix's Madison, which
was the first in the Valley to launch a tax-credit donation
campaign last January, with donated help from a parent who is a
political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Simis School already has an after-school ``homework club'' up
and running, funded with about $2,000 in tax-credit donations from
parents. The school has a total of about $11,000 so far, much of
which will be used to send kids to camp early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy parents such as those in Madison realized early on that in
1997 the Legislature had tacked on the so-called ``public school
activity fee'' tax credit to a bill allowing people to subtract up
to $500 in donations to private school tuition scholarship funds.
</P>
<P>
   The private school credit is facing a court challenge, but not
the public school credit.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer hustle on tax credits, few people can beat Mike
Cromer, headmaster of South Beaver Elementary School in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   He was eager to offer all-day kindergarten at the back-to-basics
neighborhood school, but most parents couldn't afford the $125
monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Working his contacts as a lifelong Flagstaff resident, Cromer
used the lure of tax credits to drum up $10,000. Most of the money
will help expand the kindergarten school day _ parents will pay $25
a month _ and the rest will go to music programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature originally estimated that both tax credits would
eat into the general fund $6 million to $8 million a year, said
Georganna Meyer, chief economist at the Department of Revenue. But
she guesses the figure will shoot 10 times higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year it could be lower,'' she added, ``in large part
due to disbelief that it's real.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no overall figures available on how much money has
been raised across Arizona. A flood of money may come in near the
close of 1998. Meyer said most accountants would urge their clients
to wait until December to make donations, reducing the amount of
time they lose use of the money.
</P>
<P>
   The effective deadline for donating money at many schools is
Dec. 18, when they shut down for the holidays. But the Mesa
district, for one, is equipped to accept checks up to Dec. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hogan, executive director of the Arizona Center for Law in
the Public Interest, is troubled that the lion's share of the
credit money will go to well-heeled districts such as Mesa and
Paradise Valley, and not places like the cash-strapped Roosevelt
district. He has already sued Arizona on behalf of Roosevelt once
and won, leading to the state's new school construction finance
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously poorer schools just can't keep up in a program like
this, and I think most people would agree that's just unfair,'' he
said. ``These after-school programs are all programs that people
would support for schools everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan isn't sure what the solution is. But he said the
Legislature should resolve the inequity next session.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of tax-credit money moving through school coffers can
be deceptive. In many cases, parents are ``donating'' the fees
required for extracurricular activities and then getting reimbursed
through the credit.
</P>
<P>
   That can lift a big burden. The Paradise Valley district, for
instance, charges $40 per activity, with a maximum of $120 per
family. And then there are such extras as field trips to California
to learn about ocean life.
</P>
<P>
   The state Auditor General's Office, meanwhile, is watching to
make sure the money ends up where donors intend.
</P>
<P>
   School districts must follow a system that's ``as restrictive as
you could get,'' said Ross Ehrick, manager in the auditor's
accounting services division. ``They're required to spend it for
the purpose it's donated for.''
</P>
<P>
   That means giving contributors pre-numbered receipts describing
the activity for which the money is intended. And districts must
keep detailed records showing the money was used for the school and
the purpose earmarked by the taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent and an accountant, Kathy Bissette is busy these days
explaining such fine points about the tax credit and urging people
to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Bissette, who chairs the budget committee of Paradise Valley's
United Parents Council, hears one objection all the time: It sounds
too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder, she said. ``It's kind of hard to believe.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
