<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SKINS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN SET FOR SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA -- Tom Lehman will undergo surgery on his right
shoulder on Monday morning in Los Angeles, and Greg Norman knows
exactly what the future holds for him.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's surgery, which will repair the A.C. joint in his right
shoulder, will not be as extensive as the procedure Norman had
seven months ago, when he had his left shoulder socket
reconstructed, bone spurs shaved away and muscles tightened. Norman
did say Lehman will benefit in the long run -- both from the
standpoint of his shoulder and state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Tom, `You'll get your life back,' Norman said after
Saturday's first day of the 16th annual Skins Game at Rancho La
Quinta Country Club. ``You don't know what it's like to wake up
Saturday morning in your own bed at home, or spend the weekend with
your kids. You have no mandate on your time ... no regimen to do
something. You control your own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I never missed the game. I did miss the competition
... I missed these guys. Tom will find out the same thing. It will
be a very cleansing thing for him. He will come back with an
unfiltered approach toward life and the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to step away from something and look back at it.
These guys haven't been seven months away from something they've
loved for 20-25 years. It really is a wonderful thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should do it.
</P>
<P>
   Norman also said he is eagerly awaiting the Presidents Cup,
which will be held next month at Royal Melbourne Golf Course in
Melbourne, Australia. He said the move of the tournament away from
the United States couldn't have come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was important to move, said Norman, who tops a
strong international team which also will include the likes of
Steve Elkington, Ernie Els and Nick Price. ``In the last 12 or 15
years, the Ryder Cup has risen to the next level because of the
exposure. For the Presidents Cup to go that route, I think it was
important for it to be moved away from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. has a very, very strong team. We have a very strong
team. I think it will be a very good match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
