<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-HURRICANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANES BEAT ISLES, 3-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Mike Milbury shuffled the Islanders' forward
lines and scratched two ineffective wings Saturday in an effort to
get more production from an offense that has suddenly slumped.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work. The Islanders got a decent performance from
their goaltender and a better-than-average effort from their
defenders, but the slumping forwards failed to cash in on many
chances in a ho-hum 3-1 loss to the Carolina Hurricanes at Nassau
Coliseum. It was the Islanders' second straight defeat and their
fifth in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't score,'' said Milbury, the Islanders' coach
and general manager. ``Early on, we needed a goal and we couldn't
put it in. On not one line did we have enough offense to get
ignited.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders (10-13), who were playing their third game in four
days, were competitive early but disintegrated in the span of 7
minutes 26 seconds in the second period. During that stretch the
Hurricanes' Kevin Dineen, Sami Kapanen and Keith Primeau scored
against Tommy Salo. The Islanders, who got a third-period goal from
Sergei Nemchinov, lacked the offensive punch to come back either on
the power play (where they were 0 for 3) or at even strength.
</P>
<P>
   Salo had 20 saves and Trevor Kidd made 21 stops for Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   There are many underachieving Islander forwards, but at the
center of the team's woes are the two players Milbury scratched
Saturday: left wing Ted Donato and right wing Jason Dawe. Dawe has
not scored a goal since Oct. 29 and has just 3 points in his last
11 games. Donato, who was acquired from the Bruins earlier this
month, has no goals and four assists in nine games with the
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donato has been lousy since he got here; Dawe decides to play
when we put him on a line,'' Milbury said, suggesting that Dawe
puts forth more effort when he is on a scoring line.
</P>
<P>
   Mariusz Czerkawski and Robert Reichel generated some chances,
registering 11 shots on goal between them. But hitting the goalie
or the post, as Czerkawski did in the second period, doesn't count.
Mike Watt and Joe Sacco did not sniff the net, while Trevor Linden
shot on goal only once.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Bryan Smolinski, a versatile forward,
sustained a bruised shoulder early in the third period after
colliding with the boards and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 12,472 fans at Nassau Coliseum revived the ``We want
Ziggy'' chant in the third period. It had not been heard here since
the first week of the season. The Long Island fans might not have
missed Zigmund Palffy, the Islanders' unsigned wing, while the team
was winning. But Saturday they called on the team to sign him.
Palffy's contract dispute with the Islanders is in its second
month. Undeniably, the free agent Palffy, a three-time 40-goal
scorer, would help the Islanders' undermanned offense.
</P>
<P>
   Dineen scored at 3:07 of the second period, launching a perfect
shot through a screen and over the shoulder of Salo. Kapanen made
the score 2-0 at 6:25 with another good shot, backhanding the puck
off of the far post on a semi-wraparound. And Primeau tallied at
7:26 on the power play, knocking in a rebound after defenseman
Scott Lachance failed to clear the puck. Nemchinov put a backhander
from the slot past Kidd at 14:02 of the third period for the
Islanders' lone goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to generate more offense,'' said Linden, the
Islanders' captain. Then, referring to Palffy, Linden said:
``Certainly when you have a guy like that in the lineup that can
score and make things happen, it's obviously a huge advantage.
There are a handful of players that are in his league
offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman KENNY JONSSON, who sustained a concussion last week,
missed his third game Saturday and was questionable for Wednesday's
game against the Rangers at Nassau Coliseum. ... The Islanders
recalled the 6-foot-9-inch defenseman ZDENO CHARA and the enforcer
STEVE WEBB. Both made their season debuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
